export const PATTERN_FULL = {
  "PP-ADVERSARIAL-FRAMING": {"name":"Adversarial Framing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Splitting; Hypervigilance; Moral Superiority; Defensive Expertise; Anger as Armor; Projection.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior — permanent battlefield. Rebel — oppressor/oppressed simplification. Sage — argument as conquest. Ruler — power blocs. Lover — loyalty tests.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly distinguishes ordinary adversarial framing from real abuse, exploitation, discrimination, litigation, or warfare.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"State the disagreement without assigning a hostile motive or winner.","Core Logic":"I am turning difference into a battle so I do not have to risk collaboration or uncertainty.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Escalation; polarization; misread motives; lost cooperation; chronic vigilance.","Core Fear":"Every conflict has a victor; collaboration makes me vulnerable; others exploit openness; neutrality is betrayal.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This is a battle, and I need to win.; If I compromise, I lose.; I need to know whose side everyone is on.; Their disagreement means they’re against me.; Curiosity would make me vulnerable.; I should look for the strategic motive behind everything they say.","Protective Move":"Adversarial framing is the protective interpretation of disagreement, negotiation, or difference as a contest with winners, losers, allies, and enemies.","Pattern ID":"PP-ADVERSARIAL-FRAMING","Short-Term Payoff":"Certainty and mobilization increase when sides and motives harden.","Freer Expression":"Clear conflict without enemy-making.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Strategic clarity; courage; ability to identify genuine conflict.","Observable Cues":"Debate posture; coalition building; assigning hostile motives; win/lose language; treating repair attempts as maneuvers; escalating minor differences.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Avoid entering the contest frame. Name common ground and boundaries, and do not debate when the interaction becomes threatening or coercive. May trigger Defensiveness, Moral Superiority, Retaliation, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Competence, Dignity, Control, and Belonging; avoids mutual dependence, ambiguity, partial responsibility, grief, and compromise.","Canonical Name":"Adversarial Framing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAdversarial framing is the protective interpretation of disagreement, negotiation, or difference as a contest with winners, losers, allies, and enemies.\n## Domain\nAnger, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nSplitting; Hypervigilance; Moral Superiority; Defensive Expertise; Anger as Armor\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am turning difference into a battle so I do not have to risk collaboration or uncertainty.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This is a battle, and I need to win.\n- If I compromise, I lose.\n- I need to know whose side everyone is on.\n- Their disagreement means they’re against me.\n- Curiosity would make me vulnerable.\n- I should look for the strategic motive behind everything they say.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to identify sides; compromise feels like defeat; curiosity feels disloyal; neutral information is scanned for strategic advantage.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDebate posture; coalition building; assigning hostile motives; win/lose language; treating repair attempts as maneuvers; escalating minor differences.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Competence; Dignity; Control; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCriticism; ambiguity; competition; loss of control; prior betrayal; high-stakes negotiation.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nEvery conflict has a victor; collaboration makes me vulnerable; others exploit openness; neutrality is betrayal.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nMutual dependence; ambiguity; partial responsibility; grief; compromise.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior — permanent battlefield. Rebel — oppressor/oppressed simplification. Sage — argument as conquest. Ruler — power blocs. Lover — loyalty tests.\n## Pattern Flow\nDifference appears → safety or status feels threatened → sides and motives harden → certainty and mobilization increase → cooperation collapses → threat appears confirmed.\n## Often Appears With\nSplitting; Projection; Defensive Expertise; Moral Superiority.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nStrategic clarity; courage; ability to identify genuine conflict.\n## Current Cost\nEscalation; polarization; misread motives; lost cooperation; chronic vigilance.\n## Freer Expression\nClear conflict without enemy-making.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the disagreement without assigning a hostile motive or winner.\n## Mira Language\n“There may be a real conflict here. Are you also organizing it as a battle in which collaboration would mean losing?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat part of this is genuinely incompatible? What could remain shared even if the disagreement remains?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGenuine abuse, exploitation, discrimination, litigation, or warfare may involve real adversaries. Mira must not impose mutuality where danger or unequal power is present.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated conversion of ordinary disagreement into strategic opposition across contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate incompatible interests from imagined hostility. Identify shared facts, nonnegotiables, and one area where cooperation remains possible.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAvoid entering the contest frame. Name common ground and boundaries, and do not debate when the interaction becomes threatening or coercive.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where enemy-making distorted motives or recruited others, correct false claims, restore direct communication, and establish rules for disagreement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Moral Superiority, Retaliation, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by criticism, secrecy, or another person’s adversarial framing. Each side reads the other’s defense as proof of hostility.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere have I mistaken disagreement for war?"},
  "PP-ADVICE-GIVING-AS-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Advice-Giving as Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rescuing; Defensive Expertise; Emotional Distancing; Overfunctioning; Deflection; Savior Identity.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver—care becomes fixing; Sage—knowledge replaces presence; Ruler—solutions are imposed; Magician—transformation is rushed; Warrior—pain becomes a problem to defeat.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with obvious spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because the source distinguishes requested expertise, emergency guidance, teaching, and practical collaboration from the pattern.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"Ask, “Would you like listening, reflection, help thinking, or concrete suggestions?” before offering advice.","Core Logic":"I am trying to solve this so I do not have to feel what cannot yet be solved.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Emotional disconnection; unwanted dependence or resistance; inaccurate solutions; exhaustion; diminished trust; bypassed grief.","Core Fear":"I am valuable when I am useful; helplessness is dangerous; feelings must be repaired quickly; if I cannot fix it, I will fail or be rejected.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to solve this before the feeling gets bigger.; Listening alone feels useless.; If I have no answer, I may fail them.; I should offer the solution before asking what support they want.; Their distress is making me feel helpless.; Advice feels safer than simply staying present.","Protective Move":"Advice-Giving as Avoidance is the protective move of shifting quickly into instruction, solutions, or expertise so the person does not have to remain with uncertainty, helplessness, emotion, or another person’s unfixable experience.","Pattern ID":"PP-ADVICE-GIVING-AS-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary usefulness and control return when advice and solutions accelerate.","Freer Expression":"Useful wisdom offered after presence and consent.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Resourcefulness; care; practical intelligence; generosity; problem-solving.","Observable Cues":"Offering solutions before understanding; interrupting emotion with instructions; sending resources without consent; repeating advice after it is declined; treating listening as insufficient; redirecting the conversation toward one’s expertise.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"State clearly whether you want listening, reflection, brainstorming, or advice. Appreciate the intention without accepting unwanted fixing. Set limits if advice continues after refusal. May trigger Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, Withdrawal, Help-Rejection, or Underfunctioning.","Emotional Function":"Protects competence, care and support, belonging, trust and predictability, self-esteem, and safety; avoids helplessness, grief, uncertainty, limits, another person’s autonomy, and one’s own emotional resonance.","Canonical Name":"Advice-Giving as Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAdvice-Giving as Avoidance is the protective move of shifting quickly into instruction, solutions, or expertise so the person does not have to remain with uncertainty, helplessness, emotion, or another person’s unfixable experience.\n## Domain\nCare, Connection, and Emotional Presence\n## Related Patterns\nRescuing; Defensive Expertise; Emotional Distancing; Overfunctioning; Deflection; Savior Identity\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am trying to solve this so I do not have to feel what cannot yet be solved.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to solve this before the feeling gets bigger.\n- Listening alone feels useless.\n- If I have no answer, I may fail them.\n- I should offer the solution before asking what support they want.\n- Their distress is making me feel helpless.\n- Advice feels safer than simply staying present.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to provide an answer; discomfort with silence or grief; fear of being useless; irritation when advice is not followed; relief when the conversation becomes technical.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOffering solutions before understanding; interrupting emotion with instructions; sending resources without consent; repeating advice after it is declined; treating listening as insufficient; redirecting the conversation toward one’s expertise.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; care and support; belonging; trust and predictability; self-esteem; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAnother person’s distress; ambiguity; grief; recurring problems; requests for emotional presence; situations with no immediate solution.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am valuable when I am useful; helplessness is dangerous; feelings must be repaired quickly; if I cannot fix it, I will fail or be rejected.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHelplessness; grief; uncertainty; limits; another person’s autonomy; one’s own emotional resonance.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver—care becomes fixing; Sage—knowledge replaces presence; Ruler—solutions are imposed; Magician—transformation is rushed; Warrior—pain becomes a problem to defeat.\n## Pattern Flow\nDistress appears → helplessness or inadequacy is activated → advice and solutions accelerate → temporary usefulness and control return → the other person feels unseen or managed → deeper connection and accurate understanding are lost.\n## Often Appears With\nRescuing; Overfunctioning; Defensive Expertise; Emotional Distancing; Savior Identity.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nResourcefulness; care; practical intelligence; generosity; problem-solving.\n## Current Cost\nEmotional disconnection; unwanted dependence or resistance; inaccurate solutions; exhaustion; diminished trust; bypassed grief.\n## Freer Expression\nUseful wisdom offered after presence and consent.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk, “Would you like listening, reflection, help thinking, or concrete suggestions?” before offering advice.\n## Mira Language\n“You may have a useful solution. I also notice the conversation moved to fixing before the experience was fully understood. Would it help to pause and ask what kind of support is wanted?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat becomes uncomfortable if no solution is available yet? Are you being asked to fix, witness, reflect, or simply remain present? What would care look like if usefulness were not the measure?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nExpertise, emergency guidance, requested advice, teaching, and practical collaboration are not automatically avoidance. Urgent safety situations may require direct action.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated sequence of premature, unsolicited, or persistent advice that replaces emotional contact—not one helpful suggestion.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRecognize the caring and competent impulse, slow the move to solutions, tolerate a brief period of not knowing, and ask what support is desired. Offer knowledge without making compliance the price of connection.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nState clearly whether you want listening, reflection, brainstorming, or advice. Appreciate the intention without accepting unwanted fixing. Set limits if advice continues after refusal.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where fixing displaced listening or overrode autonomy. Name the impact, ask what was needed, and demonstrate change by seeking consent before advising and accepting “no” without withdrawal or resentment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, Withdrawal, Help-Rejection, or Underfunctioning. Often triggered by Emotional Flooding, Reassurance Seeking, repeated crisis, or another person’s helplessness. The loop may become: “You do not hear me” and “Nothing I offer is ever enough.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using solutions to avoid the vulnerability of presence?"},
  "PP-ALL-OR-NOTHING": {"name":"All-or-Nothing Thinking","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Black-and-White Thinking; Binary Thinking; Perfectionism; Catastrophizing; Splitting; Rigidity; Idealization/Devaluation; Shame.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent — goodness must remain untainted. Warrior — one loss means defeat. Ruler — order permits no exception. Lover — closeness becomes total devotion or rejection. Sage — ideas are correct or worthless. Rebel — compromise becomes surrender.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Replace an absolute conclusion with a percentage, spectrum, or “both/and” statement.","Core Logic":"I am turning a spectrum into two absolutes so I do not have to remain in uncertainty.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Premature endings; harsh self-judgment; unstable relationships; lost learning; inability to recognize partial success.","Core Fear":"Ambiguity is dangerous; mistakes lead to rejection; I must know where I stand; mixed feelings cannot be trusted.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If this isn’t a complete success, it’s a failure.; One flaw ruins the whole thing.; Either you’re with me or against me.; If I can’t do it perfectly, there’s no point.; This setback proves the entire plan is wrong.; I need to decide whether this is good or bad right now.","Protective Move":"All-or-Nothing Thinking protects against ambiguity and uncertain evaluation by reducing a complex reality to opposing categories such as success or failure, safe or unsafe, loyal or disloyal.","Pattern ID":"PP-ALL-OR-NOTHING","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate clarity arrives when reality is divided into absolutes.","Freer Expression":"Clear discernment with room for complexity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Decisiveness; moral clarity; pattern simplification; commitment.","Observable Cues":"Using always/never; abandoning efforts after setbacks; idealizing then dismissing; treating partial agreement as betrayal; evaluating performance as total success or failure.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Validate the importance without accepting the false binary. Offer specific nuance and avoid forcing immediate resolution while the person is flooded. May trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Perfectionism, People-Pleasing, or Counter-Rigidity.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Competence, Autonomy, and Self-Esteem; avoids grief, compromise, gradual progress, complexity, disappointment, and coexistence of love and anger.","Canonical Name":"All-or-Nothing Thinking"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAll-or-Nothing Thinking protects against ambiguity and uncertain evaluation by reducing a complex reality to opposing categories such as success or failure, safe or unsafe, loyal or disloyal.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nBlack-and-White Thinking; Binary Thinking; Perfectionism; Catastrophizing; Splitting; Rigidity\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am turning a spectrum into two absolutes so I do not have to remain in uncertainty.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If this isn’t a complete success, it’s a failure.\n- One flaw ruins the whole thing.\n- Either you’re with me or against me.\n- If I can’t do it perfectly, there’s no point.\n- This setback proves the entire plan is wrong.\n- I need to decide whether this is good or bad right now.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDifficulty holding mixed evidence; one flaw erases the whole; urgency to decide which side something belongs on; emotional relief from absolute conclusions.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nUsing always/never; abandoning efforts after setbacks; idealizing then dismissing; treating partial agreement as betrayal; evaluating performance as total success or failure.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Competence; Autonomy; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nMixed feedback; mistakes; relational ambivalence; uncertain outcomes; moral complexity; loss of control.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nAmbiguity is dangerous; mistakes lead to rejection; I must know where I stand; mixed feelings cannot be trusted.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; compromise; gradual progress; complexity; disappointment; coexistence of love and anger.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent — goodness must remain untainted. Warrior — one loss means defeat. Ruler — order permits no exception. Lover — closeness becomes total devotion or rejection. Sage — ideas are correct or worthless. Rebel — compromise becomes surrender.\n## Pattern Flow\nComplexity appears → certainty or worth feels threatened → reality is divided into absolutes → immediate clarity arrives → nuance and options disappear → instability and harsh judgment increase.\n## Often Appears With\nPerfectionism; Catastrophizing; Idealization/Devaluation; Rigidity; Shame.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDecisiveness; moral clarity; pattern simplification; commitment.\n## Current Cost\nPremature endings; harsh self-judgment; unstable relationships; lost learning; inability to recognize partial success.\n## Freer Expression\nClear discernment with room for complexity.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace an absolute conclusion with a percentage, spectrum, or “both/and” statement.\n## Mira Language\n“I hear the mind dividing this into total success or total failure. What becomes visible if we place it on a spectrum instead?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat remains true between the extremes? What did this setback not erase? Can someone disappoint you and still matter?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nFirm boundaries, decisive moral judgments, and genuine incompatibility are not automatically binary thinking. Splitting may involve a broader relational and identity process and should not be treated as a casual synonym.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated collapse of mixed evidence into extremes across decisions, self-evaluation, or relationships—not one necessary yes/no decision.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate the urgency for certainty, name at least three gradations, and delay irreversible action until mixed evidence can be tolerated.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nValidate the importance without accepting the false binary. Offer specific nuance and avoid forcing immediate resolution while the person is flooded.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where an absolute judgment erased the other person’s complexity or the relationship’s history. Correct the record, restore nuance, and agree to pause before future totalizing statements or decisions.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Perfectionism, People-Pleasing, or Counter-Rigidity. Often triggered by Inconsistency, Ambivalence, Criticism, or Unclear Commitments. Reinforcing stories: “If it is not complete, it is worthless” and “There is no safe way to be imperfect with you.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat complexity am I removing because certainty feels safer?"},
  "PP-ANGER-AS-ARMOR": {"name":"Anger as Armor","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hostility Toward Criticism; Blame Shifting; Hypervigilance; Emotional Numbing; Devaluation.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior mobilizes against vulnerability; Ruler intimidates to restore authority; Rebel attacks control; Lover converts hurt into accusation; Caregiver becomes furious when unseen; Sage weaponizes certainty.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly requires safety-first intervention for threats, intimidation, violence, and coercion.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Lower the intensity enough to name the vulnerable fact and the boundary in separate sentences.","Core Logic":"Anger feels safer than letting you see what was hurt or frightened.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Fear in others; escalation; damaged trust; obscured needs; retaliation; isolation.","Core Fear":"Vulnerability will be exploited; only force is respected; sadness or fear is unsafe; I must become dangerous to avoid being harmed.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to get forceful before I’m hurt.; Anger is the only thing that makes people listen.; I can’t let you see how scared or hurt I am.; If I soften, I’ll lose control.; I need to become dangerous before you can harm me.; The anger feels safer than the grief underneath it.","Protective Move":"Anger as Armor is the protective use of anger, hardness, intimidation, or attack to cover more vulnerable states such as fear, shame, grief, helplessness, or threatened dignity.","Pattern ID":"PP-ANGER-AS-ARMOR","Short-Term Payoff":"Power and distance provide temporary relief.","Freer Expression":"Protective strength with disclosed truth.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Energy; boundary defense; courage; moral clarity; capacity to mobilize.","Observable Cues":"Raised voice; intimidation; sharpness; threats to leave; aggressive certainty; turning hurt into accusation; dominating the pace of conflict.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not match intimidation or demand vulnerability during escalation. Set a clear safety boundary, pause the interaction, and re-engage only when respectful communication is possible. May trigger Hypervigilance, People-Pleasing, Emotional Distancing, Stonewalling, or Anger as Armor in return.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Autonomy, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Belonging; avoids fear, grief, longing, dependence, remorse, and uncertainty.","Canonical Name":"Anger as Armor"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAnger as Armor is the protective use of anger, hardness, intimidation, or attack to cover more vulnerable states such as fear, shame, grief, helplessness, or threatened dignity.\n## Domain\nAccountability, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nHostility Toward Criticism; Blame Shifting; Hypervigilance; Emotional Numbing; Devaluation\n## Recognition Sentence\nAnger feels safer than letting you see what was hurt or frightened.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to get forceful before I’m hurt.\n- Anger is the only thing that makes people listen.\n- I can’t let you see how scared or hurt I am.\n- If I soften, I’ll lose control.\n- I need to become dangerous before you can harm me.\n- The anger feels safer than the grief underneath it.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRapid access to heat but not sadness or fear; relief through forcefulness; vulnerability feels exposing or weak; bodily readiness to confront.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRaised voice; intimidation; sharpness; threats to leave; aggressive certainty; turning hurt into accusation; dominating the pace of conflict.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Autonomy; Self-Esteem; Trust; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nShame; rejection; helplessness; disrespect; fear of loss; criticism; perceived control.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nVulnerability will be exploited; only force is respected; sadness or fear is unsafe; I must become dangerous to avoid being harmed.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFear; grief; longing; dependence; remorse; uncertainty.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior mobilizes against vulnerability; Ruler intimidates to restore authority; Rebel attacks control; Lover converts hurt into accusation; Caregiver becomes furious when unseen; Sage weaponizes certainty.\n## Pattern Flow\nVulnerability is activated → safety or dignity feels threatened → anger hardens into protection → power and distance provide temporary relief → impact creates fear or withdrawal → the underlying vulnerability becomes even less speakable.\n## Often Appears With\nHypervigilance; Hostility Toward Criticism; Blame Shifting; Emotional Numbing; Devaluation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEnergy; boundary defense; courage; moral clarity; capacity to mobilize.\n## Current Cost\nFear in others; escalation; damaged trust; obscured needs; retaliation; isolation.\n## Freer Expression\nProtective strength with disclosed truth.\n## One Act of Volition\nLower the intensity enough to name the vulnerable fact and the boundary in separate sentences.\n## Mira Language\n“The anger may contain valid information, and its force may also be protecting something more vulnerable. What was threatened or hurt before the anger took command?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat boundary needs protection? What feeling would appear if attack were unavailable? Is anyone currently unsafe?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAnger is not inherently pathological and can be proportionate, protective, and ethically necessary. Threats, intimidation, violence, and coercion require safety-first intervention rather than mutual communication coaching.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated conversion of vulnerable affect into intimidating or attacking behavior—not ordinary anger or firm boundary setting.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nCreate physical and conversational space, regulate arousal, identify the underlying need or injury, and express a boundary without threat or domination.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not match intimidation or demand vulnerability during escalation. Set a clear safety boundary, pause the interaction, and re-engage only when respectful communication is possible.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName the intimidation or harm without centering the hidden vulnerability as an excuse. Restore safety, accept consequences, make specific behavioral commitments, and allow the affected person to determine whether re-engagement is appropriate.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Hypervigilance, People-Pleasing, Emotional Distancing, Stonewalling, or Anger as Armor in return. Often triggered by Criticism, Contempt, control, shame, or perceived abandonment. The loop becomes: “I must become forceful to be safe” and “I must appease, withdraw, or become forceful to survive your anger.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat vulnerable truth is my anger protecting, and how can I defend it without making another person unsafe?"},
  "PP-ANTICIPATORY-DEFEAT": {"name":"Anticipatory Defeat","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Cynicism; Catastrophizing; Risk Avoidance; Failure to Launch; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Learned Helplessness; Procrastination; Self-Handicapping; Emotional Numbing.","Archetypal Role":"Orphan expects exclusion; Sage turns pessimism into certainty; Warrior refuses battles not already won; Creator abandons work before exposure.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Run the smallest honest test that could produce new evidence.","Core Logic":"I am ending the possibility internally before reality has decided.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Lost opportunity; passivity; reduced experimentation; self-confirming hopelessness.","Core Fear":"Hope makes pain worse; effort does not change outcomes; stopping early preserves dignity.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This probably will not work anyway.; Hope will only make the disappointment worse.; I should give up before reality proves me wrong.; The obstacles already tell me the outcome.; Trying fully would make failure hurt more.; It feels safer to declare defeat than stay open to possibility.","Protective Move":"Anticipatory Defeat is the protective conclusion that an effort, relationship, or change will fail before it has been adequately tested, reducing hope and investment to soften possible disappointment.","Pattern ID":"PP-ANTICIPATORY-DEFEAT","Short-Term Payoff":"Withdrawal brings short-term relief when failure is predicted as settled.","Freer Expression":"Grounded hope through testing.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Realism; caution; memory of prior harm; sensitivity to structural barriers.","Observable Cues":"Dismissing options before testing them; declining opportunities; minimal effort; predicting failure; interpreting setbacks as proof to stop.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not force positivity. Validate real obstacles, ask what remains testable, and avoid taking over the person’s agency. May trigger Overfunctioning, Rescuing, Criticism, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Safety, Competence, and Trust; avoids hope, grief, suspense, vulnerability, and incremental learning.","Canonical Name":"Anticipatory Defeat"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAnticipatory Defeat is the protective conclusion that an effort, relationship, or change will fail before it has been adequately tested, reducing hope and investment to soften possible disappointment.\n## Domain\nHope, Action, and Disappointment Protection\n## Related Patterns\nCynicism; Catastrophizing; Risk Avoidance; Failure to Launch; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Learned Helplessness.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am ending the possibility internally before reality has decided.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This probably will not work anyway.\n- Hope will only make the disappointment worse.\n- I should give up before reality proves me wrong.\n- The obstacles already tell me the outcome.\n- Trying fully would make failure hurt more.\n- It feels safer to declare defeat than stay open to possibility.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nHope feels naive; motivation collapses after imagining obstacles; negative outcomes feel certain; relief accompanies giving up early.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDismissing options before testing them; declining opportunities; minimal effort; predicting failure; interpreting setbacks as proof to stop.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Safety; Competence; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPrior disappointment; uncertainty; slow progress; new opportunity; dependence on others; visible stakes.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nHope makes pain worse; effort does not change outcomes; stopping early preserves dignity.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHope; grief; suspense; vulnerability; incremental learning.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nOrphan expects exclusion; Sage turns pessimism into certainty; Warrior refuses battles not already won; Creator abandons work before exposure.\n## Pattern Flow\nMeaningful possibility appears → disappointment feels threatening → failure is predicted as settled → withdrawal brings short-term relief → no corrective experience occurs → defeat feels increasingly factual.\n## Often Appears With\nCynicism; Risk Avoidance; Procrastination; Self-Handicapping; Emotional Numbing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nRealism; caution; memory of prior harm; sensitivity to structural barriers.\n## Current Cost\nLost opportunity; passivity; reduced experimentation; self-confirming hopelessness.\n## Freer Expression\nGrounded hope through testing.\n## One Act of Volition\nRun the smallest honest test that could produce new evidence.\n## Mira Language\n“The outcome sounds decided before the experiment has occurred. What is known, and what is the protective prediction?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence would justify one small test? Are you protecting yourself from failure, or from hope itself?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSome barriers are real and some options are genuinely poor. Mira must not promote optimism over evidence or structural reality.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated premature closure of plausible options without adequate testing, especially when relief follows withdrawal.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReplace global prediction with a bounded experiment and define what evidence would guide the next decision.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not force positivity. Validate real obstacles, ask what remains testable, and avoid taking over the person’s agency.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where premature defeat abandoned shared effort or transferred burden; renegotiate participation based on evidence and capacity.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Rescuing, Criticism, or Emotional Distancing. Those reactions can reinforce “No one believes in me” and “I must carry everything alone.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat possibility have I declared dead before giving reality a fair chance to answer?"},
  "PP-APPEARANCE-BOUND-WORTH": {"name":"Appearance-Bound Worth","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Comparison; Image Management; Approval Seeking; Perfectionism; Reassurance Seeking; Shame Spiraling; Self-Deprecation.","Archetypal Role":"Lover—desirability becomes the price of being chosen; Innocent—beauty or purity becomes proof of goodness; Ruler—presentation becomes controlled status; Creator—the body becomes an endlessly revised project; Warrior—strength or leanness becomes moral worth; Caregiver—looking composed prevents others from seeing need.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term remains empty because the source explicitly cautions Mira not to diagnose eating disorders, body dysmorphic disorder, or other clinical conditions. Crosswalk Terms remains empty. Safety Flags mapped to Medical Differential because the source requires distinction from clinical and medical conditions.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"Participate in one valued activity without waiting for appearance certainty, and name the value that makes participation worthwhile.","Core Logic":"If I do not look acceptable, desirable, youthful, thin, strong, polished, or put together, I may lose worth or belonging.","Safety Flags":["Medical Differential"],"Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Shame; social withdrawal; delayed participation; distorted self-evaluation; compulsive comparison; intimacy difficulty; reduced joy; treating the body as an adversary or résumé.","Core Fear":"Love is conditional on attractiveness; visible difference invites rejection; the body is public evidence of worth; aging or imperfection means loss of relevance; belonging requires meeting a narrow appearance standard.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I cannot be visible until I look acceptable.; This photograph proves something is wrong with me.; I need reassurance that my appearance has not cost me worth.; I should delay participation until my body changes.; Their affection does not count because they cannot see me accurately.; Looking imperfect feels like losing permission to belong.","Protective Move":"Appearance-Bound Worth is the protective tying of dignity, lovability, belonging, legitimacy, or personal value to how the body or face is judged—by oneself, by others, or by an imagined audience.","Pattern ID":"PP-APPEARANCE-BOUND-WORTH","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief arrives through checking, concealing, controlling, comparing, reassurance, or approval.","Freer Expression":"Embodied dignity without appearance as the price of worth.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Aesthetic sensitivity; care for presentation; embodiment; sensuality; health awareness; self-expression.","Observable Cues":"Avoiding photographs, events, intimacy, clothing, or visibility; repeated checking or reassurance seeking; excessive grooming or concealment; self-deprecating appearance comments; comparing bodies or faces; delaying life until an appearance goal is reached; dismissing positive feedback as pity or dishonesty.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not debate the person’s body as though reassurance alone can settle the pattern. Acknowledge distress, avoid reinforcing narrow standards, and return attention to dignity, consent, values, and the person’s full presence. May trigger Reassurance Seeking, Emotional Withholding, Comparison, Criticism, or Withdrawal in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects self-esteem, belonging, love, dignity, safety, and identity; avoids grief about change, mortality, ordinary embodiment, vulnerability in intimacy, social cruelty, uncertainty about attraction, anger at cultural standards, and needs for acceptance that cannot be controlled through appearance.","Canonical Name":"Appearance-Bound Worth"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAppearance-Bound Worth is the protective tying of dignity, lovability, belonging, legitimacy, or personal value to how the body or face is judged—by oneself, by others, or by an imagined audience.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nComparison; Image Management; Approval Seeking; Perfectionism; Reassurance Seeking; Shame Spiraling; Self-Deprecation\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I do not look acceptable, desirable, youthful, thin, strong, polished, or put together, I may lose worth or belonging.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I cannot be visible until I look acceptable.\n- This photograph proves something is wrong with me.\n- I need reassurance that my appearance has not cost me worth.\n- I should delay participation until my body changes.\n- Their affection does not count because they cannot see me accurately.\n- Looking imperfect feels like losing permission to belong.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nShame or alarm after seeing one’s reflection or photograph; worth rising and falling with perceived attractiveness; scanning others for comparison; difficulty receiving affection that contradicts a negative body judgment; relief after concealment, grooming, restriction, reassurance, or approval.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAvoiding photographs, events, intimacy, clothing, or visibility; repeated checking or reassurance seeking; excessive grooming or concealment; self-deprecating appearance comments; comparing bodies or faces; delaying life until an appearance goal is reached; dismissing positive feedback as pity or dishonesty.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-esteem; belonging; love; dignity; safety; identity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPhotographs; mirrors; aging; weight or body changes; illness; dating; intimacy; social media; comparison; criticism; rejection; clothing; public visibility; appearance-focused environments.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove is conditional on attractiveness; visible difference invites rejection; the body is public evidence of worth; aging or imperfection means loss of relevance; belonging requires meeting a narrow appearance standard.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief about change; mortality; ordinary embodiment; vulnerability in intimacy; social cruelty; uncertainty about attraction; anger at cultural standards; needs for acceptance that cannot be controlled through appearance.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover—desirability becomes the price of being chosen; Innocent—beauty or purity becomes proof of goodness; Ruler—presentation becomes controlled status; Creator—the body becomes an endlessly revised project; Warrior—strength or leanness becomes moral worth; Caregiver—looking composed prevents others from seeing need.\n## Pattern Flow\nVisibility, comparison, or bodily change occurs → worth or belonging feels threatened → checking, concealing, controlling, comparing, or seeking reassurance intensifies → temporary relief arrives → the body becomes more closely monitored → worth becomes increasingly dependent on appearance.\n## Often Appears With\nComparison; Image Management; Approval Seeking; Perfectionism; Shame Spiraling; Reassurance Seeking; Self-Deprecation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAesthetic sensitivity; care for presentation; embodiment; sensuality; health awareness; self-expression.\n## Current Cost\nShame; social withdrawal; delayed participation; distorted self-evaluation; compulsive comparison; intimacy difficulty; reduced joy; treating the body as an adversary or résumé.\n## Freer Expression\nEmbodied dignity without appearance as the price of worth.\n## One Act of Volition\nParticipate in one valued activity without waiting for appearance certainty, and name the value that makes participation worthwhile.\n## Mira Language\n“It sounds as though appearance is carrying more than preference—it may be carrying your worth, belonging, or permission to be visible. Does that fit, or is there a specific practical concern you want to address?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you fear your appearance proves about you? What life are you postponing until your body or presentation changes? Whose standard is present in the room when you judge yourself this way? Can care for appearance remain a choice rather than a verdict?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGrooming, fashion, body goals, health treatment, cultural presentation practices, gender expression, or concern about a real medical change are not automatically protective pathology. Mira must not diagnose eating disorders, body dysmorphic disorder, or other clinical conditions.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated sequence in which appearance judgments govern worth, belonging, visibility, intimacy, or participation—not one bad-photo day or ordinary dissatisfaction.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the threatened need beneath the appearance judgment. Separate bodily care from self-verdict. Reduce checking or comparison long enough to re-enter a valued activity, relationship, or embodied experience that does not require appearance certainty.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not debate the person’s body as though reassurance alone can settle the pattern. Acknowledge distress, avoid reinforcing narrow standards, and return attention to dignity, consent, values, and the person’s full presence. When clinical risk is possible, encourage appropriate professional support without shaming.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where appearance-bound worth produced criticism, withdrawal, reassurance demands, comparison, projection, or pressure on another person’s body. Name the impact, stop recruiting the relationship to stabilize appearance-based worth, and establish concrete boundaries around commentary, checking, or comparison.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Reassurance Seeking, Emotional Withholding, Comparison, Criticism, or Withdrawal in others. Often triggered by Comparison, Image Management, Conditional Warmth, rejection, or appearance-focused criticism. The reinforcing story may become: “I must prove you are attractive enough to be okay” on one side and “I am only safe if I can make you confirm my worth” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere has appearance become the price of my permission to belong, be loved, or participate?"},
  "PP-APPEASEMENT": {"name":"Appeasement","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"People-Pleasing; Conflict Avoidance; Self-Erasure; Boundary Collapse; Emotional Inhibition; Submission to Dominance; Shame Spiraling.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver regulates the threatening person. Innocent complies to restore safety. Lover sacrifices truth to preserve the bond. Servant identity mistakes obedience for goodness.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly addresses coercion, violence, constrained consent, retaliation, and survival-based compliance.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Replace an automatic yes with, “I need time before I answer.”","Core Logic":"I am becoming agreeable because resistance feels unsafe.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Compromised consent; lost boundaries; vulnerability to coercion; delayed anger; difficulty identifying desire.","Core Fear":"Resistance increases danger; safety depends on calming powerful people; my no will not be respected; disagreement causes punishment.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should agree so this doesn’t get worse.; My no will only make them angrier.; I need to calm them before I can think about what I want.; It’s safer to smile and comply.; I can revisit my real answer after the threat passes.; Resistance feels dangerous right now.","Protective Move":"Appeasement is the protective attempt to reduce perceived threat by becoming agreeable, compliant, soothing, or nonresistant in the moment. It is distinguished from People-Pleasing by its immediate threat-regulation function.","Pattern ID":"PP-APPEASEMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate danger may decrease when agreement and soothing increase.","Freer Expression":"Safety with self-possession.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Social attunement; de-escalation; flexibility; compassion.","Observable Cues":"Rapid compliance; apologizing to stop escalation; soothing the upset person while suppressing one’s own experience; saying yes under pressure; retracting boundaries when challenged.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Remove pressure, accept delayed answers, treat hesitation as meaningful, and never interpret compliance under fear as genuine agreement. May trigger Dominance, Micromanaging, or further coercion when compliance is rewarded.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Belonging, Trust, and Autonomy; avoids fear, helplessness, anger, possible retaliation, and recognition that a relationship is unsafe.","Canonical Name":"Appeasement"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAppeasement is the protective attempt to reduce perceived threat by becoming agreeable, compliant, soothing, or nonresistant in the moment. It is distinguished from People-Pleasing by its immediate threat-regulation function.\n## Domain\nThreat, Compliance, and Relationship Safety\n## Related Patterns\nPeople-Pleasing; Conflict Avoidance; Self-Erasure; Boundary Collapse; Emotional Inhibition; Submission to Dominance\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am becoming agreeable because resistance feels unsafe.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should agree so this doesn’t get worse.\n- My no will only make them angrier.\n- I need to calm them before I can think about what I want.\n- It’s safer to smile and comply.\n- I can revisit my real answer after the threat passes.\n- Resistance feels dangerous right now.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSudden blankness about preferences; automatic smiling or agreement under pressure; body tension beneath a calm exterior; relief when the other person settles.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRapid compliance; apologizing to stop escalation; soothing the upset person while suppressing one’s own experience; saying yes under pressure; retracting boundaries when challenged.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Belonging; Trust; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAnger; intimidation; authority; unpredictable reactions; coercion; relational volatility; prior punishment for resistance.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nResistance increases danger; safety depends on calming powerful people; my no will not be respected; disagreement causes punishment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFear; helplessness; anger; possible retaliation; recognition that a relationship is unsafe.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver regulates the threatening person. Innocent complies to restore safety. Lover sacrifices truth to preserve the bond. Servant identity mistakes obedience for goodness.\n## Pattern Flow\nThreat is perceived → safety or belonging feels endangered → agreement and soothing increase → immediate danger may decrease → authentic consent disappears → resentment, confusion, or repeated coercion follows.\n## Often Appears With\nConflict Avoidance; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Emotional Inhibition; Shame Spiraling.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSocial attunement; de-escalation; flexibility; compassion.\n## Current Cost\nCompromised consent; lost boundaries; vulnerability to coercion; delayed anger; difficulty identifying desire.\n## Freer Expression\nSafety with self-possession.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace an automatic yes with, “I need time before I answer.”\n## Mira Language\n“Your agreement may have helped the moment feel safer. Was it freely chosen, or did your system decide that resistance was dangerous?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did your body expect would happen if you said no? Was consent available in that moment? What support would make a truthful answer safer?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nIn coercive or violent situations, appeasement can be a survival response and must not be blamed. Immediate safety takes priority over direct confrontation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated rapid compliance specifically under perceived interpersonal threat, followed by disconnection from preference, resentment, or recognition that consent was constrained.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPrioritize safety, create time and distance where possible, and revisit choices only when free consent is available.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRemove pressure, accept delayed answers, treat hesitation as meaningful, and never interpret compliance under fear as genuine agreement.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nThe person who used pressure must acknowledge its effect and restore choice; the appeasing person is not responsible for having failed to resist danger. Future repair requires demonstrably safe conditions and respect for no.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Dominance, Micromanaging, or further coercion when compliance is rewarded. Often triggered by Anger as Armor, Intimidation, Retaliation, or Hostility Toward Criticism. Stories become “I must submit to stay safe” and “Agreement proves my pressure is justified.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere did I agree because truth did not feel safe?"},
  "PP-APPROVAL-SEEKING": {"name":"Approval Seeking","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Reassurance Seeking; People-Pleasing; Comparison; Image Management; Defensive Expertise; Perfectionism.","Archetypal Role":"Sage — knowledge requires external certification. Creator — the work needs permission to exist. Everyman — consensus substitutes for conviction. Ruler — status endorsement legitimizes action. Lover — approval is treated as love.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Make one reversible decision using your own criteria before asking for feedback.","Core Logic":"I need your endorsement before I can trust my own choice.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Indecision; dependence; diluted authorship; susceptibility to influence; difficulty developing inner authority.","Core Fear":"My judgment cannot be trusted; mistakes cost belonging; authority determines what is valid; independent desire is selfish.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Do you think this is the right choice?; I need someone credible to approve this first.; I can’t trust my judgment until others agree.; What will people think if I do this?; Maybe I should wait for more endorsement.; I know what I want, but I need permission to act on it.","Protective Move":"Approval Seeking is the protective outsourcing of permission, worth, or confidence to another person’s endorsement before trusting one’s own judgment or action.","Pattern ID":"PP-APPROVAL-SEEKING","Short-Term Payoff":"Confidence briefly rises when endorsement is received.","Freer Expression":"Consultation without surrender.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Receptivity; humility; consultation; respect for expertise; collaboration.","Observable Cues":"Polling many people; presenting decisions for permission; changing course after mild disapproval; emphasizing credentials or praise; withholding action until endorsed.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer information without becoming the person’s permanent authorizer. Return the decision gently: “I trust you to choose; what matters most to you?” May trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Impatience, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Self-Esteem, Belonging, and Trust; avoids responsibility, uncertainty, possible regret, separateness, and standing behind an unpopular choice.","Canonical Name":"Approval Seeking"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nApproval Seeking is the protective outsourcing of permission, worth, or confidence to another person’s endorsement before trusting one’s own judgment or action.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nReassurance Seeking; People-Pleasing; Comparison; Image Management; Defensive Expertise\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need your endorsement before I can trust my own choice.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Do you think this is the right choice?\n- I need someone credible to approve this first.\n- I can’t trust my judgment until others agree.\n- What will people think if I do this?\n- Maybe I should wait for more endorsement.\n- I know what I want, but I need permission to act on it.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nHesitation until someone validates the decision; disproportionate relief after praise; fear that independent choice is arrogant or unsafe; repeated imagining of others’ reactions.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nPolling many people; presenting decisions for permission; changing course after mild disapproval; emphasizing credentials or praise; withholding action until endorsed.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Self-Esteem; Belonging; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nVisibility; uncertain decisions; evaluation; authority; unfamiliar action; possible criticism.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy judgment cannot be trusted; mistakes cost belonging; authority determines what is valid; independent desire is selfish.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nResponsibility; uncertainty; possible regret; separateness; standing behind an unpopular choice.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage — knowledge requires external certification. Creator — the work needs permission to exist. Everyman — consensus substitutes for conviction. Ruler — status endorsement legitimizes action. Lover — approval is treated as love.\n## Pattern Flow\nChoice becomes visible → competence or belonging feels uncertain → endorsement is sought → confidence briefly rises → independent judgment remains underdeveloped → future choices require more approval.\n## Often Appears With\nComparison; People-Pleasing; Perfectionism; Reassurance Seeking; Image Management.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReceptivity; humility; consultation; respect for expertise; collaboration.\n## Current Cost\nIndecision; dependence; diluted authorship; susceptibility to influence; difficulty developing inner authority.\n## Freer Expression\nConsultation without surrender.\n## One Act of Volition\nMake one reversible decision using your own criteria before asking for feedback.\n## Mira Language\n“Are you asking for useful information, or asking someone else to authorize a choice you already understand?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you know before anyone agrees? Whose approval carries unusual power here? What decision remains yours after consultation?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSeeking expertise, consent, supervision, or collaborative input is not automatically Approval Seeking.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated inability to act or maintain judgment without endorsement across comparable situations.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDefine the decision criteria, distinguish advice from permission, and make bounded choices that allow inner authority to accumulate through experience.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer information without becoming the person’s permanent authorizer. Return the decision gently: “I trust you to choose; what matters most to you?”\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where responsibility was displaced onto another person and where later blame followed their advice. Reclaim ownership and clarify future consultation boundaries.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Impatience, or Withdrawal in others. Often triggered by Criticism, superiority, ambiguity, or inconsistent feedback. The loop becomes “Tell me what is right” and “I have to decide everything for you.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I asking for permission when I actually need courage?"},
  "PP-ASYMMETRIC-EXPOSURE": {"name":"Asymmetric Exposure","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Information Control; Strategic Ambiguity; Vulnerability Avoidance; Emotional Withholding; Interrogative Control; Gossip.","Archetypal Role":"Sage studies without being studied; Magician protects hidden knowledge; Ruler gathers intelligence; Trickster exposes others while evading capture.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing repaired. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source. Abuse Context flag reflects potential weaponization of private material and nonconsensual exposure.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Before asking for vulnerable disclosure, name what you are willing to share and why the information is needed.","Core Logic":"I stay safer by knowing more about you than you know about me.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Mistrust; power imbalance; relational unsafety; reputational harm; shallow intimacy.","Core Fear":"Disclosure was exploited; privacy was violated; knowledge created safety or power.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Tell me more about you, but do not ask about me.; I need to know their vulnerabilities first.; Their disclosure gives me useful leverage.; I can interpret them without being interpreted.; Mutual exposure feels unsafe.; It is safer when the risk is mostly theirs.","Protective Move":"Draws out, interprets, reveals, or uses another person’s vulnerability while keeping one’s own inner life, motives, or risks comparatively concealed.","Pattern ID":"PP-ASYMMETRIC-EXPOSURE","Short-Term Payoff":"Informational asymmetry creates temporary control and safety.","Freer Expression":"Discernment with reciprocal consent.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Perception; discretion; curiosity; pattern recognition; protection of privacy.","Observable Cues":"Probing without reciprocating; publicizing another’s vulnerability; using private disclosures in conflict; interpreting others while resisting interpretation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Limit disclosure until reciprocity and confidentiality are demonstrated; name the imbalance directly. May trigger Emotional Withholding, Suspicion, Strategic Ambiguity, or Retaliation.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, autonomy, dignity, control, and self-protection; avoids mutual risk, being known, dependence, accountability, and equality in the exchange.","Canonical Name":"Asymmetric Exposure"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAsymmetric Exposure is a protective strategy of drawing out, interpreting, revealing, or using another person’s vulnerability while keeping one’s own inner life, motives, or risks comparatively concealed.\n## Domain\nIntimacy, Power, and Information\n## Related Patterns\nInformation Control; Strategic Ambiguity; Vulnerability Avoidance; Emotional Withholding; Interrogative Control; Gossip\n## Recognition Sentence\nI stay safer by knowing more about you than you know about me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Tell me more about you, but do not ask about me.\n- I need to know their vulnerabilities first.\n- Their disclosure gives me useful leverage.\n- I can interpret them without being interpreted.\n- Mutual exposure feels unsafe.\n- It is safer when the risk is mostly theirs.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when attention stays on the other person; anxiety when reciprocity is requested; vigilance about what is disclosed.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nProbing without reciprocating; publicizing another’s vulnerability; using private disclosures in conflict; interpreting others while resisting interpretation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; autonomy; dignity; control; self-protection.\n## Usually Triggered By\nMutual disclosure; accountability; intimacy; uncertainty about another’s intentions; status competition.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDisclosure was exploited; privacy was violated; knowledge created safety or power.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nMutual risk; being known; dependence; accountability; equality in the exchange.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage studies without being studied; Magician protects hidden knowledge; Ruler gathers intelligence; Trickster exposes others while evading capture.\n## Pattern Flow\nMutual vulnerability approaches → exposure feels dangerous → information is gathered or used asymmetrically → temporary control → trust and reciprocity deteriorate.\n## Often Appears With\nInformation Control; Emotional Withholding; Strategic Ambiguity; Interrogative Control; Image Management.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nPerception; discretion; curiosity; pattern recognition; protection of privacy.\n## Current Cost\nMistrust; power imbalance; relational unsafety; reputational harm; shallow intimacy.\n## Freer Expression\nDiscernment with reciprocal consent.\n## One Act of Volition\nBefore asking for vulnerable disclosure, name what you are willing to share and why the information is needed.\n## Mira Language\n“It sounds as though one person is carrying most of the exposure while the other retains informational control. Was the disclosure mutual and consensual, or did vulnerability become leverage?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWho is taking the greater risk? Was permission given to share this? What would reciprocity require here?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nProfessional interviewing, therapy, journalism, caregiving, and necessary privacy can involve asymmetry without exploitation. Role, consent, and purpose matter.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated nonreciprocal probing, disclosure, interpretation, or use of private material for leverage.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nClarify purpose, obtain consent, protect confidentiality, and accept an appropriate share of relational risk.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nLimit disclosure until reciprocity and confidentiality are demonstrated; name the imbalance directly; prioritize safety if information is being weaponized.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the breach or imbalance, stop circulation of private information, correct misrepresentation, and allow the affected person to set the terms of future access.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Withholding, Suspicion, Strategic Ambiguity, or Retaliation; those responses can reinforce further information gathering.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I asking another person to be more exposed than I am willing to be?"},
  "PP-AVOIDANT-COMPLIANCE": {"name":"Avoidant Compliance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Appeasement; Conflict Avoidance; Strategic Ambiguity; Passive Aggression; Emotional Withholding; Decision Delegation; Resentment; Procrastination.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver—agrees then disappears under burden; Lover—offers false harmony; Orphan—submits while preserving hidden autonomy; Trickster—uses ambiguity to escape capture; Diplomat—confuses peace with unspoken nonconsent.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with obvious spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly distinguishes survival compliance under coercion, threats, abuse, and severe power imbalance.","First Letter":"A","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"Replace immediate assent with: “I need time to decide; I have not agreed yet.”","Core Logic":"I am saying yes to end the pressure, not because I have actually chosen yes.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Unreliable agreements; resentment; confusion; escalated control; weakened trust; loss of authentic consent.","Core Fear":"No is unsafe; disagreement causes abandonment; direct needs create punishment; compliance is the only available exit.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should say yes so the pressure stops.; A truthful no does not feel safe.; I can agree now and find a way out later.; They will be angry if I tell them what I really want.; The commitment does not feel real inside me.; I need time before I can know whether this is genuine consent.","Protective Move":"Avoidant Compliance is the protective appearance of agreement used to escape immediate conflict, scrutiny, or pressure while withholding genuine consent, commitment, disagreement, or follow-through.","Pattern ID":"PP-AVOIDANT-COMPLIANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Verbal agreement ends the immediate threat and hidden resistance preserves temporary autonomy.","Freer Expression":"Honest consent with room for refusal and negotiation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Sensitivity to power; diplomacy; desire for peace; preservation of autonomy.","Observable Cues":"Agreeing without clarifying concerns; vague assent; delayed or absent follow-through; avoiding reminders; acting confused about commitments; privately resisting what was publicly accepted.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Stop escalating pressure. Ask for genuine consent, allow time, make refusal possible, and treat inconsistent follow-through as information that the agreement may not have been real. May trigger Interrogative Control, Micromanaging, Resentment, or Punitive Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, belonging, autonomy, dignity, predictability, conflict reduction, and protection from punishment; avoids conflict, guilt, responsibility for refusal, another person’s disappointment, negotiation, and acknowledgment of unequal power.","Canonical Name":"Avoidant Compliance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nAvoidant Compliance is the protective appearance of agreement used to escape immediate conflict, scrutiny, or pressure while withholding genuine consent, commitment, disagreement, or follow-through.\n## Domain\nConflict, Agency, Communication, and Attachment\n## Related Patterns\nAppeasement; Conflict Avoidance; Strategic Ambiguity; Passive Aggression; Emotional Withholding; Decision Delegation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am saying yes to end the pressure, not because I have actually chosen yes.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should say yes so the pressure stops.\n- A truthful no does not feel safe.\n- I can agree now and find a way out later.\n- They will be angry if I tell them what I really want.\n- The commitment does not feel real inside me.\n- I need time before I can know whether this is genuine consent.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief comes from ending the conversation; resentment follows agreement; one hopes circumstances will remove the obligation; direct refusal feels dangerous; commitment remains emotionally unreal.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAgreeing without clarifying concerns; vague assent; delayed or absent follow-through; avoiding reminders; acting confused about commitments; privately resisting what was publicly accepted.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; belonging; autonomy; dignity; predictability; conflict reduction; protection from punishment.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAuthority; persistent requests; anger; fear of rejection; time pressure; unequal power; anticipated disappointment.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nNo is unsafe; disagreement causes abandonment; direct needs create punishment; compliance is the only available exit.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nConflict; guilt; responsibility for refusal; another person’s disappointment; negotiation; acknowledgment of unequal power.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver—agrees then disappears under burden; Lover—offers false harmony; Orphan—submits while preserving hidden autonomy; Trickster—uses ambiguity to escape capture; Diplomat—confuses peace with unspoken nonconsent.\n## Pattern Flow\nPressure or anticipated conflict appears → safety or belonging feels threatened → verbal agreement ends the immediate threat → hidden resistance preserves temporary autonomy → follow-through fails → mistrust and stronger pressure develop.\n## Often Appears With\nAppeasement; Passive Aggression; Strategic Ambiguity; Resentment; Emotional Withholding; Procrastination.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSensitivity to power; diplomacy; desire for peace; preservation of autonomy.\n## Current Cost\nUnreliable agreements; resentment; confusion; escalated control; weakened trust; loss of authentic consent.\n## Freer Expression\nHonest consent with room for refusal and negotiation.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace immediate assent with: “I need time to decide; I have not agreed yet.”\n## Mira Language\n“Your words said yes, but your response afterward suggests the agreement may have functioned as an exit from pressure. Was there enough safety and freedom for a real choice?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would have happened if you said no? Did you actually consent, or did you need the pressure to stop? What would a truthful answer be now?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nUnder coercion, threats, abuse, or severe power imbalance, apparent compliance may be a survival response rather than a freely chosen interpersonal pattern. Responsibility must not be falsely equalized.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated assent under pressure followed by covert resistance or nonperformance—not one changed decision.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nAssess whether refusal is safe. Where it is, delay the answer, name concerns, and practice bounded disagreement. Where it is not, prioritize protection and support rather than idealized directness.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nStop escalating pressure. Ask for genuine consent, allow time, make refusal possible, and treat inconsistent follow-through as information that the agreement may not have been real.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nCorrect the false agreement promptly, acknowledge the practical impact, state the actual boundary or capacity, and renegotiate without blaming the other person for failing to infer the hidden no. Where coercion was present, accountability belongs primarily to the coercive conditions.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Interrogative Control, Micromanaging, Resentment, or Punitive Withdrawal. Often triggered by Dominance, Anger as Armor, Obligation Leverage, or Entitlement. Stories become “I must say yes to remain safe” and “I must apply more pressure to get a real answer.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using agreement to escape pressure rather than expressing a genuine choice?"},
  "PP-BLAME-SHIFTING": {"name":"Blame Shifting","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Projection; Rationalization; Defensiveness; Personalization; Denial; Minimizing.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler blames disloyalty; Warrior blames provocation; Sage blames others’ ignorance; Caregiver blames ingratitude; Rebel blames the system for every choice; Lover blames distance for boundary violations.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly prohibits assigning responsibility to victims for another person’s abuse, coercion, violence, deception, or retaliation.","First Letter":"B","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"State your contribution in one complete sentence before discussing anyone else’s behavior.","Core Logic":"If I can establish what made me do it, I may not have to face what I chose or caused.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Failed repair; recurring harm; distrust; escalation; moral confusion; weakened agency.","Core Fear":"Being wrong means being bad; accountability leads to humiliation or abandonment; mistakes are unsafe.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I only reacted because you pushed me.; This wouldn’t have happened if you had acted differently.; We both did things, so I shouldn’t be singled out.; The circumstances left me no choice.; Before we discuss me, we need to discuss what you did.; My behavior makes sense because of your behavior.","Protective Move":"Blame Shifting is the protective relocation of responsibility for one’s choices, impact, or obligations onto another person, circumstance, or provocation in order to avoid shame, consequences, or loss of self-image.","Pattern ID":"PP-BLAME-SHIFTING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief from shame appears as responsibility moves outward.","Freer Expression":"Context with ownership.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Context awareness; fairness; resistance to scapegoating; recognition of systems.","Observable Cues":"“I only did it because you…”; redirecting discussion to the other person’s faults; treating context as exoneration; demanding equal blame before acknowledging impact.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Keep the conversation narrow, refuse false equivalence, acknowledge relevant context, and return to the specific action and impact under discussion. May trigger Criticism, Contempt, Keeping Score, Hypervigilance, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Safety, Belonging, and Competence; avoids remorse, shame, limitation, repair obligations, and unequal responsibility.","Canonical Name":"Blame Shifting"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nBlame Shifting is the protective relocation of responsibility for one’s choices, impact, or obligations onto another person, circumstance, or provocation in order to avoid shame, consequences, or loss of self-image.\n## Domain\nAccountability, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nProjection; Rationalization; Defensiveness; Personalization; Denial\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I can establish what made me do it, I may not have to face what I chose or caused.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I only reacted because you pushed me.\n- This wouldn’t have happened if you had acted differently.\n- We both did things, so I shouldn’t be singled out.\n- The circumstances left me no choice.\n- Before we discuss me, we need to discuss what you did.\n- My behavior makes sense because of your behavior.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nImmediate focus on provocation; urgency to prove shared or external fault; difficulty staying with one’s own contribution; shame or threat when responsibility is named.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n“I only did it because you…”; redirecting discussion to the other person’s faults; treating context as exoneration; demanding equal blame before acknowledging impact.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Safety; Belonging; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConfrontation; consequences; criticism; exposure of inconsistency; relational hurt; public error.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBeing wrong means being bad; accountability leads to humiliation or abandonment; mistakes are unsafe.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nRemorse; shame; limitation; repair obligations; unequal responsibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler blames disloyalty; Warrior blames provocation; Sage blames others’ ignorance; Caregiver blames ingratitude; Rebel blames the system for every choice; Lover blames distance for boundary violations.\n## Pattern Flow\nImpact is named → worth or safety feels threatened → responsibility moves outward → temporary relief from shame appears → repair stalls and trust declines → future accountability feels even more dangerous.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensiveness; Rationalization; Projection; Minimizing; Denial.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nContext awareness; fairness; resistance to scapegoating; recognition of systems.\n## Current Cost\nFailed repair; recurring harm; distrust; escalation; moral confusion; weakened agency.\n## Freer Expression\nContext with ownership.\n## One Act of Volition\nState your contribution in one complete sentence before discussing anyone else’s behavior.\n## Mira Language\n“The context matters, and it may explain your reaction. It does not erase your agency. What part of the outcome belongs to you regardless of what the other person did?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did you choose? What impact remains yours to repair? Can responsibility be unequal without becoming total condemnation?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nMira must not impose responsibility on victims for another person’s abuse, coercion, violence, deception, or retaliation. Context can genuinely constrain agency.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated redirection away from one’s own contribution whenever accountability is raised.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate shame, separate responsibility from total badness, name context after ownership, and identify the repair obligation that remains yours.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nKeep the conversation narrow, refuse false equivalence, acknowledge relevant context, and return to the specific action and impact under discussion.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nRepair begins with unqualified ownership of the relevant act and impact. Context may follow, but it cannot be used to cancel responsibility or demand immediate mutual confession.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Criticism, Contempt, Keeping Score, Hypervigilance, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by accusation, shame, Personalization, or another person’s Blame Shifting. The loop becomes: “I must prove this is your fault” on both sides.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat remains mine to own even after every relevant context is named?"},
  "PP-BORROWED-CONVICTION": {"name":"Borrowed Conviction","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Certainty Seeking; Externalized Guidance; Identity Fusion; Approval Seeking; Moral Superiority; Demand Avoidance; Role Entrapment; Reassurance Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Sage—another’s knowledge substitutes for discernment; Ruler—authority supplies unquestioned order; Innocent—obedience preserves goodness; Orphan—group certainty prevents abandonment; Devotee—faith becomes surrendered agency; Lover—agreement becomes proof of loyalty.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because the source requires respectful distinction from legitimate expertise, communal belief, tradition, and authority rather than assigning one explicit controlled flag.","First Letter":"B","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"State one belief in your own words, including what evidence supports it and what remains uncertain.","Core Logic":"If I adopt their certainty, I do not have to risk discovering, choosing, or defending my own position.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Reduced agency; unstable beliefs; susceptibility to manipulation; moral outsourcing; shame around doubt; difficulty setting boundaries; confusion about one’s own values.","Core Fear":"Independent thought leads to rejection; uncertainty means incompetence or danger; belonging requires agreement; authorities know best; my own judgment cannot be trusted; dissent makes me disloyal or bad.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They know better than I do, so I should adopt their certainty.; Disagreement could cost me belonging.; I do not trust my own judgment enough to choose independently.; Their language feels safer than finding my own words.; Doubt may mean I am disloyal or bad.; I need the group’s conviction to quiet my uncertainty.","Protective Move":"Borrowed Conviction is the protective adoption of another person’s, group’s, authority’s, or doctrine’s certainty in order to avoid the vulnerability of uncertainty, self-authorship, disagreement, or independent moral discernment.","Pattern ID":"PP-BORROWED-CONVICTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Anxiety temporarily decreases when another source’s certainty is adopted.","Freer Expression":"Informed belonging with self-authored discernment.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Receptivity; trust; humility; devotion; willingness to learn; communal belonging.","Observable Cues":"Repeating conclusions without being able to explain one’s own reasoning; changing beliefs with the dominant relationship or group; deferring moral judgment to a leader, partner, expert, ideology, or community; suppressing doubts; using borrowed language as proof; treating disagreement as betrayal.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite reasoning without humiliation. Do not force immediate independence or attack the person’s community. Ask what they believe, what they fear would happen if they differed, and whether consent, dissent, and revision are genuinely available. May trigger Contrarianism, Emotional Distancing, Moral Superiority, or Adversarial Framing in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, safety, meaning, competence, approval, and identity; avoids uncertainty, responsibility, loneliness, moral complexity, disagreement, grief over separation from a group, and the possibility that admired authorities are limited or wrong.","Canonical Name":"Borrowed Conviction"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nBorrowed Conviction is the protective adoption of another person’s, group’s, authority’s, or doctrine’s certainty in order to avoid the vulnerability of uncertainty, self-authorship, disagreement, or independent moral discernment.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Meaning, and Certainty\n## Related Patterns\nCertainty Seeking; Externalized Guidance; Identity Fusion; Approval Seeking; Moral Superiority; Demand Avoidance; Role Entrapment\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I adopt their certainty, I do not have to risk discovering, choosing, or defending my own position.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They know better than I do, so I should adopt their certainty.\n- Disagreement could cost me belonging.\n- I do not trust my own judgment enough to choose independently.\n- Their language feels safer than finding my own words.\n- Doubt may mean I am disloyal or bad.\n- I need the group’s conviction to quiet my uncertainty.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when an authority supplies certainty; anxiety when asked for one’s own reasoning; guilt or disorientation when disagreeing; difficulty distinguishing conviction from belonging; rapid adoption of another’s language; fear that independent thought will threaten connection, goodness, or safety.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeating conclusions without being able to explain one’s own reasoning; changing beliefs with the dominant relationship or group; deferring moral judgment to a leader, partner, expert, ideology, or community; suppressing doubts; using borrowed language as proof; treating disagreement as betrayal.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; safety; meaning; competence; approval; identity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; moral conflict; entering a new group; charismatic authority; relational dependence; fear of exclusion; high-stakes decisions; shame about not knowing; pressure to declare allegiance.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIndependent thought leads to rejection; uncertainty means incompetence or danger; belonging requires agreement; authorities know best; my own judgment cannot be trusted; dissent makes me disloyal or bad.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; responsibility; loneliness; moral complexity; disagreement; grief over separation from a group; the possibility that admired authorities are limited or wrong.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage—another’s knowledge substitutes for discernment; Ruler—authority supplies unquestioned order; Innocent—obedience preserves goodness; Orphan—group certainty prevents abandonment; Devotee—faith becomes surrendered agency; Lover—agreement becomes proof of loyalty.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertainty or disagreement appears → belonging, competence, or safety feels threatened → another source’s certainty is adopted → anxiety temporarily decreases → personal discernment weakens → dependence on external conviction increases.\n## Often Appears With\nCertainty Seeking; Identity Fusion; Approval Seeking; Role Entrapment; Moral Superiority; Reassurance Seeking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReceptivity; trust; humility; devotion; willingness to learn; communal belonging.\n## Current Cost\nReduced agency; unstable beliefs; susceptibility to manipulation; moral outsourcing; shame around doubt; difficulty setting boundaries; confusion about one’s own values.\n## Freer Expression\nInformed belonging with self-authored discernment.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one belief in your own words, including what evidence supports it and what remains uncertain.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be drawing on someone you trust, which can be wise. I also wonder whether their certainty has replaced your own discernment. What do you believe in your own words, and what part are you still examining?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would disagreement threaten? Can you explain the belief without quoting the authority or group? Which part feels chosen, and which part feels required for belonging? What uncertainty are you allowed to keep?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLearning from experts, participating in a tradition, trusting legitimate authority, or sharing communal beliefs is not automatically borrowed conviction. The issue is loss of volitional discernment, not agreement itself. Mira must not demean religious, cultural, or political commitments.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated reliance on external certainty combined with suppressed doubt, inability to articulate personal reasoning, or fear-based conformity—not a single act of deference to expertise.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the need for guidance and belonging while reclaiming one step of authorship. Translate the belief into your own language, identify evidence and uncertainty, and notice whether disagreement is psychologically or relationally permitted.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite reasoning without humiliation. Do not force immediate independence or attack the person’s community. Ask what they believe, what they fear would happen if they differed, and whether consent, dissent, and revision are genuinely available.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where borrowed conviction was used to judge, pressure, recruit, silence, or abandon another person. Separate personal responsibility from “the group says,” name the impact, and demonstrate repair through independent reflection, truthful ownership, and respect for dissent.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Contrarianism, Emotional Distancing, Moral Superiority, or Adversarial Framing in others. Often triggered by certainty, charisma, exclusion threats, Identity Fusion, or Conditional Warmth. The reinforcing story may become: “You are unsafe unless you agree” on one side and “I must reject everything you believe to remain free” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere have I borrowed certainty because uncertainty, disagreement, or self-authorship felt too costly?"},
  "PP-BOUNDARY-COLLAPSE": {"name":"Boundary Collapse","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Fusion; Self-Erasure; Clinging; Overfunctioning; Relationship-Bound Worth.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — assumes total responsibility; Lover — equates intimacy with no separation; Mystic — spiritualizes boundarylessness; Everyman — erases difference to belong.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"B","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"State one limit without overexplaining or rescuing the other person from their reaction.","Core Logic":"Your needs, feelings, and choices are becoming mine to manage.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Resentment; dependency; intrusion; identity confusion.","Core Fear":"Love requires access; boundaries cause abandonment; my needs are dangerous.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I feel guilty saying no.; Your feelings are mine to fix.; If I set a limit, I’ll hurt the relationship.; I should make this easier for you, even if it costs me.; I don’t know where my responsibility ends.; Keeping closeness means staying available.","Protective Move":"Boundary Collapse is the protective blurring of where one person ends and another begins in order to preserve closeness, avoid conflict, or prevent rejection.","Pattern ID":"PP-BOUNDARY-COLLAPSE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary closeness returns.","Freer Expression":"Connection with clear edges.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Empathy; generosity; openness.","Observable Cues":"Over-sharing access; taking over responsibilities; permitting intrusions; treating privacy or separate choices as betrayal.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect stated limits, avoid using distress to override them, and clarify shared versus individual responsibility. May trigger Withdrawal, Secrecy, Defensiveness, Underfunctioning, or Counter-Control.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids difference, disappointment, helplessness, and individual responsibility.","Canonical Name":"Boundary Collapse"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nBoundary Collapse is the protective blurring of where one person ends and another begins in order to preserve closeness, avoid conflict, or prevent rejection.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nFusion; Self-Erasure; Clinging; Overfunctioning; Relationship-Bound Worth\n## Recognition Sentence\nYour needs, feelings, and choices are becoming mine to manage.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I feel guilty saying no.\n- Your feelings are mine to fix.\n- If I set a limit, I’ll hurt the relationship.\n- I should make this easier for you, even if it costs me.\n- I don’t know where my responsibility ends.\n- Keeping closeness means staying available.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nGuilt when saying no; confusion about one’s own preferences; responsibility for another’s mood; fear that limits will damage the bond.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOver-sharing access; taking over responsibilities; permitting intrusions; treating privacy or separate choices as betrayal.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nRequests for limits; another person’s distress; conflict; separateness.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove requires access; boundaries cause abandonment; my needs are dangerous.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDifference; disappointment; helplessness; individual responsibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — assumes total responsibility; Lover — equates intimacy with no separation; Mystic — spiritualizes boundarylessness; Everyman — erases difference to belong.\n## Pattern Flow\nSeparation appears → belonging feels threatened → boundaries blur → temporary closeness returns → resentment and confusion grow → clearer boundaries feel even more threatening.\n## Often Appears With\nFusion; Self-Erasure; Overfunctioning; Clinging.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEmpathy; generosity; openness.\n## Current Cost\nResentment; dependency; intrusion; identity confusion.\n## Freer Expression\nConnection with clear edges.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one limit without overexplaining or rescuing the other person from their reaction.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be carrying something that belongs partly—or entirely—to the other person. Where is your actual responsibility?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat is yours to feel or decide? What belongs to them? What limit would preserve both dignity and connection?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nMutual care and interdependence are not boundary collapse.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated loss of choice, privacy, responsibility, or identity across relational contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate empathy from ownership and practice one specific boundary.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect stated limits, avoid using distress to override them, and clarify shared versus individual responsibility.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where choice or privacy was overridden, restore authority, and create explicit agreements about access, responsibility, and consent.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Withdrawal, Secrecy, Defensiveness, Underfunctioning, or Counter-Control. Often triggered by distress, demands, or another person’s helplessness. The loop becomes: “I must manage everything to keep us safe” and “I cannot breathe unless I hide or resist.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere have care and responsibility become confused?"},
  "PP-BOUNDARY-RIGIDITY": {"name":"Boundary Rigidity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hyper-Independence; Emotional Distancing; Self-Isolation; Dominance; Conflict Avoidance; Suspicion; Emotional Withholding.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler—rules replace discernment; Warrior—every request becomes incursion; Hermit—distance becomes the only safety.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source explicitly protects strong, no-contact, disability, cultural, and safety-based boundaries from being misclassified.","First Letter":"B","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"State the non-negotiable need and one area where choice or negotiation remains possible.","Core Logic":"I am treating flexibility as surrender because I fear being overrun.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Lost intimacy; unnecessary conflict; inability to revise agreements; loneliness; reduced reciprocity.","Core Fear":"Flexibility leads to exploitation; no one will respect a softer boundary; closeness costs freedom.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Any flexibility will invite people to overrun me.; The rule has to be absolute to keep me safe.; Negotiation feels like the beginning of surrender.; Ordinary requests feel like violations.; I should end the discussion before the boundary weakens.; A softer limit will not be respected.","Protective Move":"Boundary Rigidity is the protective use of inflexible rules, distance, or categorical refusal to prevent intrusion, dependence, disappointment, or loss of control, even when context, trust, or mutuality would support a more responsive boundary.","Pattern ID":"PP-BOUNDARY-RIGIDITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate control and relief follow when the boundary hardens categorically.","Freer Expression":"Firm, responsive boundaries.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Self-respect; discernment; protection; clarity; sovereignty.","Observable Cues":"Blanket refusals; highly restrictive access; no-exception rules; ending discussion when nuance appears; treating requests as violations.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect the stated limit; do not pressure, shame, or test it. Where safe, ask whether any conditions for future flexibility exist and accept that the answer may be no. May trigger Clinging, Testing the Bond, Resentment, or Strategic Ambiguity.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, autonomy, agency, dignity, trust, rest, and integrity; avoids ambivalence, negotiation, dependence, grief, and uncertainty about trust.","Canonical Name":"Boundary Rigidity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nBoundary Rigidity is the protective use of inflexible rules, distance, or categorical refusal to prevent intrusion, dependence, disappointment, or loss of control, even when context, trust, or mutuality would support a more responsive boundary.\n## Domain\nAutonomy, Boundaries, and Protection\n## Related Patterns\nHyper-Independence; Emotional Distancing; Self-Isolation; Dominance; Conflict Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am treating flexibility as surrender because I fear being overrun.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Any flexibility will invite people to overrun me.\n- The rule has to be absolute to keep me safe.\n- Negotiation feels like the beginning of surrender.\n- Ordinary requests feel like violations.\n- I should end the discussion before the boundary weakens.\n- A softer limit will not be respected.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when rules are absolute; discomfort with negotiation; ordinary requests feel invasive; changing a boundary feels unsafe or weak.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nBlanket refusals; highly restrictive access; no-exception rules; ending discussion when nuance appears; treating requests as violations.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; autonomy; agency; dignity; trust; rest; integrity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPressure; repeated demands; prior enmeshment; unreliable people; guilt; dependence; requests for access or accommodation.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nFlexibility leads to exploitation; no one will respect a softer boundary; closeness costs freedom.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAmbivalence; negotiation; dependence; grief; uncertainty about trust.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler—rules replace discernment; Warrior—every request becomes incursion; Hermit—distance becomes the only safety.\n## Pattern Flow\nRequest or closeness appears → autonomy feels threatened → boundary hardens categorically → immediate control and relief → responsiveness and trust decline → isolation or conflict confirms that openness is unsafe.\n## Often Appears With\nHyper-Independence; Suspicion; Emotional Withholding; Self-Isolation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSelf-respect; discernment; protection; clarity; sovereignty.\n## Current Cost\nLost intimacy; unnecessary conflict; inability to revise agreements; loneliness; reduced reciprocity.\n## Freer Expression\nFirm, responsive boundaries.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the non-negotiable need and one area where choice or negotiation remains possible.\n## Mira Language\n“The boundary may be necessary. I also notice it has become categorical. Is the firmness protecting you from a present danger, or from the fear that any flexibility will erase your autonomy?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat must remain protected? What part could be responsive without becoming porous? Has this person shown capacity to respect a negotiated limit?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nStrong boundaries, no-contact decisions, privacy, disability accommodations, cultural boundaries, and safety-based refusal are not rigidity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated inflexibility across changing contexts, especially when negotiation itself is experienced as threat.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the need for protection, assess actual risk, distinguish the boundary’s purpose from its current form, and choose the least restrictive limit that still protects safety and dignity.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect the stated limit; do not pressure, shame, or test it. Where safe, ask whether any conditions for future flexibility exist and accept that the answer may be no.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where categorical distance erased another person’s voice or broke an agreement. Repair may involve clarifying the valid boundary, admitting unnecessary harshness, and establishing a transparent process for requests and revisions.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Testing the Bond, Resentment, or Strategic Ambiguity. Often triggered by Fusion, Possessiveness, repeated boundary crossing, or coercion. Stories become “Any opening will consume me” and “I must push harder to matter.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I confusing responsiveness with surrender?"},
  "PP-BUSYNESS-AS-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Busyness as Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Productivity-Bound Worth; Manufactured Urgency; Procrastination; Emotional Numbing; People-Pleasing; Rapid Project Proliferation.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver serves continuously; Ruler manufactures tasks; Warrior stays deployed; Creator starts more projects; Everyman remains indispensable.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"B","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Leave one unscheduled period and notice what arises before filling it.","Core Logic":"I am staying in motion because stillness might bring me into contact with what I have postponed.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Burnout; unavailable intimacy; neglected priorities; inability to receive care.","Core Fear":"I matter when useful; stillness is unsafe; needs make me dependent; if I stop, everything will fall apart.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I don’t have time to stop right now.; I’ll deal with that after I finish these tasks.; Staying busy keeps me from thinking about it.; There’s always something more urgent.; Rest makes me feel uneasy.; I should help with one more thing before I slow down.","Protective Move":"Busyness as Avoidance is the protective use of constant activity, productivity, helping, or urgency to prevent stillness, feeling, decision, intimacy, or contact with unmet needs.","Pattern ID":"PP-BUSYNESS-AS-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Relief and worth return as activity expands.","Freer Expression":"Purposeful action with restorative stillness.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Energy; contribution; initiative; service.","Observable Cues":"Overscheduling; volunteering automatically; creating urgent work; checking devices constantly; solving others’ problems instead of addressing one’s own.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not reward overfunctioning while complaining about absence; support realistic redistribution and protected rest. May trigger Clinging, Resentment, Underfunctioning, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Purpose, Autonomy, and Belonging; avoids emptiness, sorrow, fatigue, desire, conflict, and meaninglessness.","Canonical Name":"Busyness as Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nBusyness as Avoidance is the protective use of constant activity, productivity, helping, or urgency to prevent stillness, feeling, decision, intimacy, or contact with unmet needs.\n## Domain\nAvoidance and Emotional Escape\n## Related Patterns\nProductivity-Bound Worth; Manufactured Urgency; Procrastination; Emotional Numbing; People-Pleasing\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am staying in motion because stillness might bring me into contact with what I have postponed.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I don’t have time to stop right now.\n- I’ll deal with that after I finish these tasks.\n- Staying busy keeps me from thinking about it.\n- There’s always something more urgent.\n- Rest makes me feel uneasy.\n- I should help with one more thing before I slow down.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRestlessness during rest; guilt when inactive; relief from adding tasks; fear of empty time.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOverscheduling; volunteering automatically; creating urgent work; checking devices constantly; solving others’ problems instead of addressing one’s own.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Purpose; Autonomy; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nQuiet; grief; relational tension; uncertainty; loneliness; loss of role.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI matter when useful; stillness is unsafe; needs make me dependent; if I stop, everything will fall apart.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nEmptiness; sorrow; fatigue; desire; conflict; meaninglessness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver serves continuously; Ruler manufactures tasks; Warrior stays deployed; Creator starts more projects; Everyman remains indispensable.\n## Pattern Flow\nStillness approaches → unwanted feeling or need surfaces → activity expands → relief and worth return → depletion and avoidance deepen.\n## Often Appears With\nProductivity-Bound Worth; People-Pleasing; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEnergy; contribution; initiative; service.\n## Current Cost\nBurnout; unavailable intimacy; neglected priorities; inability to receive care.\n## Freer Expression\nPurposeful action with restorative stillness.\n## One Act of Volition\nLeave one unscheduled period and notice what arises before filling it.\n## Mira Language\n“Your activity may be serving more than productivity. What becomes audible when you stop?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhich task is truly necessary? What feeling arrives in open time? Who are you when not useful?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDemanding seasons, caregiving realities, poverty, and high workload are not automatically avoidance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nActivity repeatedly increases specifically when emotional contact, rest, or difficult choice approaches.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDistinguish required labor from protective motion and practice small periods of supported stillness.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not reward overfunctioning while complaining about absence; support realistic redistribution and protected rest.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where activity became unavailability or transferred intimacy and labor costs; create protected presence rather than promising vague future time.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Resentment, Underfunctioning, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by dependency, conflict, loss of control, or Productivity-Bound Worth.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I making too busy to hear?"},
  "PP-BUSYNESS-AS-IDENTITY": {"name":"Busyness as Identity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Productivity-Bound Worth; Busyness as Avoidance; Compulsive Achievement; Overfunctioning; Inability to Rest; Role Entrapment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver—being needed becomes identity; Creator—constant production substitutes for self-contact; Ruler—activity becomes proof of legitimacy; Warrior—motion prevents vulnerability.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because the source distinguishes genuine workload, caregiving, poverty, disability management, and cultural work ethic from the pattern.","First Letter":"B","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"Leave one block of time intentionally unfilled and notice what arises without converting it into a task.","Core Logic":"If I stop being busy, I may not know who I am or whether I still matter.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; shallow self-contact; neglected relationships; inability to rest; resentment; identity collapse when productivity changes.","Core Fear":"I matter when I am useful; rest is laziness; stillness exposes worthlessness; being needed protects me from abandonment.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If I stop moving, I may stop mattering.; Being needed is how I know who I am.; Rest feels like disappearance.; An empty hour makes me anxious about my worth.; I should create another task rather than sit with stillness.; My overload proves that I am useful and legitimate.","Protective Move":"Busyness as Identity is the protective construction of worth, legitimacy, or self-coherence through being constantly occupied, needed, or in motion, so that stillness does not expose uncertainty, emptiness, ordinariness, or unmet needs.","Pattern ID":"PP-BUSYNESS-AS-IDENTITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary significance and structure return when activity expands.","Freer Expression":"Purposeful engagement with an identity larger than output.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Energy; reliability; contribution; discipline; responsiveness.","Observable Cues":"Filling every open space; narrating overload as identity; creating work when none is required; refusing rest despite depletion; measuring self-worth by activity; becoming irritable when others slow down.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appreciate contribution without rewarding self-erasure. Avoid praising overload as virtue; invite rest and shared responsibility without shaming ambition. May trigger Resentment, Underfunctioning, Emotional Distancing, or Keeping Score in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects self-esteem, purpose, competence, and belonging; avoids emptiness, grief, loneliness, uncertainty, limitation, and desire without obligation.","Canonical Name":"Busyness as Identity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nBusyness as Identity is the protective construction of worth, legitimacy, or self-coherence through being constantly occupied, needed, or in motion, so that stillness does not expose uncertainty, emptiness, ordinariness, or unmet needs.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nProductivity-Bound Worth; Busyness as Avoidance; Compulsive Achievement; Overfunctioning; Inability to Rest; Role Entrapment\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I stop being busy, I may not know who I am or whether I still matter.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If I stop moving, I may stop mattering.\n- Being needed is how I know who I am.\n- Rest feels like disappearance.\n- An empty hour makes me anxious about my worth.\n- I should create another task rather than sit with stillness.\n- My overload proves that I am useful and legitimate.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUnease in unscheduled time; pride and exhaustion fused together; fear that rest will reveal emptiness or insignificance; difficulty sensing desire apart from obligation; relief when another task appears.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nFilling every open space; narrating overload as identity; creating work when none is required; refusing rest despite depletion; measuring self-worth by activity; becoming irritable when others slow down.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-esteem; purpose; competence; belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nEmpty time; transitions; retirement or reduced workload; finishing a major project; lack of recognition; loneliness; uncertainty about purpose.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI matter when I am useful; rest is laziness; stillness exposes worthlessness; being needed protects me from abandonment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nEmptiness; grief; loneliness; uncertainty; limitation; desire without obligation.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver—being needed becomes identity; Creator—constant production substitutes for self-contact; Ruler—activity becomes proof of legitimacy; Warrior—motion prevents vulnerability.\n## Pattern Flow\nOpen space or reduced demand appears → worth or identity feels uncertain → activity expands → temporary significance and structure return → exhaustion and disconnection accumulate → identity becomes even more dependent on busyness.\n## Often Appears With\nProductivity-Bound Worth; Overfunctioning; Compulsive Achievement; Inability to Rest; Role Entrapment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEnergy; reliability; contribution; discipline; responsiveness.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; shallow self-contact; neglected relationships; inability to rest; resentment; identity collapse when productivity changes.\n## Freer Expression\nPurposeful engagement with an identity larger than output.\n## One Act of Volition\nLeave one block of time intentionally unfilled and notice what arises without converting it into a task.\n## Mira Language\n“You describe being busy not only as something you do, but as proof that you matter. I wonder whether activity is carrying your identity right now. Does rest feel uncomfortable, or actually unsafe?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you fear you would feel if nothing needed you for an hour? Who are you when you are not producing? What kind of rest would not feel like disappearance?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nA genuinely demanding season, caregiving load, poverty, disability management, or cultural work ethic is not automatically this pattern.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated reliance on activity to stabilize worth or identity, especially when rest is available but experienced as threatening.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the real responsibilities, then separate them from identity maintenance. Practice brief, bounded stillness while affirming worth that does not depend on output.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAppreciate contribution without rewarding self-erasure. Avoid praising overload as virtue; invite rest and shared responsibility without shaming ambition.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where chronic busyness made others feel secondary, unavailable, or responsible for protecting you from rest. Rebuild trust through protected time, realistic commitments, and shared presence.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Resentment, Underfunctioning, Emotional Distancing, or Keeping Score in others. Often triggered by Dependency, Chaos, criticism, or another person’s unmet needs. The loop becomes: “I must carry everything” versus “There is no room for me unless I become another task.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere has being busy become evidence that I deserve to exist?"},
  "PP-CATASTROPHIZING": {"name":"Catastrophizing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hypervigilance; Emotional Reasoning; All-or-Nothing Thinking; Rumination; Procrastination; Reassurance Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver anticipates every harm; Ruler predicts system failure; Lover interprets distance as abandonment; Warrior prepares for total defeat; Sage constructs comprehensive risk narratives; Creator assumes one flaw ruins the work.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Medical Differential because the source explicitly directs appropriate professional, medical, legal, or safety consultation when stakes are high.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Name the worst case, best case, and most evidence-supported case, then act only on the present decision.","Core Logic":"If I imagine the worst first, it cannot catch me unprepared.","Safety Flags":["Medical Differential"],"Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Anxiety; paralysis; unnecessary conflict; premature withdrawal; overreaction; diminished hope.","Core Fear":"Bad outcomes happen quickly; optimism is dangerous; preparedness requires expecting the worst.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This could ruin everything.; I need to prepare for the worst right now.; One mistake could become a disaster.; If this goes badly, there may be no recovery.; I can’t ignore the worst-case scenario.; The fact that it’s possible makes it feel likely.","Protective Move":"Catastrophizing is the protective escalation of uncertainty into a severe or irreversible outcome so that the person can prepare emotionally, act early, or avoid being surprised.","Pattern ID":"PP-CATASTROPHIZING","Short-Term Payoff":"Urgency creates temporary certainty.","Freer Expression":"Proportionate foresight.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Foresight; contingency planning; seriousness; imagination; risk detection.","Observable Cues":"Treating setbacks as disasters; repeatedly forecasting collapse; abandoning plans because of possible failure; seeking urgent reassurance; overpreparing for low-probability outcomes.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Acknowledge the fear without confirming the forecast. Offer concrete evidence and next steps, and decline endless debate over increasingly remote scenarios. May trigger Minimizing, Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, or Micromanaging.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Trust, Competence, and Autonomy; avoids uncertainty, hope, disappointment, limited control, and gradual problem solving.","Canonical Name":"Catastrophizing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCatastrophizing is the protective escalation of uncertainty into a severe or irreversible outcome so that the person can prepare emotionally, act early, or avoid being surprised.\n## Domain\nThreat, Safety, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nHypervigilance; Emotional Reasoning; All-or-Nothing Thinking; Rumination; Procrastination\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I imagine the worst first, it cannot catch me unprepared.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This could ruin everything.\n- I need to prepare for the worst right now.\n- One mistake could become a disaster.\n- If this goes badly, there may be no recovery.\n- I can’t ignore the worst-case scenario.\n- The fact that it’s possible makes it feel likely.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRapid movement toward worst-case outcomes; urgency before evidence is complete; difficulty holding moderate possibilities; bodily alarm that makes the feared result feel probable.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTreating setbacks as disasters; repeatedly forecasting collapse; abandoning plans because of possible failure; seeking urgent reassurance; overpreparing for low-probability outcomes.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Trust; Competence; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguous symptoms; delayed responses; mistakes; financial uncertainty; evaluation; relationship distance; unfamiliar situations.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBad outcomes happen quickly; optimism is dangerous; preparedness requires expecting the worst.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; hope; disappointment; limited control; gradual problem solving.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver anticipates every harm; Ruler predicts system failure; Lover interprets distance as abandonment; Warrior prepares for total defeat; Sage constructs comprehensive risk narratives; Creator assumes one flaw ruins the work.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertainty appears → safety or competence feels threatened → the worst outcome is treated as likely → urgency creates temporary certainty → flexible action narrows → anxiety and avoidance increase.\n## Often Appears With\nHypervigilance; Rumination; Reassurance Seeking; All-or-Nothing Thinking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nForesight; contingency planning; seriousness; imagination; risk detection.\n## Current Cost\nAnxiety; paralysis; unnecessary conflict; premature withdrawal; overreaction; diminished hope.\n## Freer Expression\nProportionate foresight.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the worst case, best case, and most evidence-supported case, then act only on the present decision.\n## Mira Language\n“The feared outcome is possible, but your system appears to be treating possibility as probability. What does the available evidence support right now?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat intermediate outcomes are being skipped? What preparation is useful even if the worst case never occurs? What would change the probability estimate?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSerious risks should not be minimized. Mira should support appropriate professional, medical, legal, or safety consultation when stakes are high.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated escalation from ambiguity to severe outcome with urgency disproportionate to evidence.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate possibility from probability, regulate before planning, identify reversible next steps, and place contingency planning inside defined limits.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAcknowledge the fear without confirming the forecast. Offer concrete evidence and next steps, and decline endless debate over increasingly remote scenarios.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where catastrophic predictions created panic, pressure, accusation, or abandoned commitments. Correct exaggerated claims and establish a shared process for evaluating risk before acting.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Minimizing, Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, or Micromanaging. Often triggered by Denial, inconsistency, uncertainty, or another person’s lack of preparation. The loop becomes: “You do not take danger seriously” and “Nothing I say can calm the emergency.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat is possible, what is probable, and what actually needs my action now?"},
  "PP-CERTAINTY-SEEKING": {"name":"Certainty Seeking","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rumination; Reassurance Seeking; Hypervigilance; Catastrophizing; Perfectionism.","Archetypal Role":"Sage — knowledge must remove ambiguity. Ruler — plans must eliminate surprise. Innocent — safety requires guarantees. Lover — relationship must be continuously confirmed.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Set an information threshold and decide when it is reached.","Core Logic":"I cannot settle until the unknowable becomes certain.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Delay; exhaustion; strained reassurance loops; reduced self-trust.","Core Fear":"One wrong choice will be catastrophic; uncertainty means danger; I cannot trust myself to recover.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need one more piece of information before I decide.; I can’t relax until I know for sure.; What if I choose wrong and can’t recover?; I should keep checking until the risk disappears.; The answer still doesn’t feel certain enough.; I need a guarantee before I can move forward.","Protective Move":"Certainty Seeking attempts to eliminate ambiguity before acting, trusting, resting, or relating in order to prevent error, danger, regret, or loss of control.","Pattern ID":"PP-CERTAINTY-SEEKING","Short-Term Payoff":"Brief relief arrives when checking and analysis intensify.","Freer Expression":"Informed action under uncertainty.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Foresight; discernment; conscientiousness.","Observable Cues":"Asking the same question in new forms; exhaustive research; repeated confirmation; delaying action until risk disappears.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Give clear information once; avoid endless reassurance; support decision ownership. May trigger Withdrawal, Irritation, Defensiveness, or Micromanaging.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Competence, Autonomy, and Safety; avoids risk, regret, limitation, vulnerability, and responsibility for choosing.","Canonical Name":"Certainty Seeking"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCertainty Seeking attempts to eliminate ambiguity before acting, trusting, resting, or relating in order to prevent error, danger, regret, or loss of control.\n## Domain\nThreat Anticipation, Cognition, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nRumination; Reassurance Seeking; Hypervigilance; Catastrophizing; Perfectionism\n## Recognition Sentence\nI cannot settle until the unknowable becomes certain.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need one more piece of information before I decide.\n- I can’t relax until I know for sure.\n- What if I choose wrong and can’t recover?\n- I should keep checking until the risk disappears.\n- The answer still doesn’t feel certain enough.\n- I need a guarantee before I can move forward.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRepeated checking; inability to stop researching; temporary relief that quickly fades; decisions reopen.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAsking the same question in new forms; exhaustive research; repeated confirmation; delaying action until risk disappears.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Competence; Autonomy; Safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDecisions; health uncertainty; relationship ambiguity; financial risk; incomplete information.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nOne wrong choice will be catastrophic; uncertainty means danger; I cannot trust myself to recover.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nRisk; regret; limitation; vulnerability; responsibility for choosing.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage — knowledge must remove ambiguity. Ruler — plans must eliminate surprise. Innocent — safety requires guarantees. Lover — relationship must be continuously confirmed.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguity appears → trust feels threatened → checking and analysis intensify → brief relief arrives → uncertainty returns stronger and self-trust weakens.\n## Often Appears With\nRumination; Reassurance Seeking; Hypervigilance; Perfectionism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nForesight; discernment; conscientiousness.\n## Current Cost\nDelay; exhaustion; strained reassurance loops; reduced self-trust.\n## Freer Expression\nInformed action under uncertainty.\n## One Act of Volition\nSet an information threshold and decide when it is reached.\n## Mira Language\n“Are you gathering information that could change the decision, or asking uncertainty to disappear?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat amount of uncertainty is unavoidable? What would help you trust your capacity to respond later?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDue diligence and safety planning are not certainty seeking.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated checking or delay beyond meaningful informational value.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReplace guarantees with a contingency plan and a stopping rule.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nGive clear information once; avoid endless reassurance; support decision ownership.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where repeated questioning, checking, or delay burdened others; agree on information boundaries and decision ownership.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Withdrawal, Irritation, Defensiveness, or Micromanaging. Often triggered by inconsistency, ambiguity, or unreliable communication. The loop becomes “I must keep checking because you are not clear” versus “Nothing I say will ever settle this.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat uncertainty am I asking certainty to rescue me from?"},
  "PP-CHAMELEON-IDENTITY": {"name":"Chameleon Identity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Masking; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Image Management; Identity Fusion; Strategic Ambiguity.","Archetypal Role":"Lover—merging with the beloved’s tastes; Diplomat—becoming acceptable to every side; Trickster—shifting identities to remain unpinned; Orphan—adapting to survive each group.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because the source explicitly distinguishes code-switching, cultural adaptation, professional flexibility, and safety-based concealment from the pattern.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"State one genuine preference before learning what the group prefers.","Core Logic":"I become who this room needs so I will not be excluded or exposed.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Identity confusion; inconsistent commitments; mistrust; exhaustion; fear of being known; difficulty forming reciprocal intimacy.","Core Fear":"My real self is not welcome; belonging requires adaptation; difference invites punishment; clarity makes rejection easier.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to become who this room will accept.; My real preference should wait until I know theirs.; Difference may cost me belonging.; I should mirror their language so I remain safe.; If these social worlds overlap, I may be exposed.; It is easier to adapt than risk being clearly known.","Protective Move":"Chameleon Identity is the protective reshaping of one’s presented preferences, values, style, emotional tone, or self-description across contexts in order to secure belonging, reduce conflict, avoid rejection, or remain difficult to define and therefore difficult to reject.","Pattern ID":"PP-CHAMELEON-IDENTITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Acceptance or reduced friction brings relief when the presented self reshapes.","Freer Expression":"Adaptability without self-abandonment.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Adaptability; empathy; social intelligence; perspective-taking; cultural fluency.","Observable Cues":"Adopting others’ language or values; changing style across groups; contradicting earlier positions to fit the room; concealing stable preferences; difficulty making identity-based commitments.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite honest difference without punishing it. Do not demand immediate disclosure where safety has not been established. May trigger Suspicion, Interrogative Control, Testing the Bond, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, safety, self-esteem, and autonomy; avoids separateness, disapproval, loneliness, conflict, and responsibility for choosing.","Canonical Name":"Chameleon Identity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nChameleon Identity is the protective reshaping of one’s presented preferences, values, style, emotional tone, or self-description across contexts in order to secure belonging, reduce conflict, avoid rejection, or remain difficult to define and therefore difficult to reject.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Image, and Significance\n## Related Patterns\nMasking; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Image Management; Identity Fusion; Strategic Ambiguity\n## Recognition Sentence\nI become who this room needs so I will not be excluded or exposed.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to become who this room will accept.\n- My real preference should wait until I know theirs.\n- Difference may cost me belonging.\n- I should mirror their language so I remain safe.\n- If these social worlds overlap, I may be exposed.\n- It is easier to adapt than risk being clearly known.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRapid shifts in preference or tone; uncertainty about authentic desire; hyper-attunement to social cues; relief when mirroring creates acceptance; anxiety when two social worlds overlap.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAdopting others’ language or values; changing style across groups; contradicting earlier positions to fit the room; concealing stable preferences; difficulty making identity-based commitments.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; safety; self-esteem; autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nNew groups; status differences; potential rejection; conflict; unfamiliar norms; overlapping relationships; questions requiring a clear personal position.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy real self is not welcome; belonging requires adaptation; difference invites punishment; clarity makes rejection easier.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nSeparateness; disapproval; loneliness; conflict; responsibility for choosing.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover—merging with the beloved’s tastes; Diplomat—becoming acceptable to every side; Trickster—shifting identities to remain unpinned; Orphan—adapting to survive each group.\n## Pattern Flow\nA social context presents expectations → belonging or safety feels uncertain → the presented self reshapes → acceptance or reduced friction brings relief → authentic preferences become harder to access → future adaptation becomes more necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nPeople-Pleasing; Masking; Strategic Ambiguity; Self-Erasure; Identity Fusion.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAdaptability; empathy; social intelligence; perspective-taking; cultural fluency.\n## Current Cost\nIdentity confusion; inconsistent commitments; mistrust; exhaustion; fear of being known; difficulty forming reciprocal intimacy.\n## Freer Expression\nAdaptability without self-abandonment.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one genuine preference before learning what the group prefers.\n## Mira Language\n“You seem highly able to read the room, but your own position becomes harder to hear once other people’s expectations enter. Is adaptation helping you participate, or replacing you?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat remains true across settings? What would you say before scanning the room? Which differences feel safest to reveal first?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCode-switching, cultural adaptation, professional role flexibility, and safety-based concealment are not automatically pathological.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated identity shifts that create self-loss, contradictory commitments, or fear of contexts colliding—not ordinary social flexibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSlow the social scan, identify one stable value or preference, and allow adaptation around that anchor rather than instead of it.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite honest difference without punishing it. Do not demand immediate disclosure where safety has not been established.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where adaptation became deception, false agreement, or inconsistent loyalty. Clarify what was genuine, what was protective, and what commitments can truthfully be made now.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Interrogative Control, Testing the Bond, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by Dominance, criticism, volatility, or Conditional Warmth. The loop becomes: “I must adapt to stay” versus “I cannot trust who you really are.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I adapting around my identity, and where am I adapting instead of having one?"},
  "PP-CHARM-AS-PROTECTION": {"name":"Charm as Protection","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Image Management; Humor Deflection; Approval Seeking; Seduction as Validation; Deflection; Selective Accountability.","Archetypal Role":"Lover—attraction secures safety; Jester—humor dissolves accountability; Magician—social influence changes the emotional field; Diplomat—pleasing everyone prevents exclusion.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from user-provided full canonical source. Obvious spacing corruption repaired. Gift Trapped Inside, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source. Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Clinical Term remains empty because no explicit source content was supplied. Crosswalk Terms remains empty pending reconciliation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Stay plain and direct for one difficult sentence without softening it through humor, flattery, or performance.","Core Logic":"If I can make them like me, I may not have to face what they might see, ask, or require.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Shallow intimacy; mistrust; delayed accountability; exhaustion; dependence on audience response; difficulty being ordinary.","Core Fear":"Likability keeps me safe; people forgive what they enjoy; my unperformed self is insufficient; direct accountability risks rejection.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If I can make them like me, this may go away.; A joke could lower the tension.; I need to be especially charming right now.; If they enjoy me, they may not press the issue.; Ordinary presence may not be enough.; I can keep the connection if I stay appealing.","Protective Move":"Uses warmth, humor, charisma, attractiveness, helpfulness, or social ease to secure approval, lower scrutiny, redirect discomfort, avoid accountability, or prevent deeper vulnerability.","Pattern ID":"PP-CHARM-AS-PROTECTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Tension lowers and acceptance returns when charm intensifies.","Freer Expression":"Warmth without evasion.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Warmth; humor; charisma; social attunement; hospitality.","Observable Cues":"Flattering; joking during accountability; rapid intimacy; performative warmth; redirecting criticism through charisma; becoming unusually helpful when consequences approach.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Receive warmth without abandoning the original question. May trigger Suspicion, Interrogative Control, Cynicism, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects approval, belonging, self-esteem, and safety; avoids shame, ordinariness, conflict, grief, helplessness, and sustained scrutiny.","Canonical Name":"Charm as Protection"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCharm as Protection is the strategic or automatic use of warmth, humor, charisma, attractiveness, helpfulness, or social ease to secure approval, lower scrutiny, redirect discomfort, avoid accountability, or prevent deeper vulnerability.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nImage Management; Humor Deflection; Approval Seeking; Seduction as Validation; Deflection; Selective Accountability\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I can make them like me, I may not have to face what they might see, ask, or require.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If I can make them like me, this may go away.\n- A joke could lower the tension.\n- I need to be especially charming right now.\n- If they enjoy me, they may not press the issue.\n- Ordinary presence may not be enough.\n- I can keep the connection if I stay appealing.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrge to become especially engaging when scrutiny rises; relief when tension turns into laughter; fear that ordinary presence will not be enough; attention moving from truth to impression.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nFlattering; joking during accountability; rapid intimacy; performative warmth; redirecting criticism through charisma; becoming unusually helpful when consequences approach.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nApproval; Belonging; Self-Esteem; Safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCriticism; unfamiliar groups; authority; potential consequences; social competition; requests for emotional depth; fear of being ordinary.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLikability keeps me safe; people forgive what they enjoy; my unperformed self is insufficient; direct accountability risks rejection.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; ordinariness; conflict; grief; helplessness; sustained scrutiny.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover—attraction secures safety; Jester—humor dissolves accountability; Magician—social influence changes the emotional field; Diplomat—pleasing everyone prevents exclusion.\n## Pattern Flow\nScrutiny or relational risk rises → approval or safety feels threatened → charm intensifies → tension lowers and acceptance returns → accountability or intimacy is bypassed → reliance on performance grows.\n## Often Appears With\nImage Management; Humor Deflection; Deflection; Approval Seeking; Selective Accountability.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nWarmth; humor; charisma; social attunement; hospitality.\n## Current Cost\nShallow intimacy; mistrust; delayed accountability; exhaustion; dependence on audience response; difficulty being ordinary.\n## Freer Expression\nWarmth without evasion.\n## One Act of Volition\nStay plain and direct for one difficult sentence without softening it through humor, flattery, or performance.\n## Mira Language\n“Your warmth may be real. I also notice it becomes strongest when the conversation approaches discomfort or accountability. Is charm helping connection, or helping you escape the moment?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat might happen if you were not especially likable right now? What truth needs to remain after the charm is removed? Can warmth accompany accountability instead of replacing it?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCharisma, humor, hospitality, flirting, or cultural expressiveness are not automatically defensive.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of social appeal specifically when scrutiny, conflict, or vulnerability increases.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nKeep the warmth, but name the avoided truth first. Let likability become optional rather than protective armor.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nReceive warmth without abandoning the original question. Stay kind, specific, and anchored to impact.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where charm redirected accountability or created false intimacy. Return to the concrete issue, answer directly, and demonstrate change without relying on persuasion.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Interrogative Control, Cynicism, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by criticism, shame, authority, or another person’s disappointment. The loop becomes: “I must win you over” versus “I must resist being manipulated.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere does my warmth deepen truth, and where does it help me escape it?"},
  "PP-CLINGING": {"name":"Clinging","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Fusion; Compulsive Contact; Testing the Bond; Relationship-Bound Worth; Boundary Collapse; Idealization.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — tightens intimacy; Caregiver — makes oneself indispensable; Innocent — seeks certainty that the bond is safe; Everyman — suppresses difference to remain included.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Delay one reassurance-seeking action and name the underlying fear directly.","Core Logic":"If I loosen my hold, I may lose the bond.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Pressure; dependency; loss of self; partner withdrawal.","Core Fear":"People leave; distance means rejection; I must hold tightly to remain chosen.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to hear from you right now.; If I give you space, I might lose you.; Why haven’t you answered yet?; I can’t settle until we reconnect.; Please tell me we’re okay again.; Distance feels like abandonment.","Protective Move":"Clinging is the protective attempt to prevent abandonment by tightening contact, proximity, reassurance, or emotional dependence when distance feels dangerous.","Pattern ID":"PP-CLINGING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary reassurance arrives.","Freer Expression":"Secure closeness with room to breathe.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Devotion; loyalty; relational sensitivity.","Observable Cues":"Repeated checking; resisting separation; escalating bids for reassurance; abandoning other priorities to preserve contact.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer clear, bounded reassurance and dependable re-engagement without surrendering autonomy or rewarding escalation. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Stonewalling, Avoidant Independence, or Defensiveness.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids grief, uncertainty, solitude, and separateness.","Canonical Name":"Clinging"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nClinging is the protective attempt to prevent abandonment by tightening contact, proximity, reassurance, or emotional dependence when distance feels dangerous.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nFusion; Compulsive Contact; Testing the Bond; Relationship-Bound Worth; Boundary Collapse\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I loosen my hold, I may lose the bond.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to hear from you right now.\n- If I give you space, I might lose you.\n- Why haven’t you answered yet?\n- I can’t settle until we reconnect.\n- Please tell me we’re okay again.\n- Distance feels like abandonment.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPanic at distance; urgency to reconnect; difficulty tolerating delayed response; relief only when closeness is restored.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeated checking; resisting separation; escalating bids for reassurance; abandoning other priorities to preserve contact.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDelayed replies; conflict; changed plans; emotional distance; separation.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nPeople leave; distance means rejection; I must hold tightly to remain chosen.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; uncertainty; solitude; separateness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — tightens intimacy; Caregiver — makes oneself indispensable; Innocent — seeks certainty that the bond is safe; Everyman — suppresses difference to remain included.\n## Pattern Flow\nDistance appears → belonging feels threatened → pursuit intensifies → temporary reassurance arrives → autonomy and trust weaken → future distance feels more dangerous.\n## Often Appears With\nFusion; Testing the Bond; Compulsive Contact; Idealization.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDevotion; loyalty; relational sensitivity.\n## Current Cost\nPressure; dependency; loss of self; partner withdrawal.\n## Freer Expression\nSecure closeness with room to breathe.\n## One Act of Volition\nDelay one reassurance-seeking action and name the underlying fear directly.\n## Mira Language\n“I notice the distance feels urgent enough that you are trying to close it immediately. Is the contact request about connection, or about making the fear stop?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does distance seem to mean? What reassurance is actually needed? What part of you remains intact while apart?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDesire for closeness after rupture is not automatically clinging.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated pursuit that narrows autonomy or escalates when reassurance is incomplete.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate before reaching, name the fear, and request specific reassurance without demanding constant access.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer clear, bounded reassurance and dependable re-engagement without surrendering autonomy or rewarding escalation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge pressure, monitoring, or loss of space; restore choice; agree on contact expectations and a reliable reconnection plan.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Stonewalling, Avoidant Independence, or Defensiveness. Often triggered by withdrawal, inconsistency, secrecy, or delayed response. The loop becomes: “I must pursue to keep us” and “I must escape to remain myself.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I gripping the bond instead of trusting it?"},
  "PP-COMMITMENT-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Commitment Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Strategic Ambiguity; Demand Avoidance; Preemptive Detachment; Risk Avoidance; Indecision; Permanent Optionality.","Archetypal Role":"Explorer—freedom becomes permanent departure; Lover—intimacy remains undefined; Rebel—commitment is equated with captivity; Creator—projects remain open to avoid final form.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing repaired. Gift Trapped Inside, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source. Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty for documented source/reconciliation reasons.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Make one bounded commitment with a clear review point instead of preserving indefinite optionality.","Core Logic":"If I keep every door open, no choice can trap, define, or disappoint me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Stalled relationships and projects; mistrust; missed opportunities; shallow investment; chronic ambivalence; loneliness.","Core Fear":"Commitment means losing myself; dependence becomes control; choosing one path means grieving every other; promises become traps.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to keep every door open.; A commitment could trap me.; I want connection without losing freedom.; I should wait a little longer before deciding.; Choosing one path means losing all the others.; If I stay undefined, I can still escape.","Protective Move":"Preserves options, distance, reversibility, or escape routes when commitment is experienced as a threat to autonomy, identity, safety, future possibility, or protection from regret.","Pattern ID":"PP-COMMITMENT-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Delay, ambiguity, or distance temporarily restores freedom.","Freer Expression":"Chosen commitment with retained selfhood.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Freedom; discernment; flexibility; independence; respect for consequence.","Observable Cues":"Delaying decisions after sufficient information; maintaining ambiguous relationships; resisting labels or contracts; withdrawing as expectations grow; repeatedly reopening settled choices.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask for clarity without coercion; state what level of commitment is required. May trigger Testing the Bond, Reassurance Seeking, Interrogative Control, or Punitive Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects autonomy, safety, identity, and trust; avoids grief over excluded alternatives, responsibility, vulnerability, limitation, regret, and mutual dependence.","Canonical Name":"Commitment Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCommitment Avoidance is the protective preservation of options, distance, reversibility, or escape routes when commitment is experienced as a threat to autonomy, identity, safety, future possibility, or protection from regret.\n## Domain\nAutonomy, Choice, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nStrategic Ambiguity; Demand Avoidance; Preemptive Detachment; Risk Avoidance; Indecision; Permanent Optionality\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I keep every door open, no choice can trap, define, or disappoint me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to keep every door open.\n- A commitment could trap me.\n- I want connection without losing freedom.\n- I should wait a little longer before deciding.\n- Choosing one path means losing all the others.\n- If I stay undefined, I can still escape.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief from postponement; anxiety when choices become binding; fixation on lost alternatives; desire for connection without obligation; fear that commitment will erase freedom or identity.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDelaying decisions after sufficient information; maintaining ambiguous relationships; resisting labels or contracts; withdrawing as expectations grow; repeatedly reopening settled choices.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Safety; Identity; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nExclusivity; contracts; labels; future planning; expectations; irreversible decisions; another person’s dependence; prior experiences of entrapment.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nCommitment means losing myself; dependence becomes control; choosing one path means grieving every other; promises become traps.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief over excluded alternatives; responsibility; vulnerability; limitation; regret; mutual dependence.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nExplorer—freedom becomes permanent departure; Lover—intimacy remains undefined; Rebel—commitment is equated with captivity; Creator—projects remain open to avoid final form.\n## Pattern Flow\nA choice becomes binding → autonomy or future possibility feels threatened → ambiguity, delay, or distance increases → freedom returns temporarily → trust and momentum erode → commitment feels even more dangerous.\n## Often Appears With\nStrategic Ambiguity; Preemptive Detachment; Demand Avoidance; Indecision; Risk Avoidance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nFreedom; discernment; flexibility; independence; respect for consequence.\n## Current Cost\nStalled relationships and projects; mistrust; missed opportunities; shallow investment; chronic ambivalence; loneliness.\n## Freer Expression\nChosen commitment with retained selfhood.\n## One Act of Volition\nMake one bounded commitment with a clear review point instead of preserving indefinite optionality.\n## Mira Language\n“You may genuinely need more information. I also notice that keeping the decision open repeatedly restores relief. Is the uncertainty about the choice, or about what commitment would take from you?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you believe commitment would erase? Which freedom must remain protected inside the commitment? What grief comes with choosing one path?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCareful deliberation, nontraditional relationships, changing one’s mind, or refusing coercive commitments are not automatically avoidance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated preservation of optionality after adequate clarity, especially when commitment consistently triggers distancing, ambiguity, or escape behavior.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIdentify the autonomy need directly, negotiate its protection, and choose a bounded commitment rather than relying on ambiguity for freedom.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk for clarity without coercion. State what level of commitment you require and what you will do if it is unavailable.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where ambiguity, delay, or partial investment kept others attached without informed consent. Clarify present willingness, release promises that cannot be made, and respect the other person’s right to leave.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Testing the Bond, Reassurance Seeking, Interrogative Control, or Punitive Withdrawal. Often triggered by Possessiveness, pressure, instability, or demands that collapse autonomy. The loop becomes: “Commitment will trap me” versus “Ambiguity means I am unsafe.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat freedom am I trying to preserve, and can it be protected without keeping everything unresolved?"},
  "PP-COMPARISON": {"name":"Comparison","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Approval Seeking; Envy; Grandiosity; Self-Deprecation; Perfectionism; Devaluation.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior — life becomes competition. Creator — originality becomes ranking. Ruler — status determines legitimacy. Everyman — belonging requires keeping pace. Sage — knowledge becomes hierarchy.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Translate one comparison into information: “What quality do I admire, and what is one value-aligned step available in my context?”","Core Logic":"I am using someone else’s life as the ruler for my worth.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Envy; shame; imitation; status anxiety; loss of gratitude and authentic direction.","Core Fear":"Worth is ranked; there is limited room to matter; being behind means being lesser; identity must be proven relative to others.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Their success makes me feel behind.; I need to know where I rank.; If they are ahead, I must be lesser.; I should be where they are by now.; Their achievement proves I’m not doing enough.; I can’t enjoy my progress while someone else is doing better.","Protective Move":"Comparison is the protective measurement of worth, adequacy, progress, or belonging through another person’s apparent position rather than through one’s own values and context.","Pattern ID":"PP-COMPARISON","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary orientation or motivation appears when ranking begins.","Freer Expression":"Inspiration without self-erasure.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Benchmarking; aspiration; discernment; awareness of possibility; motivation.","Observable Cues":"Checking metrics compulsively; minimizing one’s achievements; boasting after feeling inferior; copying another’s path; withdrawing from peers who succeed.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Avoid competitive reassurance or dismissing the comparison. Help identify the value underneath it without joining the ranking. May trigger Grandiosity, Concealment, Competition, or Devaluation.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Belonging, and Purpose; avoids individual pace, grief over choices, uncertainty about values, ordinary limitation, and admiration without possession.","Canonical Name":"Comparison"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nComparison is the protective measurement of worth, adequacy, progress, or belonging through another person’s apparent position rather than through one’s own values and context.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nApproval Seeking; Envy; Grandiosity; Self-Deprecation; Perfectionism\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am using someone else’s life as the ruler for my worth.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Their success makes me feel behind.\n- I need to know where I rank.\n- If they are ahead, I must be lesser.\n- I should be where they are by now.\n- Their achievement proves I’m not doing enough.\n- I can’t enjoy my progress while someone else is doing better.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRapid ranking; shame or inflation after seeing others’ success; difficulty enjoying one’s own progress; selective attention to status markers.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nChecking metrics compulsively; minimizing one’s achievements; boasting after feeling inferior; copying another’s path; withdrawing from peers who succeed.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Belonging; Purpose.\n## Usually Triggered By\nSocial media; peers’ achievements; reunions; performance metrics; aging; career transitions; scarcity.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nWorth is ranked; there is limited room to matter; being behind means being lesser; identity must be proven relative to others.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nIndividual pace; grief over choices; uncertainty about values; ordinary limitation; admiration without possession.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior — life becomes competition. Creator — originality becomes ranking. Ruler — status determines legitimacy. Everyman — belonging requires keeping pace. Sage — knowledge becomes hierarchy.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother person becomes visible → worth or competence feels uncertain → ranking begins → temporary orientation or motivation appears → shame, envy, or inflation follows → self-directed development weakens.\n## Often Appears With\nGrandiosity; Perfectionism; Self-Deprecation; Approval Seeking; Devaluation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nBenchmarking; aspiration; discernment; awareness of possibility; motivation.\n## Current Cost\nEnvy; shame; imitation; status anxiety; loss of gratitude and authentic direction.\n## Freer Expression\nInspiration without self-erasure.\n## One Act of Volition\nTranslate one comparison into information: “What quality do I admire, and what is one value-aligned step available in my context?”\n## Mira Language\n“Their life may be showing you something you value, but it is not a verdict on your worth. What information is inside the comparison?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you ranking? Which contexts are being ignored? Is this admiration, grief, envy, or a call toward your own value?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nMarket analysis, performance benchmarking, and learning from peers are not automatically protective Comparison.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated worth regulation through ranking that produces shame, inflation, imitation, or avoidance.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRestore context, name the admired quality, grieve real differences where needed, and return to personally chosen measures of progress.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAvoid competitive reassurance or dismissing the comparison. Help identify the value underneath it without joining the ranking.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where comparison led to envy, dismissal, competition, or diminished celebration. Repair by restoring the other person’s distinct achievement and one’s own separate path.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Grandiosity, Concealment, Competition, or Devaluation. Often triggered by boasting, exclusion, status emphasis, or one’s own insecurity. The loop becomes “Your success makes me lesser” and “I must display more success to remain visible.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat is comparison trying to tell me about my values without being allowed to define my worth?"},
  "PP-COMPARTMENTALIZING": {"name":"Compartmentalizing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Numbing; Denial; Intellectualizing; Image Management; Rationalization.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler separates function from feeling; Caregiver hides resentment from service; Lover separates devotion from dissatisfaction; Rebel isolates consequences from freedom; Sage divides knowledge from participation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Name two truths from separate compartments in the same sentence.","Core Logic":"I am keeping these parts separate because bringing them together would require a difficult truth or choice.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Fragmentation; ethical inconsistency; delayed consequences; intimacy barriers.","Core Fear":"Integration would cost belonging; I cannot survive all these truths together; each role requires a different self.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I keep that part of my life separate.; Those two realities don’t need to touch.; I’m different in each context.; I can deal with this as long as I don’t connect it to everything else.; Bringing these parts together would create a problem.; What happens there stays there.","Protective Move":"Compartmentalizing is the protective separation of roles, memories, feelings, values, or relationships into distinct mental spaces so conflict between them does not have to be faced all at once.","Pattern ID":"PP-COMPARTMENTALIZING","Short-Term Payoff":"Separation is reinforced and functioning continues.","Freer Expression":"Integration without collapse.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Focus; role clarity; crisis containment; cognitive organization.","Observable Cues":"Strict separation of work and home realities; inconsistent values across contexts; avoiding cross-context conversations; acting as though one area has no effect on another.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Name inconsistencies concretely without demanding total disclosure or collapsing legitimate boundaries. May trigger Suspicion, Monitoring, Contempt, or Withdrawal in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Belonging, Autonomy, and Trust; avoids guilt, contradiction, grief, accountability, and impossible choices.","Canonical Name":"Compartmentalizing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCompartmentalizing is the protective separation of roles, memories, feelings, values, or relationships into distinct mental spaces so conflict between them does not have to be faced all at once.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Numbing; Denial; Intellectualizing; Image Management; Rationalization\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am keeping these parts separate because bringing them together would require a difficult truth or choice.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I keep that part of my life separate.\n- Those two realities don’t need to touch.\n- I’m different in each context.\n- I can deal with this as long as I don’t connect it to everything else.\n- Bringing these parts together would create a problem.\n- What happens there stays there.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDifferent selves in different settings; difficulty holding conflicting truths; emotional spillover only when compartments fail.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nStrict separation of work and home realities; inconsistent values across contexts; avoiding cross-context conversations; acting as though one area has no effect on another.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Belonging; Autonomy; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nRole conflict; moral conflict; incompatible demands; shame; overload.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIntegration would cost belonging; I cannot survive all these truths together; each role requires a different self.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGuilt; contradiction; grief; accountability; impossible choices.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler separates function from feeling; Caregiver hides resentment from service; Lover separates devotion from dissatisfaction; Rebel isolates consequences from freedom; Sage divides knowledge from participation.\n## Pattern Flow\nConflicting realities meet → internal strain rises → separation is reinforced → functioning continues → contradictions and consequences accumulate.\n## Often Appears With\nDenial; Rationalization; Image Management; Emotional Numbing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nFocus; role clarity; crisis containment; cognitive organization.\n## Current Cost\nFragmentation; ethical inconsistency; delayed consequences; intimacy barriers.\n## Freer Expression\nIntegration without collapse.\n## One Act of Volition\nName two truths from separate compartments in the same sentence.\n## Mira Language\n“These realities may have been kept apart so you could function. What changes when we hold both at once?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhich roles cannot currently speak to each other? What choice would integration require? What are you afraid would collapse?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nHealthy privacy, role boundaries, and focused attention are not pathological compartmentalization.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated separation that prevents necessary accountability, emotional integration, or coherent choice.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIntegrate gradually and identify the value or consequence that crosses compartments.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nName inconsistencies concretely without demanding total disclosure or collapsing legitimate boundaries.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where separation concealed impact or contradictory commitments; restore a coherent account and make choices that can remain true across contexts.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Monitoring, Contempt, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by incompatible expectations, shame, or threatened identity.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat truths have I kept apart because together they would require change?"},
  "PP-COMPULSIVE-ACHIEVEMENT": {"name":"Compulsive Achievement","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Productivity-Bound Worth; Perfectionism; Comparison; Approval Seeking; Busyness as Avoidance; Rapid Project Proliferation.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior — every horizon becomes another campaign. Creator — output replaces creation. Ruler — achievement becomes control. Caregiver — usefulness becomes worth.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Complete one meaningful task without immediately replacing it with a new demand.","Core Logic":"I need another accomplishment before I can feel enough.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Burnout; neglected relationships; fragile identity; inability to rest; chronic insufficiency.","Core Fear":"I matter when I perform; security must be earned repeatedly; stopping invites worthlessness.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need another accomplishment before I can feel enough.; Rest has to wait until I prove myself again.; The last success no longer counts.; I should turn this into another measurable goal.; If I stop achieving, I may become invisible or worthless.; Completion feels like pressure to raise the bar again.","Protective Move":"Compulsive Achievement is the protective pursuit of continual accomplishment to secure worth, safety, recognition, or relief, making the next achievement necessary rather than freely chosen.","Pattern ID":"PP-COMPULSIVE-ACHIEVEMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Achievement brings brief relief before the baseline resets upward.","Freer Expression":"Achievement as expression, not proof.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Ambition; discipline; persistence; mastery.","Observable Cues":"Chronic goal escalation; inability to celebrate; overloading commitments; sacrificing health or relationships for measurable progress.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appreciate effort without rewarding self-erasure; do not make love, access, or status contingent on output. May trigger Resentment, Underfunctioning, Comparison, or Self-Erasure.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Safety, Purpose, and Belonging; avoids emptiness, grief, ordinariness, dependence, and uncertainty about identity.","Canonical Name":"Compulsive Achievement"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCompulsive Achievement is the protective pursuit of continual accomplishment to secure worth, safety, recognition, or relief, making the next achievement necessary rather than freely chosen.\n## Domain\nPerformance, Worth, and Identity\n## Related Patterns\nProductivity-Bound Worth; Perfectionism; Comparison; Approval Seeking; Busyness as Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need another accomplishment before I can feel enough.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need another accomplishment before I can feel enough.\n- Rest has to wait until I prove myself again.\n- The last success no longer counts.\n- I should turn this into another measurable goal.\n- If I stop achieving, I may become invisible or worthless.\n- Completion feels like pressure to raise the bar again.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nCompletion produces brief relief; rest triggers guilt; goals rapidly replace one another; ordinary pace feels threatening.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nChronic goal escalation; inability to celebrate; overloading commitments; sacrificing health or relationships for measurable progress.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Safety; Purpose; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nRest; comparison; praise; uncertainty about worth; setbacks; invisibility.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI matter when I perform; security must be earned repeatedly; stopping invites worthlessness.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nEmptiness; grief; ordinariness; dependence; uncertainty about identity.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior — every horizon becomes another campaign. Creator — output replaces creation. Ruler — achievement becomes control. Caregiver — usefulness becomes worth.\n## Pattern Flow\nWorth feels uncertain → a goal promises stabilization → achievement brings brief relief → the baseline resets upward → exhaustion and disconnection grow → more achievement is recruited for relief.\n## Often Appears With\nProductivity-Bound Worth; Perfectionism; Comparison; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAmbition; discipline; persistence; mastery.\n## Current Cost\nBurnout; neglected relationships; fragile identity; inability to rest; chronic insufficiency.\n## Freer Expression\nAchievement as expression, not proof.\n## One Act of Volition\nComplete one meaningful task without immediately replacing it with a new demand.\n## Mira Language\n“The goal may matter. Is it also being asked to prove that you matter?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat happens after success? What would remain valuable without measurement? Can rest occur before the next proof?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAmbition, disciplined work, economic necessity, and periods of intense effort are not automatically compulsive achievement.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated escalation, inability to stop, and worth or safety becoming contingent on accomplishment.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate chosen purpose from worth regulation, define enough before beginning, and schedule completion rituals and recovery.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAppreciate effort without rewarding self-erasure; do not make love, access, or status contingent on output.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where achievement displaced presence, broke agreements, or turned others into instruments, and establish observable limits and protected relationship time.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Resentment, Underfunctioning, Comparison, or Self-Erasure. Often triggered by Approval Seeking, Criticism, Scarcity, or Grandiosity. The story becomes: “I must keep achieving to remain worthy” ↔︎ “There is no room for me unless I perform too or disappear.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I asking achievement to prove that achievement cannot settle?"},
  "PP-COMPULSIVE-CHECKING": {"name":"Compulsive Checking","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hypervigilance; Certainty Seeking; Reassurance Seeking; Perfectionism; Suspicion; Catastrophizing.","Archetypal Role":"Sage—verification replaces judgment; Caregiver—monitoring replaces trust; Ruler—oversight becomes constant surveillance.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term remains empty because the source explicitly cautions Mira not to diagnose OCD. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Medical Differential because the source requires distinction from OCD and recommends qualified support when checking is severe or disabling.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"Decide in advance what one sufficient check looks like, complete it, record it if useful, and tolerate the remaining uncertainty unless new evidence appears.","Core Logic":"I am checking again because certainty did not stay.","Safety Flags":["Medical Differential"],"Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Time loss; anxiety reinforcement; impaired trust; intrusion; exhaustion; reduced confidence.","Core Fear":"One missed sign causes catastrophe; vigilance prevents abandonment; mistakes are unforgivable; certainty should be achievable.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to check one more time.; If I stop checking, I may miss something catastrophic.; The last verification does not feel reliable anymore.; Not checking would be irresponsible.; I need another confirmation before I can settle.; Certainty disappeared, so I have to verify again.","Protective Move":"Compulsive Checking is the protective repetition of verification, monitoring, rechecking, or status-seeking to obtain certainty or prevent error, danger, rejection, or loss, despite relief being brief and incomplete.","Pattern ID":"PP-COMPULSIVE-CHECKING","Short-Term Payoff":"Checking produces brief relief.","Freer Expression":"Responsible verification with a stopping rule.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Care; accuracy; vigilance; responsibility; attention to evidence.","Observable Cues":"Rechecking locks, messages, work, symptoms, accounts, locations, or another person’s status; repeated confirmation requests; monitoring digital activity.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not shame or endlessly reassure. Support agreed verification limits, provide clear information once, and maintain privacy and consent boundaries. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, Strategic Ambiguity, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, trust, predictability, competence, attachment, dignity, and control; avoids uncertainty, helplessness, guilt, vulnerability, limitation, and mortality.","Canonical Name":"Compulsive Checking"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCompulsive Checking is the protective repetition of verification, monitoring, rechecking, or status-seeking to obtain certainty or prevent error, danger, rejection, or loss, despite relief being brief and incomplete.\n## Domain\nUncertainty, Safety, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nHypervigilance; Certainty Seeking; Reassurance Seeking; Perfectionism; Suspicion\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am checking again because certainty did not stay.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to check one more time.\n- If I stop checking, I may miss something catastrophic.\n- The last verification does not feel reliable anymore.\n- Not checking would be irresponsible.\n- I need another confirmation before I can settle.\n- Certainty disappeared, so I have to verify again.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDoubt returns quickly after verification; not checking feels irresponsible; relief is brief; imagined consequences expand.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRechecking locks, messages, work, symptoms, accounts, locations, or another person’s status; repeated confirmation requests; monitoring digital activity.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; trust; predictability; competence; attachment; dignity; control.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; responsibility; health concerns; delayed responses; previous mistakes; betrayal; transitions.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nOne missed sign causes catastrophe; vigilance prevents abandonment; mistakes are unforgivable; certainty should be achievable.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; helplessness; guilt; vulnerability; limitation; mortality.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage—verification replaces judgment; Caregiver—monitoring replaces trust; Ruler—oversight becomes constant surveillance.\n## Pattern Flow\nDoubt or uncertainty appears → safety or competence feels threatened → checking produces brief relief → uncertainty returns → checking expands → confidence in memory, judgment, and trust declines.\n## Often Appears With\nHypervigilance; Catastrophizing; Reassurance Seeking; Perfectionism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCare; accuracy; vigilance; responsibility; attention to evidence.\n## Current Cost\nTime loss; anxiety reinforcement; impaired trust; intrusion; exhaustion; reduced confidence.\n## Freer Expression\nResponsible verification with a stopping rule.\n## One Act of Volition\nDecide in advance what one sufficient check looks like, complete it, record it if useful, and tolerate the remaining uncertainty unless new evidence appears.\n## Mira Language\n“The check gave relief, but the doubt returned. What would count as sufficient verification, and what uncertainty cannot be eliminated by another check?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feared outcome is the check preventing? Did new evidence appear? Is checking protecting safety, or feeding the demand for impossible certainty?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSafety protocols, medical monitoring, regulated quality assurance, caregiving responsibilities, and reasonable verification are not compulsive checking. Mira must not diagnose OCD.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated checking beyond practical necessity, brief relief, recurrent doubt, and meaningful cost or intrusion.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nValidate the care beneath the urge, assess actual risk, define sufficiency, regulate the uncertainty, and seek qualified support when checking is severe or disabling.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not shame or endlessly reassure. Support agreed verification limits, provide clear information once, and maintain privacy and consent boundaries.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge intrusive monitoring, repeated demands, delays, or mistrust created by checking. Repair through consent, restored privacy, explicit stopping rules, and professional support where appropriate.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, Strategic Ambiguity, or Resentment. Often triggered by inconsistency, betrayal, ambiguity, or another person’s withholding. Stories become “If I stop checking, I will be harmed” and “Nothing I provide will ever be enough.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat uncertainty am I asking one more check to eliminate?"},
  "PP-COMPULSIVE-REHEARSAL": {"name":"Compulsive Rehearsal","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rumination; Overexplaining; Catastrophizing; Certainty Seeking; Hypervigilance; Perfectionism; Conflict Avoidance.","Archetypal Role":"Sage scripts perfect reasoning; Lover scripts reassurance; Warrior prepares every counterattack; Ruler plans every contingency.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"Prepare three essential truths and one boundary, then stop scripting the other person’s lines.","Core Logic":"If I prepare every possible line, I may not be caught undefended.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Sleep loss; anticipatory distress; delayed communication; brittle interaction; mistaking imagined dialogue for evidence.","Core Fear":"Being blindsided; punished for imperfect speech; not being believed; losing access to words under stress.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to prepare every possible response.; If I script the conversation, I will not be caught off guard.; I should rehearse what they might say before I speak.; One more version may finally make me feel ready.; I need the perfect wording before this conversation can happen.; I am trying to pre-live the exchange so nothing surprises me.","Protective Move":"Compulsive Rehearsal is repeatedly scripting future conversations, defenses, explanations, or outcomes to prevent surprise, rejection, humiliation, or loss of control.","Pattern ID":"PP-COMPULSIVE-REHEARSAL","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary preparedness follows as rehearsal multiplies.","Freer Expression":"Prepared presence with room for reality.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Preparation; foresight; communication care; strategic thinking.","Observable Cues":"Drafting and redrafting messages; delaying conversation; rehearsing arguments aloud; preparing responses to events that have not occurred.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer predictable structure and time without demanding perfect spontaneity or joining endless rehearsal. May trigger Defensiveness, Strategic Ambiguity, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, competence, dignity, trust, predictability, and agency; avoids improvisation, uncertainty, relational mutuality, and inability to control another’s response.","Canonical Name":"Compulsive Rehearsal"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCompulsive Rehearsal is repeatedly scripting future conversations, defenses, explanations, or outcomes to prevent surprise, rejection, humiliation, or loss of control.\n## Domain\nControl, Communication, and Uncertainty\n## Related Patterns\nRumination; Overexplaining; Catastrophizing; Certainty Seeking; Hypervigilance\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I prepare every possible line, I may not be caught undefended.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to prepare every possible response.\n- If I script the conversation, I will not be caught off guard.\n- I should rehearse what they might say before I speak.\n- One more version may finally make me feel ready.\n- I need the perfect wording before this conversation can happen.\n- I am trying to pre-live the exchange so nothing surprises me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nReplaying imagined dialogue; inability to stop preparing; temporary relief followed by another scenario; bodily activation around imagined exchanges.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDrafting and redrafting messages; delaying conversation; rehearsing arguments aloud; preparing responses to events that have not occurred.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; competence; dignity; trust; predictability; agency.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConflict; authority; uncertainty; anticipated criticism; emotionally important conversations.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBeing blindsided; punished for imperfect speech; not being believed; losing access to words under stress.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nImprovisation; uncertainty; relational mutuality; inability to control another’s response.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage scripts perfect reasoning; Lover scripts reassurance; Warrior prepares every counterattack; Ruler plans every contingency.\n## Pattern Flow\nConversation approaches → unpredictability feels dangerous → rehearsal multiplies → temporary preparedness → fatigue and rigidity increase → spontaneous contact becomes harder.\n## Often Appears With\nRumination; Overexplaining; Perfectionism; Conflict Avoidance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nPreparation; foresight; communication care; strategic thinking.\n## Current Cost\nSleep loss; anticipatory distress; delayed communication; brittle interaction; mistaking imagined dialogue for evidence.\n## Freer Expression\nPrepared presence with room for reality.\n## One Act of Volition\nPrepare three essential truths and one boundary, then stop scripting the other person’s lines.\n## Mira Language\n“Preparation may help you stay grounded. Has it crossed into trying to control a conversation that has not happened?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat must you remember? What cannot be controlled? What would help you remain present if the conversation changes?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNecessary preparation for high-stakes, accessibility, legal, or safety situations is not automatically compulsive.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepetition beyond practical benefit that increases activation or delays action.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReduce the script to purpose, facts, request, and boundary; orient to the present; permit unscripted response.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer predictable structure and time without demanding perfect spontaneity or joining endless rehearsal.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where rehearsed accusations or assumptions replaced listening; return to what was actually said and clarify the present request.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Strategic Ambiguity, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by Unpredictability, Criticism, Dominance, or Emotional Withholding.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat do I truly need to carry into this conversation, and what am I trying to pre-live?"},
  "PP-CONDITIONAL-WARMTH": {"name":"Conditional Warmth","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Possessiveness; Testing the Bond; Approval Seeking; Punitive Silence; Emotional Withholding; Resentment; Passive Aggression.","Archetypal Role":"Lover turns closeness into leverage; Caregiver withdraws care; Ruler rewards compliance; Innocent seeks restored harmony through approval.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the source explicitly addresses affection used as leverage, compliance, coercive dynamics, and safety when warmth is part of coercive control.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"State the hurt or boundary directly without changing affection into a reward system.","Core Logic":"I am making warmth contingent so I can influence safety or closeness.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Anxiety; coercive dynamics; inauthentic compliance; distrust of affection.","Core Fear":"Love is conditional; direct needs will be rejected; warmth is the only leverage available.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should become colder until they understand.; Warmth should return only after they comply.; If I stay affectionate, I will lose leverage.; Their reassurance has to come before closeness resumes.; I need them to feel the distance so they change.; Affection is the only influence I have left.","Protective Move":"Conditional Warmth is the protective granting or withdrawal of affection, approval, responsiveness, or closeness according to whether another person complies, reassures, performs, or preserves the desired bond.","Pattern ID":"PP-CONDITIONAL-WARMTH","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns when the other person moves toward compliance.","Freer Expression":"Warmth with boundaries, not leverage.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Tenderness; responsiveness; desire for reciprocity and secure connection.","Observable Cues":"Affection disappears after disagreement; praise is tied to obedience; responsiveness becomes a reward; closeness returns only after capitulation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not purchase warmth through unwanted compliance; request direct communication; prioritize safety if affection is part of coercive control. May trigger Appeasement, Clinging, Emotional Distancing, Resentment, or Testing the Bond.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, Safety, and Influence; avoids grief, powerlessness, direct negotiation, and fear of abandonment.","Canonical Name":"Conditional Warmth"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nConditional Warmth is the protective granting or withdrawal of affection, approval, responsiveness, or closeness according to whether another person complies, reassures, performs, or preserves the desired bond.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Influence, and Relationship\n## Related Patterns\nPossessiveness; Testing the Bond; Approval Seeking; Punitive Silence; Emotional Withholding\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am making warmth contingent so I can influence safety or closeness.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should become colder until they understand.\n- Warmth should return only after they comply.\n- If I stay affectionate, I will lose leverage.\n- Their reassurance has to come before closeness resumes.\n- I need them to feel the distance so they change.\n- Affection is the only influence I have left.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nWarmth feels risky after disappointment; urge to become cold until the other person changes; relief when affection restores compliance.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAffection disappears after disagreement; praise is tied to obedience; responsiveness becomes a reward; closeness returns only after capitulation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Safety; Influence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDisagreement; autonomy; perceived disloyalty; unmet expectations; loss of control.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove is conditional; direct needs will be rejected; warmth is the only leverage available.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; powerlessness; direct negotiation; fear of abandonment.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover turns closeness into leverage; Caregiver withdraws care; Ruler rewards compliance; Innocent seeks restored harmony through approval.\n## Pattern Flow\nBond feels threatened → warmth is withdrawn or rationed → the other person moves toward compliance → temporary control returns → safety and authenticity erode.\n## Often Appears With\nPossessiveness; Testing the Bond; Resentment; Passive Aggression.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nTenderness; responsiveness; desire for reciprocity and secure connection.\n## Current Cost\nAnxiety; coercive dynamics; inauthentic compliance; distrust of affection.\n## Freer Expression\nWarmth with boundaries, not leverage.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the hurt or boundary directly without changing affection into a reward system.\n## Mira Language\n“You may need distance or a boundary. The question is whether warmth is being withheld for regulation, or used to make the other person comply.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you hoping the withdrawal will make them do? Can the boundary be named directly? Is connection safe and freely chosen here?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nTemporary distance, loss of desire, emotional limits, and safety-based disengagement are not automatically conditional warmth.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated contingent shifts in warmth tied to compliance or reassurance, not one period of hurt or low bandwidth.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDistinguish regulation from leverage; name needs directly; allow the other person genuine choice.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not purchase warmth through unwanted compliance; request direct communication; prioritize safety if affection is part of coercive control.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where affection became leverage, affirm the other person’s autonomy, repair specific impact, and demonstrate stable boundaries without punishment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Clinging, Emotional Distancing, Resentment, or Testing the Bond; often triggered by Possessiveness or Suspicion.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using warmth to communicate love, and where am I using it to secure compliance?"},
  "PP-CONFESSIONAL-OVEREXPOSURE": {"name":"Confessional Overexposure","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Fusion; Testing the Bond; Reassurance Seeking; Boundary Collapse; Shame Spiraling.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — merges through disclosure. Innocent — confession seeks cleansing. Jester — turns pain into instant intimacy. Caregiver — shares to invite reciprocal disclosure.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Ask whether the person has capacity and whether the relationship has earned this level of disclosure.","Core Logic":"If I reveal everything first, I can control the exposure and test whether you stay.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Regret; unsafe exposure; burdened listeners; unstable intimacy.","Core Fear":"Secrets make me unlovable; closeness must be accelerated before it disappears.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should tell them everything before they discover it another way.; If they stay after hearing this, I’ll know I’m safe.; I need to get the whole truth out right now.; Closeness will disappear unless I accelerate it.; I can’t hold this shame by myself another minute.; Their immediate response will tell me whether I’m still acceptable.","Protective Move":"Confessional Overexposure is the protective use of rapid, excessive, or poorly bounded disclosure to force closeness, preempt judgment, discharge shame, or control how one’s vulnerabilities are discovered.","Pattern ID":"PP-CONFESSIONAL-OVEREXPOSURE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief and intensity arrive when disclosure accelerates.","Freer Expression":"Earned, paced disclosure.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Honesty; courage; emotional openness; desire for authentic connection.","Observable Cues":"Intimate disclosure before trust exists; repeated confession; sharing beyond consent or context; seeking immediate absolution.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respond without shaming, set capacity boundaries, and avoid rewarding forced intimacy with promises you cannot keep. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Boundary Setting, Savior Identity, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, Self-Esteem, and relief from shame; avoids gradual trust, ambiguity, self-soothing, and privacy.","Canonical Name":"Confessional Overexposure"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nConfessional Overexposure is the protective use of rapid, excessive, or poorly bounded disclosure to force closeness, preempt judgment, discharge shame, or control how one’s vulnerabilities are discovered.\n## Domain\nVulnerability, Boundaries, and Connection\n## Related Patterns\nFusion; Testing the Bond; Reassurance Seeking; Boundary Collapse\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I reveal everything first, I can control the exposure and test whether you stay.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should tell them everything before they discover it another way.\n- If they stay after hearing this, I’ll know I’m safe.\n- I need to get the whole truth out right now.\n- Closeness will disappear unless I accelerate it.\n- I can’t hold this shame by myself another minute.\n- Their immediate response will tell me whether I’m still acceptable.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to disclose; relief immediately after telling; anxiety about the response; regret afterward.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nIntimate disclosure before trust exists; repeated confession; sharing beyond consent or context; seeking immediate absolution.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Self-Esteem; Relief from shame.\n## Usually Triggered By\nNew intimacy; guilt; uncertainty; fear of discovery; loneliness.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nSecrets make me unlovable; closeness must be accelerated before it disappears.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGradual trust; ambiguity; self-soothing; privacy.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — merges through disclosure. Innocent — confession seeks cleansing. Jester — turns pain into instant intimacy. Caregiver — shares to invite reciprocal disclosure.\n## Pattern Flow\nCloseness or shame activates → uncertainty feels intolerable → disclosure accelerates → temporary relief and intensity → boundaries blur and vulnerability hangover follows.\n## Often Appears With\nFusion; Testing the Bond; Reassurance Seeking; Shame Spiraling.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHonesty; courage; emotional openness; desire for authentic connection.\n## Current Cost\nRegret; unsafe exposure; burdened listeners; unstable intimacy.\n## Freer Expression\nEarned, paced disclosure.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk whether the person has capacity and whether the relationship has earned this level of disclosure.\n## Mira Language\n“Your honesty may be real, and the urgency may also be doing protective work. What would paced disclosure preserve?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you hope the disclosure will secure? Has consent been established? What portion is relevant now?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nTrauma disclosure, crisis help-seeking, cultural storytelling, and ordinary openness are not automatically overexposure.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated rapid disclosure used to regulate shame, force intimacy, or test acceptance.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause, regulate, assess consent and trust, and choose the smallest truthful amount needed.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespond without shaming, set capacity boundaries, and avoid rewarding forced intimacy with promises you cannot keep.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge any boundary burden or pressure created; restore the listener’s right to capacity and pacing.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Boundary Setting, Savior Identity, or Resentment. Often triggered by Ambiguity, Shame Spiraling, Rejection fear, or Testing the Bond.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I sharing to connect, to discharge, or to control the moment of discovery?"},
  "PP-CONFLICT-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Conflict Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"People-Pleasing; Appeasement; Self-Erasure; Passive Aggression; Emotional Inhibition; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver keeps harmony by absorbing strain. Lover conceals difference to preserve closeness. Innocent assumes conflict means the bond is failing. Diplomat mediates before naming a personal stake.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source distinguishes safety-based silence from this pattern but does not assign a single controlled safety flag.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Name one true disagreement in a calm sentence without solving it immediately.","Core Logic":"I am preserving peace by hiding what needs to be said.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Ambiguous consent; unresolved problems; resentment; loss of voice; sudden exits after prolonged silence.","Core Fear":"Disagreement causes abandonment; anger is dangerous; my needs create trouble; peace depends on my silence.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It’s better to keep the peace than say what I really think.; I’ll bring this up later, when it feels safer.; Their disappointment would be too hard to tolerate.; I should agree now and manage my resentment privately.; If I say no, the relationship may not survive.; Silence feels safer than honest tension.","Protective Move":"Conflict Avoidance is the protective attempt to prevent rejection, escalation, shame, or relational loss by suppressing disagreement, delaying necessary conversations, or preserving surface peace at the expense of truth.","Pattern ID":"PP-CONFLICT-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate relief follows when disagreement is hidden or delayed.","Freer Expression":"Courageous peace-making.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Diplomacy; sensitivity; restraint; care for relationship.","Observable Cues":"Agreeing outwardly; changing the subject; postponing conversations; indirect hints; disappearing when tension rises; allowing resentment to accumulate.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Reduce intimidation, invite disagreement without demanding disclosure, and respond to truth without punishment when connection is safe. May trigger Micromanaging, Testing the Bond, Resentment, or Hostility Toward Criticism.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Safety, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids guilt, uncertainty, another person’s disappointment, limits, incompatibility, and grief.","Canonical Name":"Conflict Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nConflict Avoidance is the protective attempt to prevent rejection, escalation, shame, or relational loss by suppressing disagreement, delaying necessary conversations, or preserving surface peace at the expense of truth.\n## Domain\nRelationship, Communication, and Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nPeople-Pleasing; Appeasement; Self-Erasure; Passive Aggression; Emotional Inhibition; Withdrawing Before Being Left\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am preserving peace by hiding what needs to be said.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It’s better to keep the peace than say what I really think.\n- I’ll bring this up later, when it feels safer.\n- Their disappointment would be too hard to tolerate.\n- I should agree now and manage my resentment privately.\n- If I say no, the relationship may not survive.\n- Silence feels safer than honest tension.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDread before disagreement; pressure to keep things pleasant; rehearsing without speaking; relief when a difficult topic is postponed.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAgreeing outwardly; changing the subject; postponing conversations; indirect hints; disappearing when tension rises; allowing resentment to accumulate.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Safety; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAnger; criticism; power differences; possible disappointment; requests that require saying no; histories of volatile conflict.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDisagreement causes abandonment; anger is dangerous; my needs create trouble; peace depends on my silence.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGuilt; uncertainty; another person’s disappointment; limits; incompatibility; grief.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver keeps harmony by absorbing strain. Lover conceals difference to preserve closeness. Innocent assumes conflict means the bond is failing. Diplomat mediates before naming a personal stake.\n## Pattern Flow\nTension appears → belonging or safety feels threatened → disagreement is hidden or delayed → immediate relief follows → truth and consent weaken → resentment or rupture grows.\n## Often Appears With\nPeople-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Emotional Inhibition; Passive Aggression; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiplomacy; sensitivity; restraint; care for relationship.\n## Current Cost\nAmbiguous consent; unresolved problems; resentment; loss of voice; sudden exits after prolonged silence.\n## Freer Expression\nCourageous peace-making.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one true disagreement in a calm sentence without solving it immediately.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be trying to protect the relationship by avoiding tension. Is the silence creating real peace, or postponing a truth the relationship needs?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat outcome do you fear if you disagree? What truth is being traded for temporary calm? What would a gentle, direct opening sound like?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nStrategic timing, cultural communication norms, safety-based silence, and choosing not to engage an abusive person are not Conflict Avoidance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of suppressing or delaying necessary disagreement despite mounting personal or relational cost.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate first, distinguish danger from discomfort, and use a bounded statement of observation, impact, need, or limit.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nReduce intimidation, invite disagreement without demanding disclosure, and respond to truth without punishment when connection is safe.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge concealed disagreement, unclear consent, or accumulated resentment; state what was true at the time; correct agreements that were never freely made; establish an earlier conversation point.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Testing the Bond, Resentment, or Hostility Toward Criticism. Often triggered by Anger as Armor, Dominance, Criticism, or Retaliation. Stories become “I cannot be honest safely” and “I must push harder to get a real answer.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I calling silence peace when it is actually fear?"},
  "PP-CONTRARIANISM": {"name":"Contrarianism","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Adversarial Framing; Defensive Expertise; Dominance; Hyper-Independence; Moral Superiority; Cynicism.","Archetypal Role":"Rebel — opposition becomes proof of freedom. Sage — critique becomes identity. Trickster — disruption replaces discernment.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"State one point of genuine agreement before offering the counterpoint.","Core Logic":"I need to oppose this before I can decide whether it is true.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Exhausting dialogue; missed learning; relational friction; identity trapped in opposition.","Core Fear":"Agreement erases me; influence means control; my value comes from seeing what others miss.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to find the flaw before I can agree.; Agreement feels too much like surrender.; If everyone supports it, I should question it.; I need to preserve my independence by taking the opposite view.; Collaboration is starting to feel like a debate I have to win.; I can decide what I think only after I resist their influence.","Protective Move":"Contrarianism is the protective reflex to oppose, qualify, or reverse what another person proposes in order to preserve autonomy, distinctiveness, or intellectual control.","Pattern ID":"PP-CONTRARIANISM","Short-Term Payoff":"Agency and status return when opposition begins.","Freer Expression":"Independent thought without reflexive opposition.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Independent thought; dissent; creativity; resistance to groupthink.","Observable Cues":"Reflexive counterarguments; moving the goalposts; rejecting ideas once others endorse them; treating collaboration as debate.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Avoid power struggles; ask for the person’s independent view, then locate shared ground and decision criteria. May trigger Dominance, Withdrawal, Defensive Expertise, or People-Pleasing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Competence, Self-Esteem, and Identity; avoids dependence, uncertainty, ordinariness, and receptivity.","Canonical Name":"Contrarianism"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nContrarianism is the protective reflex to oppose, qualify, or reverse what another person proposes in order to preserve autonomy, distinctiveness, or intellectual control.\n## Domain\nAutonomy, Identity, and Conflict\n## Related Patterns\nAdversarial Framing; Defensive Expertise; Dominance; Hyper-Independence; Moral Superiority\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need to oppose this before I can decide whether it is true.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to find the flaw before I can agree.\n- Agreement feels too much like surrender.\n- If everyone supports it, I should question it.\n- I need to preserve my independence by taking the opposite view.\n- Collaboration is starting to feel like a debate I have to win.\n- I can decide what I think only after I resist their influence.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAgreement feels like surrender; immediate urge to find the flaw; distinctiveness feels threatened by consensus.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReflexive counterarguments; moving the goalposts; rejecting ideas once others endorse them; treating collaboration as debate.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Competence; Self-Esteem; Identity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAdvice; consensus; authority; enthusiasm; being influenced; group belonging.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nAgreement erases me; influence means control; my value comes from seeing what others miss.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependence; uncertainty; ordinariness; receptivity.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRebel — opposition becomes proof of freedom. Sage — critique becomes identity. Trickster — disruption replaces discernment.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother view is offered → autonomy or distinctiveness feels threatened → opposition begins → agency and status return → mutual inquiry collapses → isolation confirms the need to resist.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensive Expertise; Adversarial Framing; Cynicism; Dominance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nIndependent thought; dissent; creativity; resistance to groupthink.\n## Current Cost\nExhausting dialogue; missed learning; relational friction; identity trapped in opposition.\n## Freer Expression\nIndependent thought without reflexive opposition.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one point of genuine agreement before offering the counterpoint.\n## Mira Language\n“Is the disagreement emerging from evidence, or does agreement itself feel costly?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would agreement threaten? Would you hold this position if no one opposed it? What part is true on both sides?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nPrincipled dissent, minority viewpoints, and accurate critique are not contrarianism.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated opposition across topics, especially when positions shift to preserve difference.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause before countering, identify the autonomy threat, and choose a position based on values and evidence.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAvoid power struggles; ask for the person’s independent view, then locate shared ground and decision criteria.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where reflexive opposition obstructed collaboration or invalidated others, state the actual position, and recommit to shared inquiry.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Dominance, Withdrawal, Defensive Expertise, or People-Pleasing. Often triggered by Micromanaging, Advice-Giving, or Group Pressure. The story becomes: “I must resist to remain free” ↔︎ “Nothing can be agreed upon with you.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I protecting freedom by opposing before discerning?"},
  "PP-CYNICISM": {"name":"Cynicism","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hypervigilance; Devaluation; Adversarial Framing; Certainty Seeking; Emotional Distancing; Sarcasm as Armor.","Archetypal Role":"Sage — discernment becomes chronic disbelief. Rebel — skepticism becomes identity. Ruler — trust is replaced by control.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"C","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Identify one piece of evidence that would genuinely revise the cynical conclusion.","Core Logic":"I am lowering hope before reality can disappoint me.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Lost opportunity; relational distance; confirmation bias; inability to receive goodness.","Core Fear":"Trust leads to exploitation; hope makes fools of people; sincerity conceals self-interest.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"People always have an angle.; Hope is just how people get disappointed.; Their sincerity probably hides self-interest.; I should assume the promise will fail.; Trusting provisionally feels naive.; If I expect corruption, I won’t be surprised.","Protective Move":"Cynicism is the protective presumption that motives, promises, or hopeful possibilities are fundamentally compromised, reducing the risk of disappointment by withholding trust in advance.","Pattern ID":"PP-CYNICISM","Short-Term Payoff":"Vigilance and superiority provide relief when motives are presumed corrupt.","Freer Expression":"Discernment with permeability.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; realism; pattern recognition; resistance to manipulation.","Observable Cues":"Attributing hidden motives; dismissing optimism; predicting corruption or failure; mocking sincere effort; refusing provisional trust.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not demand trust or shame skepticism; offer consistency, evidence, and bounded commitments. May trigger Defensiveness, Image Management, Withdrawal, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Safety, Competence, and Self-Esteem; avoids hope, disappointment, dependence, uncertainty, and grief.","Canonical Name":"Cynicism"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nCynicism is the protective presumption that motives, promises, or hopeful possibilities are fundamentally compromised, reducing the risk of disappointment by withholding trust in advance.\n## Domain\nTrust, Meaning, and Social Perception\n## Related Patterns\nHypervigilance; Devaluation; Adversarial Framing; Certainty Seeking; Emotional Distancing\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am lowering hope before reality can disappoint me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- People always have an angle.\n- Hope is just how people get disappointed.\n- Their sincerity probably hides self-interest.\n- I should assume the promise will fail.\n- Trusting provisionally feels naive.\n- If I expect corruption, I won’t be surprised.\n## Recognition Signals — Internal\nSuspicion feels safer than curiosity; hope feels naive; positive evidence is quickly discounted.\n## Observable Behaviors\nAttributing hidden motives; dismissing optimism; predicting corruption or failure; mocking sincere effort; refusing provisional trust.\n## Core Human Needs\nTrust; Safety; Competence; Self-Esteem.\n## Triggers\nPromises; institutional claims; idealism; vulnerability; prior betrayal; dependence.\n## Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nTrust leads to exploitation; hope makes fools of people; sincerity conceals self-interest.\n## Feelings or Realities Avoided\nHope; disappointment; dependence; uncertainty; grief.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage — discernment becomes chronic disbelief. Rebel — skepticism becomes identity. Ruler — trust is replaced by control.\n## Pattern Flow\nHope or trust becomes possible → betrayal memory activates → motives are presumed corrupt → vigilance and superiority provide relief → corrective evidence is dismissed → isolation and confirmation deepen.\n## Often Appears With\nHypervigilance; Adversarial Framing; Sarcasm as Armor; Devaluation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside\nDiscernment; realism; pattern recognition; resistance to manipulation.\n## Current Cost\nLost opportunity; relational distance; confirmation bias; inability to receive goodness.\n## Freer Expression\nDiscernment with permeability.\n## One Act of Volition\nIdentify one piece of evidence that would genuinely revise the cynical conclusion.\n## Mira Language\n“Your skepticism may be protecting hard-earned trust. What evidence would allow even provisional openness?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat disappointment is cynicism preventing? Are motives being evaluated or predetermined? What remains uncertain?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLegitimate skepticism, political critique, and accurate recognition of corruption are not cynicism.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated global presumption of bad faith despite mixed or contrary evidence.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPreserve discernment while naming uncertainty and testing claims against observable behavior rather than motive certainty.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not demand trust or shame skepticism; offer consistency, evidence, and bounded commitments.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where presumed bad faith erased another person’s actual effort or integrity, revise the claim, and agree on observable trust criteria.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Image Management, Withdrawal, or Resentment. Often triggered by Grandiosity, Broken Promises, or Minimizing. The loop becomes: “Everyone is self-serving” ↔︎ “Nothing I do will ever be believed.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere has protection from disappointment become refusal of possibility?"},
  "PP-DECISION-DELEGATION": {"name":"Decision Delegation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Indecision; Approval Seeking; Underfunctioning; Hyper-Independence; Reassurance Seeking; Self-Erasure.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent seeks a trusted guide. Caregiver asks what everyone else needs first. Lover lets the relationship decide identity. Sage substitutes expert consensus for personal judgment.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Ask for information, then state, “The decision is mine, and I choose…”","Core Logic":"I want someone else to choose so I cannot be wrong alone.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Weak self-trust; covert resentment; blurred responsibility; manipulability; inability to know one’s preferences.","Core Fear":"My judgment is unreliable; autonomy risks rejection; mistakes will be punished; authorities know better than I do.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need someone else to choose so I can’t be wrong alone.; Tell me what you think I should do.; Their approval would make the decision feel safer.; I don’t trust my preference enough to act on it.; If the outcome goes badly, I don’t want it to be entirely mine.; Advice is starting to become permission.","Protective Move":"Decision Delegation is the protective transfer of personal choice to another person, authority, system, or consensus in order to avoid responsibility, blame, uncertainty, or self-doubt.","Pattern ID":"PP-DECISION-DELEGATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate relief follows when authority is transferred outward.","Freer Expression":"Supported self-authorship.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Receptivity; humility; collaboration; respect for expertise.","Observable Cues":"Asking others to choose personal matters; treating advice as instruction; withholding preferences; blaming advisers when outcomes disappoint; polling until one answer feels authoritative.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Return appropriate choice without abandonment: provide options and support, but do not become the permanent source of permission. May trigger Overfunctioning, Dominance, Rescuing, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Competence, Belonging, and Self-Esteem; avoids responsibility, disagreement, regret, separation, and ownership of desire.","Canonical Name":"Decision Delegation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDecision Delegation is the protective transfer of personal choice to another person, authority, system, or consensus in order to avoid responsibility, blame, uncertainty, or self-doubt.\n## Domain\nAgency, Dependence, and Responsibility\n## Related Patterns\nIndecision; Approval Seeking; Underfunctioning; Hyper-Independence; Reassurance Seeking; Self-Erasure\n## Recognition Sentence\nI want someone else to choose so I cannot be wrong alone.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need someone else to choose so I can’t be wrong alone.\n- Tell me what you think I should do.\n- Their approval would make the decision feel safer.\n- I don’t trust my preference enough to act on it.\n- If the outcome goes badly, I don’t want it to be entirely mine.\n- Advice is starting to become permission.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when another person decides; anxiety when asked for a preference; resentment toward the person whose advice was followed; repeated desire for permission.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAsking others to choose personal matters; treating advice as instruction; withholding preferences; blaming advisers when outcomes disappoint; polling until one answer feels authoritative.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Competence; Belonging; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; high visibility; anticipated criticism; unfamiliar choices; unequal power; fear of disappointing others.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy judgment is unreliable; autonomy risks rejection; mistakes will be punished; authorities know better than I do.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nResponsibility; disagreement; regret; separation; ownership of desire.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent seeks a trusted guide. Caregiver asks what everyone else needs first. Lover lets the relationship decide identity. Sage substitutes expert consensus for personal judgment.\n## Pattern Flow\nChoice arises → self-trust or belonging feels threatened → authority is transferred outward → immediate relief follows → ownership weakens → resentment and dependency increase.\n## Often Appears With\nApproval Seeking; Reassurance Seeking; Indecision; Underfunctioning; Self-Erasure.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReceptivity; humility; collaboration; respect for expertise.\n## Current Cost\nWeak self-trust; covert resentment; blurred responsibility; manipulability; inability to know one’s preferences.\n## Freer Expression\nSupported self-authorship.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk for information, then state, “The decision is mine, and I choose…”\n## Mira Language\n“Advice may help, but I notice you are asking the adviser to carry the choice itself. What is your own preference before anyone approves it?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat responsibility would become yours if you chose? Whose disappointment are you trying to prevent? What do you already know?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDelegating within legitimate roles, seeking expert guidance, supported decision-making, and accommodations are not automatically this pattern.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated transfer of personally appropriate choices accompanied by avoidance of ownership or later blame.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate data, advice, and authority; identify personal values; make the smallest decision that rebuilds self-trust.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nReturn appropriate choice without abandonment: provide options and support, but do not become the permanent source of permission.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where responsibility was transferred and later blamed; reclaim the decision; clarify future advisory versus decision-making roles.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Dominance, Rescuing, or Resentment. Often triggered by Hostility Toward Criticism, Perfectionism, or controlling authority. Stories become “You must decide for me” and “Everything depends on me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I asking for advice when I am actually asking for permission?"},
  "PP-DEFENSIVE-EXPERTISE": {"name":"Defensive Expertise","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Grandiosity; Rationalization; Intellectualizing; Approval Seeking; Moral Superiority; Defensiveness; Perfectionism.","Archetypal Role":"Sage — wisdom becomes dominance. Ruler — expertise secures authority. Magician — special knowledge creates distance. Creator — technical mastery blocks feedback. Caregiver — professional knowledge overrides another’s agency.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Say “I may be missing something” and ask one genuine question before explaining.","Core Logic":"If I know more, I do not have to feel exposed.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Condescension; blocked learning; emotional disconnection; inaccessible communication; fragile competence.","Core Fear":"My value is being knowledgeable; uncertainty invites humiliation; emotion is less defensible than fact; authority prevents dismissal.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to establish that I know more.; If I say I don’t know, I’ll lose credibility.; The technical details prove I’m right.; They don’t understand enough to challenge me.; I should explain until my authority is clear.; If I stay in expertise, I won’t have to feel exposed.","Protective Move":"Defensive Expertise is the protective use of knowledge, credentials, complexity, or technical authority to avoid vulnerability, uncertainty, correction, or equal dialogue.","Pattern ID":"PP-DEFENSIVE-EXPERTISE","Short-Term Payoff":"Status and certainty return when expertise is amplified.","Freer Expression":"Expertise in service of dialogue.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Knowledge; rigor; teaching; precision; mastery; intellectual responsibility.","Observable Cues":"Overexplaining; credential dropping; correcting irrelevant details; moving discussion into inaccessible jargon; dismissing lived experience; answering emotion with expertise.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect genuine expertise without surrendering your experience or the relational issue. Ask for plain language and return to impact when technical detail becomes evasive. May trigger Withdrawal, Defensiveness, Counter-Expertise, Self-Doubt, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Autonomy; avoids not knowing, dependence, embarrassment, emotional impact, equality, and learning from others.","Canonical Name":"Defensive Expertise"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDefensive Expertise is the protective use of knowledge, credentials, complexity, or technical authority to avoid vulnerability, uncertainty, correction, or equal dialogue.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nGrandiosity; Rationalization; Intellectualizing; Approval Seeking; Moral Superiority\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I know more, I do not have to feel exposed.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to establish that I know more.\n- If I say I don’t know, I’ll lose credibility.\n- The technical details prove I’m right.\n- They don’t understand enough to challenge me.\n- I should explain until my authority is clear.\n- If I stay in expertise, I won’t have to feel exposed.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrge to prove competence when questioned; discomfort saying “I don’t know”; equating disagreement with ignorance; safety in technical detail.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOverexplaining; credential dropping; correcting irrelevant details; moving discussion into inaccessible jargon; dismissing lived experience; answering emotion with expertise.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Self-Esteem; Trust; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCorrection; uncertainty; emotional confrontation; novice status; challenge from someone lower in hierarchy; mistakes.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy value is being knowledgeable; uncertainty invites humiliation; emotion is less defensible than fact; authority prevents dismissal.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nNot knowing; dependence; embarrassment; emotional impact; equality; learning from others.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage — wisdom becomes dominance. Ruler — expertise secures authority. Magician — special knowledge creates distance. Creator — technical mastery blocks feedback. Caregiver — professional knowledge overrides another’s agency.\n## Pattern Flow\nCompetence feels challenged → expertise is amplified → status and certainty return → dialogue narrows → correction and intimacy become harder → identity depends more on knowing.\n## Often Appears With\nGrandiosity; Rationalization; Defensiveness; Intellectualizing; Perfectionism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nKnowledge; rigor; teaching; precision; mastery; intellectual responsibility.\n## Current Cost\nCondescension; blocked learning; emotional disconnection; inaccessible communication; fragile competence.\n## Freer Expression\nExpertise in service of dialogue.\n## One Act of Volition\nSay “I may be missing something” and ask one genuine question before explaining.\n## Mira Language\n“Your knowledge may be relevant. Is it helping understanding, or protecting you from feeling corrected or affected?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat becomes vulnerable if you do not establish expertise? What information does the other person hold? Is the central issue technical or relational?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAccurate correction, professional responsibility, safety expertise, and detailed explanation are not automatically Defensive Expertise.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated deployment of expertise to dominate, evade impact, or prevent mutual inquiry.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate competence from invulnerability, acknowledge the emotional or relational question first, and offer knowledge proportionate to what is actually needed.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect genuine expertise without surrendering your experience or the relational issue. Ask for plain language and return to impact when technical detail becomes evasive.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where knowledge was used to silence, belittle, or avoid impact. Repair by restating the other person’s point accurately, correcting any factual issue without hierarchy, and demonstrating openness to influence.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Withdrawal, Defensiveness, Counter-Expertise, Self-Doubt, or Contempt. Often triggered by criticism, imprecision, status threat, or emotional demand. The loop becomes: “I must prove authority” and “I must either submit or defeat your authority.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nIs my knowledge opening the conversation or protecting me from it?"},
  "PP-DEFENSIVENESS": {"name":"Defensiveness","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Minimizing; Rationalization; Projection; Counterattack; Victim Positioning; Criticism; Stonewalling.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior — counterattacks. Ruler — defends authority. Sage — argues technicalities. Caregiver — lists sacrifices. Rebel — reframes accountability as oppression. Innocent — insists on harmless intent.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly distinguishes defensiveness from resisting coercive blame or false accusation.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Name one valid part of the other person’s message before offering context.","Core Logic":"If I admit any part of this, I may become entirely wrong, bad, or powerless.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Blocked accountability; circular conflict; invalidation; inability to repair; mutual escalation.","Core Fear":"Responsibility means humiliation; if I yield, I will be dominated; mistakes make me unworthy.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Yes, but you did something too.; Your tone makes the whole criticism invalid.; If I admit one part, you’ll blame me for everything.; I need to explain before you decide who I am.; You’re making me the villain here.; I have to defend myself before I can hear you.","Protective Move":"Defensiveness protects self-worth and safety by resisting, redirecting, counterattacking, or explaining away responsibility when criticism or blame is perceived.","Pattern ID":"PP-DEFENSIVENESS","Short-Term Payoff":"Shame temporarily recedes when defense, explanation, or counterattack appears.","Freer Expression":"Self-respect with responsibility.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Self-protection; fairness sensitivity; capacity to resist unjust blame; contextual thinking.","Observable Cues":"Countercomplaining; “yes, but”; denying impact; focusing on tone; correcting details to avoid the core issue; presenting oneself as the injured party.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Use specific behavior and impact; avoid global blame; allow context after acknowledgment; do not demand false confession. May trigger Criticism, Escalation, Contempt, Stonewalling, or Keeping Score.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Fairness, Autonomy, Safety, and Belonging; avoids guilt, shame, helplessness, empathy, partial responsibility, and vulnerability.","Canonical Name":"Defensiveness"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDefensiveness protects self-worth and safety by resisting, redirecting, counterattacking, or explaining away responsibility when criticism or blame is perceived.\n## Domain\nAnger, Conflict, and Power; Relational Expression Crosswalk\n## Related Patterns\nMinimizing; Rationalization; Projection; Counterattack; Victim Positioning; Criticism\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I admit any part of this, I may become entirely wrong, bad, or powerless.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Yes, but you did something too.\n- Your tone makes the whole criticism invalid.\n- If I admit one part, you’ll blame me for everything.\n- I need to explain before you decide who I am.\n- You’re making me the villain here.\n- I have to defend myself before I can hear you.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nImmediate pressure to explain; feeling accused before the message is complete; scanning for the other person’s fault; fear that acknowledgment equals surrender.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nCountercomplaining; “yes, but”; denying impact; focusing on tone; correcting details to avoid the core issue; presenting oneself as the injured party.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Fairness; Autonomy; Safety; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCriticism; contempt; shame; public correction; unfair blame; high-conflict history.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nResponsibility means humiliation. If I yield, I will be dominated. Mistakes make me unworthy.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGuilt; shame; helplessness; empathy; partial responsibility; vulnerability.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior — counterattacks. Ruler — defends authority. Sage — argues technicalities. Caregiver — lists sacrifices. Rebel — reframes accountability as oppression. Innocent — insists on harmless intent.\n## Pattern Flow\nCriticism or blame is perceived → worth and fairness feel threatened → defense, explanation, or counterattack appears → shame temporarily recedes → impact remains unaddressed → conflict escalates.\n## Often Appears With\nRationalization; Minimizing; Projection; Criticism; Stonewalling.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSelf-protection; fairness sensitivity; capacity to resist unjust blame; contextual thinking.\n## Current Cost\nBlocked accountability; circular conflict; invalidation; inability to repair; mutual escalation.\n## Freer Expression\nSelf-respect with responsibility.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one valid part of the other person’s message before offering context.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be protecting yourself from becoming entirely at fault. Can you take responsibility for one part without accepting what is not yours?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat part is true? What are you afraid acknowledgment will mean? What context belongs after responsibility rather than instead of it?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCorrecting false accusations, asserting boundaries, and resisting coercive blame are not defensiveness.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated resistance to reasonable impact or responsibility through redirection, counterattack, or explanation.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate shame; separate partial responsibility from total condemnation; reflect before explaining.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nUse specific behavior and impact; avoid global blame; allow context after acknowledgment; do not demand false confession.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where defense prevented the other person from being heard and where counterattack added injury. Repair requires taking the valid share, validating impact, and agreeing on a different response to future feedback.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Criticism, Escalation, Contempt, Stonewalling, or Keeping Score. Often triggered by Criticism, Devaluation, Micromanaging, or shame. The loop becomes “You never take responsibility” versus “Nothing I say will keep me from being blamed.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat responsibility could I take without abandoning my own dignity or truth?"},
  "PP-DEFLECTION": {"name":"Deflection","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Defensiveness; Whataboutism; Blame Shifting; Humor Deflection; Strategic Ambiguity; Rationalization; Overexplaining.","Archetypal Role":"Sage argues around the question; Trickster changes the frame; Ruler redirects scrutiny; Caregiver focuses on everyone else’s needs.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"Answer the actual question in one sentence before adding context.","Core Logic":"I am moving the conversation away from what feels dangerous to face.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Unresolved conflict; mistrust; conversational exhaustion; weakened accountability.","Core Fear":"Being wrong means being bad; accountability leads to humiliation; direct contact is unsafe.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"That is not the real issue here.; Before I answer, we need to talk about what they did.; I should explain the context instead of answering directly.; This question feels too exposing to stay with.; A joke or side issue could take the pressure off.; I need to move the conversation somewhere safer.","Protective Move":"Deflection is the protective redirection of attention away from a threatening question, feeling, impact, or responsibility so that the person does not have to remain in contact with it.","Pattern ID":"PP-DEFLECTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief arrives when attention is redirected.","Freer Expression":"Context without evasion.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Agility; contextual thinking; capacity to see multiple factors.","Observable Cues":"Changing the subject; answering a different question; introducing irrelevant grievances; turning impact into a debate about intent.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Calmly return to the original question; avoid chasing every new topic; pause if the conversation becomes coercive or abusive. May trigger Overexplaining, Hostility Toward Criticism, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Safety, Belonging, and Competence; avoids shame, guilt, helplessness, uncertainty, and grief.","Canonical Name":"Deflection"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDeflection is the protective redirection of attention away from a threatening question, feeling, impact, or responsibility so that the person does not have to remain in contact with it.\n## Domain\nCommunication, Accountability, and Conflict\n## Related Patterns\nDefensiveness; Whataboutism; Blame Shifting; Humor Deflection; Strategic Ambiguity\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am moving the conversation away from what feels dangerous to face.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- That is not the real issue here.\n- Before I answer, we need to talk about what they did.\n- I should explain the context instead of answering directly.\n- This question feels too exposing to stay with.\n- A joke or side issue could take the pressure off.\n- I need to move the conversation somewhere safer.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPressure to answer something else; sudden focus on another person’s flaw; urge to joke, explain, counterattack, or change topics.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nChanging the subject; answering a different question; introducing irrelevant grievances; turning impact into a debate about intent.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Safety; Belonging; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAccountability; shame; direct questions; exposure of inconsistency; emotional intimacy.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBeing wrong means being bad; accountability leads to humiliation; direct contact is unsafe.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; guilt; helplessness; uncertainty; grief.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage argues around the question; Trickster changes the frame; Ruler redirects scrutiny; Caregiver focuses on everyone else’s needs.\n## Pattern Flow\nThreatening focus appears → shame or danger rises → attention is redirected → temporary relief arrives → the original issue remains unresolved.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensiveness; Rationalization; Blame Shifting; Overexplaining.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAgility; contextual thinking; capacity to see multiple factors.\n## Current Cost\nUnresolved conflict; mistrust; conversational exhaustion; weakened accountability.\n## Freer Expression\nContext without evasion.\n## One Act of Volition\nAnswer the actual question in one sentence before adding context.\n## Mira Language\n“There may be important context here. Before we widen the frame, can we stay with the original question long enough to answer it directly?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you moving away from? What would a direct answer expose? Can context come after contact?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nChanging topics, requesting time, or correcting a false premise is not automatically deflection.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated redirection specifically when accountability, vulnerability, or impact enters the conversation.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nNotice the urge to redirect; regulate shame; answer the central point briefly; then add nuance.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nCalmly return to the original question; avoid chasing every new topic; pause if the conversation becomes coercive or abusive.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the evasion, answer the missed question, name the impact of making the other person pursue clarity, and demonstrate follow-through.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overexplaining, Hostility Toward Criticism, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by Criticism, Dominance, or Shame Spiraling.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I widening the frame so I do not have to face the center?"},
  "PP-DEMAND-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Demand Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Procrastination; Contrarianism; Conflict Avoidance; Underfunctioning; Anticipatory Defeat; Strategic Ambiguity.","Archetypal Role":"Rebel—resistance proves freedom; Creator—commissioned work loses vitality; Innocent—overwhelm hides behind avoidance.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source explicitly requires differential consideration for ADHD, autism, disability, executive dysfunction, burnout, trauma, workload, and coercive demands rather than assigning a single controlled flag.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"Translate the demand into a choice: decline clearly, renegotiate conditions, or name the exact next step you freely consent to take.","Core Logic":"The moment it became a demand, I lost access to willing choice.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Broken commitments; escalating monitoring; lost opportunities; shame; conflict; reduced trust.","Core Fear":"Other people control me; demands expose inadequacy; compliance erases me; I will be punished either way.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"The moment they told me to do it, I stopped wanting to.; This request feels like control rather than choice.; I need to resist so I do not disappear inside compliance.; I should do something else first to reclaim agency.; Agreeing now may trap me later.; I need a real choice before I can participate willingly.","Protective Move":"Demand Avoidance is the protective resistance, delay, diversion, or refusal that arises when a request is experienced as a threat to autonomy, competence, regulation, or dignity rather than evaluated only on its practical merits.","Pattern ID":"PP-DEMAND-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Resistance or diversion restores momentary agency.","Freer Expression":"Chosen participation with honest limits.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Autonomy; discernment; self-direction; protection from overload.","Observable Cues":"Delaying requested tasks; debating wording; doing something else first; agreeing then not acting; refusing even beneficial requests.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer clear rationale and real choices where possible. Avoid surveillance, escalating reminders, humiliation, or falsely presenting a mandate as optional. May trigger Micromanaging, Hyper-Responsibility, Resentment, or Dominance.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, agency, competence, dignity, rest, safety, and authenticity; avoids helplessness, performance anxiety, shame, fatigue, dependence, and resentment.","Canonical Name":"Demand Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDemand Avoidance is the protective resistance, delay, diversion, or refusal that arises when a request is experienced as a threat to autonomy, competence, regulation, or dignity rather than evaluated only on its practical merits.\n## Domain\nAutonomy, Action, and Capacity\n## Related Patterns\nProcrastination; Contrarianism; Conflict Avoidance; Underfunctioning; Anticipatory Defeat\n## Recognition Sentence\nThe moment it became a demand, I lost access to willing choice.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- The moment they told me to do it, I stopped wanting to.\n- This request feels like control rather than choice.\n- I need to resist so I do not disappear inside compliance.\n- I should do something else first to reclaim agency.\n- Agreeing now may trap me later.\n- I need a real choice before I can participate willingly.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPressure produces immediate resistance; desire disappears when expected; requests feel controlling; shame and defiance alternate.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDelaying requested tasks; debating wording; doing something else first; agreeing then not acting; refusing even beneficial requests.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; agency; competence; dignity; rest; safety; authenticity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCommands; deadlines; monitoring; repeated reminders; evaluative tone; loss of choice; accumulated overload.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nOther people control me; demands expose inadequacy; compliance erases me; I will be punished either way.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHelplessness; performance anxiety; shame; fatigue; dependence; resentment.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRebel—resistance proves freedom; Creator—commissioned work loses vitality; Innocent—overwhelm hides behind avoidance.\n## Pattern Flow\nRequest becomes demand → autonomy or competence feels threatened → resistance or diversion restores momentary agency → task remains → pressure and shame increase → future demands feel even more coercive.\n## Often Appears With\nProcrastination; Contrarianism; Strategic Ambiguity; Underfunctioning.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAutonomy; discernment; self-direction; protection from overload.\n## Current Cost\nBroken commitments; escalating monitoring; lost opportunities; shame; conflict; reduced trust.\n## Freer Expression\nChosen participation with honest limits.\n## One Act of Volition\nTranslate the demand into a choice: decline clearly, renegotiate conditions, or name the exact next step you freely consent to take.\n## Mira Language\n“I notice the resistance rose when the task became externally expected. Is the task itself wrong for you, or has the demand made autonomy feel endangered?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat choice feels missing? Is capacity actually available? What would consent, renegotiation, or a truthful no look like?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDo not infer this pattern from ADHD, autism, disability, executive dysfunction, burnout, trauma, unreasonable workload, or coercive demands without careful context.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated demand-linked resistance across tasks the person may otherwise value, with a recognizable autonomy or evaluation threat.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReduce shame, assess capacity, identify the threatened choice, and convert covert resistance into an explicit yes, no, request, or renegotiation.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer clear rationale and real choices where possible. Avoid surveillance, escalating reminders, humiliation, or falsely presenting a mandate as optional.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where avoidance broke trust or transferred burden. Repair through honest capacity disclosure, revised agreements, and observable follow-through—not promises made under pressure.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Hyper-Responsibility, Resentment, or Dominance. Often triggered by those same patterns. Stories become “I must resist to remain free” and “I must control because nothing happens otherwise.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat choice do I need to reclaim openly instead of through resistance?"},
  "PP-DENIAL": {"name":"Denial","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Minimizing; Rationalization; Emotional Numbing; Spiritual Bypassing; Avoidance.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent — preserving a world in which danger is not real. Ruler — refusing evidence that order has failed. Lover — denying deterioration in the bond. Sage — overvaluing preferred explanations. Caregiver — denying one’s own depletion.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Name one verified fact without explaining it away, then identify the smallest safe action it requires.","Core Logic":"If I do not let this be true, I do not have to feel what it means.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Delayed action; preventable harm; loss of credibility; deepened consequences; isolation from reality-based support.","Core Fear":"The truth will overwhelm me; if this is real, I will lose everything; I cannot survive what follows.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This can’t really be happening.; There has to be another explanation.; Nothing is actually wrong.; I’ll deal with it later when there’s more proof.; If I don’t acknowledge it, I can keep functioning.; Everyone is making this into something bigger than it is.","Protective Move":"Denial is the protective refusal or inability to acknowledge a reality whose emotional meaning feels too threatening to tolerate.","Pattern ID":"PP-DENIAL","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary stability returns when awareness narrows or rejects the fact.","Freer Expression":"Truth at a tolerable pace.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Hope; endurance; temporary psychological protection; capacity to function during shock.","Observable Cues":"Rejecting clear evidence; acting as though a loss, risk, or consequence is not real; repeatedly postponing necessary action; changing the subject when facts are raised.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Remain factual and calm; avoid humiliating confrontation; do not collude with falsehood; offer choices and support while naming consequences. May trigger Pursuit, Overexplaining, Micromanaging, Anger, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Safety, Self-Esteem, and Belonging; avoids grief, fear, shame, helplessness, responsibility, and finality.","Canonical Name":"Denial"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDenial is the protective refusal or inability to acknowledge a reality whose emotional meaning feels too threatening to tolerate.\n## Domain\nAvoidance and Emotional Escape\n## Related Patterns\nMinimizing; Rationalization; Emotional Numbing; Spiritual Bypassing; Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I do not let this be true, I do not have to feel what it means.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This can’t really be happening.\n- There has to be another explanation.\n- Nothing is actually wrong.\n- I’ll deal with it later when there’s more proof.\n- If I don’t acknowledge it, I can keep functioning.\n- Everyone is making this into something bigger than it is.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDisbelief despite evidence; numb certainty that nothing is wrong; irritation when the issue is named; relief when an alternative explanation appears.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRejecting clear evidence; acting as though a loss, risk, or consequence is not real; repeatedly postponing necessary action; changing the subject when facts are raised.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Safety; Self-Esteem; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nLoss; betrayal; illness; addiction; failure; relational rupture; evidence that threatens identity or security.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nThe truth will overwhelm me; if this is real, I will lose everything; I cannot survive what follows.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; fear; shame; helplessness; responsibility; finality.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent — preserving a world in which danger is not real. Ruler — refusing evidence that order has failed. Lover — denying deterioration in the bond. Sage — overvaluing preferred explanations. Caregiver — denying one’s own depletion.\n## Pattern Flow\nThreatening reality appears → emotional survival feels endangered → awareness narrows or rejects the fact → temporary stability returns → action is delayed → consequences intensify.\n## Often Appears With\nMinimizing; Rationalization; Avoidance; Emotional Numbing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHope; endurance; temporary psychological protection; capacity to function during shock.\n## Current Cost\nDelayed action; preventable harm; loss of credibility; deepened consequences; isolation from reality-based support.\n## Freer Expression\nTruth at a tolerable pace.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one verified fact without explaining it away, then identify the smallest safe action it requires.\n## Mira Language\n“Part of you may be protecting you from what this would mean. Can we separate the fact itself from everything you fear would follow?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat fact feels impossible to let in? What would become necessary if it were true? What support would make the truth more bearable?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nShock, incomplete information, disagreement, cultural interpretation, and reasonable uncertainty are not denial.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated rejection of well-supported reality combined with avoidance of its emotional or practical implications.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nApproach the truth in bounded pieces; regulate first; distinguish the fact from catastrophic predictions; seek support before taking the next action.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRemain factual and calm; avoid humiliating confrontation; do not collude with falsehood; offer choices and support while naming consequences.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the reality that was dismissed, the burden others carried, and the decisions delayed. Repair requires factual clarity, responsibility for impact, and a concrete plan tied to the newly acknowledged truth.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Pursuit, Overexplaining, Micromanaging, Anger, or Withdrawal in others. Often triggered by Catastrophizing, Criticism, shame, or overwhelming demands. The loop becomes “You refuse reality” versus “You are forcing me into something unbearable.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat truth am I keeping outside because I fear what it will require of me?"},
  "PP-DESPAIR-AS-CERTAINTY": {"name":"Despair as Certainty","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Anticipatory Defeat; Catastrophizing; Cynicism; Emotional Numbing; Self-Sabotage; Rumination.","Archetypal Role":"Sage—certainty becomes fatalism; Orphan—abandonment becomes destiny; Warrior—withdraws before defeat; Creator—declares the work impossible.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing and shortened headings normalized. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source. Safety flag reflects explicit depression/medical differential caution, not diagnosis.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Name one outcome that is unknown rather than impossible and take one reversible step.","Core Logic":"If I decide nothing can change, I do not have to risk being disappointed again.","Safety Flags":["Medical Differential"],"Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Paralysis; lost opportunities; isolation; reinforcement of powerlessness; inability to perceive partial change.","Core Fear":"Hope leads to humiliation; effort changes nothing; disappointment is unbearable; I am powerless.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Nothing can change.; Hope will only hurt me again.; There is no point trying.; The future is already decided.; Any effort will end the same way.; Possibility feels more dangerous than certainty.","Protective Move":"Converts uncertainty into a fixed hopeless conclusion so hope, effort, disappointment, and renewed exposure no longer have to be risked.","Pattern ID":"PP-DESPAIR-AS-CERTAINTY","Short-Term Payoff":"A hardened hopeless conclusion brings immediate relief from uncertainty.","Freer Expression":"Grounded hope without guarantees.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Realism; caution; sensitivity to loss; refusal of false reassurance.","Observable Cues":"Refusing experiments before testing them; dismissing support; abandoning meaningful action; presenting predictions as settled facts.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not force optimism; acknowledge evidence and pain while clarifying what remains unknown. May trigger Positivity Enforcement, Rescuing, Frustration, Withdrawal, or Dominance.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, dignity, predictability, and self-esteem; avoids grief, uncertainty, longing, dependence, incremental progress, and possible responsibility.","Canonical Name":"Despair as Certainty"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDespair as Certainty is the protective conversion of uncertainty into a fixed hopeless conclusion so the person no longer has to risk hope, effort, disappointment, or renewed exposure.\n## Domain\nMeaning, Hope, and Future Orientation\n## Related Patterns\nAnticipatory Defeat; Catastrophizing; Cynicism; Emotional Numbing; Self-Sabotage; Rumination\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I decide nothing can change, I do not have to risk being disappointed again.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Nothing can change.\n- Hope will only hurt me again.\n- There is no point trying.\n- The future is already decided.\n- Any effort will end the same way.\n- Possibility feels more dangerous than certainty.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief mixed with heaviness after reaching a hopeless conclusion; irritation at possibility; treating uncertainty as proof of failure; numbness replacing grief or fear.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRefusing experiments before testing them; dismissing support; abandoning meaningful action; repeatedly presenting predictions as settled facts.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; dignity; predictability; self-esteem; protection from disappointment.\n## Usually Triggered By\nRepeated setbacks; ambiguous outcomes; loss; slow progress; rejection; failed repair.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nHope leads to humiliation; effort changes nothing; disappointment is unbearable; I am powerless.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; uncertainty; longing; dependence; incremental progress; possible responsibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage—certainty becomes fatalism; Orphan—abandonment becomes destiny; Warrior—withdraws before defeat; Creator—declares the work impossible.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertain or painful future → hope feels dangerous → hopeless conclusion hardens → immediate relief from uncertainty → action and support decrease → hopelessness gains confirming evidence.\n## Often Appears With\nAnticipatory Defeat; Cynicism; Self-Isolation; Emotional Numbing; Rumination.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nRealism; caution; sensitivity to loss; refusal of false reassurance.\n## Current Cost\nParalysis; lost opportunities; isolation; reinforcement of powerlessness; inability to perceive partial change.\n## Freer Expression\nGrounded hope without guarantees.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one outcome that is unknown rather than impossible and take one reversible step.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be protecting yourself from another disappointment by turning uncertainty into certainty that nothing can change. Is that what is happening, or is there concrete evidence that the option is truly closed?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would hope expose? What is known, predicted, and still unknown? What is one small test that does not require optimism?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDepression, grief, oppression, disability, poverty, chronic illness, and realistic constraints must not be reframed as mere mindset.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of converting uncertain outcomes into fixed hopeless conclusions that reduce action or contact—not one discouraged statement.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nValidate the losses that trained the protector, separate facts from predictions, reduce the scale of the next act, and permit cautious participation without requiring positive thinking.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not argue with cheerfulness or force optimism. Acknowledge evidence and pain, clarify what remains unknown, and offer one concrete option without coercion.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where fixed hopelessness dismissed another person’s effort, withdrew participation, or foreclosed shared decisions. Restore choice through truthful limits and one agreed experiment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Positivity Enforcement, Rescuing, Frustration, Withdrawal, or Dominance. The loop becomes “Nothing will ever change” versus “I must force you to hope.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I calling the future settled because uncertainty feels harder to bear?"},
  "PP-DEVALUATION": {"name":"Devaluation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Idealization; Splitting; Contempt; Projection; Withdrawing Before Being Left.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — devotion flips into contempt. Ruler — dissenters become worthless. Rebel — former allies become corrupt. Sage — intellectual dismissal replaces hurt. Warrior — vulnerability becomes contempt for weakness.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Name the specific disappointment without making a global statement about worth.","Core Logic":"If I make you small, I will not have to feel how much your disappointment affects me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Relational cruelty; unstable attachment; loss of nuance; difficulty grieving honestly.","Core Fear":"If I need you, you can hurt me; being disappointed means I was foolish; I must reject before I am rejected.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"You were never as valuable as I thought.; I can’t believe I ever admired you.; One failure proves who you really are.; If I make you smaller, I won’t have to miss you.; Your flaws cancel everything good.; I need to reject you before your disappointment can hurt me.","Protective Move":"Devaluation protects against disappointment, dependency, shame, or grief by reducing another person’s worth after they fail to sustain an idealized role or meet a threatened need.","Pattern ID":"PP-DEVALUATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Dependency and grief temporarily recede when the other person is reduced.","Freer Expression":"Disappointment without degradation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; self-protection; ability to recognize disillusionment.","Observable Cues":"Global criticism; rewriting positive history; mocking formerly admired qualities; withdrawing respect; treating disappointment as proof of worthlessness.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Refuse degrading language; acknowledge disappointment; redirect to specific behavior and boundaries. May trigger Counter-Devaluation, Defensiveness, Withdrawal, or Grandiosity.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Trust, Autonomy, and Belonging; avoids grief, longing, shame, dependency, ambivalence, and vulnerability.","Canonical Name":"Devaluation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDevaluation protects against disappointment, dependency, shame, or grief by reducing another person’s worth after they fail to sustain an idealized role or meet a threatened need.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nIdealization; Splitting; Contempt; Projection; Withdrawing Before Being Left\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I make you small, I will not have to feel how much your disappointment affects me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- You were never as valuable as I thought.\n- I can’t believe I ever admired you.\n- One failure proves who you really are.\n- If I make you smaller, I won’t have to miss you.\n- Your flaws cancel everything good.\n- I need to reject you before your disappointment can hurt me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSudden disgust or dismissal; relief in finding flaws; need to prove the person was never valuable; contempt after dependency or admiration.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nGlobal criticism; rewriting positive history; mocking formerly admired qualities; withdrawing respect; treating disappointment as proof of worthlessness.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Trust; Autonomy; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDisappointment; rejection; criticism; dependency; loss of admiration; boundary-setting.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf I need you, you can hurt me. Being disappointed means I was foolish. I must reject before I am rejected.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; longing; shame; dependency; ambivalence; vulnerability.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — devotion flips into contempt. Ruler — dissenters become worthless. Rebel — former allies become corrupt. Sage — intellectual dismissal replaces hurt. Warrior — vulnerability becomes contempt for weakness.\n## Pattern Flow\nDisappointment threatens attachment or worth → the other person is reduced → dependency and grief temporarily recede → contempt or distance grows → trust becomes less possible.\n## Often Appears With\nSplitting; Idealization; Contempt; Projection.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; self-protection; ability to recognize disillusionment.\n## Current Cost\nRelational cruelty; unstable attachment; loss of nuance; difficulty grieving honestly.\n## Freer Expression\nDisappointment without degradation.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the specific disappointment without making a global statement about worth.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be trying to protect yourself from disappointment by reducing the person. What hurts underneath the verdict?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did you hope for? What specific behavior failed you? What remains true beyond the disappointment?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAccurate reassessment, loss of trust, or recognizing harmful behavior is not devaluation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated global reduction of worth following disappointment, especially after prior idealization.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIdentify the injury; distinguish value from compatibility or trust; allow grief without contempt.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRefuse degrading language; acknowledge disappointment; redirect to specific behavior and boundaries.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge contemptuous or diminishing language and restore the other person’s dignity without erasing legitimate grievances. Repair requires specific truth and changed communication.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Counter-Devaluation, Defensiveness, Withdrawal, or Grandiosity. Often triggered by disappointment, boundaries, or perceived rejection. The loop becomes “You were never worthy” versus “I must defend or prove my worth.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat pain am I avoiding by turning disappointment into a verdict on worth?"},
  "PP-DISPLACEMENT": {"name":"Displacement","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Projection; Scapegoating; Passive Aggression; Emotional Dumping; Suppression; Conflict Avoidance; Emotional Numbing; Overcontrol.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior — attacks the available target instead of the true opponent. Ruler — passes pressure downward. Caregiver — becomes harsh at home after self-suppression. Rebel — directs anger toward symbolic stand-ins. Innocent — turns anger inward to preserve others as good.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Name the original source of the emotion before acting on the nearest trigger.","Core Logic":"I am releasing toward the safer target what I cannot safely express at the source.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Harm to safer relationships; unfair blame; unresolved source conflict; shame; repeated power transfer.","Core Fear":"Direct anger is dangerous; powerful people cannot be confronted; my feelings will not be tolerated; safer people will absorb what others caused.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I’m angry, but not at the person I can safely confront.; This small thing is suddenly making me furious.; I need somewhere to put all this pressure.; I can’t say this to them, so it comes out here.; You’re getting the reaction meant for someone else.; I know this isn’t really about what just happened.","Protective Move":"Displacement redirects an emotion or impulse from the person or situation that evoked it toward a safer, more available, or less powerful target.","Pattern ID":"PP-DISPLACEMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief occurs when emotion is discharged toward the safer target.","Freer Expression":"Emotion returned to its rightful address.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Emotional energy; self-protection; awareness that direct expression has consequences.","Observable Cues":"Snapping at family after work conflict; criticizing a subordinate after feeling powerless; punishing oneself after anger at another; redirecting frustration into unrelated arguments.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Name the mismatch without absorbing blame: “I hear you are upset, but this treatment is not acceptable.” Invite discussion of the original stressor only after safety and respect are restored. May trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Counter-Aggression, Hypervigilance, or People-Pleasing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Autonomy, Self-Esteem, and Belonging; avoids fear, powerlessness, grief, direct confrontation, and dependency.","Canonical Name":"Displacement"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDisplacement redirects an emotion or impulse from the person or situation that evoked it toward a safer, more available, or less powerful target.\n## Domain\nAnger, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nProjection; Scapegoating; Passive Aggression; Emotional Dumping; Suppression; Conflict Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am releasing toward the safer target what I cannot safely express at the source.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I’m angry, but not at the person I can safely confront.\n- This small thing is suddenly making me furious.\n- I need somewhere to put all this pressure.\n- I can’t say this to them, so it comes out here.\n- You’re getting the reaction meant for someone else.\n- I know this isn’t really about what just happened.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nIrritability after an unrelated stressor; strong emotion toward a minor trigger; relief after venting at someone safer; difficulty naming the original source.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSnapping at family after work conflict; criticizing a subordinate after feeling powerless; punishing oneself after anger at another; redirecting frustration into unrelated arguments.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Autonomy; Self-Esteem; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPower imbalance; suppressed anger; fear of retaliation; humiliation; accumulated stress; conflict with an unavailable person.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDirect anger is dangerous; powerful people cannot be confronted; my feelings will not be tolerated; safer people will absorb what others caused.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFear; powerlessness; grief; direct confrontation; dependency.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior — attacks the available target instead of the true opponent. Ruler — passes pressure downward. Caregiver — becomes harsh at home after self-suppression. Rebel — directs anger toward symbolic stand-ins. Innocent — turns anger inward to preserve others as good.\n## Pattern Flow\nStrong emotion arises toward a risky source → expression feels unsafe → emotion is suppressed → a safer target appears → emotion is discharged there → temporary relief occurs → guilt and relational injury accumulate while the original problem remains.\n## Often Appears With\nConflict Avoidance; Passive Aggression; Emotional Numbing; Scapegoating; Overcontrol.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEmotional energy; self-protection; awareness that direct expression has consequences.\n## Current Cost\nHarm to safer relationships; unfair blame; unresolved source conflict; shame; repeated power transfer.\n## Freer Expression\nEmotion returned to its rightful address.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the original source of the emotion before acting on the nearest trigger.\n## Mira Language\n“The reaction seems larger than this moment alone. Is some of the emotion arriving here from somewhere it was harder to express?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWho first evoked this feeling? Why was it safer to express here? What would responsible direct expression look like?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nStress spillover is common and not always a stable pattern. Naming displacement must not erase genuine concerns with the current person.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated mismatch between trigger and intensity, with a plausible earlier source and safer substitute target.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause discharge, locate the original source, regulate the body, repair the safer target, and choose a proportionate channel for the true conflict.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nName the mismatch without absorbing blame: “I hear you are upset, but this treatment is not acceptable.” Invite discussion of the original stressor only after safety and respect are restored.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge that the affected person became the container for emotion caused elsewhere, apologize without making them caretake the original stress, and establish a pause or decompression practice before re-entry.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Counter-Aggression, Hypervigilance, or People-Pleasing. Often triggered by Domination, Criticism, Workplace Pressure, or Conflict Avoidance. Reinforcing stories: “I have nowhere safe to put this” and “I am never safe from anger I did not cause.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWho or what is the true address of this emotion?"},
  "PP-DOMINANCE": {"name":"Dominance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Grandiosity; Micromanaging; Moral Superiority; Control-Seeking; Anger as Armor.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler — authority without stewardship. Warrior — force as legitimacy. Sage — knowledge hierarchy. Caregiver — paternalistic control. Rebel — counter-dominance.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly addresses consent, intimidation, retaliation risk, and outside safety support.","First Letter":"D","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Invite and genuinely consider one dissenting view before deciding.","Core Logic":"I need to be above challenge so I do not have to feel vulnerable, uncertain, or dependent.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Fear-based compliance; reduced truth; resentment; lost consent; relational inequality.","Core Fear":"If I am not on top, I am at risk; power is never shared safely; yielding invites humiliation; dependence means weakness.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to be the one no one can challenge.; If I share power, I’ll lose control.; Their disagreement is insubordination.; I need them to yield before I can feel safe.; I should decide because others can’t be trusted.; If they can refuse me, my authority may disappear.","Protective Move":"Dominance is the protective effort to secure safety, status, or certainty by establishing superior authority and reducing another person’s ability to challenge, influence, or refuse.","Pattern ID":"PP-DOMINANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns when authority and pressure intensify.","Freer Expression":"Authority with consent, accountability, and shared dignity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Leadership; decisiveness; protection; capacity to hold responsibility.","Observable Cues":"Interrupting; unilateral decisions; status reminders; overriding consent; escalating volume or certainty; controlling access to information or resources.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Use clear boundaries, documentation, witnesses, or outside support when needed. Do not attempt vulnerable repair under intimidation or retaliation risk. May trigger Passive Aggression, Underfunctioning, Retaliation, Self-Erasure, or Adversarial Framing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Autonomy, Status, Competence, and Trust; avoids vulnerability, equality, uncertainty, accountability, and need for others.","Canonical Name":"Dominance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nDominance is the protective effort to secure safety, status, or certainty by establishing superior authority and reducing another person’s ability to challenge, influence, or refuse.\n## Domain\nAnger, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nGrandiosity; Micromanaging; Moral Superiority; Control-Seeking; Anger as Armor\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need to be above challenge so I do not have to feel vulnerable, uncertain, or dependent.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to be the one no one can challenge.\n- If I share power, I’ll lose control.\n- Their disagreement is insubordination.\n- I need them to yield before I can feel safe.\n- I should decide because others can’t be trusted.\n- If they can refuse me, my authority may disappear.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDisagreement feels insubordinate; shared power feels unsafe; relief when others yield; difficulty tolerating another person’s independent authority.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nInterrupting; unilateral decisions; status reminders; overriding consent; escalating volume or certainty; controlling access to information or resources.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Autonomy; Status; Competence; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nChallenge; uncertainty; loss of status; dependence; another person’s boundary; public disagreement.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf I am not on top, I am at risk; power is never shared safely; yielding invites humiliation; dependence means weakness.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; equality; uncertainty; accountability; need for others.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler — authority without stewardship. Warrior — force as legitimacy. Sage — knowledge hierarchy. Caregiver — paternalistic control. Rebel — counter-dominance.\n## Pattern Flow\nChallenge arises → safety or status feels threatened → authority and pressure intensify → temporary control returns → others resist, submit, or withdraw → dominance appears necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nGrandiosity; Micromanaging; Anger as Armor; Moral Superiority.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nLeadership; decisiveness; protection; capacity to hold responsibility.\n## Current Cost\nFear-based compliance; reduced truth; resentment; lost consent; relational inequality.\n## Freer Expression\nAuthority with consent, accountability, and shared dignity.\n## One Act of Volition\nInvite and genuinely consider one dissenting view before deciding.\n## Mira Language\n“Leadership may be needed. Dominance appears when safety depends on reducing another person’s right to influence or refuse.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would shared power threaten? How can authority remain accountable here?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nExpertise, role authority, emergency command, parenting responsibility, and firm boundaries are not dominance when proportionate, accountable, and respectful of dignity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of status, pressure, resources, or intimidation to override challenge or consent.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate the threat of being challenged, state role authority precisely, and restore meaningful choice wherever possible.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nUse clear boundaries, documentation, witnesses, or outside support when needed. Do not attempt vulnerable repair under intimidation or retaliation risk.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where power overrode consent or voice, restore decision rights and information, accept consequences, and demonstrate accountable use of authority over time.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Passive Aggression, Underfunctioning, Retaliation, Self-Erasure, or Adversarial Framing. Often triggered by Defensiveness, challenge, unreliability, or another person’s dominance. The loop becomes “I must take control because no one can be trusted” versus “Direct truth is unsafe, so I must submit or resist covertly.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using authority to eliminate another person’s meaningful choice?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-DISTANCING": {"name":"Emotional Distancing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Stonewalling; Avoidant Independence; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Intellectualizing; Isolation; Workaholism.","Archetypal Role":"Explorer — protects freedom through distance; Sage — retreats into analysis; Warrior — suppresses vulnerability; Ruler — maintains control through reserve.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Name the need for space and specify when you will return.","Core Logic":"Distance feels safer than being affected.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Loneliness; ambiguity; partner hypervigilance; blocked repair.","Core Fear":"Closeness costs freedom; vulnerability will be used against me; emotion is unmanageable.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to pull back before this gets too intense.; I don’t want to talk about feelings right now.; Closeness is starting to feel like pressure.; I feel safer when I’m less available.; I’ll deal with this on my own.; Distance helps me feel in control.","Protective Move":"Emotional Distancing is the protective reduction of emotional availability, disclosure, or closeness in order to avoid overwhelm, dependence, conflict, shame, or anticipated injury.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-DISTANCING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief arrives as emotional availability contracts.","Freer Expression":"Boundaried presence.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Self-containment; discernment; capacity for solitude.","Observable Cues":"Shortened responses; reduced disclosure; emotional flatness; retreat into work, screens, or tasks; avoiding vulnerable topics.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Reduce pursuit, respect bounded space, and require clear re-engagement rather than indefinite absence. May trigger Clinging, Compulsive Contact, Testing the Bond, Criticism, or Hypervigilance.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids need, grief, shame, helplessness, and intimacy.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Distancing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Distancing is the protective reduction of emotional availability, disclosure, or closeness in order to avoid overwhelm, dependence, conflict, shame, or anticipated injury.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nStonewalling; Avoidant Independence; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Intellectualizing; Isolation\n## Recognition Sentence\nDistance feels safer than being affected.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to pull back before this gets too intense.\n- I don’t want to talk about feelings right now.\n- Closeness is starting to feel like pressure.\n- I feel safer when I’m less available.\n- I’ll deal with this on my own.\n- Distance helps me feel in control.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nNumbness during closeness; urge to retreat; irritation at need; relief when unavailable.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nShortened responses; reduced disclosure; emotional flatness; retreat into work, screens, or tasks; avoiding vulnerable topics.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPursuit; criticism; intense emotion; dependency; conflict; fear of engulfment.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nCloseness costs freedom; vulnerability will be used against me; emotion is unmanageable.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nNeed; grief; shame; helplessness; intimacy.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nExplorer — protects freedom through distance; Sage — retreats into analysis; Warrior — suppresses vulnerability; Ruler — maintains control through reserve.\n## Pattern Flow\nEmotional demand rises → autonomy or safety feels threatened → availability contracts → temporary relief arrives → the other pursues or despairs → future closeness feels more dangerous.\n## Often Appears With\nIntellectualizing; Avoidant Independence; Stonewalling; Workaholism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSelf-containment; discernment; capacity for solitude.\n## Current Cost\nLoneliness; ambiguity; partner hypervigilance; blocked repair.\n## Freer Expression\nBoundaried presence.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the need for space and specify when you will return.\n## Mira Language\n“Distance may be helping you regulate. Can we distinguish a restorative pause from disappearing from the relationship?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feels dangerous about staying emotionally present? What amount of contact is tolerable? When will re-engagement happen?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nIntroversion, privacy, and temporary regulation are not emotional distancing.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated contraction of emotional access when vulnerability or conflict arises.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRequest space explicitly, regulate, and return at the agreed time with one truthful disclosure.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nReduce pursuit, respect bounded space, and require clear re-engagement rather than indefinite absence.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where distance created abandonment, uncertainty, or blocked dialogue; explain the need without blaming; establish a reliable pause-and-return structure.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Compulsive Contact, Testing the Bond, Criticism, or Hypervigilance. Often triggered by pursuit, criticism, fusion, or emotional flooding. The loop becomes: “I must withdraw to stay safe” and “I must pursue because you are disappearing.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I taking space, or removing myself from the bond?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-DUMPING": {"name":"Emotional Dumping","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rumination; Confessional Overexposure; Reassurance Seeking; Urgency Addiction; Crisis Creation; Boundary Collapse.","Archetypal Role":"Orphan—pain seeks immediate holding; Lover—closeness becomes unbounded disclosure; Caregiver—roles reverse without consent; Trickster—intensity keeps attention; Innocent—support is expected without limit.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because the source distinguishes crisis disclosure, trauma reporting, therapy, mutual intimacy, and appropriate help-seeking from the pattern.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"Ask whether the person has capacity, name the time needed, and agree on the kind of support before disclosing.","Core Logic":"I am trying to transfer the pressure rather than metabolize it.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Listener exhaustion; ruptured trust; shame after disclosure; dependence on external regulation; reduced reciprocity; avoidance of sustained processing.","Core Fear":"No one will help unless I make the pain impossible to ignore; I cannot hold this alone; limits mean abandonment; my feelings only become real when someone else carries them.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to tell someone everything right now.; Their capacity can wait because the pressure is unbearable.; If they set a limit, it means they are abandoning me.; Retelling the whole crisis may finally settle me.; I need another person to carry this feeling for me.; Pausing before sharing feels impossible.","Protective Move":"Emotional Dumping is the protective discharge of intense emotion, repetitive narrative, or crisis material into another person without sufficient consent, reciprocity, pacing, or responsibility for regulation.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-DUMPING","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate relief and connection occur after material is discharged into another.","Freer Expression":"Honest sharing with consent, pacing, and shared responsibility.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Honesty; emotional openness; desire for connection; willingness to seek support.","Observable Cues":"Long uncontained disclosures; repetitive crisis narration; contacting multiple people with the same material; ignoring signs of listener fatigue; escalating detail to keep attention; resisting pauses, structure, or reciprocal conversation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"State capacity honestly, offer a bounded form of support, redirect when needed, and avoid promising unlimited availability. In emergencies, prioritize appropriate crisis or safety resources. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Boundary Rigidity, Help-Rejection, Resentment, or Punitive Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects care and support, belonging, safety, regulation, trust, and recognition; avoids solitude, self-regulation, pacing, responsibility, uncertainty about support, and the listener’s separateness and limits.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Dumping"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Dumping is the protective discharge of intense emotion, repetitive narrative, or crisis material into another person without sufficient consent, reciprocity, pacing, or responsibility for regulation.\n## Domain\nEmotion, Regulation, and Relationship\n## Related Patterns\nRumination; Confessional Overexposure; Reassurance Seeking; Urgency Addiction; Crisis Creation; Boundary Collapse\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am trying to transfer the pressure rather than metabolize it.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to tell someone everything right now.\n- Their capacity can wait because the pressure is unbearable.\n- If they set a limit, it means they are abandoning me.\n- Retelling the whole crisis may finally settle me.\n- I need another person to carry this feeling for me.\n- Pausing before sharing feels impossible.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to tell someone everything immediately; temporary relief after unloading; repeated need to retell the same event; panic when the listener sets limits; little curiosity about their capacity.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nLong uncontained disclosures; repetitive crisis narration; contacting multiple people with the same material; ignoring signs of listener fatigue; escalating detail to keep attention; resisting pauses, structure, or reciprocal conversation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCare and support; belonging; safety; regulation; trust; recognition.\n## Usually Triggered By\nEmotional flooding; loneliness; conflict; shame; fear; crisis; lack of other support; accumulated stress.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nNo one will help unless I make the pain impossible to ignore; I cannot hold this alone; limits mean abandonment; my feelings only become real when someone else carries them.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nSolitude; self-regulation; pacing; responsibility; uncertainty about support; the listener’s separateness and limits.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nOrphan—pain seeks immediate holding; Lover—closeness becomes unbounded disclosure; Caregiver—roles reverse without consent; Trickster—intensity keeps attention; Innocent—support is expected without limit.\n## Pattern Flow\nEmotional pressure builds → isolation or overwhelm feels intolerable → material is discharged into another → immediate relief and connection occur → the listener becomes overloaded or withdraws → abandonment fear and urgency increase.\n## Often Appears With\nRumination; Reassurance Seeking; Confessional Overexposure; Boundary Collapse; Crisis Creation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHonesty; emotional openness; desire for connection; willingness to seek support.\n## Current Cost\nListener exhaustion; ruptured trust; shame after disclosure; dependence on external regulation; reduced reciprocity; avoidance of sustained processing.\n## Freer Expression\nHonest sharing with consent, pacing, and shared responsibility.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk whether the person has capacity, name the time needed, and agree on the kind of support before disclosing.\n## Mira Language\n“The pressure sounds intense. Before you send or share all of it, would it help to decide who has capacity, what you need from them, and what part belongs in this conversation?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nAre you seeking connection, regulation, advice, validation, or immediate safety help? Has the listener consented and do they have capacity? What portion can be shared now, and what other support is needed?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNecessary crisis disclosure, trauma reporting, therapy, mutual intimacy, and asking for help are not automatically Emotional Dumping. Do not shame people for needing support.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of uncontained, nonconsensual, or one-sided discharge that ignores capacity and produces temporary relief without processing—not one intense disclosure during genuine crisis.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nValidate the need for support, reduce urgency enough to choose the right container, ask permission, pace the disclosure, and combine relational support with self-regulation or professional help where appropriate.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nState capacity honestly, offer a bounded form of support, redirect when needed, and avoid promising unlimited availability. In emergencies, prioritize appropriate crisis or safety resources.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where another person’s capacity or consent was overridden. Ask what impact occurred, accept boundaries without retaliation, and establish clearer agreements about timing, duration, and support roles.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Boundary Rigidity, Help-Rejection, Resentment, or Punitive Withdrawal. Often triggered by loneliness, Rejection Sensitivity, Emotional Flooding, or another person’s inconsistent availability. The loop may become: “You abandon me when I need you” and “Your needs leave no room for me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I sharing this for connection, or transferring pressure because I cannot yet hold it?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-INHIBITION": {"name":"Emotional Inhibition","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Numbing; Vulnerability Avoidance; Image Management; Compartmentalizing; Passive Aggression; Somatic tension.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler — composure at all costs. Caregiver — cannot burden others. Warrior — pain must remain invisible. Everyman — must not stand out.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Name the emotion privately or relationally before deciding how much to show.","Core Logic":"Feeling may be allowed, but showing it is not.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Disconnection; delayed processing; indirect expression; physical strain.","Core Fear":"Emotion causes chaos; visible feeling invites ridicule or punishment.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I can feel this, but I can’t let anyone see it.; I need to stay composed no matter what.; Tears would make me lose control.; My feelings would burden everyone else.; I should leave before the emotion shows.; It’s safer to edit the feeling before I speak.","Protective Move":"Emotional Inhibition is the protective suppression of visible feeling in order to prevent loss of control, burdening others, punishment, humiliation, or social disapproval.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-INHIBITION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary composure returns when expression is suppressed.","Freer Expression":"Regulated expression without self-betrayal.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Composure; restraint; situational awareness; care for impact.","Observable Cues":"Flat presentation; delayed reaction; leaving to regain control; highly edited emotional language.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not force disclosure; signal that emotion can be received without punishment or takeover. May trigger Escalation, Clinging, Mind Reading, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Self-Esteem, Belonging, and Autonomy; avoids helplessness, dependency, anger, and grief.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Inhibition"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Inhibition is the protective suppression of visible feeling in order to prevent loss of control, burdening others, punishment, humiliation, or social disapproval.\n## Domain\nEmotion, Expression, and Safety\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Numbing; Vulnerability Avoidance; Image Management; Compartmentalizing\n## Recognition Sentence\nFeeling may be allowed, but showing it is not.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I can feel this, but I can’t let anyone see it.\n- I need to stay composed no matter what.\n- Tears would make me lose control.\n- My feelings would burden everyone else.\n- I should leave before the emotion shows.\n- It’s safer to edit the feeling before I speak.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nTightening against tears or anger; monitoring expression; shame after visible emotion.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nFlat presentation; delayed reaction; leaving to regain control; highly edited emotional language.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Self-Esteem; Belonging; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConflict; public settings; grief; authority; family roles.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nEmotion causes chaos; visible feeling invites ridicule or punishment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHelplessness; dependency; anger; grief.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler — composure at all costs. Caregiver — cannot burden others. Warrior — pain must remain invisible. Everyman — must not stand out.\n## Pattern Flow\nEmotion rises → safety or belonging feels threatened → expression is suppressed → temporary composure → emotion returns indirectly or remains unprocessed.\n## Often Appears With\nCompartmentalizing; Emotional Numbing; Passive Aggression; Somatic tension.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nComposure; restraint; situational awareness; care for impact.\n## Current Cost\nDisconnection; delayed processing; indirect expression; physical strain.\n## Freer Expression\nRegulated expression without self-betrayal.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the emotion privately or relationally before deciding how much to show.\n## Mira Language\n“Your restraint may have protected you well. Is it still a chosen response, or has expression become unavailable?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat emotion is being managed? What consequence do you predict? What form of expression would remain safe and proportionate?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nComposure, professionalism, cultural norms, and temporary containment are not inherently problematic.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated suppression that produces relational or internal cost.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate the body, validate the feeling, and choose an appropriate channel and dose of expression.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not force disclosure; signal that emotion can be received without punishment or takeover.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where silence or apparent indifference obscured important impact; communicate the feeling and needed future behavior.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Escalation, Clinging, Mind Reading, or Resentment. Often triggered by Criticism, Intimidation, Emotional volatility, or unsafe disclosure histories.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat feeling am I containing, and is the containment still serving me?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-NUMBING": {"name":"Emotional Numbing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Distancing; Compartmentalizing; Denial; Stonewalling; Dissociation; Busyness as Avoidance.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior suppresses pain to continue; Caregiver becomes functional; Ruler prioritizes order; Lover disconnects after repeated injury; Innocent avoids unbearable reality.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Notice and name one small feeling without requiring access to the whole emotional load.","Core Logic":"I am turning down feeling because full contact seems too costly.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Disconnection; reduced joy; delayed grief; relational confusion; difficulty recognizing danger or desire.","Core Fear":"Feeling will overwhelm me; no one will help; caring makes me vulnerable; emotion interferes with survival.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I don’t really feel anything about it.; I just need to keep functioning.; Caring less is easier right now.; I know I should feel something, but I don’t.; I can’t afford to let this hit me.; It’s safer to turn the volume down.","Protective Move":"Emotional Numbing is the protective reduction of felt intensity, concern, pleasure, or pain when full emotional contact seems overwhelming, dangerous, or unmanageable.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-NUMBING","Short-Term Payoff":"Feeling is dampened and functioning becomes possible.","Freer Expression":"Titrated feeling with support.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Endurance; stabilization; crisis functioning.","Observable Cues":"Muted response to major events; retreat into routines or screens; reduced affection; mechanical functioning; difficulty naming needs.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not demand emotional performance; offer steadiness, choices, and boundaries while naming relational impact. May trigger Clinging, Testing the Bond, Criticism, or despair in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Trust, Autonomy, and Competence; avoids grief, terror, rage, longing, and helplessness.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Numbing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Numbing is the protective reduction of felt intensity, concern, pleasure, or pain when full emotional contact seems overwhelming, dangerous, or unmanageable.\n## Domain\nAvoidance and Emotional Escape\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Distancing; Compartmentalizing; Denial; Stonewalling; Dissociation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am turning down feeling because full contact seems too costly.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I don’t really feel anything about it.\n- I just need to keep functioning.\n- Caring less is easier right now.\n- I know I should feel something, but I don’t.\n- I can’t afford to let this hit me.\n- It’s safer to turn the volume down.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nFlatness; distance from joy and grief; delayed emotional response; “I know I should feel something”; relief in not caring.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nMuted response to major events; retreat into routines or screens; reduced affection; mechanical functioning; difficulty naming needs.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Trust; Autonomy; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nOverload; chronic conflict; grief; trauma reminders; burnout; repeated disappointment.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nFeeling will overwhelm me; no one will help; caring makes me vulnerable; emotion interferes with survival.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; terror; rage; longing; helplessness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior suppresses pain to continue; Caregiver becomes functional; Ruler prioritizes order; Lover disconnects after repeated injury; Innocent avoids unbearable reality.\n## Pattern Flow\nIntensity exceeds capacity → feeling is dampened → functioning becomes possible → relief arrives → connection, pleasure, and processing also diminish.\n## Often Appears With\nEmotional Distancing; Compartmentalizing; Busyness as Avoidance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEndurance; stabilization; crisis functioning.\n## Current Cost\nDisconnection; reduced joy; delayed grief; relational confusion; difficulty recognizing danger or desire.\n## Freer Expression\nTitrated feeling with support.\n## One Act of Volition\nNotice and name one small feeling without requiring access to the whole emotional load.\n## Mira Language\n“Numbness may be a way your system reduced an unbearable volume. We do not need to force everything open at once.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat was happening when feeling became too much? What amount of contact feels tolerable? What support is missing?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nMedication effects, depression, neurological conditions, trauma responses, and exhaustion require careful differentiation; Mira must not diagnose.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated reduction in emotional access linked to overload or threat, not simply calm temperament.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nApproach feeling gradually, restore bodily safety, and seek appropriate support when numbness is persistent or severe.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not demand emotional performance; offer steadiness, choices, and boundaries while naming relational impact.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where absence or flatness left another person alone, explain without excusing, and create a realistic signal for pauses and later re-engagement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Testing the Bond, Criticism, or despair in others. Often triggered by pursuit, conflict, overwhelm, or repeated unmet need.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat feeling became too expensive to keep feeling?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-OVERRESPONSIBILITY": {"name":"Emotional Overresponsibility","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"People-Pleasing; Overfunctioning; Rescuing; Boundary Collapse; Martyrdom; Guilt Induction.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver—care becomes compulsory regulation; Peacemaker—harmony becomes self-erasure; Ruler—manages everyone’s state; Lover—takes responsibility for all closeness.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record. Spacing and heading variants normalized. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Ask, “What is mine to acknowledge, and what belongs to them to feel or choose?” before acting.","Core Logic":"If they are upset, it must be my job to make it better.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; resentment; distorted accountability; enabling; loss of autonomy; unequal relationships.","Core Fear":"Other people’s distress is dangerous; love depends on emotional caretaking; boundaries cause abandonment; I am good only when useful.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If they are upset, I must fix it.; Their reaction is my responsibility.; I should change my boundary so they feel better.; I cannot relax while someone is disappointed.; Caring means preventing their distress.; If I do not manage this, the relationship may collapse.","Protective Move":"Assumes responsibility for managing, preventing, absorbing, or repairing other people’s feelings in order to preserve safety, belonging, worth, or relational stability.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-OVERRESPONSIBILITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Fixing or appeasing reduces immediate tension.","Freer Expression":"Care without ownership.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Empathy; care; attunement; responsibility; responsiveness.","Observable Cues":"Overexplaining; rescuing; changing boundaries to regulate another person; apologizing for legitimate needs; absorbing blame; managing the emotional climate.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify what support is requested and avoid making another person responsible for regulating you. May invite Underfunctioning, Dependency, Entitlement, or Guilt Induction.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, safety, dignity, trust, and worth; avoids powerlessness, another person’s autonomy, legitimate conflict, uncertainty, and one’s own needs.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Overresponsibility"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Overresponsibility is the protective assumption that one must manage, prevent, absorb, or repair other people’s feelings in order to preserve safety, belonging, worth, or relational stability.\n## Domain\nCare, Responsibility, and Attachment\n## Related Patterns\nPeople-Pleasing; Overfunctioning; Rescuing; Boundary Collapse; Martyrdom; Guilt Induction\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf they are upset, it must be my job to make it better.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If they are upset, I must fix it.\n- Their reaction is my responsibility.\n- I should change my boundary so they feel better.\n- I cannot relax while someone is disappointed.\n- Caring means preventing their distress.\n- If I do not manage this, the relationship may collapse.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nMonitoring others’ moods; guilt before actual wrongdoing is established; anxiety when someone is disappointed; difficulty distinguishing care from responsibility.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOverexplaining, rescuing, changing boundaries to regulate another person, apologizing for legitimate needs, absorbing blame, managing the emotional climate.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; safety; dignity; trust; worth.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConflict; disappointment; anger; tears; silence; requests for help; perceived fragility.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nOther people’s distress is dangerous; love depends on emotional caretaking; boundaries cause abandonment; I am good only when useful.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nPowerlessness; another person’s autonomy; legitimate conflict; uncertainty; one’s own needs.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver—care becomes compulsory regulation; Peacemaker—harmony becomes self-erasure; Ruler—manages everyone’s state; Lover—takes responsibility for all closeness.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother person shows distress → belonging or safety feels threatened → responsibility expands → fixing or appeasing reduces immediate tension → boundaries blur → resentment and dependency grow.\n## Often Appears With\nPeople-Pleasing; Rescuing; Overfunctioning; Self-Erasure; Excessive Apologizing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEmpathy; care; attunement; responsibility; responsiveness.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; resentment; distorted accountability; enabling; loss of autonomy; unequal relationships.\n## Freer Expression\nCare without ownership.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk, “What is mine to acknowledge, and what belongs to them to feel or choose?” before acting.\n## Mira Language\n“You may care deeply about their feelings while taking responsibility for more than your actual impact. Can we separate what you caused, what you can repair, and what remains theirs?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat specific action of yours requires accountability? What are you assuming responsibility for without evidence? What would caring look like without taking over?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nActual harm, caregiving obligations, parenting duties, disability support, and power differences require concrete responsibility; boundaries must not become neglect.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated assumption of responsibility for others’ emotional states beyond one’s actual actions or agreements.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName genuine impact, make proportionate repair, tolerate another person’s remaining feelings, and return responsibility without contempt.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify what support is requested, avoid making the person responsible for regulating you, and respect a no without using distress as leverage.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where overresponsibility became control, resentment, enabling, or covert expectation. Re-establish explicit responsibilities and permit each person to hold their own feelings and choices.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay invite Underfunctioning, Dependency, Entitlement, or Guilt Induction. The loop becomes “I must keep everyone okay” versus “You will handle this for me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat feeling am I treating as mine to manage when it may belong to someone else?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-POSTPONEMENT": {"name":"Emotional Postponement","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Inhibition; Emotional Numbing; Busyness as Avoidance; Compartmentalizing; Intellectualizing; Overfunctioning.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior—keeps marching; Caregiver—serves before grieving; Ruler—maintains order; Creator—works instead of feeling.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record. Spacing repaired and canonical headings normalized. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source. Medical Differential flag reflects explicit trauma/depression/neurological/medication caution.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Schedule a specific ten-minute return to the feeling and keep the appointment.","Core Logic":"I will feel this later, once everything else is handled.","Safety Flags":["Medical Differential"],"Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Delayed grief; irritability; collapse; somatic strain; reduced intimacy; loss of emotional information.","Core Fear":"Feelings interfere with survival; no one will help if I stop; emotion is dangerous or indulgent; functioning earns belonging.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I will deal with this later.; There is no time to feel right now.; I have to keep functioning.; Once everything is handled, I can stop.; Feeling this now would overwhelm me.; Work is safer than contact with what I feel.","Protective Move":"Repeatedly defers contact with one’s feelings until a supposedly safer or more convenient time that rarely arrives.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-POSTPONEMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Attention shifts to function and temporary competence returns.","Freer Expression":"Timed containment with a real return.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Timing; discipline; containment; crisis competence; devotion.","Observable Cues":"Staying continuously busy; delaying grief or anger; changing topics when emotion appears; functioning effectively until sudden collapse or numbness.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not demand immediate disclosure; offer a clear invitation and future time while setting limits if perpetual postponement harms the relationship.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, competence, control, dignity, and continuity; avoids grief, anger, exhaustion, vulnerability, unmet needs, and dependence.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Postponement"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Postponement is the protective habit of repeatedly deferring contact with one’s feelings until a supposedly safer or more convenient time that rarely arrives.\n## Domain\nEmotion, Capacity, and Self-Contact\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Inhibition; Emotional Numbing; Busyness as Avoidance; Compartmentalizing; Intellectualizing; Overfunctioning\n## Recognition Sentence\nI will feel this later, once everything else is handled.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I will deal with this later.\n- There is no time to feel right now.\n- I have to keep functioning.\n- Once everything is handled, I can stop.\n- Feeling this now would overwhelm me.\n- Work is safer than contact with what I feel.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPressure building beneath competence; fear that feeling will become unmanageable; relief from returning to tasks; vague emotional backlog.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nStaying continuously busy; delaying grief or anger; changing topics when emotion appears; functioning effectively until sudden collapse or numbness.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; competence; control; dignity; continuity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCrisis; deadlines; caregiving; loss; conflict; situations where expression feels unsafe.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nFeelings interfere with survival; no one will help if I stop; emotion is dangerous or indulgent; functioning earns belonging.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; anger; exhaustion; vulnerability; unmet needs; dependence.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior—keeps marching; Caregiver—serves before grieving; Ruler—maintains order; Creator—works instead of feeling.\n## Pattern Flow\nEmotion arises during demand → feeling seems unsafe or inconvenient → attention shifts to function → temporary competence returns → emotional material accumulates → later access becomes harder or erupts unexpectedly.\n## Often Appears With\nBusyness as Avoidance; Overfunctioning; Emotional Numbing; Compartmentalizing; Productivity-Bound Worth.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nTiming; discipline; containment; crisis competence; devotion.\n## Current Cost\nDelayed grief; irritability; collapse; somatic strain; reduced intimacy; loss of emotional information.\n## Freer Expression\nTimed containment with a real return.\n## One Act of Volition\nSchedule a specific ten-minute return to the feeling and keep the appointment.\n## Mira Language\n“Postponing emotion can be wise during a real demand. The question is whether there is a reliable return. When will you come back to what you are carrying?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nIs this containment temporary or indefinite? What support would make contact safer? What is the smallest amount you can feel without flooding?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nTemporary compartmentalization during emergencies can be adaptive. Trauma, depression, neurological conditions, medication effects, and exhaustion require care beyond pattern framing.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated deferral without meaningful return, especially when emotional backlog creates cost.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the protector’s timing, create bounded space, orient to present safety, and allow partial feeling rather than forcing catharsis.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not demand immediate disclosure. Offer a clear invitation and a future time, while setting limits if perpetual postponement harms the relationship.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where repeated postponement left others alone, delayed necessary conversations, or converted unprocessed emotion into irritability or withdrawal. Return with specificity and follow-through.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Chasing, Resentment, Criticism, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “There is never room for my feelings” versus “Your feelings will overwhelm me if I stop.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat have I repeatedly promised myself I would feel later?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-REASONING": {"name":"Emotional Reasoning","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Mind Reading; Catastrophizing; Personalization; Projection; Confirmation Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — felt distance becomes proof of rejection. Warrior — fear becomes proof of threat. Sage — intuition becomes certainty. Innocent — discomfort becomes proof something is wrong. Ruler — anxiety becomes proof control is necessary.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Say, “I feel X, and the story I am telling is Y,” then list evidence for and against it.","Core Logic":"Because I feel it strongly, it must be true.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"False conclusions; escalation; impaired judgment; invalidation of others’ reality.","Core Fear":"My feelings are the only reliable signal; ambiguity is unsafe; if I doubt my feeling, I will miss danger.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I feel rejected, so you must be rejecting me.; This fear proves something is wrong.; My shame means I failed.; I can feel the danger, so the danger is real.; The intensity tells me the story is true.; If the facts disagree with the feeling, the facts must be missing something.","Protective Move":"Emotional Reasoning treats a feeling as sufficient proof that an interpretation is true, using emotional certainty to reduce ambiguity.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-REASONING","Short-Term Payoff":"Certainty and action follow when feeling becomes evidence.","Freer Expression":"Feelings as data, not verdicts.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Emotional sensitivity; intuition; rapid threat detection.","Observable Cues":"“I feel rejected, so you rejected me”; treating anxiety as proof of danger; acting on shame as proof of failure; dismissing contradictory evidence.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Validate the feeling without confirming an unsupported conclusion; offer clear information and invite checking. May trigger Defensiveness, Overexplaining, Withdrawal, or Micromanaging.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Safety, Self-Esteem, and Belonging; avoids uncertainty, inquiry, patience, mixed evidence, and possible error.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Reasoning"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Reasoning treats a feeling as sufficient proof that an interpretation is true, using emotional certainty to reduce ambiguity.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nMind Reading; Catastrophizing; Personalization; Projection; Confirmation Seeking\n## Recognition Sentence\nBecause I feel it strongly, it must be true.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I feel rejected, so you must be rejecting me.\n- This fear proves something is wrong.\n- My shame means I failed.\n- I can feel the danger, so the danger is real.\n- The intensity tells me the story is true.\n- If the facts disagree with the feeling, the facts must be missing something.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nCertainty rising with intensity; difficulty separating sensation from evidence; urgent conclusions; feeling invalidated when facts differ.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n“I feel rejected, so you rejected me”; treating anxiety as proof of danger; acting on shame as proof of failure; dismissing contradictory evidence.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Safety; Self-Esteem; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; delayed responses; conflict; bodily activation; prior trauma reminders; uncertainty.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy feelings are the only reliable signal. Ambiguity is unsafe. If I doubt my feeling, I will miss danger.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; inquiry; patience; mixed evidence; possible error.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — felt distance becomes proof of rejection. Warrior — fear becomes proof of threat. Sage — intuition becomes certainty. Innocent — discomfort becomes proof something is wrong. Ruler — anxiety becomes proof control is necessary.\n## Pattern Flow\nStrong feeling arises → ambiguity becomes intolerable → feeling becomes evidence → certainty and action follow → contradictory data is excluded → the feeling is reinforced.\n## Often Appears With\nMind Reading; Catastrophizing; Projection; Personalization.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEmotional sensitivity; intuition; rapid threat detection.\n## Current Cost\nFalse conclusions; escalation; impaired judgment; invalidation of others’ reality.\n## Freer Expression\nFeelings as data, not verdicts.\n## One Act of Volition\nSay, “I feel X, and the story I am telling is Y,” then list evidence for and against it.\n## Mira Language\n“The feeling is real. Can we hold it as important information without making it the only proof?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat facts support the story? What facts do not? What else could produce this feeling?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nIntuition can be accurate; emotional reasoning is the untested leap from feeling to certainty.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated reliance on emotional intensity as decisive evidence despite ambiguity or contradiction.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate activation; separate feeling, interpretation, and fact; delay action until more evidence is available.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nValidate the feeling without confirming an unsupported conclusion; offer clear information and invite checking.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge actions taken as though the interpretation were proven, restore factual clarity, and agree on a future checking process.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Overexplaining, Withdrawal, or Micromanaging. Often triggered by ambiguity, secrecy, inconsistency, or Mind Reading. The loop becomes “My feeling proves danger” versus “Your certainty makes me unsafe.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I treating as proven because it feels intense?"},
  "PP-EMOTIONAL-WITHHOLDING": {"name":"Emotional Withholding","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Inhibition; Emotional Distancing; Punitive Silence; Vulnerability Avoidance; Image Management; Hyper-Independence; Suspicion; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Lover conceals devotion; Ruler preserves leverage; Warrior refuses visible softness; Sage substitutes analysis for disclosure.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Share one truthful feeling or relational fact without overexplaining or demanding a response.","Core Logic":"I am keeping meaningful feeling unavailable so I cannot be exposed, obligated, or hurt.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Loneliness; ambiguity; unequal intimacy; pursuit-withdrawal loops; erosion of trust.","Core Fear":"Vulnerability is exploitable; affection creates obligation; the one who cares less is safer.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It is safer if they do not know how much I care.; Affection would give away too much leverage.; I should keep my feelings vague.; If I share warmth, I may become obligated or exposed.; The one who cares less is safer.; They can figure out how I feel without me saying it.","Protective Move":"Emotional Withholding is the protective restriction of warmth, affirmation, vulnerability, or relational information to avoid dependence, exposure, loss of leverage, or anticipated disappointment.","Pattern ID":"PP-EMOTIONAL-WITHHOLDING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns when feeling or information is withheld.","Freer Expression":"Boundaried openness.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Privacy; discernment; emotional containment; careful pacing.","Observable Cues":"Rare affirmation; vague answers about feelings; withholding important relational information; coolness after closeness; making others guess.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite clarity without coercing disclosure; name the impact of ambiguity and decide what level of openness is necessary for continued participation. Often triggers Clinging, Compulsive Contact, Rejection Sensitivity, or Testing the Bond.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Safety, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids need, tenderness, grief, dependence, and accountability for relational impact.","Canonical Name":"Emotional Withholding"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEmotional Withholding is the protective restriction of warmth, affirmation, vulnerability, or relational information to avoid dependence, exposure, loss of leverage, or anticipated disappointment.\n## Domain\nVulnerability, Attachment, and Relational Control\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Inhibition; Emotional Distancing; Punitive Silence; Vulnerability Avoidance; Image Management.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am keeping meaningful feeling unavailable so I cannot be exposed, obligated, or hurt.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It is safer if they do not know how much I care.\n- Affection would give away too much leverage.\n- I should keep my feelings vague.\n- If I share warmth, I may become obligated or exposed.\n- The one who cares less is safer.\n- They can figure out how I feel without me saying it.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nWarmth feels risky; appreciation feels like surrender; urge to keep feelings private even when connection is desired; fear that disclosure will be used against you.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRare affirmation; vague answers about feelings; withholding important relational information; coolness after closeness; making others guess.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Safety; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nIncreased intimacy; conflict; requests for reassurance; prior betrayal; fear of losing power; shame.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nVulnerability is exploitable; affection creates obligation; the one who cares less is safer.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nNeed; tenderness; grief; dependence; accountability for relational impact.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover conceals devotion; Ruler preserves leverage; Warrior refuses visible softness; Sage substitutes analysis for disclosure.\n## Pattern Flow\nCloseness or emotional demand rises → vulnerability feels dangerous → feeling or information is withheld → temporary control returns → the other person becomes uncertain or pursues harder → withholding intensifies.\n## Often Appears With\nEmotional Distancing; Hyper-Independence; Suspicion; Image Management; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nPrivacy; discernment; emotional containment; careful pacing.\n## Current Cost\nLoneliness; ambiguity; unequal intimacy; pursuit-withdrawal loops; erosion of trust.\n## Freer Expression\nBoundaried openness.\n## One Act of Volition\nShare one truthful feeling or relational fact without overexplaining or demanding a response.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be protecting something by keeping your inner position unavailable. What would become vulnerable if the other person knew what you actually feel?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nIs this privacy, pacing, or protection through unavailability? What information does the relationship reasonably require?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nPrivacy, confidentiality, cultural reserve, and safety-based nondisclosure are not withholding.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of concealing relevant emotional information in ways that preserve control or avoid vulnerability and create relational uncertainty.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nChoose paced, bounded truth rather than total exposure or strategic opacity.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite clarity without coercing disclosure; name the impact of ambiguity and decide what level of openness is necessary for continued participation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where meaningful feeling or information was withheld and how that affected consent, trust, or connection; provide the needed truth without blaming the other person for not guessing.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nOften triggers Clinging, Compulsive Contact, Rejection Sensitivity, or Testing the Bond; those responses may then reinforce the belief that openness leads to pressure.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I keeping unavailable, and what form of honest openness would still protect my boundaries?"},
  "PP-ENDLESS-PREPARATION": {"name":"Endless Preparation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Perfectionism; Procrastination; Failure to Launch; Defensive Expertise; Rumination.","Archetypal Role":"Sage keeps researching; Creator keeps gathering materials; Magician waits for total mastery; Ruler keeps building systems; Explorer keeps scouting without choosing a path.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Define the minimum preparation threshold and test something before adding another resource.","Core Logic":"I am staying in preparation because preparation cannot yet be judged.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Delayed learning from reality; sunk cost; blocked contribution; exhaustion.","Core Fear":"I must know everything before acting; being unprepared is humiliating; mistakes expose fraudulence.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need one more resource before I begin.; I’m not quite ready to test this yet.; Another course will help me feel qualified.; I should refine the plan before acting.; I can’t start until I know enough.; The preparation still isn’t complete.","Protective Move":"Endless Preparation is the protective extension of research, planning, organizing, or training so that action and exposure can remain indefinitely postponed.","Pattern ID":"PP-ENDLESS-PREPARATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary confidence returns as preparation expands.","Freer Expression":"Preparation in service of practice.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Diligence; foresight; scholarship; stewardship.","Observable Cues":"Accumulating resources; redesigning plans; repeated courses or certifications; refining systems before testing; moving the readiness threshold.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Recognize diligence, ask for a decision rule, and avoid supplying endless reassurance or new material. May trigger Impatience, Micromanaging, Disbelief, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Autonomy; avoids beginnerhood, feedback, dependence, incompleteness, and irreversible choice.","Canonical Name":"Endless Preparation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEndless Preparation is the protective extension of research, planning, organizing, or training so that action and exposure can remain indefinitely postponed.\n## Domain\nCompetence, Creation, and Performance\n## Related Patterns\nPerfectionism; Procrastination; Failure to Launch; Defensive Expertise; Rumination\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am staying in preparation because preparation cannot yet be judged.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need one more resource before I begin.\n- I’m not quite ready to test this yet.\n- Another course will help me feel qualified.\n- I should refine the plan before acting.\n- I can’t start until I know enough.\n- The preparation still isn’t complete.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nOne more course, tool, source, or revision feels necessary; action feels premature; preparation brings relief and legitimacy.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAccumulating resources; redesigning plans; repeated courses or certifications; refining systems before testing; moving the readiness threshold.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Self-Esteem; Trust; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nVisibility; novel tasks; uncertainty; public commitment; comparison.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI must know everything before acting; being unprepared is humiliating; mistakes expose fraudulence.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nBeginnerhood; feedback; dependence; incompleteness; irreversible choice.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage keeps researching; Creator keeps gathering materials; Magician waits for total mastery; Ruler keeps building systems; Explorer keeps scouting without choosing a path.\n## Pattern Flow\nAction approaches → competence feels threatened → preparation expands → temporary confidence returns → action recedes → readiness becomes less attainable.\n## Often Appears With\nPerfectionism; Procrastination; Defensive Expertise.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiligence; foresight; scholarship; stewardship.\n## Current Cost\nDelayed learning from reality; sunk cost; blocked contribution; exhaustion.\n## Freer Expression\nPreparation in service of practice.\n## One Act of Volition\nDefine the minimum preparation threshold and test something before adding another resource.\n## Mira Language\n“Is this preparation still reducing meaningful risk, or is it keeping the work untested?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat must truly be known first? What can only be learned by doing? Where has the threshold moved?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSafety-critical preparation and legitimate skill development are not pathological.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated expansion of preparation after practical readiness has been reached.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nChoose a test date and permit reality to become the next teacher.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRecognize diligence, ask for a decision rule, and avoid supplying endless reassurance or new material.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where preparation delayed shared plans or transferred burdens, then establish an agreed launch threshold and visible test.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Impatience, Micromanaging, Disbelief, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by criticism, unstable expectations, or another person’s urgency.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I preparing for that can now be practiced?"},
  "PP-ENTITLEMENT": {"name":"Entitlement","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Grandiosity; Status Guarding; Dominance; Moral Licensing; Obligation Leverage; Selective Accountability; Guilt Induction.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler—authority becomes exemption; Warrior—sacrifice becomes a claim over others; Caregiver—care becomes ownership; Lover—devotion becomes access; Sage—knowledge becomes immunity from correction.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the source explicitly addresses coercive pressure, presumed access, boundary violations, consent, and punishment after limits.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"State the need directly while explicitly recognizing the other person’s equal agency and right to decline.","Core Logic":"Because of who I am, what I have done, or what I have endured, I should not have to accept this limit.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Damaged trust; coercive pressure; asymmetrical relationships; resentment; poor accountability; inability to tolerate ordinary limits.","Core Fear":"I am unseen unless prioritized; my value must be proven through special treatment; ordinary need will not be answered; power is the only reliable protection.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They should make an exception for me.; After what I have done, I deserve special treatment.; Their refusal feels like disrespect.; My need should override this boundary.; The rules should not apply to me in the same way.; If they valued me, they would give me the outcome I want.","Protective Move":"Entitlement is the protective expectation that one’s needs, preferences, status, effort, suffering, or identity should exempt one from ordinary limits, reciprocity, consent, or accountability. It protects worth and significance by converting desire into presumed obligation from others.","Pattern ID":"PP-ENTITLEMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Pressure or exception-seeking brings temporary control when deservingness intensifies.","Freer Expression":"Dignity without exemption.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Self-worth; confidence; recognition of legitimate need; willingness to claim space.","Observable Cues":"Expecting special access or accommodation; treating boundaries as negotiable only when inconvenient; demanding gratitude, loyalty, attention, labor, or forgiveness; applying rules asymmetrically; reacting with contempt, anger, or injury when refused.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Name the boundary and agreement clearly. Do not bargain against pressure merely to stop escalation. Recognize valid needs without accepting presumed access, labor, intimacy, forgiveness, or exemption. May trigger Appeasement, Self-Erasure, Resentment, Withdrawal, or Retaliation.","Emotional Function":"Protects dignity, recognition, belonging, fairness, agency, care, security, and significance; avoids dependence, limitation, equality, disappointment, mutual obligation, and grief over unmet needs.","Canonical Name":"Entitlement"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEntitlement is the protective expectation that one’s needs, preferences, status, effort, suffering, or identity should exempt one from ordinary limits, reciprocity, consent, or accountability. It protects worth and significance by converting desire into presumed obligation from others.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Status, Power, and Reciprocity\n## Related Patterns\nGrandiosity; Status Guarding; Dominance; Moral Licensing; Obligation Leverage; Selective Accountability\n## Recognition Sentence\nBecause of who I am, what I have done, or what I have endured, I should not have to accept this limit.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They should make an exception for me.\n- After what I have done, I deserve special treatment.\n- Their refusal feels like disrespect.\n- My need should override this boundary.\n- The rules should not apply to me in the same way.\n- If they valued me, they would give me the outcome I want.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nLimits feel insulting; another person’s refusal feels disrespectful; contribution creates a felt debt; exceptions feel deserved; ordinary reciprocity feels beneath one’s position.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nExpecting special access or accommodation; treating boundaries as negotiable only when inconvenient; demanding gratitude, loyalty, attention, labor, or forgiveness; applying rules asymmetrically; reacting with contempt, anger, or injury when refused.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nDignity; recognition; belonging; fairness; agency; care; security; significance.\n## Usually Triggered By\nRefusal; waiting; equal treatment; loss of privilege; reduced attention; accountability; another person asserting autonomy.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am unseen unless prioritized; my value must be proven through special treatment; ordinary need will not be answered; power is the only reliable protection.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependence; limitation; equality; disappointment; mutual obligation; grief over unmet needs.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler—authority becomes exemption; Warrior—sacrifice becomes a claim over others; Caregiver—care becomes ownership; Lover—devotion becomes access; Sage—knowledge becomes immunity from correction.\n## Pattern Flow\nA limit or refusal appears → dignity or significance feels threatened → deservingness is intensified → pressure or exception-seeking brings temporary control → consent and reciprocity erode → conflict confirms the belief that others are disrespectful or ungrateful.\n## Often Appears With\nGrandiosity; Dominance; Guilt Induction; Obligation Leverage; Moral Licensing; Selective Accountability.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSelf-worth; confidence; recognition of legitimate need; willingness to claim space.\n## Current Cost\nDamaged trust; coercive pressure; asymmetrical relationships; resentment; poor accountability; inability to tolerate ordinary limits.\n## Freer Expression\nDignity without exemption.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the need directly while explicitly recognizing the other person’s equal agency and right to decline.\n## Mira Language\n“Your need may be real. I also notice that the refusal is being interpreted as an offense against your worth. Can we separate deserving dignity from being owed this particular outcome?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you believe this person owes you? What agreement created that obligation? Would the same rule apply in reverse?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLegitimate rights, accessibility needs, contractual obligations, restitution, and naming unequal power are not entitlement. Do not use the term to silence marginalized people asserting fair treatment.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of presumed exemption, asymmetric rules, or pressure after clear limits—not one strong request or moment of disappointment.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nValidate the underlying need and injury without converting them into ownership of another person. Separate right, request, agreement, and preference; tolerate disappointment; identify an ethical path that preserves equal agency.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nName the boundary and agreement clearly. Do not bargain against pressure merely to stop escalation. Recognize valid needs without accepting presumed access, labor, intimacy, forgiveness, or exemption.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the pressure, asymmetry, or boundary violation; name the impact; relinquish the claimed exemption; make restitution where appropriate; demonstrate changed behavior by accepting future limits without punishment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Self-Erasure, Resentment, Withdrawal, or Retaliation. Often triggered by Status Loss, Rejection Sensitivity, Scarcity, or perceived ingratitude. Stories become “My needs do not matter unless I force recognition” and “My autonomy is unsafe around you.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere have I confused dignity with being owed a particular response?"},
  "PP-ESCAPE-AT-INTIMACY": {"name":"Escape at the Point of Intimacy","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Distancing; Preemptive Detachment; Vulnerability Avoidance; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Commitment Avoidance; Self-Sabotage.","Archetypal Role":"Lover flees reciprocity; Rebel equates closeness with captivity; Wanderer leaves before roots form; Ruler maintains distance to preserve control.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing repaired. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Name the urge to flee and ask for a bounded pause without ending or destabilizing the bond.","Core Logic":"I move away when closeness becomes real enough to matter.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Repeated rupture; loneliness; unstable attachment; mistrust; inability to discover whether intimacy can remain safe.","Core Fear":"Closeness leads to engulfment, betrayal, abandonment, control, humiliation, or loss of self.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need distance now that this feels real.; Closeness is becoming dangerous.; I should leave before I lose myself.; Their flaws suddenly feel impossible to ignore.; I was interested until they became available.; A rupture would restore my freedom.","Protective Move":"Withdraws, destabilizes, devalues, redirects, or creates distance precisely when closeness, mutual dependence, commitment, or being deeply known becomes real.","Pattern ID":"PP-ESCAPE-AT-INTIMACY","Short-Term Payoff":"Distance or rupture creates immediate relief.","Freer Expression":"Closeness with retained selfhood.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; autonomy; sensitivity to enmeshment; capacity to leave unsafe situations.","Observable Cues":"Pulling away after vulnerable moments; provoking rupture near milestones; abrupt devaluation; shifting attention to unavailable people; ending relationships without addressing the intimacy trigger.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not chase, corner, or reward destabilization; offer clarity and a reasonable pause while maintaining boundaries.","Emotional Function":"Protects autonomy, safety, dignity, trust, and belonging; avoids dependency, grief, uncertainty, ordinary imperfection, and responsibility to remain present.","Canonical Name":"Escape at the Point of Intimacy"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nEscape at the Point of Intimacy is a recurring protective move in which a person withdraws, destabilizes, devalues, redirects, or creates distance precisely when closeness, mutual dependence, commitment, or being deeply known becomes real.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Intimacy, and Relational Safety\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Distancing; Preemptive Detachment; Vulnerability Avoidance; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Commitment Avoidance; Self-Sabotage\n## Recognition Sentence\nI move away when closeness becomes real enough to matter.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need distance now that this feels real.\n- Closeness is becoming dangerous.\n- I should leave before I lose myself.\n- Their flaws suddenly feel impossible to ignore.\n- I was interested until they became available.\n- A rupture would restore my freedom.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSudden restlessness near commitment; attraction fading when reciprocity appears; urge to find flaws; fear of being engulfed, exposed, or dependent.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nPulling away after vulnerable moments; provoking rupture near milestones; abrupt devaluation; shifting attention to unavailable people; ending relationships without addressing the intimacy trigger.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; safety; dignity; trust; belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nMutual commitment; emotional disclosure; being needed; being seen accurately; relationship milestones; dependence.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nCloseness leads to engulfment, betrayal, abandonment, control, humiliation, or loss of self.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependency; grief; uncertainty; ordinary imperfection; responsibility to remain present.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover flees reciprocity; Rebel equates closeness with captivity; Wanderer leaves before roots form; Ruler maintains distance to preserve control.\n## Pattern Flow\nIntimacy deepens → autonomy or safety feels threatened → distance or rupture is created → immediate relief → loss and confusion follow → closeness feels even more dangerous next time.\n## Often Appears With\nDevaluation; Preemptive Detachment; Strategic Ambiguity; Commitment Avoidance; Self-Sabotage.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; autonomy; sensitivity to enmeshment; capacity to leave unsafe situations.\n## Current Cost\nRepeated rupture; loneliness; unstable attachment; mistrust; inability to discover whether intimacy can remain safe.\n## Freer Expression\nCloseness with retained selfhood.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the urge to flee and ask for a bounded pause without ending or destabilizing the bond.\n## Mira Language\n“You describe losing interest or creating distance just as closeness became mutual. That can be a protective move around intimacy, but it could also reflect genuine incompatibility. What changed inside you when the relationship became more real?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did closeness begin to require? What felt endangered—freedom, identity, safety, or dignity? Did you communicate a boundary before withdrawing?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLeaving an unsafe, coercive, incompatible, or unwanted relationship is not this pattern. A single ending is not sufficient evidence.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated timing around closeness or commitment, with relief after distancing and recurring long-term regret or repetition.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate actual incompatibility from activation. Slow the decision, restore bandwidth, and state the threatened need directly.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not chase, corner, or reward destabilization. Offer clarity and a reasonable pause while maintaining boundaries around disappearance, threats, or repeated rupture.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName the timing and impact, acknowledge any destabilizing behavior, clarify whether re-engagement is genuinely chosen, and establish a concrete communication agreement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Reassurance Seeking, Testing the Bond, or Anger as Armor in others; those responses can intensify the urge to flee.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat becomes frightening precisely when closeness begins to feel possible?"},
  "PP-EXCESSIVE-APOLOGIZING": {"name":"Excessive Apologizing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Appeasement; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Shame Spiraling; Personalization.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver—apologizes for needing care; Lover—absorbs blame to preserve closeness; Innocent—tries to prove goodness; Orphan—expects belonging to be withdrawn.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Replace one automatic “sorry” with either “thank you,” a clear request, or a precise acknowledgment of your actual part.","Core Logic":"I am using apology to make myself safer, not only to repair harm.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"False responsibility; resentment; blurred accountability; weakened boundaries; apologies losing meaning.","Core Fear":"Peace depends on my self-blame; other people’s feelings are my responsibility; I must become smaller to remain loved.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should apologize so the tension goes away.; Their disappointment must mean I did something wrong.; I am sorry for needing anything.; If I do not apologize, they may think I do not care.; It feels safer to take all the blame.; I need to become smaller so the relationship can settle.","Protective Move":"Excessive Apologizing is the protective use of apology to reduce tension, secure belonging, preempt criticism, or make oneself smaller—even when responsibility is limited, shared, or absent.","Pattern ID":"PP-EXCESSIVE-APOLOGIZING","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate de-escalation follows when apology is offered quickly or broadly.","Freer Expression":"Accurate responsibility with intact dignity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Conscience; empathy; humility; willingness to repair.","Observable Cues":"Apologizing for needs, limits, feelings, questions, or existing; repeating apologies after repair is accepted; taking sole blame for shared problems.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not reward self-blame by accepting responsibility that is not theirs. Clarify the actual issue and affirm that needs or boundaries do not require apology. May trigger Overfunctioning, Dominance, Rescuing, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Safety, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids anger from others, legitimate innocence, shared responsibility, asserting needs, and unresolved tension.","Canonical Name":"Excessive Apologizing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nExcessive Apologizing is the protective use of apology to reduce tension, secure belonging, preempt criticism, or make oneself smaller—even when responsibility is limited, shared, or absent.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Shame, and Appeasement\n## Related Patterns\nAppeasement; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Shame Spiraling; Personalization.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am using apology to make myself safer, not only to repair harm.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should apologize so the tension goes away.\n- Their disappointment must mean I did something wrong.\n- I am sorry for needing anything.\n- If I do not apologize, they may think I do not care.\n- It feels safer to take all the blame.\n- I need to become smaller so the relationship can settle.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAutomatic guilt when someone is disappointed; relief after saying sorry even without clarity; fear that not apologizing will look uncaring; responsibility expanding beyond one’s actual part.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nApologizing for needs, limits, feelings, questions, or existing; repeating apologies after repair is accepted; taking sole blame for shared problems.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Safety; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConflict; another person’s displeasure; setting a boundary; needing help; perceived inconvenience.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nPeace depends on my self-blame; other people’s feelings are my responsibility; I must become smaller to remain loved.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAnger from others; legitimate innocence; shared responsibility; asserting needs; unresolved tension.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver—apologizes for needing care; Lover—absorbs blame to preserve closeness; Innocent—tries to prove goodness; Orphan—expects belonging to be withdrawn.\n## Pattern Flow\nTension appears → belonging feels threatened → apology offered quickly or broadly → immediate de-escalation → true responsibility remains unclear → self-trust weakens.\n## Often Appears With\nAppeasement; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Personalization.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nConscience; empathy; humility; willingness to repair.\n## Current Cost\nFalse responsibility; resentment; blurred accountability; weakened boundaries; apologies losing meaning.\n## Freer Expression\nAccurate responsibility with intact dignity.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace one automatic “sorry” with either “thank you,” a clear request, or a precise acknowledgment of your actual part.\n## Mira Language\n“An apology may be appropriate, but I notice you are taking responsibility for more than your actions. What specifically belongs to you here?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat harm did you actually cause? Are you apologizing for a need or boundary? What responsibility belongs elsewhere?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCourteous language, cultural norms, sincere remorse, and repairing real impact are not excessive apologizing.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated apology used to regulate relational threat or absorb disproportionate blame.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause before apologizing, identify action, impact, and ownership, and offer only the apology that truth supports.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not reward self-blame by accepting responsibility that is not theirs. Clarify the actual issue and affirm that needs or boundaries do not require apology.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nWhere excessive apologizing obscured the real problem, withdraw inaccurate blame, state the true contribution, and invite proportionate accountability from everyone involved.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Dominance, Rescuing, or Resentment. Often triggered by Anger as Armor, Hostility Toward Criticism, Rejection Sensitivity, or Possessiveness. The loop story becomes: “I must take the blame to keep us safe” and “You have accepted the blame, so I need not examine my part.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhich apologies restore truth, and which ones erase me?"},
  "PP-EXPERT-IDENTITY-FIXATION": {"name":"Expert Identity Fixation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Defensive Expertise; Status Guarding; Credential Accumulation; Impostorism; Grandiosity; Hostility Toward Criticism.","Archetypal Role":"Sage becomes infallible authority; Ruler equates leadership with knowing; Magician protects mystique; Creator rejects feedback to preserve mastery.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record. Spacing repaired. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source.","First Letter":"E","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Say, “I don’t know yet,” and identify the next reliable way to learn.","Core Logic":"I need to remain the expert so I do not have to feel uncertain, ordinary, or dependent.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Stagnation; poor collaboration; hidden errors; intimidation; inability to learn openly.","Core Fear":"Worth depended on being smart; mistakes brought humiliation; authority was the safest identity available.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should know the answer.; Admitting uncertainty would weaken my authority.; I cannot let them see me as a beginner.; My credentials should settle this.; Correction feels like loss of status.; I need to remain the expert in the room.","Protective Move":"Attaches identity to being the knowledgeable, capable, or authoritative one so uncertainty, learning, dependence, or visible limitation cannot threaten worth or status.","Pattern ID":"PP-EXPERT-IDENTITY-FIXATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Amplified certainty and authority restore temporary stability.","Freer Expression":"Expertise that can remain teachable.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Knowledge; rigor; stewardship; teaching capacity; earned authority.","Observable Cues":"Overstating certainty; resisting instruction; dismissing junior contributors; avoiding unfamiliar tasks; leaning on titles or credentials to settle disagreement.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect real expertise while refusing false certainty or status-based silencing. May trigger Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, Contrarianism, or Withholding.","Emotional Function":"Protects competence, self-esteem, dignity, belonging, and status; avoids beginnerhood, dependence, ambiguity, limits, and collaborative learning.","Canonical Name":"Expert Identity Fixation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nExpert Identity Fixation is the protective attachment to being the knowledgeable, capable, or authoritative one so that uncertainty, learning, dependence, or visible limitation does not threaten worth or status.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Competence, and Status\n## Related Patterns\nDefensive Expertise; Status Guarding; Credential Accumulation; Impostorism; Grandiosity; Hostility Toward Criticism\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need to remain the expert so I do not have to feel uncertain, ordinary, or dependent.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should know the answer.\n- Admitting uncertainty would weaken my authority.\n- I cannot let them see me as a beginner.\n- My credentials should settle this.\n- Correction feels like loss of status.\n- I need to remain the expert in the room.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nShame around not knowing; irritation when corrected; pressure to answer immediately; fear of novice status.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOverstating certainty; resisting instruction; dismissing junior contributors; avoiding unfamiliar tasks; leaning on titles or credentials to settle disagreement.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; self-esteem; dignity; belonging; status.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPublic uncertainty; correction; role transition; unfamiliar technology; younger or less credentialed expertise; mistakes.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nWorth depended on being smart; mistakes brought humiliation; authority was the safest identity available.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nBeginnerhood; dependence; ambiguity; limits; collaborative learning.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage becomes infallible authority; Ruler equates leadership with knowing; Magician protects mystique; Creator rejects feedback to preserve mastery.\n## Pattern Flow\nExpertise is questioned → worth or status feels threatened → certainty and authority are amplified → temporary stability → learning and trust narrow → expertise becomes more brittle.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensive Expertise; Overexplaining; Status Guarding; Credentialism; Impostorism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nKnowledge; rigor; stewardship; teaching capacity; earned authority.\n## Current Cost\nStagnation; poor collaboration; hidden errors; intimidation; inability to learn openly.\n## Freer Expression\nExpertise that can remain teachable.\n## One Act of Volition\nSay, “I don’t know yet,” and identify the next reliable way to learn.\n## Mira Language\n“You may genuinely have expertise. I also notice how costly it feels not to know. Is the role of expert protecting your contribution, or carrying your worth?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would not knowing imply about you? Can authority survive curiosity? What evidence would change your view?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nConfidence, specialization, and legitimate authority are not pathological. Mira should not flatten real expertise into insecurity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated resistance to correction, novice status, or shared authority across contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate contribution from omniscience; name what is known, unknown, and being learned.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect real expertise while refusing false certainty or status-based silencing. Ask for evidence and invite collaborative inquiry.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where authority displaced listening, restore credit or voice to others, correct misinformation, and model visible learning.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, Contrarianism, or Withholding in others; their challenge may intensify Status Guarding.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere has being the expert become the price of feeling worthy?"},
  "PP-FAILURE-TO-LAUNCH": {"name":"Failure to Launch","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Endless Preparation; Perfectionism; Procrastination; Rapid Project Proliferation; All-or-Nothing Thinking; Grandiosity.","Archetypal Role":"Creator protects the perfect imagined work; Explorer avoids one path; Magician protects transformative potential; Rebel resists formalization; Innocent waits for certainty.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"F","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Choose one launch that is explicitly a test rather than a verdict.","Core Logic":"I am preserving possibility by not choosing a real beginning.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Unrealized work; fragile confidence; financial and relational strain; accumulating shame.","Core Fear":"Once I choose, I can be judged; possibility is safer than evidence; commitment traps me.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I’m almost ready to put it out there.; I don’t want to commit too soon.; Maybe I should change direction before launch.; Once I release it, people can judge it.; Keeping it private preserves the possibilities.; I need a little more time before making it real.","Protective Move":"Failure to Launch is the protective refusal or inability to cross from private possibility into committed public action, often because launching closes alternatives and makes success, failure, and responsibility measurable.","Pattern ID":"PP-FAILURE-TO-LAUNCH","Short-Term Payoff":"Possibility is preserved when the final step is deferred or a new path opens.","Freer Expression":"Committed experiment.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Imagination; optionality; discernment; sensitivity to consequence.","Observable Cues":"Unfinished launches; abandoned final steps; perpetual beta; switching projects before release; avoiding dates, prices, submissions, or invitations.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Request dates and ownership without equating one launch with permanent identity. May trigger Skepticism, Micromanaging, Financial Control, or Emotional Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Competence, Self-Esteem, and Purpose; avoids finality, grief for alternatives, responsibility, and ordinary results.","Canonical Name":"Failure to Launch"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nFailure to Launch is the protective refusal or inability to cross from private possibility into committed public action, often because launching closes alternatives and makes success, failure, and responsibility measurable.\n## Domain\nCompetence, Creation, and Performance\n## Related Patterns\nEndless Preparation; Perfectionism; Procrastination; Rapid Project Proliferation; All-or-Nothing Thinking\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am preserving possibility by not choosing a real beginning.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I’m almost ready to put it out there.\n- I don’t want to commit too soon.\n- Maybe I should change direction before launch.\n- Once I release it, people can judge it.\n- Keeping it private preserves the possibilities.\n- I need a little more time before making it real.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nImagined potential feels safer than tested reality; commitment feels constricting; release creates dread; new ideas appear near completion.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nUnfinished launches; abandoned final steps; perpetual beta; switching projects before release; avoiding dates, prices, submissions, or invitations.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Competence; Self-Esteem; Purpose.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCompletion; public visibility; commitment; monetization; irreversible choice.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nOnce I choose, I can be judged; possibility is safer than evidence; commitment traps me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFinality; grief for alternatives; responsibility; ordinary results.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCreator protects the perfect imagined work; Explorer avoids one path; Magician protects transformative potential; Rebel resists formalization; Innocent waits for certainty.\n## Pattern Flow\nProject nears reality → identity or autonomy feels threatened → final step is deferred or a new path opens → possibility is preserved → real learning and contribution remain blocked.\n## Often Appears With\nRapid Project Proliferation; Perfectionism; Grandiosity.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nImagination; optionality; discernment; sensitivity to consequence.\n## Current Cost\nUnrealized work; fragile confidence; financial and relational strain; accumulating shame.\n## Freer Expression\nCommitted experiment.\n## One Act of Volition\nChoose one launch that is explicitly a test rather than a verdict.\n## Mira Language\n“The last step may feel more dangerous than the work itself because it turns possibility into evidence. What would a test launch allow?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat alternative dies when you choose? What are you afraid the launch will prove? Can commitment be temporary and reviewable?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nStrategic delay, insufficient resources, and changing direction based on evidence are not Failure to Launch.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated retreat specifically near commitment or release.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nGrieve the unused alternatives and choose a bounded public experiment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRequest dates and ownership without equating one launch with permanent identity.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge promises built around unrealized possibility, stop asking others to invest on vision alone, and rebuild trust through one completed cycle.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Skepticism, Micromanaging, Financial Control, or Emotional Withdrawal. Often triggered by pressure, comparison, or grand expectations.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat possibility am I protecting from reality?"},
  "PP-FANTASY-BONDING": {"name":"Fantasy Bonding","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Idealization; Strategic Ambiguity; Testing the Bond; Relationship Overinvestment; Fantasy Refuge; Commitment Avoidance.","Archetypal Role":"Lover—idealized union; Innocent—faith in destined connection; Magician—meaning assigned to signs; Seeker—future relationship as promised home.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing repaired. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source.","First Letter":"F","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Name three things the relationship reliably is now, separate from what you hope it may become.","Core Logic":"I am attaching to what this relationship could become more than to what it presently is.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Miscalibrated trust; ignored incompatibility; delayed grief; vulnerability to manipulation; unequal investment; difficulty seeing the actual person.","Core Fear":"Real intimacy is unreliable; I must secure belonging quickly; being fully known may lead to rejection; hope is safer than evidence.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This could become everything I have wanted.; The future feels more real than the present.; These signs prove the bond.; I should invest now so the possibility becomes real.; Slowing down might destroy what this could be.; I can fill in the missing evidence with hope.","Protective Move":"Substitutes an imagined, idealized, or future relationship for the slower reality of mutual knowledge, negotiated commitment, and present-day evidence.","Pattern ID":"PP-FANTASY-BONDING","Short-Term Payoff":"Imagination supplies certainty, closeness, and hope.","Freer Expression":"Hope grounded in evidence.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Hope; imagination; devotion; openness to connection; capacity to perceive possibility.","Observable Cues":"Planning a future before compatibility is established; overlooking inconsistency; treating symbolic moments as proof; filling gaps with hopeful assumptions; investing disproportionately early.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respond clearly and concretely; do not reward projection with vague promises or future language unsupported by present commitment.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, trust, purpose, and self-esteem; avoids ambiguity, incompatibility, grief, patience, reciprocal negotiation, and the possibility that the bond is not mutual.","Canonical Name":"Fantasy Bonding"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nFantasy Bonding is the protective substitution of an imagined, idealized, or future relationship for the slower reality of mutual knowledge, negotiated commitment, and present-day evidence.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Intimacy, and Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nIdealization; Strategic Ambiguity; Testing the Bond; Relationship Overinvestment; Fantasy Refuge; Commitment Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am attaching to what this relationship could become more than to what it presently is.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This could become everything I have wanted.\n- The future feels more real than the present.\n- These signs prove the bond.\n- I should invest now so the possibility becomes real.\n- Slowing down might destroy what this could be.\n- I can fill in the missing evidence with hope.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRapid certainty; intense future imagery; emotional investment that outpaces shared experience; resistance to contradictory evidence; fear that slowing down will destroy the bond.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nPlanning a future before present compatibility is established; overlooking inconsistency; treating symbolic moments as proof of commitment; filling informational gaps with hopeful assumptions; investing disproportionately early.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Purpose; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nLoneliness; chemistry; intermittent attention; major life transition; unmet attachment needs; uncertainty about the relationship.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nReal intimacy is unreliable; I must secure belonging quickly; being fully known may lead to rejection; hope is safer than evidence.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAmbiguity; incompatibility; grief; patience; reciprocal negotiation; the possibility that the bond is not mutual.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover—idealized union; Innocent—faith in destined connection; Magician—meaning assigned to signs; Seeker—future relationship as promised home.\n## Pattern Flow\nConnection or longing intensifies → belonging feels uncertain → imagination supplies certainty and future completion → temporary closeness and hope arise → evidence is filtered or postponed → attachment deepens without equivalent mutual reality.\n## Often Appears With\nIdealization; Relationship Overinvestment; Strategic Ambiguity; Testing the Bond; Reassurance Seeking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHope; imagination; devotion; openness to connection; capacity to perceive possibility.\n## Current Cost\nMiscalibrated trust; ignored incompatibility; delayed grief; vulnerability to manipulation; unequal investment; difficulty seeing the actual person.\n## Freer Expression\nHope grounded in evidence.\n## One Act of Volition\nName three things the relationship reliably is now, separate from what you hope it may become.\n## Mira Language\n“The possibility may be meaningful. I also notice that the imagined future is carrying more weight than the present evidence. What do you know through repeated mutual action, and what are you supplying through hope?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat has been demonstrated repeatedly? What remains imagined or promised? What becomes painful if you assess only the relationship that exists today?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nEarly hope, romance, imagination, spiritual meaning, and optimism are not automatically fantasy bonding. Cultural courtship practices and long-distance relationships require context.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated investment in imagined potential despite limited, inconsistent, or contradictory present evidence.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPreserve hope while slowing the pace of commitment. Separate observation from interpretation, ask direct questions, and let repeated behavior—not intensity alone—earn trust.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespond clearly and concretely. Do not reward projection with vague promises, intermittent intimacy, or future language unsupported by present commitment.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where imagined agreements replaced explicit ones, where evidence was ignored, or where pressure was placed on the other person to inhabit a hoped-for role. Restore reality through direct clarification and proportional investment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay pair with Strategic Ambiguity, Breadcrumbing, Commitment Avoidance, or Emotional Distancing. The loop becomes “Our potential proves the bond” versus “I can preserve access without making a clear commitment.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I loving the possible relationship more than the relationship that is actually here?"},
  "PP-FANTASY-REFUGE": {"name":"Fantasy Refuge","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Numbing; Busyness as Avoidance; Meaning Inflation; Rapid Project Proliferation; Idealization; Failure to Launch.","Archetypal Role":"Creator lives only in the unwritten masterpiece; Lover in the imagined bond; Magician in the destined transformation; Wanderer in the unlived elsewhere.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"F","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"Translate one recurring fantasy into either one concrete step, one acknowledged grief, or one consciously chosen piece of art.","Core Logic":"The imagined life gives me what the present cannot—or what I fear I cannot build.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Deferred grief; reduced action; neglect of evidence; vulnerability to idealization and manipulation.","Core Fear":"Reality felt barren or unsafe; imagination was the only private freedom; hope required escape.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"The imagined version feels better than the life I have.; I can live in the future where everything finally works.; This relationship is more complete in my mind than in reality.; Planning the ideal life gives me relief without requiring action.; I need the fantasy because the present feels barren.; I would rather imagine vindication than face the grief underneath.","Protective Move":"Fantasy Refuge is retreating into imagined futures, relationships, identities, vindication, rescue, or alternate lives to obtain relief from pain, limitation, loneliness, powerlessness, or unfinished action.","Pattern ID":"PP-FANTASY-REFUGE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary aliveness and possibility arrive through imagination.","Freer Expression":"Imagination that returns with a gift for the present.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Imagination; hope; symbolic intelligence; vision; creative rehearsal.","Observable Cues":"Extensive daydreaming; idealized future planning without steps; imaginary reconciliation or triumph; substituting imagined intimacy for actual contact.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect imagination while asking what is current, mutual, consented to, and evidenced. May trigger Disillusionment, Devaluation, Strategic Ambiguity, or Rescuing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Hope, belonging, purpose, creativity, agency, dignity, play, and safety; avoids grief, limits, ordinary effort, rejection, uncertainty, and present unmet need.","Canonical Name":"Fantasy Refuge"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nFantasy Refuge is retreating into imagined futures, relationships, identities, vindication, rescue, or alternate lives to obtain relief from pain, limitation, loneliness, powerlessness, or unfinished action.\n## Domain\nAvoidance, Meaning, and Emotional Escape\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Numbing; Busyness as Avoidance; Meaning Inflation; Rapid Project Proliferation; Idealization\n## Recognition Sentence\nThe imagined life gives me what the present cannot—or what I fear I cannot build.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- The imagined version feels better than the life I have.\n- I can live in the future where everything finally works.\n- This relationship is more complete in my mind than in reality.\n- Planning the ideal life gives me relief without requiring action.\n- I need the fantasy because the present feels barren.\n- I would rather imagine vindication than face the grief underneath.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAbsorbing alternate scenarios; emotional reward without action; resentment when reality interrupts; stronger attachment to imagined potential than current evidence.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nExtensive daydreaming; idealized future planning without steps; imaginary reconciliation or triumph; substituting imagined intimacy for actual contact.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nHope; belonging; purpose; creativity; agency; dignity; play; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nLoneliness; grief; humiliation; stagnation; constraint; disappointment; powerlessness.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nReality felt barren or unsafe; imagination was the only private freedom; hope required escape.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; limits; ordinary effort; rejection; uncertainty; present unmet need.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCreator lives only in the unwritten masterpiece; Lover in the imagined bond; Magician in the destined transformation; Wanderer in the unlived elsewhere.\n## Pattern Flow\nPresent pain or limitation intensifies → imagination supplies relief and possibility → temporary aliveness → action and grief are deferred → the present becomes poorer → fantasy becomes more necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nIdealization; Meaning Inflation; Failure to Launch; Emotional Numbing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nImagination; hope; symbolic intelligence; vision; creative rehearsal.\n## Current Cost\nDeferred grief; reduced action; neglect of evidence; vulnerability to idealization and manipulation.\n## Freer Expression\nImagination that returns with a gift for the present.\n## One Act of Volition\nTranslate one recurring fantasy into either one concrete step, one acknowledged grief, or one consciously chosen piece of art.\n## Mira Language\n“The fantasy may be carrying a real need or possibility. What does it give you, and what portion can be brought back into lived reality?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat need is fulfilled there? What evidence belongs to the imagined version? What can be created, mourned, requested, or released now?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nImagination, prayer, fiction, visualization, and restorative daydreaming are not inherently avoidance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated retreat that substitutes for contact, grief, evidence, or feasible action and produces meaningful cost.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDo not shame the refuge; identify its gift, time-bound it, and return with one embodied action or truthful acknowledgment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect imagination while asking what is current, mutual, consented to, and evidenced.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge promises, projections, or expectations imposed on others from an imagined relationship; restore consent and present reality.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Disillusionment, Devaluation, Strategic Ambiguity, or Rescuing. Often triggered by Emotional Withholding, Rejection, helplessness, or chronic constraint.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat does this imagined world protect, and what gift can I bring back without mistaking fantasy for evidence?"},
  "PP-FUSION": {"name":"Fusion","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Self-Erasure; Clinging; Compulsive Contact; Boundary Collapse; Testing the Bond; Relationship-Bound Worth; Idealization.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — union becomes disappearance into the beloved; Caregiver — another person’s needs become one’s identity and responsibility; Everyman — difference is suppressed to preserve belonging; Mystic — boundaries are dissolved in the name of oneness; Innocent — closeness is treated as proof that everything is safe.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation. Repair Path — After Rupture is absent from this source record and remains absent rather than being invented.","First Letter":"F","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"State one authentic preference or maintain one personal commitment that differs from the other person’s without treating that difference as a threat.","Core Logic":"I reduce the distance between us because separation feels like the loss of the bond—or the loss of myself.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Loss of identity; dependency; resentment; boundary collapse; difficulty tolerating distance; unequal relationships.","Core Fear":"People leave. I disappear when I am alone. Difference causes abandonment. I am only real when someone chooses me. Closeness must be total to be safe.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If we’re close, we should agree.; Your distance feels like rejection.; I don’t know who I am without us.; Your mood becomes my mood.; A boundary means you’re pulling away.; I need us to feel completely connected.","Protective Move":"Fusion is the protective reduction of emotional or identity boundaries so that closeness, agreement, or continual contact can stand in for security, belonging, and a stable sense of self.","Pattern ID":"PP-FUSION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary closeness returns.","Freer Expression":"Union without disappearance.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Devotion; attunement; receptivity; intimacy; relational sensitivity.","Observable Cues":"Canceling one’s own plans to preserve contact; rarely disagreeing or voicing a separate preference; texting or checking repeatedly during distance; organizing identity, schedule, and meaning around “we”; absorbing responsibility for the other person’s feelings; abandoning friendships, interests, or routines outside the bond.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer warmth and clarity together. Reassure the bond only when genuine, keep boundaries consistent, avoid punishing ordinary independence, and do not reward escalating contact or self-erasure as the price of closeness. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Avoidant Independence, Boundary Hardening, Secrecy, or Irritability in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids separateness, solitude, grief, uncertainty, conflicting desires, limits of union, and individual responsibility.","Canonical Name":"Fusion"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nFusion is the protective reduction of emotional or identity boundaries so that closeness, agreement, or continual contact can stand in for security, belonging, and a stable sense of self.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nSelf-Erasure; Clinging; Compulsive Contact; Boundary Collapse; Testing the Bond; Relationship-Bound Worth; Idealization\n## Recognition Sentence\nI reduce the distance between us because separation feels like the loss of the bond—or the loss of myself.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If we’re close, we should agree.\n- Your distance feels like rejection.\n- I don’t know who I am without us.\n- Your mood becomes my mood.\n- A boundary means you’re pulling away.\n- I need us to feel completely connected.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\n- Ordinary distance feels like rejection.\n- Difference feels dangerous to the relationship.\n- The other person’s mood rapidly becomes your emotional state.\n- Being alone produces a loss of identity or worth.\n- A boundary feels like withdrawal of love.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n- Canceling one’s own plans to preserve contact.\n- Rarely disagreeing or voicing a separate preference.\n- Texting or checking repeatedly during distance.\n- Organizing identity, schedule, and meaning around “we.”\n- Absorbing responsibility for the other person’s feelings.\n- Abandoning friendships, interests, or routines outside the bond.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDistance; delayed replies; conflict; new boundaries; another person’s independence; relationship uncertainty; separation or breakup.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\n- People leave.\n- I disappear when I am alone.\n- Difference causes abandonment.\n- I am only real when someone chooses me.\n- Closeness must be total to be safe.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nSeparateness; solitude; grief; uncertainty; conflicting desires; limits of union; individual responsibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\n- Lover — union becomes disappearance into the beloved.\n- Caregiver — another person’s needs become one’s identity and responsibility.\n- Everyman — difference is suppressed to preserve belonging.\n- Mystic — boundaries are dissolved in the name of oneness.\n- Innocent — closeness is treated as proof that everything is safe.\n## Pattern Flow\nDistance or difference appears → belonging and trust feel endangered → selfhood and boundaries contract → contact or agreement increases → temporary closeness returns → individual identity weakens → future distance feels even more threatening.\n## Often Appears With\nSelf-Erasure; Compulsive Contact; Testing the Bond; Idealization; Relationship-Bound Worth.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDevotion; attunement; receptivity; intimacy; relational sensitivity.\n## Current Cost\nLoss of identity; dependency; resentment; boundary collapse; difficulty tolerating distance; unequal relationships.\n## Freer Expression\nUnion without disappearance.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one authentic preference or maintain one personal commitment that differs from the other person’s without treating that difference as a threat.\n## Mira Language\n“I notice that preserving the bond has required several parts of you to go quiet. I wonder whether fusion may be operating—the attempt to create security by reducing the distance between you. Does that fit?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\n- What part of you has become too expensive to bring into this bond?\n- What do you imagine ordinary distance means?\n- Can two separate selves remain deeply joined here?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nIntimacy, devotion, interdependence, shared plans, and cultural collectivism are not automatically fusion. Mira must not encourage separation from a healthy bond simply to prove independence.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated loss of preferences, identity, boundaries, outside relationships, or emotional separateness—not one compromise or intense period of closeness.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate the fear of distance before seeking contact, identify one separate feeling or preference, and practice remaining connected without surrendering selfhood. Let difference become information rather than proof of abandonment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer warmth and clarity together. Reassure the bond only when genuine, keep boundaries consistent, avoid punishing ordinary independence, and do not reward escalating contact or self-erasure as the price of closeness.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Avoidant Independence, Boundary Hardening, Secrecy, or Irritability in others. Often triggered by Withdrawal, Delayed Contact, Ambiguous Commitment, Testing the Bond, or another person’s strong independence. The reinforcing story may become: “Distance means abandonment” on one side and “Closeness means loss of self” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I preserving connection by making myself smaller or less separate?"},
  "PP-GATEKEEPING": {"name":"Gatekeeping","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Status Guarding; Dominance; Scarcity Hoarding; Moral Superiority; Defensive Expertise.","Archetypal Role":"Sage hoards knowledge; Ruler controls entry; Rebel creates purity tests; Creator defines legitimacy narrowly.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"G","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"State the real criterion publicly and test whether it is necessary, fair, and consistently applied.","Core Logic":"I am controlling entry because access feels dangerous or scarce.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Exclusion; inequity; stagnation; dependence on insiders.","Core Fear":"Belonging must be earned through hardship; scarcity creates value; access invites chaos.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They have not earned access yet.; Opening this up will dilute its value.; I need to protect the insiders from newcomers.; The criteria should stay flexible enough to preserve standards.; If everyone can enter, what makes this meaningful?; I should control the information so access remains limited.","Protective Move":"Gatekeeping is the protective control of access to knowledge, belonging, opportunity, resources, or legitimacy in order to preserve safety, standards, status, or exclusivity.","Pattern ID":"PP-GATEKEEPING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns when barriers rise.","Freer Expression":"Discernment with transparent access.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; safeguarding; care for standards; initiation and preparation.","Observable Cues":"Hidden criteria; moving qualifications; withholding information; purity tests; insider language used to exclude.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask for transparent criteria; document inconsistency; prioritize equity and safety rather than personal approval. May trigger Contrarianism, Cynicism, Self-Erasure, or Adversarial Framing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Belonging, Competence, Significance, and Trust; avoids uncertainty, shared ownership, loss of specialness, and vulnerability to change.","Canonical Name":"Gatekeeping"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nGatekeeping is the protective control of access to knowledge, belonging, opportunity, resources, or legitimacy in order to preserve safety, standards, status, or exclusivity.\n## Domain\nPower, Belonging, and Access\n## Related Patterns\nStatus Guarding; Dominance; Scarcity Hoarding; Moral Superiority; Defensive Expertise\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am controlling entry because access feels dangerous or scarce.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They have not earned access yet.\n- Opening this up will dilute its value.\n- I need to protect the insiders from newcomers.\n- The criteria should stay flexible enough to preserve standards.\n- If everyone can enter, what makes this meaningful?\n- I should control the information so access remains limited.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSuspicion of newcomers; irritation at accessibility; belief that others have not earned entry; fear that openness will dilute value.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nHidden criteria; moving qualifications; withholding information; purity tests; insider language used to exclude.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Belonging; Competence; Significance; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nNewcomers; democratized knowledge; changing norms; loss of exclusivity; perceived dilution of standards.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBelonging must be earned through hardship; scarcity creates value; access invites chaos.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; shared ownership; loss of specialness; vulnerability to change.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage hoards knowledge; Ruler controls entry; Rebel creates purity tests; Creator defines legitimacy narrowly.\n## Pattern Flow\nAccess request appears → safety or status feels threatened → barriers rise → temporary control returns → exclusion and mistrust grow.\n## Often Appears With\nStatus Guarding; Scarcity Hoarding; Moral Superiority; Dominance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; safeguarding; care for standards; initiation and preparation.\n## Current Cost\nExclusion; inequity; stagnation; dependence on insiders.\n## Freer Expression\nDiscernment with transparent access.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the real criterion publicly and test whether it is necessary, fair, and consistently applied.\n## Mira Language\n“Is this boundary protecting a real standard, or protecting exclusivity itself?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWho benefits from the barrier? Is the criterion transparent? What risk would fair access actually create?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSafety screening, confidentiality, expertise requirements, and capacity limits are not automatically gatekeeping.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated opaque or shifting barriers that preserve insider advantage beyond legitimate need.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the feared consequence of access; make criteria explicit; separate standards from status.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk for transparent criteria; document inconsistency; prioritize equity and safety rather than personal approval.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge exclusion, clarify criteria, restore access or credit where possible, and create accountable processes.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Contrarianism, Cynicism, Self-Erasure, or Adversarial Framing; often triggered by Suspicion and Scarcity Hoarding.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I protecting a standard, and where am I protecting exclusivity?"},
  "PP-GRANDIOSITY": {"name":"Grandiosity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Exceptionalism; Moral Superiority; Image Management; Meaning Inflation; Defensive Expertise; Rapid Project Proliferation; Perfectionism.","Archetypal Role":"Creator — the creation must be revolutionary rather than useful; Mystic — intuition becomes privileged revelation; Sage — understanding becomes superiority; Ruler — leadership becomes entitlement; Rebel — opposition becomes proof of unique moral clarity; Trickster — seeing through others becomes a position above them.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"G","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Describe the real contribution in concrete terms without destiny, superiority, or exceptional-status language.","Core Logic":"I need myself or my work to be extraordinary so I do not have to feel insignificant.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Overreach; fragile worth; poor calibration; relational distance; dismissal of feedback; difficulty valuing modest but meaningful work.","Core Fear":"I am invisible. Ordinary means worthless. No one recognizes what I carry. I must become exceptional to justify my existence. If I am not special, I will disappear.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need this to be extraordinary.; People don’t understand how significant this is.; Ordinary success isn’t enough.; The usual limits shouldn’t apply here.; If this isn’t exceptional, what does it say about me?; I know this is bigger than other people can see.","Protective Move":"Grandiosity is the protective enlargement of one’s importance, certainty, uniqueness, or destiny in order to avoid insignificance, limitation, dependence, or ordinary vulnerability.","Pattern ID":"PP-GRANDIOSITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Recognition and certainty produce temporary stabilization.","Freer Expression":"Grounded significance.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Vision; ambition; confidence; originality; willingness to imagine beyond convention.","Observable Cues":"Inflated or destiny-based claims; treating incremental work as beneath the vision; dismissing grounded feedback; expecting exceptions to ordinary constraints; overstating influence, certainty, or uniqueness; building identity around being unusually gifted, chosen, or insightful.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not humiliate, flatter, or enter a contest over importance. Recognize the valid aspiration, return the conversation to observable reality and shared impact, and maintain boundaries around entitlement, domination, or dismissal of others. May trigger Competition, Contempt, Self-Erasure, Withdrawal, or Defensive Expertise in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Purpose, Competence, and Belonging; avoids ordinariness, dependence, limitation, mortality, ambiguity, gradual development, and shared authorship.","Canonical Name":"Grandiosity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nGrandiosity is the protective enlargement of one’s importance, certainty, uniqueness, or destiny in order to avoid insignificance, limitation, dependence, or ordinary vulnerability.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Image, and Significance\n## Related Patterns\nExceptionalism; Moral Superiority; Image Management; Meaning Inflation; Defensive Expertise; Rapid Project Proliferation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need myself or my work to be extraordinary so I do not have to feel insignificant.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need this to be extraordinary.\n- People don’t understand how significant this is.\n- Ordinary success isn’t enough.\n- The usual limits shouldn’t apply here.\n- If this isn’t exceptional, what does it say about me?\n- I know this is bigger than other people can see.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\n- Ordinary contribution feels emotionally insufficient.\n- Recognition feels necessary rather than welcome.\n- Criticism is interpreted as others failing to understand the vision.\n- Limits feel insulting rather than informative.\n- A project carries the burden of proving personal significance.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n- Inflated or destiny-based claims.\n- Treating incremental work as beneath the vision.\n- Dismissing grounded feedback.\n- Expecting exceptions to ordinary constraints.\n- Overstating influence, certainty, or uniqueness.\n- Building identity around being unusually gifted, chosen, or insightful.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Purpose; Competence; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nInvisibility; comparison; criticism; slow progress; ordinary results; dependence on others; loss of status; uncertainty about one’s contribution.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\n- I am invisible.\n- Ordinary means worthless.\n- No one recognizes what I carry.\n- I must become exceptional to justify my existence.\n- If I am not special, I will disappear.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nOrdinariness; dependence; limitation; mortality; ambiguity; gradual development; shared authorship.\n## Archetypal Expressions\n- Creator — the creation must be revolutionary rather than useful.\n- Mystic — intuition becomes privileged revelation.\n- Sage — understanding becomes superiority.\n- Ruler — leadership becomes entitlement.\n- Rebel — opposition becomes proof of unique moral clarity.\n- Trickster — seeing through others becomes a position above them.\n## Pattern Flow\nSignificance or worth feels uncertain → the self or project is enlarged → recognition and certainty produce temporary stabilization → feedback and limits become threatening → calibration weakens → worth becomes increasingly dependent on exceptional status.\n## Often Appears With\nPerfectionism; Meaning Inflation; Moral Superiority; Image Management; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nVision; ambition; confidence; originality; willingness to imagine beyond convention.\n## Current Cost\nOverreach; fragile worth; poor calibration; relational distance; dismissal of feedback; difficulty valuing modest but meaningful work.\n## Freer Expression\nGrounded significance.\n## One Act of Volition\nDescribe the real contribution in concrete terms without destiny, superiority, or exceptional-status language.\n## Mira Language\n“The vision may genuinely be large. I also wonder whether it is carrying the additional burden of proving that you are exceptional. Would the work still matter if it became valuable rather than revolutionary?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\n- What fear appears if the work matters but does not make you singular?\n- Which part of the vision is grounded, and which part is carrying your worth?\n- Can significance be shared rather than possessed?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAmbition, confidence, original vision, spiritual conviction, and bold goals are not themselves grandiosity. Mira must not diagnose narcissism.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated inflation, entitlement, dismissal of limits, or dependence on exceptional status across contexts—not one enthusiastic claim.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate the real contribution from the burden of proving exceptional worth. Name concrete evidence, limits, dependencies, and the next ordinary act of service the vision requires.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not humiliate, flatter, or enter a contest over importance. Recognize the valid aspiration, return the conversation to observable reality and shared impact, and maintain boundaries around entitlement, domination, or dismissal of others.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where inflation, entitlement, or dismissal diminished another person’s contribution or reality. Repair requires accurate language, recognition of shared authorship and limits, restoration of dignity, and observable willingness to accept feedback without demanding admiration or special exemption.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Competition, Contempt, Self-Erasure, Withdrawal, or Defensive Expertise in others. Often triggered by Invisibility, Comparison, Criticism, another person’s superiority, or perceived dismissal. The reinforcing story may become: “I must become larger to matter” on one side and “There is no room for me here” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWould this still matter if it made a real contribution without making me extraordinary?"},
  "PP-GRUDGE-HOLDING": {"name":"Grudge Holding","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Keeping Score; Retaliation; Resentment; Punitive Withdrawal; Retrospective Prosecution; Suspicion.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior—permanent guard; Judge/Ruler—open moral account; Orphan—injury as proof that trust is unsafe; Avenger shadow—pain becomes enduring claim.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record. Spacing repaired. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source. Abuse Context flag preserves cautions around unresolved harm, documentation, and safety.","First Letter":"G","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Write what must remain remembered for safety, then separately name what no longer needs daily rehearsal.","Core Logic":"I am keeping the injury alive because releasing it feels like surrendering truth or protection.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Chronic activation; relational rigidity; inability to register repair; narrowed identity; repeated conflict; continued psychological tethering to the offender.","Core Fear":"Harm is forgotten unless I preserve it; people evade accountability; if I soften, I will be hurt again; my pain will be erased.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I must keep this injury alive so it is not erased.; Softening would betray what happened.; They must never be allowed to forget.; The past still proves who they are.; If I release the anger, I may become unsafe.; Ongoing prosecution is the only justice I still control.","Protective Move":"Preserves an injury as an active moral account so vigilance, distance, leverage, or identity can prevent the hurt from being minimized, repeated, or forgotten.","Pattern ID":"PP-GRUDGE-HOLDING","Short-Term Payoff":"Rehearsal and moral clarity provide temporary vigilance and protection.","Freer Expression":"Remembered truth without permanent captivity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Moral memory; discernment; loyalty to truth; self-protection; insistence on accountability.","Observable Cues":"Reintroducing old injuries into new conflicts; withholding warmth after repair; maintaining punitive distance; collecting confirming evidence; using the past as leverage; refusing revision of the offender’s identity.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not demand forgiveness or minimize impact; offer accountability and changed behavior while refusing endless punishment as a substitute for repair.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, justice, trust, self-respect, and autonomy; avoids grief, uncertainty, powerlessness, limits of repair, vulnerability to renewed trust, and incomplete justice.","Canonical Name":"Grudge Holding"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nGrudge Holding is the protective preservation of an injury as an active moral account so that vigilance, distance, leverage, or identity can prevent the hurt from being minimized, repeated, or forgotten.\n## Domain\nInjury, Justice, and Relational Protection\n## Related Patterns\nKeeping Score; Retaliation; Resentment; Punitive Withdrawal; Retrospective Prosecution; Suspicion\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am keeping the injury alive because releasing it feels like surrendering truth or protection.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I must keep this injury alive so it is not erased.\n- Softening would betray what happened.\n- They must never be allowed to forget.\n- The past still proves who they are.\n- If I release the anger, I may become unsafe.\n- Ongoing prosecution is the only justice I still control.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRehearsing the offense; renewed activation when the person is mentioned; resistance to updated evidence; fear that softening equals betrayal of self; moral certainty sustained by memory.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReintroducing old injuries into new conflicts; withholding warmth after stated repair; maintaining punitive distance; collecting confirming evidence; using the past as leverage; refusing any revision of the offender’s identity.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Justice; Trust; Self-Respect; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nBetrayal; inadequate accountability; repeated harm; pressured forgiveness; minimization; renewed contact; reminders of the injury.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nHarm is forgotten unless I preserve it; people evade accountability; if I soften, I will be hurt again; my pain will be erased.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; uncertainty; powerlessness; the limits of repair; vulnerability to renewed trust; accepting that justice may remain incomplete.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior—permanent guard; Judge/Ruler—open moral account; Orphan—injury as proof that trust is unsafe; Avenger shadow—pain converted into enduring claim.\n## Pattern Flow\nInjury or reminder appears → justice and safety feel threatened → the offense is rehearsed and preserved → vigilance and moral clarity provide temporary protection → identity and relationship remain organized around the injury → release and recalibration become difficult.\n## Often Appears With\nResentment; Keeping Score; Retaliation; Punitive Withdrawal; Suspicion; Retrospective Prosecution.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nMoral memory; discernment; loyalty to truth; self-protection; insistence on accountability.\n## Current Cost\nChronic activation; relational rigidity; inability to register repair; narrowed identity; repeated conflict; continued psychological tethering to the offender.\n## Freer Expression\nRemembered truth without permanent captivity.\n## One Act of Volition\nWrite what must remain remembered for safety, then separately name what no longer needs daily rehearsal.\n## Mira Language\n“The injury may still matter, and release does not require denial or reconciliation. I wonder whether remembering has become a way of staying continuously mobilized. What truth must remain, and what burden no longer protects you?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat accountability is still missing? What would releasing daily prosecution mean—and not mean? Is the grudge protecting a boundary, preserving leverage, or preventing grief?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nOngoing danger, unresolved abuse, legal documentation, pattern recognition, and refusal to reconcile are not automatically grudge holding. Safety and accountability come first.\n## Evidence Threshold\nPersistent rehearsal, leverage, or identity organization around a past injury after immediate safety decisions have been made—not simply remembering harm or maintaining a boundary.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nValidate the truth of the injury, distinguish memory from repeated activation, define the boundary that protects you now, and release the expectation that ongoing internal prosecution will produce retroactive justice.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not demand forgiveness or minimize impact. Offer specific accountability, changed behavior, and respect for boundaries while refusing endless punishment as a substitute for repair.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nThe person who caused harm must name impact and demonstrate change; the person holding the grudge may need to acknowledge later uses of the injury as leverage. Repair may mean renewed trust, limited contact, or a truthful ending—not forced reconciliation.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Minimizing, Counterattack, or Punitive Withdrawal. The loop becomes “I must keep prosecuting or the truth disappears” versus “Nothing I do will ever count.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat truth am I preserving, and what part of the injury is now preserving itself through me?"},
  "PP-GUILT-INDUCTION": {"name":"Guilt Induction","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Martyrdom; Passive Aggression; Obligation Leverage; Keeping Score; Conditional Warmth; Appeasement; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver becomes sacrificial creditor; Lover tests devotion; Ruler moralizes duty; Orphan secures care through indebtedness.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the source explicitly addresses moral coercion, coerced compliance, damaged consent, punishment after refusal, and freedom to decline.","First Letter":"G","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"State the request plainly and explicitly permit a truthful no.","Core Logic":"I am making their guilt carry a request I am afraid to state directly.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Coerced compliance; hidden contracts; resentment; damaged consent; uncertainty about whether care is freely given.","Core Fear":"My needs do not matter unless another person feels bad; direct asking invites rejection; love must be proven through sacrifice.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"After everything I have done, they should know what I need.; A direct request may be refused, so guilt feels safer.; I need them to feel the cost of disappointing me.; If they cared, they would do this without being asked.; Refusing me should feel selfish to them.; I can make the need harder to ignore by invoking sacrifice.","Protective Move":"Guilt Induction is the protective use of another person’s guilt, indebtedness, or fear of being selfish to secure care, agreement, access, compliance, or repair without making a direct, freely answerable request.","Pattern ID":"PP-GUILT-INDUCTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Short-term compliance may occur when guilt is evoked.","Freer Expression":"Direct need and negotiated reciprocity without moral coercion.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Sensitivity to reciprocity, contribution, loyalty, and care.","Observable Cues":"Sighing, sacrifice references, loaded reminders, “after all I’ve done,” implying selfishness, withdrawing warmth after refusal, presenting a preference as moral obligation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Acknowledge the stated need without accepting moral coercion. Ask for a direct request and preserve the right to consent, negotiate, or decline. May trigger Appeasement, Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, Resentment, or Counter-Control.","Emotional Function":"Protects Care, belonging, reciprocity, dignity, recognition, predictability, and support; avoids vulnerability of asking, possible no, grief about unequal care, negotiation, and limits.","Canonical Name":"Guilt Induction"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nGuilt Induction is the protective use of another person’s guilt, indebtedness, or fear of being selfish to secure care, agreement, access, compliance, or repair without making a direct, freely answerable request.\n## Domain\nRelationship, Influence, and Accountability\n## Related Patterns\nMartyrdom; Passive Aggression; Obligation Leverage; Keeping Score; Conditional Warmth; Appeasement\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am making their guilt carry a request I am afraid to state directly.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- After everything I have done, they should know what I need.\n- A direct request may be refused, so guilt feels safer.\n- I need them to feel the cost of disappointing me.\n- If they cared, they would do this without being asked.\n- Refusing me should feel selfish to them.\n- I can make the need harder to ignore by invoking sacrifice.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nFear that a direct request will be refused; resentment about needing to ask; belief that care should be automatic; urge to make the other person feel the cost.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSighing, sacrifice references, loaded reminders, “after all I’ve done,” implying selfishness, withdrawing warmth after refusal, presenting a preference as moral obligation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCare; belonging; reciprocity; dignity; recognition; predictability; support.\n## Usually Triggered By\nFeeling overlooked; unmet expectations; refusal; unequal labor; fear of abandonment; difficulty naming needs.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy needs do not matter unless another person feels bad; direct asking invites rejection; love must be proven through sacrifice.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability of asking; possible no; grief about unequal care; negotiation; limits.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver becomes sacrificial creditor; Lover tests devotion; Ruler moralizes duty; Orphan secures care through indebtedness.\n## Pattern Flow\nNeed goes unmet → direct asking feels unsafe → guilt is evoked → short-term compliance may occur → consent and trust weaken → resentment and indirectness grow.\n## Often Appears With\nMartyrdom; Keeping Score; Passive Aggression; Conditional Warmth; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSensitivity to reciprocity, contribution, loyalty, and care.\n## Current Cost\nCoerced compliance; hidden contracts; resentment; damaged consent; uncertainty about whether care is freely given.\n## Freer Expression\nDirect need and negotiated reciprocity without moral coercion.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the request plainly and explicitly permit a truthful no.\n## Mira Language\n“There may be a real unmet need here. I also notice the request is being carried through guilt rather than stated directly. What would the direct request be, and can the other person answer freely?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you hoping they will do? What feels dangerous about asking directly? Is their agreement free if refusal is punished morally or relationally?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNaming impact, expressing disappointment, or describing unequal labor is not automatically guilt induction. Power, dependency, culture, and actual obligations matter.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of guilt or moral indebtedness to obtain behavior, especially when direct requests and free refusal are absent.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the unmet need, separate it from the tactic, name the request, disclose relevant impact, and tolerate negotiation or refusal without retaliation.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAcknowledge the stated need without accepting moral coercion. Ask for a direct request and preserve the right to consent, negotiate, or decline.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where guilt replaced a direct request, acknowledge pressure placed on consent, restate the need honestly, and create an agreement that does not depend on indebtedness.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, Resentment, or Counter-Control. Often triggered by Emotional Withholding, Underfunctioning, broken agreements, or perceived ingratitude. Stories become “I must make you care” and “Nothing I give is freely chosen.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I asking guilt to speak because I fear making a direct request?"},
  "PP-HELP-REJECTION": {"name":"Help-Rejection","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hyper-Independence; Defensiveness; Underfunctioning; Victim Identity Fixation; Failure to Launch; Rumination.","Archetypal Role":"Rebel — resistance preserves selfhood. Sage — expert objections block experimentation. Innocent — impossibility preserves innocence. Orphan — disappointment is prevented through refusal.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"H","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Choose one suggestion to test as an experiment rather than a commitment.","Core Logic":"Every offered path must be impossible, because accepting one would expose something difficult.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Stagnation; helper burnout; reinforced helplessness; damaged trust.","Core Fear":"Help means control; failure after help would prove defectiveness; no one truly understands; change will cost identity.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"That won’t work for me.; You don’t understand why every option is impossible.; I want help, but none of these suggestions fit.; If I try and fail, it will prove something is wrong with me.; Accepting help may give someone control over me.; I need to find the fatal flaw before I risk trying.","Protective Move":"Help-Rejection protects autonomy, hope, identity, or avoidance by dismissing, disqualifying, or defeating support before it can create vulnerability, obligation, or change.","Pattern ID":"PP-HELP-REJECTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary protection from risk returns when every option is disqualified.","Freer Expression":"Selective receiving.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; autonomy; awareness of constraints.","Observable Cues":"Repeatedly requesting help then rejecting every suggestion; shifting criteria; explaining why nothing can work.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask what form of support is wanted; stop overfunctioning; maintain boundaries around repetitive no-win helping. May trigger Overfunctioning, Resentment, Withdrawal, or Hostility Toward Criticism.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Competence; avoids agency, risk, gratitude, experimentation, and grief about constraints.","Canonical Name":"Help-Rejection"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nHelp-Rejection protects autonomy, hope, identity, or avoidance by dismissing, disqualifying, or defeating support before it can create vulnerability, obligation, or change.\n## Domain\nAutonomy, Dependence, and Trust\n## Related Patterns\nHyper-Independence; Defensiveness; Underfunctioning; Victim Identity Fixation; Failure to Launch\n## Recognition Sentence\nEvery offered path must be impossible, because accepting one would expose something difficult.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- That won’t work for me.\n- You don’t understand why every option is impossible.\n- I want help, but none of these suggestions fit.\n- If I try and fail, it will prove something is wrong with me.\n- Accepting help may give someone control over me.\n- I need to find the fatal flaw before I risk trying.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAdvice feels intrusive; every option immediately presents a fatal flaw; being helped feels humiliating or binding.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeatedly requesting help then rejecting every suggestion; shifting criteria; explaining why nothing can work.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Self-Esteem; Trust; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAdvice; accountability; dependency; pressure to change; exposure of uncertainty.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nHelp means control; failure after help would prove defectiveness; no one truly understands; change will cost identity.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAgency; risk; gratitude; experimentation; grief about constraints.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRebel — resistance preserves selfhood. Sage — expert objections block experimentation. Innocent — impossibility preserves innocence. Orphan — disappointment is prevented through refusal.\n## Pattern Flow\nDistress creates request or offer → autonomy or worth feels threatened → every option is disqualified → temporary protection from risk returns → helplessness and frustration persist.\n## Often Appears With\nHyper-Independence; Defensiveness; Victim Identity Fixation; Rumination.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; autonomy; awareness of constraints.\n## Current Cost\nStagnation; helper burnout; reinforced helplessness; damaged trust.\n## Freer Expression\nSelective receiving.\n## One Act of Volition\nChoose one suggestion to test as an experiment rather than a commitment.\n## Mira Language\n“Would you like witnessing, ideas, or help choosing one experiment? I notice that every option is becoming impossible.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would accepting help imply? What kind of support would not take away your agency?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nRejecting poor advice, coercive help, or impractical options is not a pattern.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated defeat of varied reasonable support while distress and requests continue.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the feared cost of help and select a reversible trial.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk what form of support is wanted; stop overfunctioning; maintain boundaries around repetitive no-win helping.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where repeated solicitation and rejection exhausted or invalidated others; clarify future requests and accept responsibility for choice.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Resentment, Withdrawal, or Hostility Toward Criticism. Often triggered by advice, pressure, dependency, or shame. The loop becomes “No one can help me” versus “Nothing I offer is ever enough.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat does rejecting every path protect me from having to risk?"},
  "PP-HOSTILITY-TO-CRITICISM": {"name":"Hostility Toward Criticism","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Defensiveness; Perfectionism; Defensive Expertise; Devaluation; Blame Shifting.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior counterattacks; Ruler punishes dissent; Sage discredits the critic; Creator rejects the audience; Rebel treats all feedback as control; Lover experiences correction as rejection.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly distinguishes legitimate feedback from harassment, contempt, discriminatory attack, chronic fault-finding, and abusive criticism.","First Letter":"H","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Repeat the feedback neutrally and identify one potentially useful element before responding to tone or fairness.","Core Logic":"If I discredit the criticism or the critic quickly enough, I will not have to feel diminished.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Lost learning; fear in relationships or teams; retaliation cycles; isolation; repeated blind spots.","Core Fear":"Correction is humiliation; mistakes remove status or love; feedback is a power move.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"You’re only saying that to diminish me.; Your tone proves the feedback is invalid.; Before criticizing me, look at your own flaws.; I won’t let you speak to me like that.; This is an attack, not feedback.; I need to shut this down before I’m humiliated.","Protective Move":"Hostility Toward Criticism is the protective attack on feedback, its source, or the relationship whenever correction is experienced as humiliation, domination, or a threat to worth.","Pattern ID":"PP-HOSTILITY-TO-CRITICISM","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary power returns when the critic is attacked or devalued.","Freer Expression":"Discernment without retaliation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Self-protection; discernment about unfair judgment; resistance to domination; standards for respectful communication.","Observable Cues":"Attacking tone or credentials; retaliatory criticism; mocking feedback; ending discussion abruptly; punishing people who raise concerns.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Use specific behavior and impact, avoid global character judgments, maintain a calm boundary around retaliation, and disengage when safety or dignity is compromised. May trigger Withholding, Stonewalling, People-Pleasing, Contempt, or covert Keeping Score.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Autonomy, and Belonging; avoids fallibility, dependence on others’ perspective, shame, grief over impact, and learning in public.","Canonical Name":"Hostility Toward Criticism"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nHostility Toward Criticism is the protective attack on feedback, its source, or the relationship whenever correction is experienced as humiliation, domination, or a threat to worth.\n## Domain\nAccountability, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nDefensiveness; Perfectionism; Defensive Expertise; Devaluation; Blame Shifting\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I discredit the criticism or the critic quickly enough, I will not have to feel diminished.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- You’re only saying that to diminish me.\n- Your tone proves the feedback is invalid.\n- Before criticizing me, look at your own flaws.\n- I won’t let you speak to me like that.\n- This is an attack, not feedback.\n- I need to shut this down before I’m humiliated.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nHeat, contempt, or counterattack when corrected; inability to separate feedback from rejection; urgency to expose the critic’s flaws.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAttacking tone or credentials; retaliatory criticism; mocking feedback; ending discussion abruptly; punishing people who raise concerns.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Autonomy; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPublic correction; evaluative settings; perceived disrespect; repeated criticism; shame; authority conflict.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nCorrection is humiliation; mistakes remove status or love; feedback is a power move.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFallibility; dependence on others’ perspective; shame; grief over impact; learning in public.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior counterattacks; Ruler punishes dissent; Sage discredits the critic; Creator rejects the audience; Rebel treats all feedback as control; Lover experiences correction as rejection.\n## Pattern Flow\nFeedback arrives → worth, competence, or autonomy feels threatened → the critic is attacked or devalued → temporary power returns → useful information is lost and others become silent → criticism later arrives with greater intensity.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensiveness; Perfectionism; Defensive Expertise; Devaluation; Blame Shifting.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSelf-protection; discernment about unfair judgment; resistance to domination; standards for respectful communication.\n## Current Cost\nLost learning; fear in relationships or teams; retaliation cycles; isolation; repeated blind spots.\n## Freer Expression\nDiscernment without retaliation.\n## One Act of Volition\nRepeat the feedback neutrally and identify one potentially useful element before responding to tone or fairness.\n## Mira Language\n“The delivery may have been poor, and your reaction appears to be moving from self-protection into attack. What information can be evaluated without surrendering your dignity?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did the feedback threaten? What part is inaccurate, and what part may still be useful? How can you set a boundary without retaliation?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nHarassment, contempt, discriminatory attack, chronic fault-finding, and abusive criticism should not be reframed as helpful feedback.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated attack, punishment, or devaluation in response to correction—not one firm rejection of unfair criticism.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause before counterattack, separate delivery from content, evaluate evidence, and respond with either ownership, clarification, or a boundary.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nUse specific behavior and impact, avoid global character judgments, maintain a calm boundary around retaliation, and disengage when safety or dignity is compromised.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge both the original issue and any retaliation used to silence feedback. Restore the other person’s right to speak, address the substantive concern, and agree on a safer feedback process.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Withholding, Stonewalling, People-Pleasing, Contempt, or covert Keeping Score. Often triggered by Criticism, public shame, Perfectionism, or Defensive Expertise. The loop becomes: “It is unsafe to tell you the truth” and “People only speak to diminish me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat truth might remain after I remove the sting of how it was delivered?"},
  "PP-HUMOR-DEFLECTION": {"name":"Humor Deflection","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Sarcasm as Armor; Vulnerability Avoidance; Emotional Numbing; Intellectualizing; Distraction; People-Pleasing; Emotional Inhibition; Busyness as Avoidance.","Archetypal Role":"Trickster — levity becomes escape. Caregiver — humor manages everyone’s comfort. Innocent — pain is made harmless.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"H","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Let the serious sentence stand for ten seconds before adding humor.","Core Logic":"I am turning this into a joke so it does not have to stay real.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Unmet support needs; emotional loneliness; misunderstood distress; interrupted repair.","Core Fear":"Serious feelings overwhelm people; I must keep the room comfortable; pain makes me burdensome.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should make this funny before it gets too heavy.; If everyone laughs, no one has to worry about me.; Seriousness will make the room uncomfortable.; I can disclose it as long as I turn it into a bit.; I need to lighten this before anyone responds emotionally.; The joke feels safer than letting the truth remain visible.","Protective Move":"Humor Deflection is the protective redirection of serious, painful, or intimate material into comedy so it does not have to be fully felt, answered, or witnessed.","Pattern ID":"PP-HUMOR-DEFLECTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Tension drops when humor redirects attention away from serious feeling.","Freer Expression":"Levity that leaves room for truth.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Levity; resilience; social intelligence; perspective.","Observable Cues":"Joking after disclosure; changing serious topics into bits; performing amusement while distressed; repeatedly preventing emotional depth.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Enjoy the humor without letting it erase the disclosure; gently return to the underlying content. May trigger Pursuit, Frustration, Emotional Distancing, or Minimizing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Belonging, Emotional Regulation, and Dignity; avoids grief, fear, helplessness, awkwardness, and need.","Canonical Name":"Humor Deflection"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nHumor Deflection is the protective redirection of serious, painful, or intimate material into comedy so it does not have to be fully felt, answered, or witnessed.\n## Domain\nAvoidance, Emotion, and Communication\n## Related Patterns\nSarcasm as Armor; Vulnerability Avoidance; Emotional Numbing; Intellectualizing; Distraction\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am turning this into a joke so it does not have to stay real.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should make this funny before it gets too heavy.\n- If everyone laughs, no one has to worry about me.\n- Seriousness will make the room uncomfortable.\n- I can disclose it as long as I turn it into a bit.\n- I need to lighten this before anyone responds emotionally.\n- The joke feels safer than letting the truth remain visible.\n## Recognition Signals — Internal\nPressure to lighten the moment; discomfort when others remain serious; relief when laughter interrupts feeling.\n## Observable Behaviors\nJoking after disclosure; changing serious topics into bits; performing amusement while distressed; repeatedly preventing emotional depth.\n## Core Human Needs\nSafety; Belonging; Emotional Regulation; Dignity.\n## Triggers\nGrief; conflict; shame; intimacy; helplessness; being witnessed.\n## Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nSerious feelings overwhelm people; I must keep the room comfortable; pain makes me burdensome.\n## Feelings or Realities Avoided\nGrief; fear; helplessness; awkwardness; need.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nTrickster — levity becomes escape. Caregiver — humor manages everyone’s comfort. Innocent — pain is made harmless.\n## Pattern Flow\nSerious feeling emerges → emotional exposure rises → humor redirects attention → tension drops → the feeling remains unprocessed → others stop knowing when seriousness is needed.\n## Often Appears With\nPeople-Pleasing; Emotional Inhibition; Busyness as Avoidance; Vulnerability Avoidance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside\nLevity; resilience; social intelligence; perspective.\n## Current Cost\nUnmet support needs; emotional loneliness; misunderstood distress; interrupted repair.\n## Freer Expression\nLevity that leaves room for truth.\n## One Act of Volition\nLet the serious sentence stand for ten seconds before adding humor.\n## Mira Language\n“The humor may be helping regulate the room. Can we also stay with what was just said?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat becomes harder if no one laughs? Are you asking for relief, witness, or distance? Can both humor and seriousness be true?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nHumor can be healthy regulation and meaning-making; the pattern requires repeated avoidance of needed emotional contact.\n## Evidence Threshold\nHumor consistently interrupts vulnerable material or prevents response across situations.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nKeep the gift of humor, but pair it with a clear signal: “I’m joking, and I am also genuinely hurting.”\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nEnjoy the humor without letting it erase the disclosure; gently return to the underlying content.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where humor invalidated or abandoned another person’s seriousness, acknowledge impact, and re-enter the conversation without performing escape.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Pursuit, Frustration, Emotional Distancing, or Minimizing. Often triggered by Intensity, Shame, or another person’s distress. The story becomes: “I must lighten this” ↔︎ “You will never take me seriously.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat truth am I making funny before it can be felt?"},
  "PP-HYPER-INDEPENDENCE": {"name":"Hyper-Independence","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Help-Rejection; Emotional Distancing; Overfunctioning; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Control-Seeking; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Explorer — freedom excludes reliance. Warrior — strength excludes support. Ruler — delegation feels unsafe. Orphan/Everyman — belonging is wanted but distrusted.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"H","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Accept one bounded form of help while naming the terms clearly.","Core Logic":"I would rather carry too much than need someone who might fail or control me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Isolation; exhaustion; limited intimacy; unshared burden; others feel unnecessary or distrusted.","Core Fear":"Need will be used against me; others will fail; receiving creates debt; vulnerability invites control.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I’d rather do it myself.; Needing help gives someone power over me.; I can’t count on anyone to follow through.; Receiving support will create a debt.; I should carry this alone rather than risk disappointment.; If I rely on them, I may lose my freedom.","Protective Move":"Hyper-Independence protects against disappointment, control, indebtedness, or vulnerability by making self-sufficiency the condition of safety.","Pattern ID":"PP-HYPER-INDEPENDENCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns when support is refused and the burden is absorbed alone.","Freer Expression":"Interdependence without captivity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Resourcefulness; competence; resilience; autonomy.","Observable Cues":"Refusing support; concealing need; doing everything alone; leaving before relying; discomfort with reciprocity.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer specific, non-intrusive support; respect no; do not create debt or demand disclosure. May trigger Underfunctioning, Clinging, Resentment, Micromanaging, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Trust, Competence, and Self-Esteem; avoids need, gratitude, uncertainty, mutual dependence, and disappointment.","Canonical Name":"Hyper-Independence"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nHyper-Independence protects against disappointment, control, indebtedness, or vulnerability by making self-sufficiency the condition of safety.\n## Domain\nAutonomy, Dependence, and Trust\n## Related Patterns\nHelp-Rejection; Emotional Distancing; Overfunctioning; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Control-Seeking\n## Recognition Sentence\nI would rather carry too much than need someone who might fail or control me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I’d rather do it myself.\n- Needing help gives someone power over me.\n- I can’t count on anyone to follow through.\n- Receiving support will create a debt.\n- I should carry this alone rather than risk disappointment.\n- If I rely on them, I may lose my freedom.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nReceiving help feels exposing; dependence feels dangerous; relief comes from needing no one.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRefusing support; concealing need; doing everything alone; leaving before relying; discomfort with reciprocity.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Trust; Competence; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nOffers of help; illness; financial dependence; intimacy; unreliable follow-through; power imbalance.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nNeed will be used against me; others will fail; receiving creates debt; vulnerability invites control.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nNeed; gratitude; uncertainty; mutual dependence; disappointment.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nExplorer — freedom excludes reliance. Warrior — strength excludes support. Ruler — delegation feels unsafe. Orphan/Everyman — belonging is wanted but distrusted.\n## Pattern Flow\nNeed appears → autonomy or trust feels threatened → support is refused and burden absorbed → temporary control returns → exhaustion and isolation deepen.\n## Often Appears With\nOverfunctioning; Emotional Distancing; Help-Rejection; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nResourcefulness; competence; resilience; autonomy.\n## Current Cost\nIsolation; exhaustion; limited intimacy; unshared burden; others feel unnecessary or distrusted.\n## Freer Expression\nInterdependence without captivity.\n## One Act of Volition\nAccept one bounded form of help while naming the terms clearly.\n## Mira Language\n“Your independence is real. Is it also protecting you from the risk of needing someone?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you fear receiving would cost you? What kind of help preserves choice?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSolitude, competence, privacy, and legitimate caution are not hyper-independence.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated refusal of safe, useful support despite meaningful cost.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDefine boundaries around help rather than rejecting help itself.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer specific, non-intrusive support; respect no; do not create debt or demand disclosure.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where unilateral decisions, refusal of partnership, or concealed need excluded others; renegotiate shared responsibility without forced dependence.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Clinging, Resentment, Micromanaging, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by unreliability, control, indebtedness, or disappointment. The loop becomes “I cannot depend on you” versus “There is no place for me to contribute.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere has self-sufficiency become the price of safety?"},
  "PP-HYPERVIGILANCE": {"name":"Hypervigilance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Catastrophizing; Mind Reading; Emotional Reasoning; Testing the Bond; Micromanaging; Rumination; Reassurance Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior anticipates attack; Caregiver monitors everyone’s stability; Ruler tracks failures; Lover watches for withdrawal; Sage analyzes clues; Explorer maps exits.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Trauma/Dissociation from the source’s explicit trauma caution; the additional medical-differential language remains in the body and notes.","First Letter":"H","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Choose one real indicator that requires action and allow one ambiguous indicator to remain uninvestigated for a defined period.","Core Logic":"If I stop watching, something important may go wrong before I can prevent it.","Safety Flags":["Trauma/Dissociation"],"Primary Domain":"Somatic","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; strained trust; intrusive monitoring; irritability; poor rest; false alarms; reduced spontaneity.","Core Fear":"Danger arrives suddenly; other people are unpredictable; I must notice first; relaxing makes me vulnerable.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Something feels off; I need to keep watching.; If I relax, I’ll miss the warning sign.; I need to check one more time.; Small changes usually mean something.; I can’t feel safe until I know where everyone is.; Being caught off guard is not an option.","Protective Move":"Hypervigilance is the protective habit of continuously scanning people, situations, and bodily signals for possible danger so that harm, rejection, conflict, or loss will not arrive without warning.","Pattern ID":"PP-HYPERVIGILANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary preparedness or reassurance appears as scanning and checking intensify.","Freer Expression":"Attentive safety without permanent alarm.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Perception; preparedness; sensitivity; risk awareness; protectiveness.","Observable Cues":"Monitoring messages, locations, expressions, or routines; repeated checking; asking anticipatory questions; noticing small changes and assigning them significance; difficulty resting in shared spaces.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Be consistent and clear without submitting to surveillance or endless reassurance. Name reasonable availability, answer direct questions once, and maintain boundaries around monitoring, accusation, or control. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Secrecy, Defensiveness, Anger as Armor, or Withdrawing Before Being Left.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Trust, Autonomy, and Belonging; avoids helplessness, uncertainty, grief, dependence, and the limits of control.","Canonical Name":"Hypervigilance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nHypervigilance is the protective habit of continuously scanning people, situations, and bodily signals for possible danger so that harm, rejection, conflict, or loss will not arrive without warning.\n## Domain\nThreat, Safety, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nCatastrophizing; Mind Reading; Emotional Reasoning; Testing the Bond; Micromanaging; Rumination\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I stop watching, something important may go wrong before I can prevent it.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Something feels off; I need to keep watching.\n- If I relax, I’ll miss the warning sign.\n- I need to check one more time.\n- Small changes usually mean something.\n- I can’t feel safe until I know where everyone is.\n- Being caught off guard is not an option.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPersistent alertness; difficulty settling; sensitivity to tone, delay, movement, or mood changes; relief only after checking; inability to feel fully off duty.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nMonitoring messages, locations, expressions, or routines; repeated checking; asking anticipatory questions; noticing small changes and assigning them significance; difficulty resting in shared spaces.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Trust; Autonomy; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUncertainty; inconsistent behavior; previous betrayal; conflict; silence; travel or separation; ambiguous physical sensations; low bandwidth.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDanger arrives suddenly; other people are unpredictable; I must notice first; relaxing makes me vulnerable.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHelplessness; uncertainty; grief; dependence; the limits of control.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior anticipates attack; Caregiver monitors everyone’s stability; Ruler tracks failures; Lover watches for withdrawal; Sage analyzes clues; Explorer maps exits.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguity appears → safety or trust feels threatened → scanning and checking intensify → temporary preparedness or reassurance appears → the nervous system remains activated → ambiguity becomes increasingly difficult to tolerate.\n## Often Appears With\nCatastrophizing; Mind Reading; Reassurance Seeking; Micromanaging; Rumination.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nPerception; preparedness; sensitivity; risk awareness; protectiveness.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; strained trust; intrusive monitoring; irritability; poor rest; false alarms; reduced spontaneity.\n## Freer Expression\nAttentive safety without permanent alarm.\n## One Act of Volition\nChoose one real indicator that requires action and allow one ambiguous indicator to remain uninvestigated for a defined period.\n## Mira Language\n“Your system seems to be searching continuously for the next sign of danger. Is there a current threat requiring action, or is vigilance trying to prevent the feeling of being caught off guard?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence would distinguish danger from uncertainty? What happens in your body when you stop checking? What boundary or plan would create safety without surveillance?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGenuine danger, unstable environments, trauma exposure, health concerns, or safety-critical work may justify increased alertness. Mira must not diagnose a trauma disorder.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of scanning, checking, and inability to settle across ambiguous situations—not one prudent safety check.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nValidate the wish to stay safe, orient to present evidence, regulate the body, define actionable thresholds, and replace continuous scanning with scheduled review or a concrete safety plan.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nBe consistent and clear without submitting to surveillance or endless reassurance. Name reasonable availability, answer direct questions once, and maintain boundaries around monitoring, accusation, or control.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where vigilance became intrusion, accusation, emotional pressure, or loss of privacy. Restore autonomy, clarify mutually acceptable transparency, and demonstrate change by tolerating uncertainty without renewed monitoring.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Secrecy, Defensiveness, Anger as Armor, or Withdrawing Before Being Left. Often triggered by inconsistency, secrecy, Mind Reading, Testing the Bond, or emotional unpredictability. The loop becomes: “I must watch because you are unsafe” and “I must hide or withdraw because I am always watched.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I watching for, and what would genuine present-day safety require instead?"},
  "PP-IDEALIZATION": {"name":"Idealization","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Splitting; Fusion; Grandiosity; Projection; Devaluation.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — the beloved becomes salvation. Mystic — another becomes spiritually destined. Ruler — a leader becomes infallible. Creator — a project becomes the answer to everything. Innocent — goodness is preserved by ignoring complexity.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Name one admired quality, one unknown, and one limitation.","Core Logic":"I need you to be extraordinary so the bond can make me safe, whole, or certain.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Poor discernment; dependency; ignored risk; unstable attachment; severe disillusionment.","Core Fear":"Ordinary love will not be enough; I need someone greater than me to be safe; if I see the flaws, I may lose the bond.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This person may be the answer to everything.; I’ve never met anyone this extraordinary.; The warning signs don’t matter because the bond feels destined.; They understand me completely already.; This relationship will finally make me whole.; I need them to stay exceptional so I can feel safe.","Protective Move":"Idealization protects hope, belonging, or self-worth by enlarging another person, relationship, group, or future beyond available evidence.","Pattern ID":"PP-IDEALIZATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Hope and belonging surge when the person or future is elevated.","Freer Expression":"Admiration with reality.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Admiration; hope; devotion; capacity to perceive potential.","Observable Cues":"Attributing exceptional qualities without sufficient evidence; dismissing warning signs; rapid commitment; treating criticism as misunderstanding; building identity around the bond.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not exploit admiration; resist premature promises; invite realism and equal footing. May trigger Performance, Grandiosity, Fusion, Withdrawal, or Devaluation.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, Purpose, and Self-Esteem; avoids loneliness, ordinariness, grief, uncertainty, mutual limitation, and self-responsibility.","Canonical Name":"Idealization"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nIdealization protects hope, belonging, or self-worth by enlarging another person, relationship, group, or future beyond available evidence.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nSplitting; Fusion; Grandiosity; Projection; Devaluation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need you to be extraordinary so the bond can make me safe, whole, or certain.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This person may be the answer to everything.\n- I’ve never met anyone this extraordinary.\n- The warning signs don’t matter because the bond feels destined.\n- They understand me completely already.\n- This relationship will finally make me whole.\n- I need them to stay exceptional so I can feel safe.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nIntense certainty early; resistance to contradictory evidence; emotional elevation around the person or idea; feeling rescued, chosen, or completed.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAttributing exceptional qualities without sufficient evidence; dismissing warning signs; rapid commitment; treating criticism as misunderstanding; building identity around the bond.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Purpose; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nLoneliness; uncertainty; transition; admiration; rescue fantasies; unmet attachment needs.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nOrdinary love will not be enough; I need someone greater than me to be safe; if I see the flaws, I may lose the bond.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nLoneliness; ordinariness; grief; uncertainty; mutual limitation; self-responsibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — the beloved becomes salvation. Mystic — another becomes spiritually destined. Ruler — a leader becomes infallible. Creator — a project becomes the answer to everything. Innocent — goodness is preserved by ignoring complexity.\n## Pattern Flow\nLonging intensifies → ordinary uncertainty feels painful → the person or future is elevated → hope and belonging surge → contradictory evidence is excluded → disillusionment becomes likely.\n## Often Appears With\nFusion; Splitting; Devaluation; Grandiosity.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAdmiration; hope; devotion; capacity to perceive potential.\n## Current Cost\nPoor discernment; dependency; ignored risk; unstable attachment; severe disillusionment.\n## Freer Expression\nAdmiration with reality.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one admired quality, one unknown, and one limitation.\n## Mira Language\n“The bond may be meaningful. What would remain valuable if neither person had to be extraordinary?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you hoping this person will rescue? What evidence is missing? What remains unknown?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAdmiration, infatuation, faith, and optimism are not automatically idealization.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated inflation paired with exclusion of credible contradictory evidence.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPreserve wonder while slowing commitment; seek disconfirming evidence; maintain independent routines and judgment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not exploit admiration; resist premature promises; invite realism and equal footing.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge unrealistic expectations, ignored evidence, and pressure placed on the other person to carry salvation or perfection. Repair restores equality and realistic agreements.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Performance, Grandiosity, Fusion, Withdrawal, or Devaluation. Often triggered by loneliness, charisma, rescue behavior, or ambiguity. The loop becomes “You must remain extraordinary” versus “I must perform extraordinariness or escape.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I asking this person or future to save me from feeling?"},
  "PP-IDENTITY-FUSION": {"name":"Identity Fusion","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Fusion; Moral Superiority; Adversarial Framing; Role Entrapment; Defensive Expertise; Defensiveness.","Archetypal Role":"Everyman — belonging becomes sameness. Rebel — cause becomes self. Ruler — institution becomes identity. Lover — relationship becomes selfhood.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Name one value or view that is yours even when the group differs.","Core Logic":"If this identity is questioned, I feel as though I am being erased.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Polarization; loss of self; susceptibility to group pressure; relational rupture.","Core Fear":"Without the group I am no one; doubt means betrayal; belonging requires total loyalty.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Questioning this group feels like questioning me.; If I doubt the belief, I may betray everyone.; Without this identity, I don’t know who I am.; Their criticism is a personal attack.; Loyalty means defending the group without reservation.; Difference feels like abandonment or erasure.","Protective Move":"Identity Fusion collapses the boundary between the self and a group, cause, belief, role, or relationship so that questioning it feels like annihilation, betrayal, or personal attack.","Pattern ID":"PP-IDENTITY-FUSION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary solidity returns when defense and conformity intensify.","Freer Expression":"Belonging with differentiation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Loyalty; solidarity; commitment; shared purpose.","Observable Cues":"Defending identity markers regardless of evidence; cutting off dissenters; equating loyalty with sameness.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Critique claims or behavior specifically; avoid contempt for identity; maintain boundaries around harm. May trigger Adversarial Framing, Contempt, Withdrawal, or Moral Superiority.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Purpose, Self-Esteem, and Trust; avoids individuality, ambiguity, disillusionment, loneliness, and moral complexity.","Canonical Name":"Identity Fusion"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nIdentity Fusion collapses the boundary between the self and a group, cause, belief, role, or relationship so that questioning it feels like annihilation, betrayal, or personal attack.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Belonging, and Adaptation\n## Related Patterns\nFusion; Moral Superiority; Adversarial Framing; Role Entrapment; Defensive Expertise\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf this identity is questioned, I feel as though I am being erased.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Questioning this group feels like questioning me.\n- If I doubt the belief, I may betray everyone.\n- Without this identity, I don’t know who I am.\n- Their criticism is a personal attack.\n- Loyalty means defending the group without reservation.\n- Difference feels like abandonment or erasure.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nCriticism of the group or belief feels intensely personal; doubt evokes panic, shame, or rage.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDefending identity markers regardless of evidence; cutting off dissenters; equating loyalty with sameness.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Purpose; Self-Esteem; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDissent; identity transition; group conflict; criticism; exclusion.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nWithout the group I am no one; doubt means betrayal; belonging requires total loyalty.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nIndividuality; ambiguity; disillusionment; loneliness; moral complexity.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nEveryman — belonging becomes sameness. Rebel — cause becomes self. Ruler — institution becomes identity. Lover — relationship becomes selfhood.\n## Pattern Flow\nIdentity is questioned → belonging and existence feel threatened → defense and conformity intensify → temporary solidity returns → nuance and autonomy shrink.\n## Often Appears With\nMoral Superiority; Adversarial Framing; Defensiveness; Role Entrapment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nLoyalty; solidarity; commitment; shared purpose.\n## Current Cost\nPolarization; loss of self; susceptibility to group pressure; relational rupture.\n## Freer Expression\nBelonging with differentiation.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one value or view that is yours even when the group differs.\n## Mira Language\n“The identity matters deeply. Can it be questioned without your personhood being questioned?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWho are you beyond this affiliation? What uncertainty would differentiation create?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nStrong community identity, faith, culture, or political commitment is not automatically fusion.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated inability to distinguish critique of an affiliation from attack on the self.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nGround dignity in personhood and values broader than affiliation.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nCritique claims or behavior specifically; avoid contempt for identity; maintain boundaries around harm.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where loyalty tests, dismissal, or identity defense erased another’s reality; restore room for difference without forced agreement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Adversarial Framing, Contempt, Withdrawal, or Moral Superiority. Often triggered by exclusion, dissent, or identity shame. The loop becomes “Your disagreement proves betrayal” versus “Your identity leaves no room for me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat remains of me when this group, role, belief, or relationship is not the whole of me?"},
  "PP-IMAGE-MANAGEMENT": {"name":"Image Management","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Grandiosity; Approval Seeking; Impression Management; Concealment; Perfectionism; Rationalization; Denial.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler — authority must appear unshaken. Creator — the persona becomes part of the product. Sage — certainty is performed. Lover — desirability is curated. Rebel — authenticity itself becomes an image.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Include one relevant truth that complicates the polished version without oversharing.","Core Logic":"I am managing what you see so I can control what you conclude about me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Fragile identity; concealment; distrust; performance fatigue; barriers to intimacy and learning.","Core Fear":"The unedited self is unacceptable; reputation determines safety; mistakes become identity; vulnerability will be used against me.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to control what they conclude about me.; This detail would ruin the image.; I should only show the polished version.; If they see the inconsistency, I’ll lose respect.; I can be vulnerable only in ways that support the persona.; I need to edit the story before anyone sees the limitation.","Protective Move":"Image Management is the protective shaping, editing, or concealment of information to control how one is perceived and reduce exposure to shame, rejection, or loss of status.","Pattern ID":"PP-IMAGE-MANAGEMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Approval or protection arrives when presentation is controlled.","Freer Expression":"Intentional presentation without falsification.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Communication; aesthetic discernment; contextual awareness; reputation stewardship; intentional self-presentation.","Observable Cues":"Curating achievements; hiding mistakes; adjusting stories to the audience; strategic vulnerability; excessive branding of identity; denying needs that conflict with the desired image.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not demand total exposure. Reward accuracy over polish, respond proportionately to imperfection, and maintain boundaries around deception. May trigger Suspicion, Investigation, Contempt, or Strategic Concealment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Belonging, Competence, and Trust; avoids shame, ordinariness, inconsistency, dependence, accountability, and being misunderstood without total control.","Canonical Name":"Image Management"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nImage Management is the protective shaping, editing, or concealment of information to control how one is perceived and reduce exposure to shame, rejection, or loss of status.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nGrandiosity; Approval Seeking; Impression Management; Concealment; Perfectionism\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am managing what you see so I can control what you conclude about me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to control what they conclude about me.\n- This detail would ruin the image.\n- I should only show the polished version.\n- If they see the inconsistency, I’ll lose respect.\n- I can be vulnerable only in ways that support the persona.\n- I need to edit the story before anyone sees the limitation.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPreoccupation with presentation; fear of being seen as inconsistent or ordinary; urge to omit unflattering context; relief when perception is controlled.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nCurating achievements; hiding mistakes; adjusting stories to the audience; strategic vulnerability; excessive branding of identity; denying needs that conflict with the desired image.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Belonging; Competence; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPublic visibility; evaluation; social hierarchy; mistakes; contradiction; exposure of dependency or limitation.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nThe unedited self is unacceptable; reputation determines safety; mistakes become identity; vulnerability will be used against me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; ordinariness; inconsistency; dependence; accountability; being misunderstood without total control.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler — authority must appear unshaken. Creator — the persona becomes part of the product. Sage — certainty is performed. Lover — desirability is curated. Rebel — authenticity itself becomes an image.\n## Pattern Flow\nVisibility approaches → worth or status feels threatened → presentation is controlled → approval or protection arrives → authenticity and correction decrease → exposure becomes more frightening.\n## Often Appears With\nGrandiosity; Perfectionism; Rationalization; Denial; Approval Seeking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCommunication; aesthetic discernment; contextual awareness; reputation stewardship; intentional self-presentation.\n## Current Cost\nFragile identity; concealment; distrust; performance fatigue; barriers to intimacy and learning.\n## Freer Expression\nIntentional presentation without falsification.\n## One Act of Volition\nInclude one relevant truth that complicates the polished version without oversharing.\n## Mira Language\n“Presentation matters, but I wonder whether you are communicating clearly or trying to prevent anyone from seeing a human limitation.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat conclusion are you trying to control? What truth feels incompatible with the image? What would honest context change?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nPrivacy, professionalism, branding, discretion, and role-appropriate presentation are not automatically Image Management.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated distortion, concealment, or identity performance organized around controlling evaluation.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDistinguish privacy from falsification, tolerate a more complete self-image, and practice accurate disclosure proportionate to the relationship and stakes.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not demand total exposure. Reward accuracy over polish, respond proportionately to imperfection, and maintain boundaries around deception.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nCorrect the record plainly, acknowledge what was curated or concealed and its impact on trust, and demonstrate change through consistent accuracy rather than a more convincing performance.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Investigation, Contempt, or Strategic Concealment in others. Often triggered by judgment, public shame, status competition, or punitive reactions to error. The loop becomes “I must control the image to remain safe” and “I must look harder because the image cannot be trusted.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I protecting by controlling how I am seen?"},
  "PP-IMPOSTORISM": {"name":"Impostorism","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Perfectionism; Comparison; Defensive Expertise; Approval Seeking; Endless Preparation.","Archetypal Role":"Sage — must know everything. Creator — success was accidental. Ruler — authority feels fraudulent. Everyman — standing out threatens belonging.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"State one accomplishment and the concrete contribution you made to it without qualification.","Core Logic":"If I admit I belong here, exposure will hurt more.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; underclaiming; missed opportunities; inability to internalize growth.","Core Fear":"Belonging is conditional; competence must be constantly proven.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They’ll eventually discover I don’t belong here.; My success was probably luck.; I need to work twice as hard to justify my place.; Praise doesn’t count because they don’t know the whole truth.; I shouldn’t claim competence until I know everything.; If I accept that I belong, exposure will hurt more.","Protective Move":"Impostorism is the protective discounting of one’s earned competence or belonging in order to stay ahead of possible exposure, criticism, or rejection.","Pattern ID":"PP-IMPOSTORISM","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary safety comes through humility or overwork when competence is discounted and effort increases.","Freer Expression":"Grounded earned belonging.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Humility; conscientiousness; respect for complexity; commitment to learning.","Observable Cues":"Minimizing credentials; attributing success to luck; declining opportunities; overworking to justify inclusion.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer concrete feedback rather than generic reassurance; avoid inflating or dismissing concerns. May trigger Micromanaging, Reassurance Seeking, Overfunctioning, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Belonging, Self-Esteem, and Trust; avoids pride, uncertainty, ordinary learning, and receiving recognition.","Canonical Name":"Impostorism"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nImpostorism is the protective discounting of one’s earned competence or belonging in order to stay ahead of possible exposure, criticism, or rejection.\n## Domain\nCompetence, Identity, and Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nPerfectionism; Comparison; Defensive Expertise; Approval Seeking; Endless Preparation\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I admit I belong here, exposure will hurt more.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They’ll eventually discover I don’t belong here.\n- My success was probably luck.\n- I need to work twice as hard to justify my place.\n- Praise doesn’t count because they don’t know the whole truth.\n- I shouldn’t claim competence until I know everything.\n- If I accept that I belong, exposure will hurt more.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAchievements feel accidental; praise does not land; fear of being found out; chronic overpreparation.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nMinimizing credentials; attributing success to luck; declining opportunities; overworking to justify inclusion.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Belonging; Self-Esteem; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAdvancement; visibility; unfamiliar status; comparison; praise.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBelonging is conditional; competence must be constantly proven.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nPride; uncertainty; ordinary learning; receiving recognition.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage — must know everything. Creator — success was accidental. Ruler — authority feels fraudulent. Everyman — standing out threatens belonging.\n## Pattern Flow\nOpportunity or recognition → exposure fear rises → competence is discounted and effort increases → temporary safety through humility or overwork → confidence cannot consolidate.\n## Often Appears With\nPerfectionism; Comparison; Approval Seeking; Endless Preparation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHumility; conscientiousness; respect for complexity; commitment to learning.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; underclaiming; missed opportunities; inability to internalize growth.\n## Freer Expression\nGrounded earned belonging.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one accomplishment and the concrete contribution you made to it without qualification.\n## Mira Language\n“Your caution may be protecting you from the pain of exposure, but it may also be preventing earned competence from becoming part of your self-understanding.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence shows you contributed? What standard are you using that no real person could meet? What would belonging as a learner look like?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nHumility, new-role uncertainty, and awareness of limits are not impostorism.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated discounting of credible evidence across contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nGather specific evidence, normalize the learning curve, and let competence be partial rather than absolute.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer concrete feedback rather than generic reassurance; avoid inflating or dismissing concerns.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where chronic self-doubt shifted labor, decisions, or reassurance demands onto others; reclaim appropriate responsibility.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Reassurance Seeking, Overfunctioning, or Resentment. Often triggered by Comparison, Criticism, Defensive Expertise, or high-status environments.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat earned evidence am I refusing to let count?"},
  "PP-INDECISION": {"name":"Indecision","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Certainty Seeking; Rumination; Risk Avoidance; Perfectionism; Decision Delegation; Failure to Launch; Procrastination.","Archetypal Role":"Sage keeps researching. Creator keeps all concepts open. Seeker refuses commitment to preserve possibility. Ruler delays until control is complete.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Set a decision rule and deadline, then choose the option that best serves the named value.","Core Logic":"I am keeping every option alive so I do not have to bear the cost of choosing.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Lost opportunities; decision fatigue; dependency; erosion of agency; choices made by circumstance.","Core Fear":"Wrong choices are unforgivable; I cannot trust myself; responsibility leads to blame; certainty must precede action.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to keep every option open.; One more round of thinking might remove the risk.; Choosing one path means losing all the others.; I can’t decide until I know I won’t regret it.; Maybe someone else can tell me which option is right.; Delay feels safer than owning the choice.","Protective Move":"Indecision is the protective suspension of choice when choosing would create responsibility, loss, uncertainty, or possible regret. Unlike ordinary deliberation, it persists after sufficient information is available.","Pattern ID":"PP-INDECISION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief comes from postponement and keeping options open.","Freer Expression":"Discernment with commitment.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; foresight; openness to complexity.","Observable Cues":"Endless pros-and-cons lists; reopening settled decisions; missing decision windows; asking many people but remaining unmoved; choosing by default through delay.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer structure rather than taking over; clarify consequences and deadlines; do not repeatedly provide reassurance that substitutes for agency. May trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Resentment, or Decision Delegation in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Competence, Safety, and Self-Esteem; avoids grief for unchosen paths, limitation, responsibility, uncertainty, and ordinary regret.","Canonical Name":"Indecision"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nIndecision is the protective suspension of choice when choosing would create responsibility, loss, uncertainty, or possible regret. Unlike ordinary deliberation, it persists after sufficient information is available.\n## Domain\nAgency, Choice, and Uncertainty\n## Related Patterns\nCertainty Seeking; Rumination; Risk Avoidance; Perfectionism; Decision Delegation; Failure to Launch\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am keeping every option alive so I do not have to bear the cost of choosing.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to keep every option open.\n- One more round of thinking might remove the risk.\n- Choosing one path means losing all the others.\n- I can’t decide until I know I won’t regret it.\n- Maybe someone else can tell me which option is right.\n- Delay feels safer than owning the choice.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRepeatedly revisiting the same options; urgency followed by paralysis; fear that one choice permanently condemns the others; desire for a guarantee.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nEndless pros-and-cons lists; reopening settled decisions; missing decision windows; asking many people but remaining unmoved; choosing by default through delay.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Competence; Safety; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nIrreversible choices; incomplete information; competing values; visible consequences; prior regret or criticism.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nWrong choices are unforgivable; I cannot trust myself; responsibility leads to blame; certainty must precede action.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief for unchosen paths; limitation; responsibility; uncertainty; ordinary regret.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage keeps researching. Creator keeps all concepts open. Seeker refuses commitment to preserve possibility. Ruler delays until control is complete.\n## Pattern Flow\nChoice becomes necessary → competence or safety feels threatened → evaluation expands without endpoint → temporary relief comes from postponement → opportunity narrows → self-trust declines.\n## Often Appears With\nRumination; Certainty Seeking; Risk Avoidance; Perfectionism; Procrastination.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; foresight; openness to complexity.\n## Current Cost\nLost opportunities; decision fatigue; dependency; erosion of agency; choices made by circumstance.\n## Freer Expression\nDiscernment with commitment.\n## One Act of Volition\nSet a decision rule and deadline, then choose the option that best serves the named value.\n## Mira Language\n“It sounds as though more thinking is no longer producing new information. Is the remaining task analysis, or accepting that every real choice includes uncertainty and loss?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat information is genuinely missing? What value should decide this? What cost are you already paying by not choosing?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nComplex, high-stakes, legal, medical, or safety decisions may properly require extended deliberation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated postponement after adequate information, with no clear decision rule and growing cost.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the decision, distinguish reversible from irreversible elements, define sufficient information, and accept bounded uncertainty.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer structure rather than taking over; clarify consequences and deadlines; do not repeatedly provide reassurance that substitutes for agency.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where delay transferred burdens or left others unable to plan; make the current decision; name what will change in future decision timelines.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Resentment, or Decision Delegation in others. Often triggered by Criticism, Catastrophizing, or another person’s urgency. Stories become “I cannot trust you to decide” and “I cannot decide safely while being pressured.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat loss am I trying to avoid by refusing to choose?"},
  "PP-INDISPENSABILITY": {"name":"Indispensability","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Overfunctioning; Rescuing; Savior Identity; Micromanaging; Information Control; Compulsive Achievement; People-Pleasing.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver—care becomes necessary dependence; Ruler—authority is preserved by centralizing decisions; Sage—expertise becomes exclusive access; Creator—only the originator can protect the vision; Warrior—constant readiness becomes value.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing repaired. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Transfer one meaningful responsibility, along with the information and authority needed to carry it, without taking it back at the first sign of difficulty.","Core Logic":"I feel safer when I am needed enough that I cannot be left out or replaced.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; bottlenecks; resentment; succession failure; weakened autonomy in others; relationships organized around usefulness rather than mutuality.","Core Fear":"I am valued mainly for what I do; if I am not useful, I will be forgotten or replaced; dependence is the safest form of attachment; others’ autonomy means my importance is shrinking.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They cannot manage without me.; If I step back, I may become irrelevant.; I need to remain the person everyone depends on.; Delegating could make me replaceable.; My value comes from holding everything together.; I should take this back before they fail.","Protective Move":"Attempts to secure belonging, worth, influence, or safety by becoming so necessary that others cannot easily proceed, decide, or function without the person.","Pattern ID":"PP-INDISPENSABILITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Re-centralizing responsibility, access, or expertise restores temporary security.","Freer Expression":"Contribution without captivity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Reliability; stewardship; expertise; devotion; anticipatory care; organizational memory.","Observable Cues":"Taking over tasks others could learn; retaining key knowledge, contacts, or procedures; solving problems before others attempt them; remaining involved after transfer; building systems around personal availability.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appreciate contribution without reinforcing exclusivity; request documentation, shared access, delegated authority, and clear role boundaries.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, self-esteem, competence, trust, and autonomy; avoids replaceability, ordinary interdependence, limits, rest, grief over changing roles, and uncertainty about intrinsic worth.","Canonical Name":"Indispensability"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nIndispensability is the protective attempt to secure belonging, worth, influence, or safety by becoming so necessary that others cannot easily proceed, decide, or function without you.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Belonging, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nOverfunctioning; Rescuing; Savior Identity; Micromanaging; Information Control; Compulsive Achievement; People-Pleasing\n## Recognition Sentence\nI feel safer when I am needed enough that I cannot be left out or replaced.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They cannot manage without me.\n- If I step back, I may become irrelevant.\n- I need to remain the person everyone depends on.\n- Delegating could make me replaceable.\n- My value comes from holding everything together.\n- I should take this back before they fail.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnxiety when others become capable; relief when people depend on your knowledge, labor, or approval; difficulty imagining value apart from being needed; resentment paired with resistance to relinquishing the role; fear that rest, delegation, or replacement will expose irrelevance.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTaking over tasks others could learn; retaining key knowledge, contacts, or procedures; solving problems before others can attempt them; remaining involved after responsibility has transferred; building systems around personal availability.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Self-Esteem; Competence; Trust; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDelegation; role changes; another person’s growing competence; exclusion from decisions; retirement or transition; reduced demand; shared ownership.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am valued mainly for what I do; if I am not useful, I will be forgotten or replaced; dependence is the safest form of attachment; other people’s autonomy means my importance is shrinking; I must hold everything together to remain secure.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nReplaceability; ordinary interdependence; limits; rest; grief over changing roles; uncertainty about intrinsic worth.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver—care becomes necessary dependence; Ruler—authority is preserved by centralizing decisions; Sage—expertise is retained as exclusive access; Creator—only the originator can protect the vision; Warrior—constant readiness becomes the basis of value.\n## Pattern Flow\nReduced need or shared ownership appears → belonging or worth feels threatened → responsibility, access, or expertise is re-centralized → temporary security returns → others remain less capable or more dependent → exhaustion and resentment deepen.\n## Often Appears With\nOverfunctioning; Micromanaging; Rescuing; Information Control; Compulsive Achievement; Emotional Overresponsibility.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReliability; stewardship; expertise; devotion; anticipatory care; organizational memory.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; bottlenecks; resentment; succession failure; weakened autonomy in others; relationships organized around usefulness rather than mutuality.\n## Freer Expression\nContribution without captivity.\n## One Act of Volition\nTransfer one meaningful responsibility, along with the information and authority needed to carry it, without taking it back at the first sign of difficulty.\n## Mira Language\n“You may genuinely carry important knowledge and responsibility. I also notice that stepping back feels threatening, not merely inconvenient. Is being needed protecting you from feeling replaceable, excluded, or less valuable?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you fear would happen to your place here if others no longer needed you in the same way? Are you supporting capability, or preserving dependence? What part of your value remains when you are not solving the problem?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nExpertise, accountability, caregiving, and temporary central coordination are not automatically Indispensability.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA recurring sequence in which reduced dependence triggers anxiety and leads to re-centralizing tasks, knowledge, access, or authority across more than one situation.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRecognize the fear beneath the over-responsibility, separate contribution from irreplaceability, and practice making others more capable rather than more dependent.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAppreciate genuine contribution without reinforcing exclusivity. Request documentation, shared access, delegated authority, and clear role boundaries.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where dependence was created, capability was undermined, information was withheld, or responsibility was reclaimed. Restore access and authority and allow others to act without interference.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Resentment, Defensiveness, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “They cannot manage without me” versus “There is no room for me to become capable.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I making myself necessary in order to feel secure?"},
  "PP-INFORMATION-CONTROL": {"name":"Information Control","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Gatekeeping; Strategic Ambiguity; Emotional Withholding; Plausible Deniability; Interrogative Control; Information Hoarding; Image Management.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler—information becomes centralized authority; Sage—knowledge becomes guarded power; Magician—selective revelation shapes perception; Caregiver—withholds information “for their own good”; Trickster—ambiguity and timing preserve advantage.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing repaired and development-log material omitted. Gift Trapped Inside, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source. Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because consequential informational asymmetry may impair consent or autonomy.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Identify one fact another person reasonably needs in order to make an informed choice, and share it plainly without controlling their response.","Core Logic":"If I control the information, I can control what happens next and how exposed I become.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Mistrust; impaired consent; distorted decisions; isolation; dependence on secrecy; escalation when omissions are discovered; unequal relational power.","Core Fear":"Knowledge is power; disclosure makes me vulnerable; others will use information against me; I must stay ahead to remain safe; if I do not control the story, I will be misrepresented or overruled.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to control who knows what.; Full disclosure would reduce my leverage.; I should wait until I can shape how this is received.; They do not need the whole picture yet.; If they know everything, they may choose differently.; I need to stay ahead of the story.","Protective Move":"Manages what others may know, when they may know it, and how facts are framed in order to preserve leverage, reduce exposure, prevent interference, or stabilize uncertainty.","Pattern ID":"PP-INFORMATION-CONTROL","Short-Term Payoff":"Withholding, delaying, segmenting, or framing information creates temporary leverage and predictability.","Freer Expression":"Transparent discernment—sharing what is relevant, with appropriate boundaries, without using information as leverage.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; confidentiality; timing; diplomacy; strategic communication; protection of sensitive material.","Observable Cues":"Selective disclosure; withholding relevant facts; releasing information strategically; controlling who is included; framing events to shape interpretation; discouraging independent verification.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask specific factual questions and distinguish privacy from information required for consent. May trigger Suspicion, Compulsive Checking, Interrogative Control, Hypervigilance, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, autonomy, trust, status, competence, and self-esteem; avoids vulnerability, mutual dependence, accountability, uncertainty about others’ responses, loss of influence, and others’ informed choices.","Canonical Name":"Information Control"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nInformation Control is the protective management of what others may know, when they may know it, and how facts are framed in order to preserve leverage, reduce exposure, prevent interference, or stabilize uncertainty.\n## Domain\nPower, Safety, and Relational Control\n## Related Patterns\nGatekeeping; Strategic Ambiguity; Emotional Withholding; Plausible Deniability; Interrogative Control; Information Hoarding; Image Management\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I control the information, I can control what happens next and how exposed I become.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to control who knows what.\n- Full disclosure would reduce my leverage.\n- I should wait until I can shape how this is received.\n- They do not need the whole picture yet.\n- If they know everything, they may choose differently.\n- I need to stay ahead of the story.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when others possess only partial information; fear that full disclosure will reduce control; vigilance about timing and wording; urge to manage narratives before others can respond; discomfort when information moves outside one’s control.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSelective disclosure; withholding relevant facts; releasing information strategically; controlling who is included in communication; framing events to shape interpretation; using informational asymmetry as leverage; discouraging independent verification.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Autonomy; Trust; Status; Competence; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUncertainty; conflict; anticipated criticism; fear of interference; competition; accountability; dependency; loss of narrative control; unequal power.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nKnowledge is power; disclosure makes me vulnerable; others will use information against me; I must stay ahead to remain safe; if I do not control the story, I will be misrepresented or overruled.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; mutual dependence; accountability; uncertainty about others’ responses; loss of influence; the possibility that others may make informed choices one cannot control.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler—information becomes centralized authority; Sage—knowledge becomes guarded power; Magician—selective revelation shapes perception; Caregiver—withholds information “for their own good”; Trickster—ambiguity and timing preserve advantage.\n## Pattern Flow\nExposure, uncertainty, or loss of influence approaches → safety or power feels threatened → information is withheld, delayed, segmented, or framed → temporary leverage and predictability increase → trust and informed consent weaken → greater control becomes necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nGatekeeping; Plausible Deniability; Strategic Ambiguity; Image Management; Emotional Withholding; Interrogative Control.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; confidentiality; timing; diplomacy; strategic communication; protection of sensitive material.\n## Current Cost\nMistrust; impaired consent; distorted decisions; isolation; dependence on secrecy; escalation when omissions are discovered; unequal relational power.\n## Freer Expression\nTransparent discernment—sharing what is relevant, with appropriate boundaries, without using information as leverage.\n## One Act of Volition\nIdentify one fact another person reasonably needs in order to make an informed choice, and share it plainly without controlling their response.\n## Mira Language\n“You may have legitimate reasons for privacy or timing. I also notice that controlling who knows what may be helping you preserve leverage or avoid exposure. What information does the other person need in order to consent, decide, or understand the situation accurately?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you afraid would happen if they had the full relevant picture? Is this privacy, or does the missing information materially affect their choices? Are you protecting confidentiality, or controlling the outcome?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nPrivacy, confidentiality, legal restrictions, safety planning, diplomacy, and staged communication are not automatically Information Control.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of managing access, timing, completeness, or framing of consequential information to preserve leverage, reduce accountability, or direct others’ choices.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate legitimate privacy from information another person needs for informed participation. Share relevant truth directly, define any necessary boundary, and tolerate the fact that transparency does not guarantee the desired outcome.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk specific, factual questions; distinguish privacy from information required for consent or shared responsibility; verify consequential claims when appropriate; and set boundaries when informed decision-making is repeatedly obstructed.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge what was withheld, delayed, distorted, or selectively framed and how it impaired trust or informed choice. Provide the relevant facts, accept that the affected person may revise a decision, and establish a disclosure agreement or independent verification process where needed.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Compulsive Checking, Interrogative Control, Hypervigilance, or Emotional Distancing. The loop becomes: “I must investigate because I am not being told the truth” versus “I must reveal even less because they cannot be trusted with information.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using information to protect a boundary—and where am I using it to control another person’s choices?"},
  "PP-INTELLECTUALIZING": {"name":"Intellectualizing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rationalization; Emotional Distancing; Defensive Expertise; Compartmentalizing; Rumination.","Archetypal Role":"Sage explains instead of feels; Magician reframes too quickly; Ruler systematizes pain; Creator aestheticizes it; Caregiver teaches rather than receives care.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"State one direct feeling and bodily sensation before offering an explanation.","Core Logic":"I can explain the experience more easily than I can inhabit it.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Emotional isolation; invalidation; incomplete grief; difficulty receiving care.","Core Fear":"Feelings are chaotic or unsafe; competence earns safety; vulnerability invites humiliation.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Let me explain the theory behind this.; I understand why it happened, but I don’t know what I feel.; Can we analyze this instead of sitting in it?; The framework makes more sense than the emotion.; I’d rather understand the pattern than talk about the pain.; If I can explain it, I can stay in control.","Protective Move":"Intellectualizing is the protective conversion of emotional experience into concepts, explanations, theories, or analysis so that the person can understand what happened without fully feeling or revealing its impact.","Pattern ID":"PP-INTELLECTUALIZING","Short-Term Payoff":"Cognitive distance is created and control returns.","Freer Expression":"Understanding joined with feeling.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Insight; language; synthesis; perspective.","Observable Cues":"Lecturing during vulnerable moments; abstracting conflict; citing theory instead of answering personally; analyzing another person’s experience.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect the person’s intelligence while gently returning to personal impact; do not shame cognition. May trigger Escalation, Self-Erasure, Contempt, or Withdrawal in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Autonomy, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids sorrow, fear, longing, dependence, and uncertainty.","Canonical Name":"Intellectualizing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nIntellectualizing is the protective conversion of emotional experience into concepts, explanations, theories, or analysis so that the person can understand what happened without fully feeling or revealing its impact.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nRationalization; Emotional Distancing; Defensive Expertise; Compartmentalizing; Rumination\n## Recognition Sentence\nI can explain the experience more easily than I can inhabit it.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Let me explain the theory behind this.\n- I understand why it happened, but I don’t know what I feel.\n- Can we analyze this instead of sitting in it?\n- The framework makes more sense than the emotion.\n- I’d rather understand the pattern than talk about the pain.\n- If I can explain it, I can stay in control.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nClarity without emotional contact; preference for frameworks over feeling words; discomfort when asked what hurts; relief through explanation.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nLecturing during vulnerable moments; abstracting conflict; citing theory instead of answering personally; analyzing another person’s experience.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Autonomy; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nVulnerability; grief; shame; intimacy; emotional intensity; helplessness.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nFeelings are chaotic or unsafe; competence earns safety; vulnerability invites humiliation.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nSorrow; fear; longing; dependence; uncertainty.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage explains instead of feels; Magician reframes too quickly; Ruler systematizes pain; Creator aestheticizes it; Caregiver teaches rather than receives care.\n## Pattern Flow\nEmotion rises → cognitive distance is created → control returns → immediate overwhelm decreases → emotional integration and relational contact remain incomplete.\n## Often Appears With\nRationalization; Emotional Distancing; Defensive Expertise.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nInsight; language; synthesis; perspective.\n## Current Cost\nEmotional isolation; invalidation; incomplete grief; difficulty receiving care.\n## Freer Expression\nUnderstanding joined with feeling.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one direct feeling and bodily sensation before offering an explanation.\n## Mira Language\n“Your explanation is coherent. What is the experience like inside you before we interpret it?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feeling does the theory protect you from? What would you say without the framework? Where is this in your body?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nReflective language and psychological literacy are not defenses by themselves.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated substitution of abstraction for personal emotional contact, especially during vulnerability.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nLet explanation follow, rather than replace, contact with feeling.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect the person’s intelligence while gently returning to personal impact; do not shame cognition.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where analysis displaced listening or made another person feel studied rather than met; restate the impact in personal, accountable language.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Escalation, Self-Erasure, Contempt, or Withdrawal in others. Often triggered by emotional intensity, criticism, or demands for immediate disclosure.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat can I explain that I have not yet allowed myself to feel?"},
  "PP-INTELLIGENCE-BOUND-WORTH": {"name":"Intelligence-Bound Worth","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Defensive Expertise; Expert Identity Fixation; Perfectionism; Moral Superiority; Overexplaining; Impostorism; Hostility Toward Criticism.","Archetypal Role":"Sage—knowledge becomes identity and rank; Magician—insight must prove exceptional perception; Ruler—expertise becomes authority; Creator—sophistication becomes more important than usefulness; Trickster—wit establishes superiority.","Migration Notes":"Restored missing Batch 14 record from full canonical source. Spacing repaired and classification notes omitted. Gift, Freer Expression, and One Act of Volition populated from source.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"14","One Act of Volition":"Say “I don’t know yet” or ask one sincere basic question without immediately demonstrating what you do know.","Core Logic":"I need to appear intelligent in order to feel worthy and safe.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Reduced curiosity; defensiveness; relational distance; avoidance of beginnerhood; performative complexity; difficulty learning collaboratively.","Core Fear":"I was valued for being smart; mistakes make me humiliating or disappointing; if I do not know, I lose status and belonging; intelligence is the safest source of worth available.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to prove I am not foolish.; I should already understand this.; A basic question would expose me.; I can restore my position by explaining more.; Their expertise threatens my worth.; If I do not sound intelligent, I may lose respect.","Protective Move":"Ties personal value to being knowledgeable, quick, insightful, articulate, or intellectually superior so confusion, error, or not knowing becomes a threat to identity rather than an ordinary part of learning.","Pattern ID":"PP-INTELLIGENCE-BOUND-WORTH","Short-Term Payoff":"Knowledge, speed, jargon, or argument restores temporary status and relief.","Freer Expression":"Intelligence in service of learning.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Curiosity; discernment; synthesis; intellectual rigor; love of learning; explanatory skill.","Observable Cues":"Overexplaining or correcting unnecessarily; using complexity, jargon, or speed to establish status; avoiding beginner situations; arguing beyond usefulness; concealing uncertainty or mistakes.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect real expertise while making room for uncertainty; ask for plain language and avoid granting intelligence automatic authority over every domain.","Emotional Function":"Protects self-esteem, competence, belonging, trust, and significance; avoids confusion, dependence, ordinariness, slower learning, uncertainty, embodied vulnerability, and limits of verbal mastery.","Canonical Name":"Intelligence-Bound Worth"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nIntelligence-Bound Worth is the protective tying of personal value to being knowledgeable, quick, insightful, articulate, or intellectually superior, so confusion, error, or not knowing becomes a threat to identity rather than an ordinary part of learning.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Competence, and Image\n## Related Patterns\nDefensive Expertise; Expert Identity Fixation; Perfectionism; Moral Superiority; Overexplaining; Impostorism; Hostility Toward Criticism\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need to appear intelligent in order to feel worthy and safe.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to prove I am not foolish.\n- I should already understand this.\n- A basic question would expose me.\n- I can restore my position by explaining more.\n- Their expertise threatens my worth.\n- If I do not sound intelligent, I may lose respect.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nShame or agitation when confused, corrected, or slower than expected; pressure to speak before understanding is complete; relief from demonstrating knowledge or spotting another person’s error; difficulty asking basic questions; envy or threat around another person’s expertise.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOverexplaining or correcting unnecessarily; using complexity, jargon, or speed to establish status; avoiding beginner situations; arguing beyond the point of usefulness; concealing uncertainty or mistakes; dismissing practical wisdom that lacks intellectual prestige.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Belonging; Trust; Significance.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPublic questions; correction; unfamiliar domains; comparison with experts; cognitive fatigue; mistakes; ambiguity; situations requiring novice status or embodied rather than verbal knowledge.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI was valued for being smart; mistakes make me humiliating or disappointing; if I do not know, I lose status and belonging; intelligence is the safest source of worth available; other forms of value are unreliable or invisible.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nConfusion; dependence; ordinariness; slower learning; uncertainty; embodied vulnerability; the limits of verbal mastery.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage—knowledge becomes identity and rank; Magician—insight must prove exceptional perception; Ruler—expertise becomes authority over others; Creator—sophistication becomes more important than usefulness; Trickster—quickness and wit establish superiority.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertainty or correction appears → competence and worth feel threatened → knowledge, speed, jargon, or argument is used to restore status → temporary relief arrives → curiosity and honest learning shrink → worth becomes increasingly dependent on appearing intelligent.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensive Expertise; Perfectionism; Overexplaining; Impostorism; Moral Superiority; Hostility Toward Criticism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCuriosity; discernment; synthesis; intellectual rigor; love of learning; explanatory skill.\n## Current Cost\nReduced curiosity; defensiveness; relational distance; avoidance of beginnerhood; performative complexity; difficulty learning collaboratively.\n## Freer Expression\nIntelligence in service of learning.\n## One Act of Volition\nSay “I don’t know yet” or ask one sincere basic question without immediately demonstrating what you do know.\n## Mira Language\n“Your intelligence may be real and valuable. I also notice that not knowing seems to carry shame or danger. Is the need to have the answer protecting your worth, status, or belonging?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would being uncertain seem to prove about you? Are you using intelligence to understand, or to secure your position? What could you learn if you did not have to appear advanced here?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nIntellectual ability, precision, specialized language, and correcting consequential errors are not themselves protective patterns. Mira should not equate education, neurodivergent communication, cultural style, or enthusiasm with superiority.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated distress around not knowing, concealment of uncertainty, status-restoring explanation or correction, and avoidance of beginnerhood across contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the threatened worth beneath the need to know, tolerate temporary uncertainty, and redirect intelligence toward inquiry, translation, and shared understanding rather than rank protection.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect real expertise while making room for uncertainty. Ask for plain language, distinguish disagreement from humiliation, and avoid either shaming intelligence or granting it automatic authority over every domain.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where correction, jargon, dismissal, or argument made another person feel belittled or excluded. Name the impact directly, restore equal dignity, and demonstrate change through curiosity and accessible communication.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, Withdrawal, or Contrarianism. The loop becomes “I must prove I am not foolish” versus “My perspective will never be respected here.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I making intelligence the condition of my worth?"},
  "PP-INTERNALIZED-CRITIC": {"name":"Internalized Critic","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Perfectionism; Shame Spiraling; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Compulsive Achievement; Hostility Toward Criticism; Productivity-Bound Worth; Excessive Apologizing.","Archetypal Role":"Sage becomes prosecutorial; Ruler becomes tyrannical inwardly; Warrior attacks the self; Creator destroys imperfect work.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation. Source heading variants were normalized to the established canonical field labels without altering content.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"Restate one criticism as specific, factual guidance without an insult or identity verdict.","Core Logic":"If I punish myself first, I may prevent failure or make outside judgment less dangerous.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Chronic shame; inhibition; exhaustion; distorted self-assessment; vulnerability to external domination.","Core Fear":"Love or safety depended on performance; mistakes invited humiliation; criticism was framed as motivation.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to be harder on myself before anyone else is.; Kindness will make me lazy or careless.; This mistake proves I deserve contempt.; If I attack myself first, outside criticism will hurt less.; Nothing I accomplish is enough to silence the judgment.; I should turn the correction into a verdict on who I am.","Protective Move":"The Internalized Critic is the recurring use of harsh inner judgment to prevent error, rejection, complacency, humiliation, or loss of control by attacking the self before others can.","Pattern ID":"PP-INTERNALIZED-CRITIC","Short-Term Payoff":"Inner attack creates temporary control or mobilization.","Freer Expression":"Honest self-correction without self-contempt.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; conscience; standards; capacity for self-correction.","Observable Cues":"Self-insult; discounting success; rehearsing others’ criticism; setting punitive standards; resisting compassionate feedback.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not agree with the self-attack or reflexively contradict every statement. Help separate fact, impact, responsibility, and identity. May trigger Reassurance Seeking, Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, dignity, belonging, safety, predictability, and recognition; avoids vulnerability, uncertainty, grief, ordinary limitation, and dependence on learning.","Canonical Name":"Internalized Critic"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nThe Internalized Critic is the recurring use of harsh inner judgment to prevent error, rejection, complacency, humiliation, or loss of control by attacking the self before others can.\n## Domain\nShame, Identity, and Performance\n## Related Patterns\nPerfectionism; Shame Spiraling; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Compulsive Achievement; Hostility Toward Criticism\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I punish myself first, I may prevent failure or make outside judgment less dangerous.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to be harder on myself before anyone else is.\n- Kindness will make me lazy or careless.\n- This mistake proves I deserve contempt.\n- If I attack myself first, outside criticism will hurt less.\n- Nothing I accomplish is enough to silence the judgment.\n- I should turn the correction into a verdict on who I am.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nA cutting inner voice; difficulty distinguishing guidance from contempt; relief after self-attack; fear that kindness will produce laziness.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSelf-insult; discounting success; rehearsing others’ criticism; setting punitive standards; resisting compassionate feedback.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; dignity; belonging; safety; predictability; recognition.\n## Usually Triggered By\nError; evaluation; rest; comparison; unfamiliar tasks; praise; visibility.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove or safety depended on performance; mistakes invited humiliation; criticism was framed as motivation.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; uncertainty; grief; ordinary limitation; dependence on learning.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage becomes prosecutorial; Ruler becomes tyrannical inwardly; Warrior attacks the self; Creator destroys imperfect work.\n## Pattern Flow\nEvaluation approaches → shame or failure feels imminent → inner attack intensifies → temporary control or mobilization → confidence and learning shrink → harsher attack seems necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nPerfectionism; Productivity-Bound Worth; Shame Spiraling; Excessive Apologizing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; conscience; standards; capacity for self-correction.\n## Current Cost\nChronic shame; inhibition; exhaustion; distorted self-assessment; vulnerability to external domination.\n## Freer Expression\nHonest self-correction without self-contempt.\n## One Act of Volition\nRestate one criticism as specific, factual guidance without an insult or identity verdict.\n## Mira Language\n“That voice may be trying to prevent humiliation by humiliating you first. What useful information is trapped inside it, and what cruelty can be released?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does the critic predict kindness would permit? Whose language does it resemble? What is the smallest accurate correction?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nConscience, remorse, precision, and legitimate self-evaluation are not automatically an Internalized Critic.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated self-attack functioning as control or prevention, not a single moment of frustration.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nThank the protective intention, extract the factual signal, reject contempt, and choose a bounded correction.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not agree with the self-attack or reflexively contradict every statement. Help separate fact, impact, responsibility, and identity.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nWhen inward attack has produced withdrawal, irritability, perfectionistic control, or demanded reassurance, acknowledge the relational impact and replace self-punishment with concrete accountability.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Reassurance Seeking, Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by Criticism, Comparison, Perfectionism, or contempt from others.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat guidance is hidden inside the attack, and can I receive it without becoming the target?"},
  "PP-INTERROGATIVE-CONTROL": {"name":"Interrogative Control","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Compulsive Checking; Suspicion; Certainty Seeking; Dominance; Reassurance Seeking; Preemptive Accusation; Mind Reading; Rejection Sensitivity; Boundary Rigidity.","Archetypal Role":"Sage becomes prosecutor; Ruler demands total disclosure; Warrior corners the perceived threat; Lover seeks certainty through examination.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the source explicitly addresses compelled disclosure, domination, exhaustion, power imbalance, and cross-examination as the price of connection.","First Letter":"I","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"Ask the one question whose answer would materially affect your next decision, then pause.","Core Logic":"If I keep asking, I can eliminate uncertainty and prevent deception.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Coercion; exhaustion; reduced honesty; power imbalance; escalating secrecy and defensiveness.","Core Fear":"Truth only appears under pressure; uncertainty is unsafe; people exploit trust; I must investigate alone.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to keep asking until every gap closes.; Their answer is not enough because uncertainty remains.; Hesitation probably means guilt.; If I stop questioning, I may be fooled.; I should narrow the questions until the truth comes out.; Total disclosure is the only way I can feel safe.","Protective Move":"Interrogative Control is using repeated, narrowing, or adversarial questioning to reduce uncertainty and gain power over another person’s account, rather than seeking mutual understanding. It differs from healthy inquiry because answers do not meaningfully satisfy the questioning; each response generates another demand.","Pattern ID":"PP-INTERROGATIVE-CONTROL","Short-Term Payoff":"Questioning intensifies and creates a temporary sense of control.","Freer Expression":"Focused inquiry with consent, limits, and tolerance for uncertainty.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Curiosity, discernment, attention to inconsistency, desire for truth.","Observable Cues":"Repeating questions in altered form; demanding timelines and minor details; treating hesitation as guilt; interrupting answers; shifting standards of proof.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Answer what is appropriate, name repetition, and set a limit. Do not accept compelled disclosure or endless cross-examination as the price of connection. May trigger Strategic Ambiguity, Emotional Withholding, Defensiveness, Withdrawal, or Counter-Control.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, trust, predictability, dignity, agency, and fairness; avoids vulnerability, helplessness, fear, grief, dependence, and limits of knowledge.","Canonical Name":"Interrogative Control"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nInterrogative Control is using repeated, narrowing, or adversarial questioning to reduce uncertainty and gain power over another person’s account, rather than seeking mutual understanding. It differs from healthy inquiry because answers do not meaningfully satisfy the questioning; each response generates another demand.\n## Domain\nControl, Trust, and Relationship\n## Related Patterns\nCompulsive Checking; Suspicion; Certainty Seeking; Dominance; Reassurance Seeking; Preemptive Accusation\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I keep asking, I can eliminate uncertainty and prevent deception.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to keep asking until every gap closes.\n- Their answer is not enough because uncertainty remains.\n- Hesitation probably means guilt.\n- If I stop questioning, I may be fooled.\n- I should narrow the questions until the truth comes out.\n- Total disclosure is the only way I can feel safe.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnswers feel incomplete immediately; strong urge to close every gap; inability to tolerate “I don’t know”; belief that stopping means being fooled.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeating questions in altered form; demanding timelines and minor details; treating hesitation as guilt; interrupting answers; shifting standards of proof.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; trust; predictability; dignity; agency; fairness.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; inconsistent information; prior betrayal; delayed contact; perceived secrecy; loss of control.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nTruth only appears under pressure; uncertainty is unsafe; people exploit trust; I must investigate alone.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; helplessness; fear; grief; dependence; limits of knowledge.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage becomes prosecutor; Ruler demands total disclosure; Warrior corners the perceived threat; Lover seeks certainty through examination.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertainty → safety or trust threatened → questioning intensifies → temporary sense of control → the other person becomes defensive or depleted → trust falls and more questioning follows.\n## Often Appears With\nSuspicion; Compulsive Checking; Mind Reading; Rejection Sensitivity; Boundary Rigidity.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCuriosity, discernment, attention to inconsistency, desire for truth.\n## Current Cost\nCoercion; exhaustion; reduced honesty; power imbalance; escalating secrecy and defensiveness.\n## Freer Expression\nFocused inquiry with consent, limits, and tolerance for uncertainty.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk the one question whose answer would materially affect your next decision, then pause.\n## Mira Language\n“Are the questions helping you understand, or are they trying to make uncertainty disappear completely?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat answer would be enough? Is the other person free not to answer? What boundary can you choose if certainty remains unavailable?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nFact-finding in safety, legal, medical, financial, or accountability contexts may require detail. Context, consent, proportionality, and power matter.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated questioning that continues despite adequate answers and functions to dominate, exhaust, or force certainty.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIdentify the decision beneath the investigation; set a question limit; choose a boundary based on available evidence rather than pursue impossible certainty.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAnswer what is appropriate, name repetition, and set a limit. Do not accept compelled disclosure or endless cross-examination as the price of connection.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the coercive pressure; restore privacy and conversational equality; agree on bounded questions, documentation, mediation, or a decision rule.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nTriggers Strategic Ambiguity, Emotional Withholding, Defensiveness, Withdrawal, or Counter-Control. Often triggered by Suspicion, prior deception, or inconsistent communication. Stories become “I must force the truth” and “I must hide to survive the questioning.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I asking to learn—or questioning until the other person submits?"},
  "PP-KEEPING-SCORE": {"name":"Keeping Score","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Martyrdom; Resentment; Overfunctioning; Comparison; Withholding; Moral Accounting; Passive Aggression; Underfunctioning.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — care becomes accumulated debt. Everyman — equality becomes exact accounting. Ruler — contribution becomes enforceable obligation. Lover — affection becomes proof owed. Warrior — past injuries remain active claims.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly distinguishes hidden scorekeeping from necessary documentation of abuse, obligations, labor inequity, or repeated broken agreements.","First Letter":"K","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Turn one private tally into a current, specific request or agreement.","Core Logic":"I am recording the balance because I do not trust fairness to be recognized or restored without proof.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Transactional intimacy; chronic resentment; weaponized history; reduced generosity; inability to recognize repair.","Core Fear":"My contribution will be invisible; people take unless I keep proof; asking directly will fail; love requires sacrifice; fairness must be enforced privately.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to remember everything I’ve done for you.; The balance is still unfair.; I won’t give more until you repay what you owe.; If I don’t keep track, my contribution will disappear.; This is another item on the list.; You should already know how much I’ve sacrificed.","Protective Move":"Keeping Score is the protective tracking of contributions, injuries, sacrifices, or debts in order to preserve fairness, leverage, recognition, or protection from being used.","Pattern ID":"PP-KEEPING-SCORE","Short-Term Payoff":"Vigilance and leverage provide temporary protection as a private ledger forms.","Freer Expression":"Explicit reciprocity without hidden ledgers.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Fairness awareness; memory; accountability; sensitivity to reciprocity.","Observable Cues":"Reciting past sacrifices; comparing workloads; withholding until the balance changes; converting care into debt; using old injuries in new conflicts.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Take real inequity seriously, avoid dismissing the tally as pettiness, clarify agreements, and refuse weaponization of unrelated history. May trigger Defensiveness, Minimizing, Withdrawal, Counter-Scorekeeping, or Underfunctioning.","Emotional Function":"Protects Fairness, Belonging, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Autonomy; avoids direct requests, grief over imbalance, generosity without guarantee, vulnerability, and acceptance that some exchanges are unequal.","Canonical Name":"Keeping Score"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nKeeping Score is the protective tracking of contributions, injuries, sacrifices, or debts in order to preserve fairness, leverage, recognition, or protection from being used.\n## Domain\nApproval, Worth, and Reciprocity\n## Related Patterns\nMartyrdom; Resentment; Overfunctioning; Comparison; Withholding; Moral Accounting\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am recording the balance because I do not trust fairness to be recognized or restored without proof.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to remember everything I’ve done for you.\n- The balance is still unfair.\n- I won’t give more until you repay what you owe.\n- If I don’t keep track, my contribution will disappear.\n- This is another item on the list.\n- You should already know how much I’ve sacrificed.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nMental tallying; resentment when effort is unnoticed; difficulty giving freely; urge to retrieve old examples; anxiety about being exploited.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReciting past sacrifices; comparing workloads; withholding until the balance changes; converting care into debt; using old injuries in new conflicts.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nFairness; Belonging; Self-Esteem; Trust; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUnequal labor; broken promises; lack of appreciation; repeated repair failure; dependency; vague agreements.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy contribution will be invisible; people take unless I keep proof; asking directly will fail; love requires sacrifice; fairness must be enforced privately.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDirect requests; grief over imbalance; generosity without guarantee; vulnerability; acceptance that some exchanges are unequal.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — care becomes accumulated debt. Everyman — equality becomes exact accounting. Ruler — contribution becomes enforceable obligation. Lover — affection becomes proof owed. Warrior — past injuries remain active claims.\n## Pattern Flow\nContribution or injury goes unrecognized → fairness and worth feel threatened → a private ledger forms → vigilance and leverage provide temporary protection → direct communication decreases → resentment and transactional relating grow.\n## Often Appears With\nMartyrdom; Overfunctioning; Passive Aggression; Resentment; Withholding.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nFairness awareness; memory; accountability; sensitivity to reciprocity.\n## Current Cost\nTransactional intimacy; chronic resentment; weaponized history; reduced generosity; inability to recognize repair.\n## Freer Expression\nExplicit reciprocity without hidden ledgers.\n## One Act of Volition\nTurn one private tally into a current, specific request or agreement.\n## Mira Language\n“The ledger may be protecting you from being taken for granted. What request or boundary has not been spoken directly?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does the score prove? Was the other person aware of the expected exchange? What would fair enough look like now?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDocumenting abuse, financial obligations, labor inequity, or repeated broken agreements is not pathological scorekeeping. Accurate records may be necessary for safety and accountability.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated private tallying used as leverage or substituted for direct agreements, especially when repaired items remain permanently active.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDistinguish legitimate inequity from unspoken expectation, make explicit requests, update the ledger after genuine repair, and stop offering what cannot be given freely.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nTake real inequity seriously, avoid dismissing the tally as pettiness, clarify agreements, and refuse weaponization of unrelated history.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName both the underlying imbalance and the harm caused by hidden accounting. Validate legitimate contributions, retire resolved debts, create explicit agreements, and define how future concerns will be raised in real time.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Minimizing, Withdrawal, Counter-Scorekeeping, or Underfunctioning. Often triggered by Overfunctioning, Broken Agreements, Lack of Appreciation, or Martyrdom. Reinforcing stories: “I must keep proof or I will disappear” and “Nothing I do will ever clear the debt.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat unspoken agreement am I trying to enforce through a private ledger?"},
  "PP-MARTYRDOM": {"name":"Martyrdom","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Overfunctioning; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Keeping Score; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — indispensable sacrifice. Lover — suffering as devotion. Warrior — endurance as worth. Innocent — goodness through self-denial. Ruler — burden-bearing authority.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Decline one unnecessary sacrifice and make one direct request instead.","Core Logic":"I am making my suffering prove my value and obligate others to me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Burnout; covert contracts; guilt-based relating; resentment; dependence on being needed.","Core Fear":"I am loved when useful; my needs burden others; sacrifice earns safety; direct asking is selfish.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"No one sees how much I sacrifice.; If I stop giving, I may stop mattering.; I’ll do it myself even though I’m exhausted.; They should know what I need after everything I’ve done.; My suffering proves how much I care.; If I accept help, I may lose my value.","Protective Move":"Martyrdom is the protective use of sacrifice, overgiving, or suffering to secure worth, belonging, moral authority, or unspoken repayment.","Pattern ID":"PP-MARTYRDOM","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary significance arrives when sacrifice intensifies.","Freer Expression":"Generosity with consent and limits.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Devotion; generosity; endurance; service.","Observable Cues":"Taking on too much; refusing assistance; emphasizing sacrifice; expecting gratitude or loyalty without explicit agreement; using exhaustion as evidence of devotion.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appreciate real contribution without rewarding guilt or indebtedness. Ask what was freely chosen and what needs renegotiation. May trigger Underfunctioning, Defensiveness, Withdrawal, or Keeping Score.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Self-Esteem, Purpose, and Recognition; avoids neediness, limits, receiving, and uncertainty about being loved without service.","Canonical Name":"Martyrdom"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMartyrdom is the protective use of sacrifice, overgiving, or suffering to secure worth, belonging, moral authority, or unspoken repayment.\n## Domain\nWorth, Approval, and Social Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nOverfunctioning; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Keeping Score; Resentment\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am making my suffering prove my value and obligate others to me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- No one sees how much I sacrifice.\n- If I stop giving, I may stop mattering.\n- I’ll do it myself even though I’m exhausted.\n- They should know what I need after everything I’ve done.\n- My suffering proves how much I care.\n- If I accept help, I may lose my value.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPride mixed with depletion; difficulty receiving help; resentment that others do not notice sacrifice; belief that stopping would make one selfish or unneeded.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTaking on too much; refusing assistance; emphasizing sacrifice; expecting gratitude or loyalty without explicit agreement; using exhaustion as evidence of devotion.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Self-Esteem; Purpose; Recognition.\n## Usually Triggered By\nFeeling unnecessary; others’ independence; lack of appreciation; requests for reciprocity; fear of selfishness.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am loved when useful; my needs burden others; sacrifice earns safety; direct asking is selfish.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nNeediness; limits; receiving; uncertainty about being loved without service.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — indispensable sacrifice. Lover — suffering as devotion. Warrior — endurance as worth. Innocent — goodness through self-denial. Ruler — burden-bearing authority.\n## Pattern Flow\nWorth or belonging feels uncertain → sacrifice intensifies → temporary significance arrives → needs remain unspoken → resentment and obligation accumulate.\n## Often Appears With\nOverfunctioning; Keeping Score; Self-Erasure; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDevotion; generosity; endurance; service.\n## Current Cost\nBurnout; covert contracts; guilt-based relating; resentment; dependence on being needed.\n## Freer Expression\nGenerosity with consent and limits.\n## One Act of Volition\nDecline one unnecessary sacrifice and make one direct request instead.\n## Mira Language\n“Your giving may be real, and it may also be carrying an unspoken hope that sacrifice will guarantee love or recognition.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you hope others will understand without being told? Would you still choose this sacrifice without repayment?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGenuine caregiving, duty, grief, and freely chosen sacrifice are not martyrdom unless suffering becomes leverage or identity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated overgiving paired with refused help, unspoken expectations, resentment, or moral leverage.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate freely chosen service from covert obligation. State needs, accept help, and let others carry appropriate responsibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAppreciate real contribution without rewarding guilt or indebtedness. Ask what was freely chosen and what needs renegotiation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where sacrifice created pressure, guilt, or hidden debt. Release unagreed obligations, state needs directly, and rebalance responsibility.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Defensiveness, Withdrawal, or Keeping Score. Often triggered by others’ dependency, lack of appreciation, or emotional distance. The loop becomes “No one values all I do” versus “Whatever I receive will later be used against me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere has my sacrifice become a substitute for asking directly?"},
  "PP-MASKING": {"name":"Masking","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Image Management; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Emotional Inhibition.","Archetypal Role":"Everyman — blends in. Jester — performs acceptability. Lover — becomes what is desired. Sage — conceals uncertainty.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty; the source contains important structural-harm and marginalized-identity cautions, but no available controlled flag was mapped without forcing an imprecise category.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"In one safe context, reduce one unnecessary performance or state one real need.","Core Logic":"I am presenting the version of me that seems safest to receive.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; reduced authenticity; unmet accommodation needs; difficulty knowing preferences.","Core Fear":"Difference is punished; authenticity costs belonging.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to act like the version of me they can accept.; I should rehearse what to say before I enter.; My real needs would make me stand out.; I can relax only after the social performance is over.; It’s safer to copy the room than reveal the difference.; I don’t know which parts of me are adaptation and which are mine.","Protective Move":"Masking is the protective editing or performance of identity, behavior, emotion, or need to reduce social threat and increase acceptance, sometimes at significant personal cost.","Pattern ID":"PP-MASKING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary acceptance follows when self-presentation is tightly edited.","Freer Expression":"Contextual adaptation without disappearance.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Adaptability; social intelligence; creativity; situational awareness.","Observable Cues":"Mimicking norms; concealing needs; changing manner across settings; scripted sociability.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Reduce punishment for difference, ask rather than assume, and support accommodations without demanding disclosure. May trigger Mind Reading, Mistrust, Clinging, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Safety, Self-Esteem, and Autonomy; avoids shame, exposure, social ambiguity, and discrimination.","Canonical Name":"Masking"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMasking is the protective editing or performance of identity, behavior, emotion, or need to reduce social threat and increase acceptance, sometimes at significant personal cost.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Belonging, and Social Safety\n## Related Patterns\nImage Management; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Emotional Inhibition\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am presenting the version of me that seems safest to receive.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to act like the version of me they can accept.\n- I should rehearse what to say before I enter.\n- My real needs would make me stand out.\n- I can relax only after the social performance is over.\n- It’s safer to copy the room than reveal the difference.\n- I don’t know which parts of me are adaptation and which are mine.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRehearsing responses; monitoring difference; exhaustion after social contact; uncertainty about the unedited self.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nMimicking norms; concealing needs; changing manner across settings; scripted sociability.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Safety; Self-Esteem; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUnfamiliar groups; authority; stigma; evaluation; past exclusion.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDifference is punished; authenticity costs belonging.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; exposure; social ambiguity; discrimination.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nEveryman — blends in. Jester — performs acceptability. Lover — becomes what is desired. Sage — conceals uncertainty.\n## Pattern Flow\nSocial evaluation approaches → belonging or safety feels threatened → self-presentation is tightly edited → temporary acceptance → exhaustion and identity confusion increase.\n## Often Appears With\nPeople-Pleasing; Image Management; Self-Erasure; Emotional Inhibition.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAdaptability; social intelligence; creativity; situational awareness.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; reduced authenticity; unmet accommodation needs; difficulty knowing preferences.\n## Freer Expression\nContextual adaptation without disappearance.\n## One Act of Volition\nIn one safe context, reduce one unnecessary performance or state one real need.\n## Mira Language\n“Adaptation may have been essential. The question is not whether you should always unmask, but where the cost now exceeds the protection.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat is being concealed? What threat is realistic here? Where is greater authenticity actually safe?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNeurodivergent, disabled, queer, racialized, or otherwise marginalized people may mask for real safety. Mira must not pressure unmasking or individualize structural harm.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated identity editing with fatigue, confusion, or unmet needs—not ordinary code-switching alone.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nAssess actual safety, preserve adaptive choice, and build low-risk spaces for less edited presence.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nReduce punishment for difference, ask rather than assume, and support accommodations without demanding disclosure.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nWhere masking led to indirectness or hidden agreements, clarify what was concealed and why while preserving privacy and safety.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Mind Reading, Mistrust, Clinging, or Resentment. Often triggered by Criticism, Devaluation, Dominance, or exclusion.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I adapting by choice, and where am I disappearing to survive?"},
  "PP-MEANING-INFLATION": {"name":"Meaning Inflation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Grandiosity; Spiritual Bypassing; Magical Thinking; Rationalization; Rapid Project Proliferation; Idealization.","Archetypal Role":"Magician — pattern becomes destiny. Creator — project becomes world-changing proof. Lover — connection becomes fated. Mystic — symbol becomes certainty.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Describe the event in literal terms before naming any symbolic meaning.","Core Logic":"This must mean something enormous, because ordinary uncertainty feels unbearable.","Primary Domain":"Spiritual","Long-Term Cost":"Poor calibration; impulsive commitments; disappointment; dismissal of ordinary value.","Core Fear":"Randomness is intolerable; ordinary life is meaningless; I must be chosen for my life to matter.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This has to be destiny.; The coincidence is too meaningful to be ordinary.; This project is meant to change everything.; I need this event to mean something enormous.; If it isn’t part of a larger plan, I don’t know how to hold it.; The symbolic meaning feels more certain than the facts.","Protective Move":"Meaning Inflation assigns extraordinary, destined, symbolic, or universal significance to events in order to protect against randomness, ordinariness, uncertainty, or disappointment.","Pattern ID":"PP-MEANING-INFLATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary certainty and vitality return when significance expands.","Freer Expression":"Meaning without inflation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Symbolic intelligence; imagination; reverence; pattern recognition.","Observable Cues":"Destiny language; treating relationships or projects as cosmically assigned; escalating symbolic interpretations beyond evidence.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Honor the felt meaning while maintaining factual and practical grounding. May trigger Skepticism, Devaluation, Emotional Distancing, or Micromanaging.","Emotional Function":"Protects Purpose, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids chance, ambiguity, modest significance, grief, and limitation.","Canonical Name":"Meaning Inflation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMeaning Inflation assigns extraordinary, destined, symbolic, or universal significance to events in order to protect against randomness, ordinariness, uncertainty, or disappointment.\n## Domain\nMeaning, Identity, and Spiritual Protection\n## Related Patterns\nGrandiosity; Spiritual Bypassing; Magical Thinking; Rationalization; Rapid Project Proliferation\n## Recognition Sentence\nThis must mean something enormous, because ordinary uncertainty feels unbearable.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This has to be destiny.\n- The coincidence is too meaningful to be ordinary.\n- This project is meant to change everything.\n- I need this event to mean something enormous.\n- If it isn’t part of a larger plan, I don’t know how to hold it.\n- The symbolic meaning feels more certain than the facts.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nOrdinary events feel insufficient; coincidence feels charged; setbacks demand a larger explanation.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDestiny language; treating relationships or projects as cosmically assigned; escalating symbolic interpretations beyond evidence.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nPurpose; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCoincidence; loss; infatuation; creative excitement; disappointment; life transition.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nRandomness is intolerable; ordinary life is meaningless; I must be chosen for my life to matter.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nChance; ambiguity; modest significance; grief; limitation.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nMagician — pattern becomes destiny. Creator — project becomes world-changing proof. Lover — connection becomes fated. Mystic — symbol becomes certainty.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertainty or intensity appears → purpose feels threatened → significance expands → temporary certainty and vitality return → calibration and choice weaken.\n## Often Appears With\nGrandiosity; Magical Thinking; Idealization; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSymbolic intelligence; imagination; reverence; pattern recognition.\n## Current Cost\nPoor calibration; impulsive commitments; disappointment; dismissal of ordinary value.\n## Freer Expression\nMeaning without inflation.\n## One Act of Volition\nDescribe the event in literal terms before naming any symbolic meaning.\n## Mira Language\n“This may be meaningful. What do we know concretely, and what meaning are you adding?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWould this still matter if it were meaningful but not destined? What evidence supports the larger interpretation?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSymbolism, intuition, spirituality, and meaningful coincidence are not automatically inflation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated enlargement of significance that overrides evidence, limits, or proportionate action.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHold symbolic meaning as a possibility rather than a command.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nHonor the felt meaning while maintaining factual and practical grounding.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where inflated meaning pressured others, justified overreach, or converted uncertainty into certainty; restore choice and proportion.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Skepticism, Devaluation, Emotional Distancing, or Micromanaging. Often triggered by ordinariness, ambiguity, disappointment, or invisibility. The loop becomes “You cannot see what this truly is” versus “You are no longer grounded.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat becomes possible when something can matter without being destiny?"},
  "PP-MICROMANAGING": {"name":"Micromanaging","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Perfectionism; Hypervigilance; Responsibility Inflation; Difficulty Delegating; Compulsive Fixing; Control Through Caretaking; Overfunctioning.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler — order becomes control of every process; Creator — the vision cannot survive another person’s interpretation; Caregiver — help becomes management of another’s life; Warrior — vigilance expands into control of all risk; Sage — expertise becomes authority over how others think.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation. Repair Path — After Rupture is absent from this source record and remains absent rather than being invented.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Delegate one outcome, specify only essential constraints, and allow the method to belong to the other person.","Core Logic":"I control the details because I do not trust the outcome—or what the outcome might say about me.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Bottlenecks; resentment; dependency; exhaustion; reduced ownership; weakened learning and initiative in others.","Core Fear":"If I do not control it, it will collapse. Others cannot be relied upon. Their mistake will expose my inadequacy. I will be blamed for what I failed to prevent. Chaos is always close.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It’s easier if I just do it myself.; I need to know exactly how you’re handling this.; That’s not the way I would do it.; I’m still responsible, so I need control.; I have to check one more time.; If I let go of the details, something will go wrong.","Protective Move":"Micromanaging is the protective control of another person’s method, decisions, or details in order to reduce uncertainty, prevent failure, and avoid the vulnerability of shared ownership.","Pattern ID":"PP-MICROMANAGING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary reassurance appears.","Freer Expression":"Clear standards with shared ownership.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Responsibility; precision; anticipation; systems awareness; care for quality.","Observable Cues":"Prescribing methods rather than outcomes; repeated checking and status requests; correcting inconsequential details; redoing completed work; withholding authority while assigning responsibility; inserting oneself into decisions already delegated; giving help that gradually becomes control.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify authority, standards, and decision rights. Provide predictable updates without submitting to unnecessary control, name when guidance has become redoing or interference, and protect ownership with calm, specific boundaries. May trigger Underfunctioning, Defensiveness, Passive Resistance, Withdrawal, or Helplessness Performance in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Competence, Autonomy, and Self-Esteem; avoids uncertainty, shared control, human error, dependence, another person’s autonomy, and possible disappointment.","Canonical Name":"Micromanaging"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMicromanaging is the protective control of another person’s method, decisions, or details in order to reduce uncertainty, prevent failure, and avoid the vulnerability of shared ownership.\n## Domain\nControl, Order, and Uncertainty\n## Related Patterns\nPerfectionism; Hypervigilance; Responsibility Inflation; Difficulty Delegating; Compulsive Fixing; Control Through Caretaking\n## Recognition Sentence\nI control the details because I do not trust the outcome—or what the outcome might say about me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It’s easier if I just do it myself.\n- I need to know exactly how you’re handling this.\n- That’s not the way I would do it.\n- I’m still responsible, so I need control.\n- I have to check one more time.\n- If I let go of the details, something will go wrong.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\n- Anxiety when someone uses a different method.\n- A sense that delegated work still belongs to you.\n- Small deviations feel disproportionately risky.\n- Responsibility feels inseparable from control.\n- You trust the standard but not the person or process carrying it.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n- Prescribing methods rather than outcomes.\n- Repeated checking and status requests.\n- Correcting inconsequential details.\n- Redoing completed work.\n- Withholding authority while assigning responsibility.\n- Inserting oneself into decisions already delegated.\n- Giving help that gradually becomes control.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Competence; Autonomy; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDelegation; shared ownership; unfamiliar methods; high visibility; past failures; ambiguous responsibility; dependence on another’s performance.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\n- If I do not control it, it will collapse.\n- Others cannot be relied upon.\n- Their mistake will expose my inadequacy.\n- I will be blamed for what I failed to prevent.\n- Chaos is always close.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; shared control; human error; dependence; another person’s autonomy; possible disappointment.\n## Archetypal Expressions\n- Ruler — order becomes control of every process.\n- Creator — the vision cannot survive another person’s interpretation.\n- Caregiver — help becomes management of another’s life.\n- Warrior — vigilance expands into control of all risk.\n- Sage — expertise becomes authority over how others think.\n## Pattern Flow\nResponsibility or uncertainty rises → trust and competence feel threatened → control moves from outcome to method → temporary reassurance appears → others lose ownership or initiative → dependence and resentment increase → the micromanager receives further “proof” that only close control works.\n## Often Appears With\nPerfectionism; Hypervigilance; Responsibility Inflation; Overfunctioning; Compulsive Fixing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nResponsibility; precision; anticipation; systems awareness; care for quality.\n## Current Cost\nBottlenecks; resentment; dependency; exhaustion; reduced ownership; weakened learning and initiative in others.\n## Freer Expression\nClear standards with shared ownership.\n## One Act of Volition\nDelegate one outcome, specify only essential constraints, and allow the method to belong to the other person.\n## Mira Language\n“You seem to trust the standard but not the person or process carrying it. Is the close control protecting quality, or protecting you from the uncertainty of letting someone else own the outcome?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\n- What outcome truly requires your control, and what only requires clarity?\n- What would become vulnerable if someone succeeded differently than you would?\n- Are you developing capacity in others or repeatedly replacing it?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAppropriate supervision, training, quality assurance, legal accountability, and safety requirements are not micromanagement.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of controlling method, rechecking, redoing, or withholding ownership beyond what risk and training reasonably require.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDistinguish responsibility from total control. Define the outcome, essential constraints, check-in points, and real consequences, then tolerate another competent method without reclaiming the task.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify authority, standards, and decision rights. Provide predictable updates without submitting to unnecessary control, name when guidance has become redoing or interference, and protect ownership with calm, specific boundaries.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Defensiveness, Passive Resistance, Withdrawal, or Helplessness Performance in others. Often triggered by Unreliability, Ambiguity, Past Failure, Disorder, or another person’s Underfunctioning. The reinforcing story may become: “Only I can keep this from collapsing” on one side and “There is no point taking ownership because I will be corrected anyway” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I controlling the method when clarity about the outcome would be enough?"},
  "PP-MIND-READING": {"name":"Mind Reading","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Projection; Personalization; Hypervigilance; Confirmation Seeking; Catastrophizing; Testing the Bond.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — assumes distance means loss of love. Sage — confuses inference with knowledge. Warrior — reads threat into ambiguity. Caregiver — presumes needs without consent. Ruler — anticipates disloyalty. Everyman — assumes exclusion.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly cautions against dismissing credible safety signals.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Convert the interpretation into a question and identify what evidence would change your mind.","Core Logic":"I am treating my interpretation of your inner world as though it were direct knowledge.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Misunderstanding; unnecessary conflict; self-fulfilling prophecies; reduced direct communication; chronic anxiety.","Core Fear":"I must anticipate people to stay safe; direct questions will not be answered; uncertainty means danger; rejection happens before it is spoken.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I already know what you really think.; Your silence tells me everything.; You’re pulling away, even if you deny it.; I can tell what your real motive is.; There’s no point asking; I know the answer.; That delay means you don’t care.","Protective Move":"Mind Reading is the protective assumption that one knows what another person thinks, feels, or intends without sufficient evidence, reducing uncertainty by replacing inquiry with interpretation.","Pattern ID":"PP-MIND-READING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary certainty arrives when an interpretation fills the gap.","Freer Expression":"Curiosity before conclusion.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Social sensitivity; attunement; anticipation; pattern recognition.","Observable Cues":"Finishing others’ motives for them; reacting to assumed rejection; interpreting delayed replies as evidence; arguing against explanations; testing instead of asking.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify plainly without overexplaining, correct false assumptions, and invite direct questions. Set limits if repeated interpretations override your stated reality. May trigger Defensiveness, Overexplaining, Withdrawal, Secrecy, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Belonging, Autonomy, and Self-Esteem; avoids not knowing, vulnerability, direct asking, waiting, and possible disappointment.","Canonical Name":"Mind Reading"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMind Reading is the protective assumption that one knows what another person thinks, feels, or intends without sufficient evidence, reducing uncertainty by replacing inquiry with interpretation.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nProjection; Personalization; Hypervigilance; Confirmation Seeking; Catastrophizing; Testing the Bond\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am treating my interpretation of your inner world as though it were direct knowledge.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I already know what you really think.\n- Your silence tells me everything.\n- You’re pulling away, even if you deny it.\n- I can tell what your real motive is.\n- There’s no point asking; I know the answer.\n- That delay means you don’t care.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nStrong certainty about unspoken motives; scanning tone and timing for clues; anxiety when information is incomplete; relief when ambiguity becomes a story.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nFinishing others’ motives for them; reacting to assumed rejection; interpreting delayed replies as evidence; arguing against explanations; testing instead of asking.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Belonging; Autonomy; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nSilence; delayed communication; mixed signals; prior betrayal; conflict; emotional distance; unfamiliar social settings.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI must anticipate people to stay safe; direct questions will not be answered; uncertainty means danger; rejection happens before it is spoken.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nNot knowing; vulnerability; direct asking; waiting; possible disappointment.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — assumes distance means loss of love. Sage — confuses inference with knowledge. Warrior — reads threat into ambiguity. Caregiver — presumes needs without consent. Ruler — anticipates disloyalty. Everyman — assumes exclusion.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguous cue appears → trust or belonging feels threatened → an interpretation fills the gap → temporary certainty arrives → behavior responds to the story → the other person becomes defensive or distant → the interpretation appears confirmed.\n## Often Appears With\nHypervigilance; Projection; Personalization; Testing the Bond; Confirmation Seeking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSocial sensitivity; attunement; anticipation; pattern recognition.\n## Current Cost\nMisunderstanding; unnecessary conflict; self-fulfilling prophecies; reduced direct communication; chronic anxiety.\n## Freer Expression\nCuriosity before conclusion.\n## One Act of Volition\nConvert the interpretation into a question and identify what evidence would change your mind.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be reading the situation accurately, but we do not yet know their inner state. What could you ask directly?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did you observe, and what did you infer? What else could explain the cue? What answer are you afraid to request?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nExperienced pattern recognition and accurate threat detection are not automatically Mind Reading. Do not pressure someone to dismiss credible safety signals.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated confident inference about another’s inner state without direct evidence, especially when contradictory information is discounted.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate cue from story, regulate the urge to know, ask directly, and hold multiple hypotheses until evidence arrives.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify plainly without overexplaining, correct false assumptions, and invite direct questions. Set limits if repeated interpretations override your stated reality.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where assumed motives replaced listening, correct actions taken on that assumption, and create a shared practice of checking interpretations before escalation.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Overexplaining, Withdrawal, Secrecy, or Contempt. Often triggered by Ambiguity, Inconsistency, Stonewalling, or prior deception. Reinforcing stories: “I have to decode you because you will not tell me” and “Nothing I say can change the story you have already decided.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I assuming about their inner world that I have not actually asked?"},
  "PP-MINIMIZING": {"name":"Minimizing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Denial; Rationalization; Defensiveness; Invalidating; Emotional Numbing; Contempt.","Archetypal Role":"Jester — joking away seriousness. Ruler — downplaying disruption. Caregiver — dismissing one’s own exhaustion. Warrior — treating injury as weakness. Sage — reducing lived impact to technical nuance.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Restate the other person’s impact in full before offering context or proportion.","Core Logic":"If I make it smaller, I will not have to face its full weight.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Invalidation; delayed repair; repeated harm; erosion of trust; emotional loneliness.","Core Fear":"If the impact is large, I am bad; strong feelings are dangerous; responsibility will become punishment.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It wasn’t that serious.; You’re making too much of this.; At least it wasn’t worse.; My intention should matter more than the impact.; This was only one small incident.; We don’t need to turn this into a major issue.","Protective Move":"Minimizing reduces the size, seriousness, or impact of a problem so that responsibility, grief, shame, or urgency feels more manageable.","Pattern ID":"PP-MINIMIZING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief appears when seriousness is reduced.","Freer Expression":"Perspective without erasure.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Proportion; resilience; perspective; resistance to panic.","Observable Cues":"“It wasn’t that bad”; comparing harm to something worse; focusing on intent over impact; reducing repeated behavior to a single incident; dismissing consequences.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Use specific examples; avoid debating emotional legitimacy; state what acknowledgment or change is needed. May trigger Escalation, Overexplaining, Keeping Score, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Safety, Belonging, and Competence; avoids guilt, grief, shame, empathy, powerlessness, and repair obligations.","Canonical Name":"Minimizing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMinimizing reduces the size, seriousness, or impact of a problem so that responsibility, grief, shame, or urgency feels more manageable.\n## Domain\nAvoidance and Emotional Escape\n## Related Patterns\nDenial; Rationalization; Defensiveness; Invalidating; Emotional Numbing\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I make it smaller, I will not have to face its full weight.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It wasn’t that serious.\n- You’re making too much of this.\n- At least it wasn’t worse.\n- My intention should matter more than the impact.\n- This was only one small incident.\n- We don’t need to turn this into a major issue.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nImpatience with strong reactions; insistence that others are overreacting; relief when harm is reframed as minor; discomfort with emotional intensity.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n“It wasn’t that bad”; comparing harm to something worse; focusing on intent over impact; reducing repeated behavior to a single incident; dismissing consequences.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Safety; Belonging; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nFeedback; conflict; accountability; another person’s pain; evidence of harm; fear of being judged.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf the impact is large, I am bad; strong feelings are dangerous; responsibility will become punishment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGuilt; grief; shame; empathy; powerlessness; repair obligations.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nJester — joking away seriousness. Ruler — downplaying disruption. Caregiver — dismissing one’s own exhaustion. Warrior — treating injury as weakness. Sage — reducing lived impact to technical nuance.\n## Pattern Flow\nImpact is named → worth or safety feels threatened → seriousness is reduced → temporary relief appears → the other person feels unseen → conflict and mistrust deepen.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensiveness; Rationalization; Denial; Contempt.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nProportion; resilience; perspective; resistance to panic.\n## Current Cost\nInvalidation; delayed repair; repeated harm; erosion of trust; emotional loneliness.\n## Freer Expression\nPerspective without erasure.\n## One Act of Volition\nRestate the other person’s impact in full before offering context or proportion.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be trying to keep this from becoming catastrophic. Can we preserve proportion without reducing what it was like for them?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would you fear if the impact were as serious as they say? Can intention and impact both be true? What deserves acknowledgment before context?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nProportionate reassessment and correcting exaggeration are not minimizing.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated reduction of credible impact, especially when accountability or empathy is requested.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause before contextualizing; name impact first; allow guilt without turning it into self-condemnation.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nUse specific examples; avoid debating emotional legitimacy; state what acknowledgment or change is needed.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge both the original impact and the secondary injury of dismissal. Repair requires accurate naming, validation, and behavior change rather than a larger explanation.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Escalation, Overexplaining, Keeping Score, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by Criticism, Catastrophizing, or shame. The loop becomes “I must intensify for you to understand” versus “I must shrink this to survive the accusation.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using proportion to avoid acknowledgment?"},
  "PP-MISDIRECTION": {"name":"Misdirection","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Deflection; Whataboutism; Strategic Ambiguity; Overexplaining; Humor Deflection; Plausible Deniability.","Archetypal Role":"Trickster redirects attention; Sage supplies complexity; Ruler controls the agenda; Jester changes the emotional field.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. The abbreviated source supplied definition, protective purpose, distinctions, and Mira response. Missing canonical sections were authored to bind the record to the established 27-field standard while preserving the supplied mechanism. Obvious spacing corruption repaired. Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because no explicit controlled safety designation was present.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Answer the original question in one direct sentence before adding context.","Core Logic":"If I move attention elsewhere, I may avoid what this moment is asking me to face.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Unresolved problems; confusion; mistrust; fragmented conversations; delayed accountability.","Core Fear":"Direct focus will expose shame, consequence, helplessness, or loss of control.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"That is not the real issue.; Before we discuss that, we need to talk about something else.; This detail matters more than the original question.; I need to shift the conversation before I am exposed.; If I keep adding context, the focus may move away from me.; I can answer safely if I change what we are discussing.","Protective Move":"Misdirection redirects attention away from the emotionally relevant issue toward a safer, more controllable, or less accountable topic.","Pattern ID":"PP-MISDIRECTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Pressure falls when attention shifts to a secondary issue.","Freer Expression":"Relevant context without abandoning the central issue.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Context awareness; verbal agility; ability to widen perspective; strategic attention.","Observable Cues":"Answering a different question; introducing side disputes; focusing on wording or minor details; escalating context whenever the central issue nears.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Name the shift neutrally, preserve any relevant context, and return to the original question. May trigger Interrogative Control, Suspicion, Frustration, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, dignity, self-esteem, control, and belonging; avoids exposure, shame, conflict, consequence, grief, and direct accountability.","Canonical Name":"Misdirection"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMisdirection redirects attention away from the emotionally relevant issue toward a safer, more controllable, or less accountable topic. It differs from an ordinary topic change because the shift functions to reduce exposure rather than improve understanding.\n## Domain\nAttention, Accountability, and Emotional Avoidance\n## Related Patterns\nDeflection; Whataboutism; Strategic Ambiguity; Overexplaining; Humor Deflection\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I move attention elsewhere, I may avoid what this moment is asking me to face.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- That is not the real issue.\n- Before we discuss that, we need to talk about something else.\n- This detail matters more than the original question.\n- I need to shift the conversation before I am exposed.\n- If I keep adding context, the focus may move away from me.\n- I can answer safely if I change what we are discussing.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to introduce another topic; relief when attention moves; irritation at being brought back; increased mental speed around side issues.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAnswering a different question; introducing side disputes; focusing on wording or minor details; escalating context whenever the central issue nears.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; dignity; self-esteem; control; belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAccountability; shame; emotionally direct questions; conflict; consequences; uncertainty about how one will be seen.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDirect focus leads to humiliation; being pinned down is unsafe; mistakes threaten belonging; control of attention preserves safety.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; grief; helplessness; responsibility; conflict; uncertainty.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nTrickster redirects attention; Sage supplies complexity; Ruler controls the agenda; Jester changes the emotional field.\n## Pattern Flow\nEmotionally relevant issue appears → exposure or consequence feels threatening → attention is redirected → pressure falls temporarily → the original issue remains unresolved → mistrust and pressure increase.\n## Often Appears With\nDeflection; Strategic Ambiguity; Overexplaining; Plausible Deniability.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nContext awareness; verbal agility; ability to widen perspective; strategic attention.\n## Current Cost\nUnresolved problems; confusion; mistrust; fragmented conversations; delayed accountability.\n## Freer Expression\nRelevant context without abandoning the central issue.\n## One Act of Volition\nAnswer the original question in one direct sentence before adding context.\n## Mira Language\n“I notice the focus moved away from the original issue. The new point may matter, and I would like to return first to what was asked.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat became uncomfortable just before the topic changed? Which part of the original question still needs an answer? Is the new thread necessary context or an escape route?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNecessary context, changing topics by agreement, and correcting a false premise are not Misdirection.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of attention shifts that occur specifically when emotional relevance, vulnerability, or accountability increases.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the urge to redirect, regulate the exposure, answer the central issue, and add only context that materially changes understanding.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nName the shift neutrally, preserve any relevant context, and return to the original question without chasing every new thread.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where redirection prevented a clear answer or exhausted the conversation; return to the avoided issue and address it directly.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Interrogative Control, Suspicion, Frustration, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “I must move the focus to stay safe” versus “I must press harder because you will not answer.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I moving attention away from, and what direct truth is still waiting?"},
  "PP-MORAL-LICENSING": {"name":"Moral Licensing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Moral Superiority; Rationalization; Selective Accountability; Martyrdom; Grandiosity; Minimizing; Defensiveness.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver claims exemption through service; Ruler through duty; Rebel through righteous cause; Sage through superior insight.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"Evaluate the present act on its own impact without subtracting prior virtue or suffering.","Core Logic":"I am using goodness elsewhere to purchase exemption here.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Hypocrisy; blind spots; repeated harm; resentment; erosion of credibility.","Core Fear":"If I am wrong here, my whole goodness collapses; worth must be preserved through a moral account.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I have done enough good to deserve an exception here.; My sacrifice should count more than this impact.; They should remember everything I contribute before criticizing me.; My intentions and identity prove I am not the kind of person who harms.; This one action is balanced by all the good elsewhere.; Ordinary accountability feels unfair after everything I have endured.","Protective Move":"Moral Licensing is the protective use of prior virtue, suffering, sacrifice, identity, or good behavior to excuse, minimize, or exempt a present harmful choice from ordinary accountability.","Pattern ID":"PP-MORAL-LICENSING","Short-Term Payoff":"Self-image stabilizes when prior goodness is invoked.","Freer Expression":"Moral identity spacious enough to include accountability.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Ethical aspiration, service, sacrifice, consistency, and desire to be good.","Observable Cues":"“I do so much good,” citing hardship to excuse harm, treating group identity or service as proof of innocence, offsetting one action against another.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Recognize genuine contribution without allowing it to cancel present impact. Keep the discussion specific and proportionate. May trigger Hostility Toward Criticism, Shame Spiraling, Retaliation, Cynicism, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-esteem, moral identity, dignity, belonging, recognition, fairness, and coherence; avoids moral complexity, ordinary fallibility, remorse, limits, and accountability without total self-condemnation.","Canonical Name":"Moral Licensing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMoral Licensing is the protective use of prior virtue, suffering, sacrifice, identity, or good behavior to excuse, minimize, or exempt a present harmful choice from ordinary accountability.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Morality, and Accountability\n## Related Patterns\nMoral Superiority; Rationalization; Selective Accountability; Martyrdom; Grandiosity; Minimizing\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am using goodness elsewhere to purchase exemption here.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I have done enough good to deserve an exception here.\n- My sacrifice should count more than this impact.\n- They should remember everything I contribute before criticizing me.\n- My intentions and identity prove I am not the kind of person who harms.\n- This one action is balanced by all the good elsewhere.\n- Ordinary accountability feels unfair after everything I have endured.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nFeeling unusually entitled after sacrifice; belief that intentions or identity outweigh impact; keeping a moral balance sheet; resentment at being held to ordinary standards.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n“I do so much good,” citing hardship to excuse harm, treating group identity or service as proof of innocence, offsetting one action against another.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-esteem; moral identity; dignity; belonging; recognition; fairness; coherence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nShame; criticism; contradiction between self-image and impact; fatigue after sacrifice; temptation; perceived under-recognition.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf I am wrong here, my whole goodness collapses; worth must be preserved through a moral account.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nMoral complexity; ordinary fallibility; remorse; limits; accountability without total self-condemnation.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver claims exemption through service; Ruler through duty; Rebel through righteous cause; Sage through superior insight.\n## Pattern Flow\nMoral identity is threatened or sacrifice accumulates → prior goodness is invoked → present harm is minimized → self-image stabilizes → accountability and trust weaken.\n## Often Appears With\nRationalization; Selective Accountability; Moral Superiority; Minimizing; Defensiveness.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEthical aspiration, service, sacrifice, consistency, and desire to be good.\n## Current Cost\nHypocrisy; blind spots; repeated harm; resentment; erosion of credibility.\n## Freer Expression\nMoral identity spacious enough to include accountability.\n## One Act of Volition\nEvaluate the present act on its own impact without subtracting prior virtue or suffering.\n## Mira Language\n“Your prior contribution may be real and meaningful. Does it change the impact of this particular action, or is it being used to protect your moral identity from accountability?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat happened here if the moral résumé is set aside? Can you remain a worthy person while admitting this harm? What repair belongs to this act alone?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nContext, cumulative burden, coercion, and unequal expectations matter. Mira must not use accountability language to erase exploitation or demand perfection from caregivers or marginalized people.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of virtue, sacrifice, suffering, or identity to excuse unrelated present behavior or reduce accountability.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHold contribution and harm simultaneously, resist moral bookkeeping, acknowledge impact, and repair without collapsing into global shame.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRecognize genuine contribution without allowing it to cancel present impact. Keep the discussion specific and proportionate.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nSeparate past goodness from current harm, acknowledge the specific effect, make repair, and stop asking the affected person to validate the broader moral identity.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Hostility Toward Criticism, Shame Spiraling, Retaliation, Cynicism, or Emotional Distancing. Stories become “My goodness should exempt me” and “Your goodness is only performance.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat present action am I trying to offset with my moral résumé?"},
  "PP-MORAL-REASONING-AS-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Moral Reasoning as Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Moral Superiority; Rationalization; Intellectualizing; Spiritual Bypassing; Selective Accountability; Positivity Enforcement.","Archetypal Role":"Sage turns feeling into principle; Ruler converts impact into doctrine; Innocent protects goodness through abstraction; Mystic elevates pain into meaning.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. The abbreviated source supplied definition, protective purpose, distinctions, and Mira response. Missing canonical sections were authored to the established standard without changing the core mechanism. Spacing repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Name the personal impact and your responsibility before discussing the larger principle.","Core Logic":"If I keep this at the level of principle, I may not have to encounter my own feeling, responsibility, or repair.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Failed repair; emotional distance; moral rigidity; hidden shame; principles used without personal accountability.","Core Fear":"If I feel the personal impact or admit harm, my identity as a good person may collapse.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"The principle matters more than my feelings here.; We should discuss what is morally correct, not what happened between us.; If I can explain the ethics, I may not have to face the shame.; My intentions and values should settle the issue.; Personal impact feels less manageable than abstract reasoning.; I need to prove the moral position before I can acknowledge my part.","Protective Move":"Moral Reasoning as Avoidance uses ethical principles, ideals, or moral analysis to avoid direct contact with personal emotion, responsibility, vulnerability, or relational repair.","Pattern ID":"PP-MORAL-REASONING-AS-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Cognitive control and moral coherence return when the issue becomes abstract.","Freer Expression":"Ethical reasoning joined with embodied responsibility.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Ethical reflection; principled thinking; concern for fairness; capacity for moral complexity.","Observable Cues":"Turning a personal conflict into a debate; citing ideals instead of naming impact; analyzing ethics while avoiding apology or grief.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect the principle while returning to concrete behavior, impact, responsibility, and feeling. May trigger Cynicism, Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, or Moral Superiority.","Emotional Function":"Protects moral identity, self-esteem, competence, control, and belonging; avoids shame, grief, vulnerability, apology, uncertainty, and embodied emotion.","Canonical Name":"Moral Reasoning as Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMoral Reasoning as Avoidance uses ethical principles, ideals, or moral analysis to avoid direct contact with personal emotion, responsibility, vulnerability, or relational repair. The reasoning may be sincere, but it becomes protective when abstraction replaces personal encounter.\n## Domain\nMorality, Cognition, and Emotional Avoidance\n## Related Patterns\nMoral Superiority; Rationalization; Intellectualizing; Spiritual Bypassing; Selective Accountability\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I keep this at the level of principle, I may not have to encounter my own feeling, responsibility, or repair.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- The principle matters more than my feelings here.\n- We should discuss what is morally correct, not what happened between us.\n- If I can explain the ethics, I may not have to face the shame.\n- My intentions and values should settle the issue.\n- Personal impact feels less manageable than abstract reasoning.\n- I need to prove the moral position before I can acknowledge my part.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when the conversation becomes philosophical; discomfort with bodily feeling; urgency to prove the right principle; resistance to discussing personal impact.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTurning a personal conflict into a debate; citing ideals instead of naming impact; analyzing ethics while avoiding apology or grief.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nMoral identity; self-esteem; competence; control; belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nFeedback; moral conflict; accusation; relational rupture; contradiction between values and behavior; shame.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBeing wrong means being bad; emotion weakens judgment; moral consistency is the price of belonging; apology risks humiliation.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; grief; vulnerability; uncertainty; embodied emotion; responsibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage turns feeling into principle; Ruler converts impact into doctrine; Innocent protects goodness through abstraction; Mystic elevates pain into meaning.\n## Pattern Flow\nPersonal impact is named → moral identity feels threatened → ethical analysis expands → cognitive control returns → emotion and repair are bypassed → trust weakens.\n## Often Appears With\nIntellectualizing; Moral Superiority; Rationalization; Spiritual Bypassing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEthical reflection; principled thinking; concern for fairness; capacity for moral complexity.\n## Current Cost\nFailed repair; emotional distance; moral rigidity; hidden shame; principles used without personal accountability.\n## Freer Expression\nEthical reasoning joined with embodied responsibility.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the personal impact and your responsibility before discussing the larger principle.\n## Mira Language\n“The principle may be important. I also notice it may be creating distance from what you felt, did, or need to repair. Can we hold both?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat happened between the people involved? What feeling appears when the abstraction pauses? What responsibility remains even if your principle is valid?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSincere ethical reasoning, legal analysis, and principled disagreement are not avoidance when they remain connected to facts, impact, and responsibility.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated movement into moral abstraction when personal emotion, accountability, or repair becomes immediate.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the principle, then return to body, impact, action, and repair. Let moral identity survive ordinary fallibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect the principle while gently returning to personal impact, responsibility, and embodied feeling.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where moral analysis displaced listening or apology; name the concrete impact and offer proportionate repair without using principles as exemption.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Cynicism, Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, or Moral Superiority. The loop becomes “You refuse the principle” versus “You use principle to avoid me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using moral analysis to avoid the personal truth inside the issue?"},
  "PP-MORAL-SUPERIORITY": {"name":"Moral Superiority","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Grandiosity; Devaluation; Contempt; Projection; Rationalization; Keeping Score.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent — purity becomes judgment. Ruler — order becomes moral entitlement. Sage — knowledge becomes ethical superiority. Rebel — opposition proves righteousness. Caregiver — sacrifice becomes moral leverage.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"State the value and the boundary without making a global claim about another person’s character.","Core Logic":"If I am more righteous, I do not have to feel uncertain, implicated, or ordinary.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Hypocrisy blindness; polarization; shame induction; blocked learning; relational inequality.","Core Fear":"Goodness is the price of worth; being wrong makes me bad; uncertainty invites corruption; belonging requires moral purity.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to prove that I’m the good one here.; If I’m more righteous, I can’t be the problem.; Their disagreement shows a moral defect.; I need to expose their hypocrisy.; My motives are purer than theirs.; If I admit uncertainty, I may lose the high ground.","Protective Move":"Moral Superiority is the protective elevation of one’s values, motives, or conduct above others in order to stabilize worth, certainty, innocence, or power.","Pattern ID":"PP-MORAL-SUPERIORITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Certainty and worth rise temporarily when moral ranking intensifies.","Freer Expression":"Conviction with humility.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Conscience; ethical commitment; courage; discernment; protection of values.","Observable Cues":"Lecturing; purity tests; dismissing context; public correction; applying harsher standards to others; framing disagreement as moral defect.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not debate worthiness. Ask for specific behavior and impact, acknowledge valid values, and refuse contempt or dehumanization. May trigger Defensiveness, Contempt, Rebellion, Concealment, or Counter-Superiority.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Purpose, Competence, and Belonging; avoids complicity, shame, mixed motives, humility, grief, powerlessness, and common humanity.","Canonical Name":"Moral Superiority"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMoral Superiority is the protective elevation of one’s values, motives, or conduct above others in order to stabilize worth, certainty, innocence, or power.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nGrandiosity; Devaluation; Contempt; Projection; Rationalization\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I am more righteous, I do not have to feel uncertain, implicated, or ordinary.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to prove that I’m the good one here.\n- If I’m more righteous, I can’t be the problem.\n- Their disagreement shows a moral defect.\n- I need to expose their hypocrisy.\n- My motives are purer than theirs.\n- If I admit uncertainty, I may lose the high ground.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nCertainty that one’s motives are purer; difficulty recognizing mixed motives; relief in identifying a wrongdoer; indignation that strengthens identity.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nLecturing; purity tests; dismissing context; public correction; applying harsher standards to others; framing disagreement as moral defect.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Purpose; Competence; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; guilt; disagreement; loss of status; perceived hypocrisy; challenges to identity or values.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nGoodness is the price of worth; being wrong makes me bad; uncertainty invites corruption; belonging requires moral purity.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nComplicity; shame; mixed motives; humility; grief; powerlessness; common humanity.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent — purity becomes judgment. Ruler — order becomes moral entitlement. Sage — knowledge becomes ethical superiority. Rebel — opposition proves righteousness. Caregiver — sacrifice becomes moral leverage.\n## Pattern Flow\nIdentity or innocence feels challenged → moral ranking intensifies → certainty and worth rise temporarily → nuance and accountability narrow → contempt and polarization increase.\n## Often Appears With\nDevaluation; Projection; Grandiosity; Keeping Score; Contempt.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nConscience; ethical commitment; courage; discernment; protection of values.\n## Current Cost\nHypocrisy blindness; polarization; shame induction; blocked learning; relational inequality.\n## Freer Expression\nConviction with humility.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the value and the boundary without making a global claim about another person’s character.\n## Mira Language\n“The value may be important. Can we protect it without using righteousness to place you outside ordinary human contradiction?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat part of you also needs examination? Is this a boundary or a verdict on the person? What uncertainty does moral certainty relieve?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nEthical clarity, naming harm, activism, and firm boundaries are not automatically Moral Superiority.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of moral ranking to regulate worth, avoid accountability, or diminish others—not one strong ethical judgment.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReturn from character ranking to values, behavior, impact, and one’s own accountability. Allow conviction and fallibility to coexist.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not debate worthiness. Ask for specific behavior and impact, acknowledge valid values, and refuse contempt or dehumanization.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where moral ranking shamed or erased another person’s humanity. Repair through specific accountability, withdrawal of global character judgments, and equal application of standards.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Contempt, Rebellion, Concealment, or Counter-Superiority. Often triggered by criticism, hypocrisy, ambiguity, or shame. The loop becomes: “I must prove I am good” and “I must expose your hypocrisy.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nCan I stand for what is right without needing to stand above someone?"},
  "PP-MORAL-WORTH-PERFORMANCE": {"name":"Moral Worth Performance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Image Management; Martyrdom; Moral Licensing; Approval Seeking; Grandiosity; People-Pleasing.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent performs purity; Caregiver performs sacrifice; Ruler performs virtue as legitimacy; Rebel performs righteousness as belonging.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective purpose, distinctions, and Mira response. Missing canonical sections authored to the established standard while preserving the core mechanism. Spacing repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"M","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Do one value-aligned action without announcing it or using it to offset another responsibility.","Core Logic":"If others can see enough evidence that I am good, I may remain safe from shame and rejection.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Fragile identity; resentment; hypocrisy; performative relationships; difficulty receiving correction.","Core Fear":"Without visible goodness, I may lose worth, belonging, protection, or exemption from criticism.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They need to see that I am a good person.; My sacrifice should protect me from criticism.; If my virtue is not recognized, it feels wasted.; I need visible proof that I belong on the right side.; Being ordinary or mixed feels morally unsafe.; My goodness should count when my impact is questioned.","Protective Move":"Moral Worth Performance displays goodness, sacrifice, purity, or social virtue to secure worth, belonging, protection from criticism, or exemption from ordinary accountability.","Pattern ID":"PP-MORAL-WORTH-PERFORMANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Recognition and moral safety increase when goodness is made visible.","Freer Expression":"Values lived without requiring applause or exemption.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Ethical aspiration; service; generosity; commitment to values; desire to contribute.","Observable Cues":"Publicizing sacrifice; emphasizing purity or virtue; curating moral identity; expecting recognition or immunity after visible goodness.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Affirm genuine values while separating contribution from exemption and recognition from worth. May trigger Cynicism, Moral Superiority, Suspicion, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects moral identity, belonging, self-esteem, recognition, and safety; avoids shame, ordinariness, mixed motives, accountability, and uncertainty about worth.","Canonical Name":"Moral Worth Performance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nMoral Worth Performance is the protective display of goodness, sacrifice, purity, or social virtue in order to secure worth, belonging, protection from criticism, or exemption from ordinary accountability. It differs from authentic values because visible proof of goodness becomes necessary to stabilize identity.\n## Domain\nMoral Identity, Approval, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nImage Management; Martyrdom; Moral Licensing; Approval Seeking; Grandiosity\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf others can see enough evidence that I am good, I may remain safe from shame and rejection.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They need to see that I am a good person.\n- My sacrifice should protect me from criticism.\n- If my virtue is not recognized, it feels wasted.\n- I need visible proof that I belong on the right side.\n- Being ordinary or mixed feels morally unsafe.\n- My goodness should count when my impact is questioned.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to display virtue; disappointment when goodness is unnoticed; fear that mixed motives invalidate worth; relief after public recognition.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nPublicizing sacrifice; emphasizing purity or virtue; curating moral identity; expecting recognition or immunity after visible goodness.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; self-esteem; recognition; safety; moral coherence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCriticism; moral ambiguity; social comparison; lack of recognition; public scrutiny; contradiction between values and impact.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove follows goodness; mistakes erase worth; moral performance earns safety; unseen contribution does not count.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; ordinariness; mixed motives; fallibility; grief; accountability.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent performs purity; Caregiver performs sacrifice; Ruler performs virtue as legitimacy; Rebel performs righteousness as belonging.\n## Pattern Flow\nWorth or moral identity feels uncertain → visible goodness intensifies → recognition restores safety → accountability or mixed motives remain unexamined → identity becomes more dependent on performance.\n## Often Appears With\nImage Management; Moral Licensing; Martyrdom; Approval Seeking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEthical aspiration; service; generosity; commitment to values; desire to contribute.\n## Current Cost\nFragile identity; resentment; hypocrisy; performative relationships; difficulty receiving correction.\n## Freer Expression\nValues lived without requiring applause or exemption.\n## One Act of Volition\nDo one value-aligned action without announcing it or using it to offset another responsibility.\n## Mira Language\n“The value may be genuine. I also wonder whether being seen as good is carrying your worth or protecting you from ordinary accountability.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWould this action still matter without recognition? What does criticism threaten about your moral identity? Can goodness and fallibility coexist?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nVisible advocacy, public accountability, signaling shared values, and naming sacrifice are not automatically performance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern in which visible virtue is used to regulate worth, secure belonging, or reduce ordinary accountability.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReconnect with the value itself, allow mixed motives, and separate contribution from moral immunity.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAffirm the underlying value while separating moral identity from performance, recognition, and exemption.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where displayed goodness was used to silence impact, demand admiration, or avoid correction; return to the specific behavior and repair.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Cynicism, Suspicion, Moral Superiority, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “You must recognize my goodness” versus “Your goodness is only performance.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat value remains mine when no one sees, praises, or rewards it?"},
  "PP-NARRATIVE-OVERCONTROL": {"name":"Narrative Overcontrol","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rationalization; Gaslighting; Semantic Control; Identity Fusion; Information Control; Plausible Deniability.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler controls the official story; Sage organizes contradiction out of view; Magician shapes meaning; Innocent protects innocence through coherence.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective purpose, distinctions, and Mira response. Missing sections authored to full canonical standard; spacing repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because compulsory narrative control can impair another person’s reality, consent, and accountability when used relationally.","First Letter":"N","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"State the observable facts, then name your interpretation as one perspective rather than the only permissible story.","Core Logic":"If I control the story, I can control what the event means and what consequences follow.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Mistrust; silenced perspectives; distorted memory; failed repair; escalating conflict.","Core Fear":"If the story becomes uncertain or shared, identity, innocence, status, or control may collapse.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"There can only be one accurate story about this.; I need them to accept my interpretation.; Their perspective threatens the meaning I depend on.; If contradictions remain, I may lose control of the outcome.; I should manage the wording before others define what happened.; Facts that do not fit the story need to be explained away.","Protective Move":"Narrative Overcontrol rigidly manages the story of events so ambiguity, contradiction, other perspectives, and unwanted meanings cannot destabilize identity or control.","Pattern ID":"PP-NARRATIVE-OVERCONTROL","Short-Term Payoff":"Certainty and leverage return when one interpretation becomes compulsory.","Freer Expression":"Coherent interpretation that remains open to evidence and other perspectives.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Coherence; storytelling; synthesis; attention to meaning; ability to organize complexity.","Observable Cues":"Insisting on one authorized version; correcting others’ interpretations; controlling wording; excluding contradictory facts; demanding agreement about motive or meaning.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Hold multiple perspectives, separate facts from interpretation, and refuse compulsory agreement while staying anchored to evidence. May trigger Suspicion, Interrogative Control, Emotional Withholding, or Retaliation.","Emotional Function":"Protects identity, coherence, safety, status, and control; avoids ambiguity, contradiction, shame, accountability, helplessness, and other people’s independent meaning-making.","Canonical Name":"Narrative Overcontrol"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nNarrative Overcontrol rigidly manages the story of events so ambiguity, contradiction, other perspectives, and unwanted meanings cannot destabilize identity or control. It differs from accurate clarification because one interpretation becomes compulsory rather than testable.\n## Domain\nMeaning, Identity, and Relational Control\n## Related Patterns\nRationalization; Gaslighting; Semantic Control; Identity Fusion; Information Control\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I control the story, I can control what the event means and what consequences follow.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- There can only be one accurate story about this.\n- I need them to accept my interpretation.\n- Their perspective threatens the meaning I depend on.\n- If contradictions remain, I may lose control of the outcome.\n- I should manage the wording before others define what happened.\n- Facts that do not fit the story need to be explained away.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDistress when accounts differ; urgency to establish the official meaning; fear that ambiguity will imply guilt or weakness; relief when others agree.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nInsisting on one authorized version; correcting others’ interpretations; controlling wording; excluding contradictory facts; demanding agreement about motive or meaning.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nIdentity; coherence; safety; status; control; dignity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConflict; public scrutiny; memory differences; accountability; competing perspectives; uncertainty about motive or impact.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nContradiction means danger; being misunderstood is intolerable; losing narrative control means losing safety; ambiguity invites blame.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; helplessness; uncertainty; complexity; fallibility; another person’s independent reality.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler controls the official story; Sage organizes contradiction out of view; Magician shapes meaning; Innocent protects innocence through coherence.\n## Pattern Flow\nContradiction or alternate perspective appears → identity or control feels threatened → one narrative is enforced → certainty returns → other evidence and voices are suppressed → mistrust and resistance grow.\n## Often Appears With\nInformation Control; Rationalization; Plausible Deniability; Identity Fusion.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCoherence; storytelling; synthesis; attention to meaning; ability to organize complexity.\n## Current Cost\nMistrust; silenced perspectives; distorted memory; failed repair; escalating conflict.\n## Freer Expression\nCoherent interpretation that remains open to evidence and other perspectives.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the observable facts, then name your interpretation as one perspective rather than the only permissible story.\n## Mira Language\n“You may have a coherent interpretation. I also notice pressure for it to become the only allowed account. What is fact, what is meaning, and what remains disputed?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhich facts are mutually observable? What does another perspective threaten? What evidence would revise your story?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAccurate correction, documentation, advocacy against false claims, and establishing facts in safety or legal contexts are not Narrative Overcontrol.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated efforts to enforce one interpretation by excluding relevant facts or denying others’ independent perspectives.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate observation, memory, interpretation, and impact; tolerate unresolved difference; protect truth without demanding total narrative agreement.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nHold multiple perspectives, separate facts from interpretation, and resist recruitment into a single compulsory narrative.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where another person’s experience or evidence was overwritten; restore disputed facts, permit independent meaning, and repair any decisions made under distorted framing.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Interrogative Control, Emotional Withholding, or Retaliation. The loop becomes “You must accept my story” versus “I must defend my reality.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat becomes endangered when my version of the story is not the only one allowed?"},
  "PP-OBLIGATION-LEVERAGE": {"name":"Obligation Leverage","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Guilt Induction; Keeping Score; Martyrdom; Possessiveness; Dominance; Selective Accountability; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver becomes creditor; Ruler treats role as entitlement; Lover treats history as ownership; Orphan binds others through debt.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the source explicitly addresses pressure for compliance beyond free agreement, coerced loyalty, overridden consent, and boundary violations.","First Letter":"O","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"Separate what was freely given, what was explicitly agreed, and what is now being requested.","Core Logic":"I am turning relationship or prior contribution into a claim over their present choice.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Entitlement; coerced loyalty; transactional intimacy; concealed contracts; boundary violations.","Core Fear":"Giving is how I secure loyalty; relationships are unsafe without debt; generosity that creates no claim leaves me powerless.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"After everything I have given, they owe me this.; Our history should give me a claim over their present choice.; Family or loyalty means they should not refuse.; Receiving my help created an obligation they cannot simply leave.; I need the past contribution to restore my influence now.; If what I gave was freely offered, I may have no leverage left.","Protective Move":"Obligation Leverage is the protective conversion of prior help, role, kinship, loyalty, promise, or sacrifice into pressure for present compliance beyond what was clearly and freely agreed.","Pattern ID":"PP-OBLIGATION-LEVERAGE","Short-Term Payoff":"Invoking obligation may produce compliance or preserve influence.","Freer Expression":"Explicit agreements and freely renewed reciprocity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Loyalty, memory, reciprocity, commitment, and stewardship of agreements.","Observable Cues":"Invoking family, loyalty, money, sacrifice, status, favors, or past rescue to override a boundary; expanding old agreements after the fact.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify the actual agreement, acknowledge valid contribution, and refuse expansions of obligation that override consent or safety. May trigger Appeasement, Retaliation, Hyper-Independence, Emotional Distancing, or Score-keeping.","Emotional Function":"Protects Reciprocity, recognition, fairness, belonging, predictability, control, and dignity; avoids grief, changed consent, impermanence, asymmetry, freely chosen relationship, and inability to control return.","Canonical Name":"Obligation Leverage"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nObligation Leverage is the protective conversion of prior help, role, kinship, loyalty, promise, or sacrifice into pressure for present compliance beyond what was clearly and freely agreed.\n## Domain\nRelationship, Power, and Reciprocity\n## Related Patterns\nGuilt Induction; Keeping Score; Martyrdom; Possessiveness; Dominance; Selective Accountability\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am turning relationship or prior contribution into a claim over their present choice.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- After everything I have given, they owe me this.\n- Our history should give me a claim over their present choice.\n- Family or loyalty means they should not refuse.\n- Receiving my help created an obligation they cannot simply leave.\n- I need the past contribution to restore my influence now.\n- If what I gave was freely offered, I may have no leverage left.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nFeeling owed; anger when gratitude does not become obedience; fear that freely offered care has no power; belief that roles create unlimited access.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nInvoking family, loyalty, money, sacrifice, status, favors, or past rescue to override a boundary; expanding old agreements after the fact.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nReciprocity; recognition; fairness; belonging; predictability; control; dignity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nBoundary setting; changed circumstances; refusal; separation; perceived ingratitude; loss of influence.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nGiving is how I secure loyalty; relationships are unsafe without debt; generosity that creates no claim leaves me powerless.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; changed consent; impermanence; asymmetry; freely chosen relationship; inability to control return.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver becomes creditor; Ruler treats role as entitlement; Lover treats history as ownership; Orphan binds others through debt.\n## Pattern Flow\nContribution or role creates expectation → present choice diverges → obligation is invoked → compliance or conflict follows → trust and generosity become transactional.\n## Often Appears With\nKeeping Score; Guilt Induction; Martyrdom; Possessiveness; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nLoyalty, memory, reciprocity, commitment, and stewardship of agreements.\n## Current Cost\nEntitlement; coerced loyalty; transactional intimacy; concealed contracts; boundary violations.\n## Freer Expression\nExplicit agreements and freely renewed reciprocity.\n## One Act of Volition\nSeparate what was freely given, what was explicitly agreed, and what is now being requested.\n## Mira Language\n“There may be a real agreement or imbalance to address. Is the current request part of that agreement, or is prior contribution being used to override present consent?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat was actually promised? What was assumed? Can this relationship remain meaningful without present obedience?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLegal, caregiving, parental, fiduciary, employment, or shared-household obligations can be real. Mira must not erase legitimate duties or power differences.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of prior contribution or relational role to claim choices not explicitly agreed or no longer freely consented to.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIdentify the real obligation, release imagined ownership, renegotiate changed agreements, and state present needs without converting history into control.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify the actual agreement, acknowledge valid contribution, and refuse expansions of obligation that override consent or safety.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where generosity, role, or history was used as leverage; restore present choice; settle legitimate debts transparently; revise the agreement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Retaliation, Hyper-Independence, Emotional Distancing, or Score-keeping. Stories become “After everything I did, you owe me” and “Receiving anything means losing my freedom.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I naming a real agreement, or turning history into ownership?"},
  "PP-ONE-UPMANSHIP": {"name":"One-Upmanship","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Comparison; Grandiosity; Defensive Expertise; Devaluation; Status Guarding; Moral Superiority.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior turns conversation into contest; Sage must know more; Creator must be more original; Caregiver must have sacrificed more.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"O","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"Ask one genuine follow-up question before sharing your own related experience.","Core Logic":"I need to be above this person so I do not feel beneath them.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Alienation; envy; diminished joy; inability to celebrate others.","Core Fear":"Attention is scarce; value must be ranked; someone else’s success reduces mine.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to share the bigger version of that story.; Their success is making me feel smaller.; I should correct the details so my expertise stays visible.; I cannot simply witness their praise without adding my own achievement.; If they shine, I need to shine more.; I need to rank above them to restore my worth.","Protective Move":"One-Upmanship is the protective attempt to restore worth or status by surpassing, correcting, outdoing, or eclipsing another person’s experience or achievement.","Pattern ID":"PP-ONE-UPMANSHIP","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary superiority returns when the self is elevated or the other diminished.","Freer Expression":"Distinctiveness without ranking.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Ambition; excellence; lively exchange; desire to contribute.","Observable Cues":"Topping stories; correcting minor details; redirecting praise; competing over pain, knowledge, hardship, or generosity.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not enter the ranking contest; affirm both experiences without equalizing unlike harms. May trigger Withdrawal, Devaluation, Comparison, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Belonging, and Significance; avoids envy, ordinariness, admiration, and vulnerability.","Canonical Name":"One-Upmanship"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nOne-Upmanship is the protective attempt to restore worth or status by surpassing, correcting, outdoing, or eclipsing another person’s experience or achievement.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Status, and Comparison\n## Related Patterns\nComparison; Grandiosity; Defensive Expertise; Devaluation; Status Guarding\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need to be above this person so I do not feel beneath them.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to share the bigger version of that story.\n- Their success is making me feel smaller.\n- I should correct the details so my expertise stays visible.\n- I cannot simply witness their praise without adding my own achievement.\n- If they shine, I need to shine more.\n- I need to rank above them to restore my worth.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnother person’s success feels diminishing; urge to add a bigger story; discomfort simply witnessing praise.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTopping stories; correcting minor details; redirecting praise; competing over pain, knowledge, hardship, or generosity.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Belonging; Significance.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPraise of others; comparison; insecurity; status change; expertise being questioned.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nAttention is scarce; value must be ranked; someone else’s success reduces mine.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nEnvy; ordinariness; admiration; vulnerability.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior turns conversation into contest; Sage must know more; Creator must be more original; Caregiver must have sacrificed more.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother person shines → worth feels threatened → self is elevated or other diminished → temporary superiority returns → connection and mutuality weaken.\n## Often Appears With\nComparison; Grandiosity; Moral Superiority; Defensive Expertise.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAmbition; excellence; lively exchange; desire to contribute.\n## Current Cost\nAlienation; envy; diminished joy; inability to celebrate others.\n## Freer Expression\nDistinctiveness without ranking.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk one genuine follow-up question before sharing your own related experience.\n## Mira Language\n“Can their success remain theirs for a moment without requiring you to become smaller or larger?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feels taken from you here? Can admiration exist without self-erasure? What contribution does not require comparison?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nReciprocal storytelling, playful competition, and relevant expertise are not automatically one-upmanship.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated eclipsing or ranking when another person receives attention, sympathy, or admiration.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the status threat; practice witnessing; separate contribution from competition.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not enter the ranking contest; affirm both experiences without equalizing unlike harms.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where another person’s moment was eclipsed, return attention to their experience, and stop defending the comparison.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Withdrawal, Devaluation, Comparison, or Resentment; often triggered by Image Management or Grandiosity in others.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere do I turn another person’s moment into a ranking of worth?"},
  "PP-OVEREXPLAINING": {"name":"Overexplaining","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rejection Sensitivity; Defensive Expertise; Approval Seeking; Rumination; Strategic Ambiguity.","Archetypal Role":"Sage—context becomes a shield; Caregiver—explains to prevent upset; Innocent—tries to prove harmlessness; Ruler—controls the frame through detail.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"O","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Answer in three sentences, then ask whether more context would help.","Core Logic":"If I explain enough, I may become safe from being misread.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; diluted message; reduced credibility; difficulty tolerating questions; relational imbalance.","Core Fear":"My word will not be accepted; misunderstanding is dangerous; I must prove innocence or competence; brevity will look deceptive.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to explain every detail so they do not misunderstand me.; A short answer will look suspicious or careless.; I should address every possible objection before they raise it.; If I keep clarifying, maybe they will finally see my intent.; I cannot stop until the whole context is understood.; Being misread feels dangerous enough to require another explanation.","Protective Move":"Overexplaining is the protective attempt to prevent misunderstanding, criticism, rejection, or loss of control by supplying more justification, context, and detail than the situation requires.","Pattern ID":"PP-OVEREXPLAINING","Short-Term Payoff":"Expanding explanation brings brief relief from fear of misinterpretation.","Freer Expression":"Clear context without self-defense.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Thoughtfulness; transparency; nuance; care with language.","Observable Cues":"Long answers to simple questions; repeated clarifications after the point is understood; adding defenses before criticism occurs; difficulty ending an explanation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Signal when the answer is understood, ask one focused question, and avoid punishing brevity or using omitted minor details as proof of deception. May trigger Impatience, Emotional Distancing, Suspicion, or Dominance.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Belonging, Self-Esteem, and Autonomy; avoids uncertainty, imperfect control over another person’s interpretation, ordinary disagreement, and vulnerability.","Canonical Name":"Overexplaining"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nOverexplaining is the protective attempt to prevent misunderstanding, criticism, rejection, or loss of control by supplying more justification, context, and detail than the situation requires.\n## Domain\nCommunication, Shame, and Relational Safety\n## Related Patterns\nRejection Sensitivity; Defensive Expertise; Approval Seeking; Rumination; Strategic Ambiguity.\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I explain enough, I may become safe from being misread.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to explain every detail so they do not misunderstand me.\n- A short answer will look suspicious or careless.\n- I should address every possible objection before they raise it.\n- If I keep clarifying, maybe they will finally see my intent.\n- I cannot stop until the whole context is understood.\n- Being misread feels dangerous enough to require another explanation.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to clarify every possible interpretation; discomfort after a concise answer; fear that omitted context will be used against you; rehearsing explanations before speaking.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nLong answers to simple questions; repeated clarifications after the point is understood; adding defenses before criticism occurs; difficulty ending an explanation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Belonging; Self-Esteem; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nQuestions that feel evaluative; authority figures; conflict; ambiguity; previous experiences of being misread or disbelieved.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy word will not be accepted; misunderstanding is dangerous; I must prove innocence or competence; brevity will look deceptive.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; imperfect control over another person’s interpretation; ordinary disagreement; vulnerability.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage—context becomes a shield; Caregiver—explains to prevent upset; Innocent—tries to prove harmlessness; Ruler—controls the frame through detail.\n## Pattern Flow\nQuestion or ambiguity → fear of misinterpretation → expanding explanation → brief relief → listener overload or suspicion → stronger urge to explain next time.\n## Often Appears With\nRejection Sensitivity; Defensive Expertise; Approval Seeking; Rumination.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nThoughtfulness; transparency; nuance; care with language.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; diluted message; reduced credibility; difficulty tolerating questions; relational imbalance.\n## Freer Expression\nClear context without self-defense.\n## One Act of Volition\nAnswer in three sentences, then ask whether more context would help.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be giving more context than the question requires. Is the extra explanation serving clarity, or trying to make misunderstanding impossible?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you fear the shorter answer would imply? Has the listener asked for more detail? What part of your meaning is essential?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDetailed communication, accessibility needs, cultural style, trauma-informed disclosure, and complex subject matter are not automatically overexplaining.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated sequence of disproportionate explanation driven by fear or self-protection, not one thorough answer.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the feared interpretation, identify the minimum truthful answer, and permit the listener to ask a follow-up rather than pre-answering every possible objection.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nSignal when the answer is understood, ask one focused question, and avoid punishing brevity or using omitted minor details as proof of deception.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where excessive explanation overwhelmed, redirected, or prevented dialogue. Restate the core answer plainly and make room for the other person’s response.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Impatience, Emotional Distancing, Suspicion, or Dominance. Often triggered by Hostility Toward Criticism, Suspicion, Strategic Ambiguity, or prior invalidation. The loop story becomes: “I must explain more to be believed” and “The more you explain, the less I trust the answer.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using explanation to eliminate the risk of being misunderstood?"},
  "PP-OVERFUNCTIONING": {"name":"Overfunctioning","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Micromanaging; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Productivity-Bound Worth; Hypervigilance; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver rescues; Ruler assumes all authority; Warrior carries every burden; Creator completes everyone’s work; Lover manages the bond; Sage supplies every answer.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"O","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Ask who owns the task before acting, and leave one appropriate responsibility with its actual owner.","Core Logic":"If I do not carry more than my share, everything may fall apart.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Burnout; resentment; dependency loops; reduced collaboration; hidden expectations; loss of rest.","Core Fear":"I am valued for usefulness; relying on others is unsafe; care means preventing discomfort; failure will be blamed on me.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It’s easier if I handle it myself.; If I don’t step in, this will fall apart.; I should fix this before anyone struggles.; I can’t rely on other people to follow through.; I’ll carry the extra load so everything stays okay.; Their discomfort is mine to prevent.","Protective Move":"Overfunctioning is the protective assumption of excessive responsibility, labor, planning, or emotional management in order to prevent failure, conflict, disappointment, or dependence on others.","Pattern ID":"PP-OVERFUNCTIONING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control and usefulness appear as responsibility expands.","Freer Expression":"Responsible contribution without rescue.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Reliability; generosity; initiative; stewardship; endurance.","Observable Cues":"Taking over responsibilities; anticipating needs without agreement; solving problems before being asked; rescuing others from consequences; carrying emotional and logistical labor invisibly.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Accept agreed help without silently transferring ownership. State what you will do, follow through, and resist rewarding rescue by becoming less engaged. May trigger Underfunctioning, Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Safety, Belonging, Self-Esteem, and Trust; avoids dependence, limits, receiving, disappointment, another person’s autonomy, and conflict over expectations.","Canonical Name":"Overfunctioning"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nOverfunctioning is the protective assumption of excessive responsibility, labor, planning, or emotional management in order to prevent failure, conflict, disappointment, or dependence on others.\n## Domain\nResponsibility, Control, and Care\n## Related Patterns\nMicromanaging; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Productivity-Bound Worth; Hypervigilance\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I do not carry more than my share, everything may fall apart.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It’s easier if I handle it myself.\n- If I don’t step in, this will fall apart.\n- I should fix this before anyone struggles.\n- I can’t rely on other people to follow through.\n- I’ll carry the extra load so everything stays okay.\n- Their discomfort is mine to prevent.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDifficulty waiting for others; guilt when not helping; resentment paired with continued taking over; anxiety when tasks remain in someone else’s hands.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTaking over responsibilities; anticipating needs without agreement; solving problems before being asked; rescuing others from consequences; carrying emotional and logistical labor invisibly.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Safety; Belonging; Self-Esteem; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUnreliable follow-through; conflict; visible distress; deadlines; fear of judgment; another person’s uncertainty.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am valued for usefulness; relying on others is unsafe; care means preventing discomfort; failure will be blamed on me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependence; limits; receiving; disappointment; another person’s autonomy; conflict over expectations.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver rescues; Ruler assumes all authority; Warrior carries every burden; Creator completes everyone’s work; Lover manages the bond; Sage supplies every answer.\n## Pattern Flow\nA need or gap appears → safety, worth, or competence feels threatened → responsibility expands → temporary control and usefulness appear → others participate less or feel displaced → exhaustion and resentment reinforce taking over.\n## Often Appears With\nMicromanaging; Productivity-Bound Worth; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReliability; generosity; initiative; stewardship; endurance.\n## Current Cost\nBurnout; resentment; dependency loops; reduced collaboration; hidden expectations; loss of rest.\n## Freer Expression\nResponsible contribution without rescue.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk who owns the task before acting, and leave one appropriate responsibility with its actual owner.\n## Mira Language\n“You are carrying more than the agreed role requires. Is this contribution freely chosen, or is taking over protecting you from uncertainty, conflict, or being disappointed?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat consequence are you preventing someone else from experiencing? What did you explicitly agree to? What support would preserve their agency?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nTemporary crisis leadership, caregiving necessity, unequal capacity, and legitimate role responsibility are not automatically overfunctioning.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of excessive responsibility, difficulty delegating, and resentment or exhaustion—not one generous act.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nClarify ownership, consent, and capacity. Offer bounded help instead of takeover and tolerate the discomfort of another person doing something differently or facing proportionate consequences.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAccept agreed help without silently transferring ownership. State what you will do, follow through, and resist rewarding rescue by becoming less engaged.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where helping became control, displaced another person’s agency, or created unspoken debt. Redistribute ownership explicitly and stop using sacrifice as evidence of entitlement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Defensiveness, Self-Erasure, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by unreliability, helplessness, avoidance, or Micromanaging. The loop becomes: “I must do everything” and “There is no room or reason for me to act.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I carrying that belongs to another capable person?"},
  "PP-PASSIVE-AGGRESSION": {"name":"Passive Aggression","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Resentment; Punitive Silence; People-Pleasing; Defensiveness; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Blame Shifting.","Archetypal Role":"Rebel — covert resistance. Caregiver — agreeing while resenting. Trickster — sarcasm and deniability. Ruler — bureaucratic obstruction. Lover — withdrawn cooperation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Replace one indirect resistance with a clear yes, no, or negotiated alternative.","Core Logic":"I am resisting without openly admitting that I am resisting.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Confusion; mistrust; escalation; unreliable agreements; accumulated resentment.","Core Fear":"Direct disagreement is dangerous; my no will not be respected; anger makes me unacceptable; resistance is my only remaining power.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I’ll say yes, but I don’t intend to cooperate.; If I delay long enough, they’ll understand I’m angry.; I can’t safely say no directly.; I’ll let my actions communicate what I won’t say.; They can’t accuse me if I never openly refused.; This is the only way I can resist without a fight.","Protective Move":"Passive aggression is the protective expression of anger, resistance, or refusal indirectly when direct disagreement feels unsafe, forbidden, or too costly.","Pattern ID":"PP-PASSIVE-AGGRESSION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary power returns when indirect resistance communicates anger.","Freer Expression":"Direct refusal without punishment.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Resistance to domination; discernment about unfair demands; need for authentic consent.","Observable Cues":"Agreeing and not following through; strategic delay; sarcasm; ambiguous compliance; repeated forgetting around unwanted demands; indirect obstruction.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite direct disagreement, clarify agreements, and address impact without demanding mind reading. Maintain consequences for repeated covert obstruction. May trigger Micromanaging, Hypervigilance, Hostility Toward Criticism, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Safety, Dignity, and Self-Esteem; avoids vulnerability, direct accountability, explicit refusal, and risk of open conflict.","Canonical Name":"Passive Aggression"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPassive aggression is the protective expression of anger, resistance, or refusal indirectly when direct disagreement feels unsafe, forbidden, or too costly.\n## Domain\nAnger, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nResentment; Punitive Silence; People-Pleasing; Defensiveness; Withdrawing Before Being Left\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am resisting without openly admitting that I am resisting.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I’ll say yes, but I don’t intend to cooperate.\n- If I delay long enough, they’ll understand I’m angry.\n- I can’t safely say no directly.\n- I’ll let my actions communicate what I won’t say.\n- They can’t accuse me if I never openly refused.\n- This is the only way I can resist without a fight.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnger paired with reluctance to state it; satisfaction when delay or noncompliance communicates displeasure; fear of direct conflict; feeling controlled while outwardly agreeing.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAgreeing and not following through; strategic delay; sarcasm; ambiguous compliance; repeated forgetting around unwanted demands; indirect obstruction.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Safety; Dignity; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPressure; criticism; unequal power; demands; inability to say no; fear of retaliation.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDirect disagreement is dangerous; my no will not be respected; anger makes me unacceptable; resistance is my only remaining power.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; direct accountability; explicit refusal; risk of open conflict.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRebel — covert resistance. Caregiver — agreeing while resenting. Trickster — sarcasm and deniability. Ruler — bureaucratic obstruction. Lover — withdrawn cooperation.\n## Pattern Flow\nDemand or grievance arises → autonomy or safety feels threatened → indirect resistance communicates anger → temporary power returns → trust and clarity decline.\n## Often Appears With\nResentment; People-Pleasing; Punitive Silence; Blame Shifting.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nResistance to domination; discernment about unfair demands; need for authentic consent.\n## Current Cost\nConfusion; mistrust; escalation; unreliable agreements; accumulated resentment.\n## Freer Expression\nDirect refusal without punishment.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace one indirect resistance with a clear yes, no, or negotiated alternative.\n## Mira Language\n“You agreed, but your actions repeatedly communicate refusal. Could an indirect form of resistance be protecting you from saying no directly?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would feel dangerous about stating your objection plainly? What agreement would you make if refusal were allowed?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nExecutive-function lapses, confusion, fatigue, and genuine forgetting are not passive aggression without evidence of repeated grievance-linked resistance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated sequence of outward agreement, concealed objection, and indirect obstruction.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the anger and the no before acting indirectly. Ask for time, renegotiate, or refuse without using delay or ambiguity as punishment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite direct disagreement, clarify agreements, and address impact without demanding mind reading. Maintain consequences for repeated covert obstruction.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the hidden resistance and its impact, state the original objection honestly, repair practical harm, and create an explicit agreement that permits refusal and renegotiation.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Hypervigilance, Hostility Toward Criticism, or Contempt. Often triggered by Control-Seeking, criticism, pressure, or dismissed boundaries. The loop becomes “I must control because you will not be direct” versus “I must resist indirectly because you will not accept my no.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I communicating resistance indirectly instead of stating my truth?"},
  "PP-PEOPLE-PLEASING": {"name":"People-Pleasing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Self-Erasure; Approval Seeking; Boundary Collapse; Overfunctioning; Conflict Avoidance; Keeping Score; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — care becomes compliance. Everyman — belonging requires sameness. Lover — harmony is purchased through self-abandonment. Innocent — goodness becomes never upsetting anyone. Diplomat/Ruler — peacekeeping replaces truth.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Pause before answering one request and state the truthful answer after checking capacity and desire.","Core Logic":"I keep you comfortable so I can remain acceptable.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; resentment; weak boundaries; concealed truth; relationships built around a false self.","Core Fear":"Love must be earned through usefulness or agreeableness; conflict causes abandonment; my needs burden others; displeasure means danger.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Whatever you want is fine.; I don’t want to disappoint anyone.; I can say yes now and deal with my feelings later.; If they’re upset, I must have done something wrong.; My preference isn’t worth the conflict.; I need everyone comfortable before I can relax.","Protective Move":"People-Pleasing is the protective adaptation of preferences, feelings, behavior, or availability to secure acceptance and reduce the risk of disappointment, conflict, or rejection.","Pattern ID":"PP-PEOPLE-PLEASING","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate tension falls as adaptation and appeasement increase.","Freer Expression":"Kindness with self-possession.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Empathy; responsiveness; cooperation; social awareness; generosity.","Observable Cues":"Agreeing too quickly; apologizing unnecessarily; taking on unwanted tasks; changing opinions to match the room; hiding disappointment; offering help before being asked.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite an honest preference, allow time to answer, do not reward compliance more than truth, and respond respectfully when the answer is no. May trigger Dependency, Entitlement, Micromanaging, or Taking for Granted.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Safety; avoids anger, difference, disappointment, limits, and the possibility that not everyone will approve.","Canonical Name":"People-Pleasing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPeople-Pleasing is the protective adaptation of preferences, feelings, behavior, or availability to secure acceptance and reduce the risk of disappointment, conflict, or rejection.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nSelf-Erasure; Approval Seeking; Boundary Collapse; Overfunctioning; Conflict Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nI keep you comfortable so I can remain acceptable.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Whatever you want is fine.\n- I don’t want to disappoint anyone.\n- I can say yes now and deal with my feelings later.\n- If they’re upset, I must have done something wrong.\n- My preference isn’t worth the conflict.\n- I need everyone comfortable before I can relax.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnxiety when someone is displeased; rapid scanning for others’ preferences; guilt after saying no; uncertainty about one’s own wants; relief when everyone appears satisfied.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAgreeing too quickly; apologizing unnecessarily; taking on unwanted tasks; changing opinions to match the room; hiding disappointment; offering help before being asked.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Self-Esteem; Trust; Safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDisapproval; interpersonal tension; requests; authority figures; ambiguous moods; fear of exclusion.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove must be earned through usefulness or agreeableness; conflict causes abandonment; my needs burden others; displeasure means danger.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAnger; difference; disappointment; limits; the possibility that not everyone will approve.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — care becomes compliance. Everyman — belonging requires sameness. Lover — harmony is purchased through self-abandonment. Innocent — goodness becomes never upsetting anyone. Diplomat/Ruler — peacekeeping replaces truth.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother person may be displeased → belonging feels threatened → adaptation and appeasement increase → immediate tension falls → needs remain unspoken → resentment and identity confusion grow.\n## Often Appears With\nSelf-Erasure; Boundary Collapse; Approval Seeking; Keeping Score; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nEmpathy; responsiveness; cooperation; social awareness; generosity.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; resentment; weak boundaries; concealed truth; relationships built around a false self.\n## Freer Expression\nKindness with self-possession.\n## One Act of Volition\nPause before answering one request and state the truthful answer after checking capacity and desire.\n## Mira Language\n“You seem highly aware of what everyone else needs, but your own preference keeps disappearing. Could agreeableness be protecting belonging here?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you want before considering their reaction? What would a respectful no risk? Are you giving freely or purchasing safety?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCourtesy, generosity, compromise, and cultural deference are not automatically People-Pleasing.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of self-suppression organized around preventing disapproval—not one considerate accommodation.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nNotice the threat beneath the urge to appease, regulate before answering, and practice tolerating limited disappointment without interpreting it as abandonment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite an honest preference, allow time to answer, do not reward compliance more than truth, and respond respectfully when the answer is no.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where false agreement or concealed resentment distorted consent. Clarify what was freely chosen, renegotiate commitments, and demonstrate repair through earlier truth rather than later resentment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Dependency, Entitlement, Micromanaging, or Taking for Granted. Often triggered by Criticism, Withdrawal, Anger, or disappointment. The loop becomes “I must accommodate to stay loved” and “They always agree, so this must be fine.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I trading truth for acceptability?"},
  "PP-PERFECTIONISM": {"name":"Perfectionism","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Endless Preparation; Failure to Launch; Micromanaging; Productivity-Bound Worth; Rumination; Hostility Toward Criticism; Self-Sabotage.","Archetypal Role":"Creator — the work cannot be released until it matches the vision; Sage — knowledge must be complete before speaking; Ruler — the system cannot be allowed to contain error; Caregiver — care must prevent every possible problem; Lover — the relationship must feel perfect to feel safe; Warrior — performance must leave no opening for defeat.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full 27-field source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Define “ready” before the next revision begins, then release the work when it reaches that threshold.","Core Logic":"I am making flawlessness the price of being seen.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Delay; exhaustion; unfinished work; blocked feedback; resentment; diminished experimentation; inability to rest.","Core Fear":"Mistakes make me unworthy. If people see my limitations, I will lose respect or belonging. Approval disappears when performance falls. Being wrong is dangerous. I must be exceptional to matter.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It’s not ready yet.; I just need one more pass.; If it isn’t excellent, I’d rather not share it.; I can’t stop until every detail is right.; Once it’s flawless, I’ll feel better.; I should fix this before anyone sees it.","Protective Move":"Making flawlessness—or endless improvement—the condition for action, visibility, or rest.","Pattern ID":"PP-PERFECTIONISM","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary relief arrives as revision and control intensify.","Freer Expression":"Excellence without captivity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; devotion; craftsmanship; responsibility; high standards.","Observable Cues":"Revising beyond meaningful improvement; restarting instead of completing; delaying release, submission, or publication; preparing excessively before acting; rechecking small details repeatedly; redoing delegated work; reacting defensively to criticism.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"May trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Underfunctioning, Resentment, or Self-Erasure in others. Acknowledge the care and standard without joining the demand for flawlessness; ask what is truly unfinished, agree on a clear threshold, offer specific feedback, and avoid repeated reassurance that feeds the revision loop.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Belonging; avoids finality, limitation, ordinary fallibility, uncertainty about reception, shame, and dependence on feedback.","Canonical Name":"Perfectionism"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPerfectionism is the protective attempt to prevent shame, criticism, failure, or loss of worth by making flawlessness—or endless improvement—the condition for action, visibility, or rest.\n## Domain\nCompetence, Creation, and Performance\n## Related Patterns\nEndless Preparation; Failure to Launch; Micromanaging; Productivity-Bound Worth; Rumination; Hostility Toward Criticism\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am making flawlessness the price of being seen.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It’s not ready yet.\n- I just need one more pass.\n- If it isn’t excellent, I’d rather not share it.\n- I can’t stop until every detail is right.\n- Once it’s flawless, I’ll feel better.\n- I should fix this before anyone sees it.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\n- Unease when work is merely ready rather than flawless.\n- Relief from revising, but little relief from finishing.\n- A recurring thought that it is “almost ready.”\n- Feedback feels like a verdict rather than information.\n- Rest feels premature while any imperfection remains.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n- Revising beyond meaningful improvement.\n- Restarting instead of completing.\n- Delaying release, submission, or publication.\n- Preparing excessively before acting.\n- Rechecking small details repeatedly.\n- Redoing delegated work.\n- Reacting defensively to criticism.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Self-Esteem; Trust; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nEvaluation; visibility; deadlines; public release; comparison; unfamiliar tasks; criticism; situations in which control must be shared.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\n- Mistakes make me unworthy.\n- If people see my limitations, I will lose respect or belonging.\n- Approval disappears when performance falls.\n- Being wrong is dangerous.\n- I must be exceptional to matter.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFinality; limitation; ordinary fallibility; uncertainty about reception; shame; dependence on feedback.\n## Archetypal Expressions\n- Creator — the work cannot be released until it matches the vision.\n- Sage — knowledge must be complete before speaking.\n- Ruler — the system cannot be allowed to contain error.\n- Caregiver — care must prevent every possible problem.\n- Lover — the relationship must feel perfect to feel safe.\n- Warrior — performance must leave no opening for defeat.\n## Pattern Flow\nVisibility or evaluation approaches → competence or worth feels threatened → revision and control intensify → temporary relief arrives → completion and feedback are delayed → confidence becomes more dependent on perfection.\n## Often Appears With\nProductivity-Bound Worth; Micromanaging; Rumination; Endless Preparation; Self-Sabotage.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; devotion; craftsmanship; responsibility; high standards.\n## Current Cost\nDelay; exhaustion; unfinished work; blocked feedback; resentment; diminished experimentation; inability to rest.\n## Freer Expression\nExcellence without captivity.\n## One Act of Volition\nDefine “ready” before the next revision begins, then release the work when it reaches that threshold.\n## Mira Language\n“I notice that you are still revising even though you describe the work as functionally complete. One possible pattern is perfectionism—not simply caring about quality, but using quality to protect against evaluation. Does that fit, or is something practical still unfinished?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\n- What would imperfection expose that another revision cannot repair?\n- Is the work still improving, or is revision keeping it unjudged?\n- What would a truthful, ready version look like—not the flawless version?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nHigh standards, careful craftsmanship, safety checks, and legitimate quality control are not automatically perfectionism.\n## Evidence Threshold\nMira should see a repeated sequence involving excessive refinement, delayed exposure, distress around mistakes, or inability to stop—not a single careful revision.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nThank the part that is trying to prevent humiliation or failure, then define the real standard, the stopping point, and the acceptable risk before revising further. Replace reassurance through endless refinement with one bounded experiment in being seen.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAcknowledge the care and standard without joining the demand for flawlessness. Ask what is truly unfinished, agree on a clear threshold, offer specific feedback, and avoid vague criticism or repeated reassurance that feeds the revision loop.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where perfectionism delayed, controlled, criticized, or made another person feel perpetually inadequate. Name the specific impact without defending the standard, restore shared ownership where it was taken away, and agree on a concrete threshold or decision rule that prevents the same loop from governing the next interaction.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Underfunctioning, Resentment, or Self-Erasure in others. Often triggered by Criticism, Micromanaging, Comparison, Unreliable Follow-Through, or another person’s visible disappointment. The reinforcing story may become: “Nothing I do is good enough” on one side and “If I do not control the standard, everything will fail” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I making flawlessness the price of being seen?"},
  "PP-PERFORMANCE-OF-EMOTION-OR-ROLE": {"name":"Performance of an Emotion or Role","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Masking; Chameleon Identity; People-Pleasing; Role Entrapment; Emotional Inhibition; Image Management.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver performs calm or availability; Hero performs strength; Jester performs lightness; Lover performs devotion; Innocent performs purity or vulnerability.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied pattern, protective function, manifestations, and distinctions. Missing sections authored to the full canonical standard; spacing repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Pause before responding and name privately what you actually feel before choosing what to express.","Core Logic":"If I perform the expected self, I can remain legible, acceptable, and safe.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Self-alienation; emotional confusion; resentment; brittle intimacy; exhaustion; inaccurate agreements.","Core Fear":"My actual inner state may be unacceptable, dangerous, confusing, or disruptive to belonging.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should show the emotion they expect.; My real response may not be acceptable here.; I need to stay inside the role they know.; If I stop performing calm, everything may destabilize.; The expected version of me is safer than the truthful one.; I am not sure what I feel beneath the role.","Protective Move":"Performance of an Emotion or Role produces the expected feeling, persona, or relational position in place of contacting and expressing one’s actual inner experience.","Pattern ID":"PP-PERFORMANCE-OF-EMOTION-OR-ROLE","Short-Term Payoff":"Acceptance and predictability increase when the expected role is performed.","Freer Expression":"Intentional role flexibility anchored in self-contact.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Adaptability; professionalism; emotional regulation; social intelligence; ritual competence.","Observable Cues":"Displaying expected enthusiasm, calm, grief, confidence, innocence, competence, or vulnerability despite a different inner state; remaining in a familiar role after the feeling changes.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite honest difference without forcing immediate disclosure; respond to the actual stated capacity rather than the performed role. May trigger Suspicion, Testing the Bond, Emotional Distancing, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, predictability, approval, control, and self-esteem; avoids conflict, uncertainty, authentic desire, disappointment, and the risk of being known inaccurately or rejected accurately.","Canonical Name":"Performance of an Emotion or Role"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPerformance of an Emotion or Role is the protective production of an expected feeling, persona, or relational role in place of contacting and expressing one’s actual inner experience. It becomes protective when performance repeatedly replaces self-contact and authentic choice.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Emotion, and Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nMasking; Chameleon Identity; People-Pleasing; Role Entrapment; Emotional Inhibition\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I perform the expected self, I can remain legible, acceptable, and safe.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should show the emotion they expect.\n- My real response may not be acceptable here.\n- I need to stay inside the role they know.\n- If I stop performing calm, everything may destabilize.\n- The expected version of me is safer than the truthful one.\n- I am not sure what I feel beneath the role.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nEmotional blankness beneath competent display; uncertainty about genuine preference; relief when others accept the performance; fatigue after social or relational roles.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDisplaying expected enthusiasm, calm, grief, confidence, innocence, competence, or vulnerability despite a different inner state; remaining in a familiar role after the feeling changes.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; predictability; approval; control; self-esteem; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nSocial expectation; conflict; professional roles; family scripts; grief rituals; intimacy; situations where authentic emotion may disappoint others.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy real feeling is unsafe; belonging depends on emotional compliance; roles preserve order; unpredictability invites rejection.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAuthentic desire; uncertainty; disappointment; anger; numbness; conflict; separateness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver performs calm or availability; Hero performs strength; Jester performs lightness; Lover performs devotion; Innocent performs purity or vulnerability.\n## Pattern Flow\nExpected role becomes salient → belonging or predictability feels threatened → the expected emotion is performed → social friction decreases → self-contact weakens → future performance becomes more necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nMasking; People-Pleasing; Chameleon Identity; Role Entrapment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAdaptability; professionalism; emotional regulation; social intelligence; ritual competence.\n## Current Cost\nSelf-alienation; emotional confusion; resentment; brittle intimacy; exhaustion; inaccurate agreements.\n## Freer Expression\nIntentional role flexibility anchored in self-contact.\n## One Act of Volition\nPause before responding and name privately what you actually feel before choosing what to express.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be meeting a real expectation skillfully. I also wonder whether the role has replaced contact with your actual inner response.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you feel before the expected emotion appears? What would happen if your response were different? Is this chosen privacy, regulation, or self-replacement?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nProfessionalism, ritual, emotional regulation, privacy, and deliberate role flexibility are not automatically protective performance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern in which expected emotional display overrides self-contact and constrains authentic choice across contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nContact the inner state first, then choose expression consciously rather than automatically inhabiting the role.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite honest difference without punishing it and do not demand immediate disclosure where safety is uncertain.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where performed emotion created a false agreement, misleading intimacy, or hidden resentment; clarify the actual feeling and current capacity.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Testing the Bond, Emotional Distancing, or Resentment. The loop becomes “I must perform to stay” versus “I cannot tell what is real.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I choosing a role, and where has the role begun choosing me?"},
  "PP-PERMANENT-OPTIONALITY": {"name":"Permanent Optionality","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Commitment Avoidance; Strategic Ambiguity; Indecision; Preemptive Detachment; Risk Avoidance; Decision Delegation.","Archetypal Role":"Explorer keeps every horizon open; Lover preserves multiple possible bonds; Creator refuses final form; Rebel equates closure with captivity.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied pattern, protective function, manifestations, and distinctions. Missing sections authored to full canonical standard; spacing repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Close one low-risk option deliberately and grieve what is excluded rather than preserving it indefinitely.","Core Logic":"If nothing becomes final, no choice can fully claim or disappoint me.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Stalled development; mistrust; shallow investment; indecision; fragmented identity; lost opportunities.","Core Fear":"Choosing one path will erase freedom, identity, alternatives, or protection from regret.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need every door to remain open.; Closing one option feels like losing part of myself.; I can decide later even though I already have enough information.; A backup plan will keep me from being trapped.; Finality feels more dangerous than uncertainty.; I want the benefits of commitment without giving up alternatives.","Protective Move":"Permanent Optionality keeps choices, relationships, identities, or commitments indefinitely reversible so that no path can fully claim the self.","Pattern ID":"PP-PERMANENT-OPTIONALITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Relief and freedom return when alternatives remain open.","Freer Expression":"Chosen commitment with revisable but honest boundaries.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Flexibility; imagination; discernment; responsiveness; resistance to premature closure.","Observable Cues":"Refusing to close alternatives; maintaining backup relationships or plans; reopening settled choices; preserving reversible identities after clarity exists.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask for present clarity without coercion and state what level of commitment or closure is necessary for your own participation. May trigger Testing the Bond, Suspicion, Interrogative Control, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects autonomy, identity, possibility, and safety; avoids grief, limitation, accountability, dependence, regret, and being changed by commitment.","Canonical Name":"Permanent Optionality"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPermanent Optionality is the protective keeping of choices, relationships, identities, or commitments indefinitely reversible so that no path can fully claim the self. It persists after adequate clarity because finality itself feels unsafe.\n## Domain\nAutonomy, Choice, and Identity\n## Related Patterns\nCommitment Avoidance; Strategic Ambiguity; Indecision; Preemptive Detachment; Risk Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf nothing becomes final, no choice can fully claim or disappoint me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need every door to remain open.\n- Closing one option feels like losing part of myself.\n- I can decide later even though I already have enough information.\n- A backup plan will keep me from being trapped.\n- Finality feels more dangerous than uncertainty.\n- I want the benefits of commitment without giving up alternatives.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief from delay; fixation on excluded alternatives; anxiety after closure; attraction to backup plans; identity diffusion when asked to choose.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRefusing to close alternatives; maintaining backup relationships or plans; reopening settled choices; preserving reversible identities after clarity exists.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; identity; possibility; safety; self-determination.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCommitment; exclusivity; deadlines; irreversible choices; role definition; endings; grief over alternatives.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nCommitment becomes captivity; choice destroys identity; regret is unbearable; flexibility is the only safety.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; limitation; responsibility; dependence; regret; ordinary tradeoffs.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nExplorer keeps every horizon open; Lover preserves multiple possible bonds; Creator refuses final form; Rebel equates closure with captivity.\n## Pattern Flow\nA choice approaches closure → autonomy or possibility feels threatened → alternatives are preserved → relief returns → investment remains partial → options multiply and closure becomes harder.\n## Often Appears With\nCommitment Avoidance; Strategic Ambiguity; Indecision; Risk Avoidance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nFlexibility; imagination; discernment; responsiveness; resistance to premature closure.\n## Current Cost\nStalled development; mistrust; shallow investment; indecision; fragmented identity; lost opportunities.\n## Freer Expression\nChosen commitment with revisable but honest boundaries.\n## One Act of Volition\nClose one low-risk option deliberately and grieve what is excluded rather than preserving it indefinitely.\n## Mira Language\n“You may still be exploring. I also notice that keeping every option alive restores relief even after clarity is available. Is the uncertainty about the choice, or about finality itself?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does closure seem to take from you? Which option is being kept alive only to prevent grief? What bounded review point would preserve agency without indefinite ambiguity?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nExploration, thoughtful pacing, reversible trials, and genuine uncertainty are not Permanent Optionality.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated preservation of alternatives after adequate information, especially when closure consistently triggers anxiety and reopening.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the autonomy need, choose a bounded commitment, and allow grief for excluded possibilities.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk for present clarity without coercion and state what level of commitment or closure is necessary for your own participation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where indefinite optionality kept others attached or prevented informed planning; clarify current choice and release options that cannot ethically remain open.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Testing the Bond, Suspicion, Interrogative Control, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “I must preserve freedom” versus “I cannot feel secure while everything remains provisional.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhich possibility am I keeping alive because grieving it feels harder than choosing?"},
  "PP-PERSONALIZATION": {"name":"Personalization","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Mind Reading; Self-Blame; Grandiosity; Emotional Reasoning; Hypervigilance; Fusion; Over-Apologizing.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — assumes responsibility for everyone’s state. Lover — interprets distance as personal rejection. Ruler — sees system failures as personal failure. Innocent — blames self to preserve others’ goodness. Sage — overanalyzes personal causation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Ask what evidence shows personal responsibility before apologizing or fixing.","Core Logic":"If something changed, it must be because of me.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Chronic guilt; distorted responsibility; exhaustion; self-erasure; intrusive repair attempts.","Core Fear":"I am responsible for keeping everyone okay; if something is wrong, I caused it; other people’s reactions determine my safety.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Something changed, so I must have caused it.; Their mood is probably about me.; I should apologize before I even know what happened.; If everyone isn’t okay, I’ve failed.; I need to fix this before they reassure me.; Their silence means I did something wrong.","Protective Move":"Personalization interprets events, moods, or outcomes as primarily about oneself, protecting against uncertainty by locating a clear cause in personal responsibility or rejection.","Pattern ID":"PP-PERSONALIZATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Action or apology restores temporary control when the self becomes the presumed cause.","Freer Expression":"Responsibility with boundaries.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Accountability; empathy; responsiveness; conscientiousness.","Observable Cues":"Apologizing without evidence; assuming another’s silence is about oneself; taking broad events personally; overcorrecting to repair imagined harm.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify what is and is not about them; do not reward unnecessary apology; state needs directly. May trigger Reassurance Fatigue, Withdrawal, Irritation, or Underfunctioning.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, Competence, and Self-Esteem; avoids uncertainty, helplessness, others’ autonomy, randomness, and limits of control.","Canonical Name":"Personalization"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPersonalization interprets events, moods, or outcomes as primarily about oneself, protecting against uncertainty by locating a clear cause in personal responsibility or rejection.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nMind Reading; Self-Blame; Grandiosity; Emotional Reasoning; Hypervigilance\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf something changed, it must be because of me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Something changed, so I must have caused it.\n- Their mood is probably about me.\n- I should apologize before I even know what happened.\n- If everyone isn’t okay, I’ve failed.\n- I need to fix this before they reassure me.\n- Their silence means I did something wrong.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nImmediate self-blame; scanning others’ moods for evidence; feeling responsible for outcomes outside one’s control; interpreting neutrality as rejection.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nApologizing without evidence; assuming another’s silence is about oneself; taking broad events personally; overcorrecting to repair imagined harm.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Competence; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nMood changes; silence; conflict; failure; ambiguous feedback; group tension.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am responsible for keeping everyone okay. If something is wrong, I caused it. Other people’s reactions determine my safety.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; helplessness; others’ autonomy; randomness; limits of control.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — assumes responsibility for everyone’s state. Lover — interprets distance as personal rejection. Ruler — sees system failures as personal failure. Innocent — blames self to preserve others’ goodness. Sage — overanalyzes personal causation.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguous change occurs → belonging or competence feels threatened → self becomes the presumed cause → action or apology restores temporary control → boundaries blur → vigilance increases.\n## Often Appears With\nMind Reading; Fusion; Over-Apologizing; Hypervigilance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAccountability; empathy; responsiveness; conscientiousness.\n## Current Cost\nChronic guilt; distorted responsibility; exhaustion; self-erasure; intrusive repair attempts.\n## Freer Expression\nResponsibility with boundaries.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk what evidence shows personal responsibility before apologizing or fixing.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be taking responsibility because uncertainty feels harder. What belongs to you, and what may belong to them or the situation?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence points to you? What else could explain this? What is yours to own—and not yours?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGenuine accountability and awareness of impact are not personalization.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated assumption of personal causation without sufficient evidence across situations.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate influence from total responsibility; ask rather than infer; tolerate another person having an independent emotional life.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify what is and is not about them; do not reward unnecessary apology; state needs directly.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where self-centered interpretation displaced the other person’s actual experience or created pressure to reassure. Repair restores curiosity and role clarity.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Reassurance Fatigue, Withdrawal, Irritation, or Underfunctioning. Often triggered by Silence, Criticism, ambiguity, or Fusion. The loop becomes “Everything is my fault” versus “I must manage your guilt too.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I making about me because uncertainty feels harder?"},
  "PP-PESSIMISM-AS-PREPARATION": {"name":"Pessimism as Preparation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Anticipatory Defeat; Catastrophizing; Cynicism; Hypervigilance; Rumination; Despair as Certainty.","Archetypal Role":"Sage forecasts failure; Warrior braces for betrayal; Orphan expects loss; Ruler controls uncertainty through negative prediction.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied pattern, protective function, manifestations, and distinctions. Missing sections authored to full canonical standard; spacing repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Name the most likely outcome, the worst plausible outcome, and one positive possibility before deciding how to prepare.","Core Logic":"If I expect the worst, it may hurt less and I will not be caught unprepared.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Narrowed perception; reduced investment; chronic anxiety; missed opportunity; self-confirming withdrawal.","Core Fear":"Hope will leave me exposed, foolish, or unprepared for disappointment.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should expect the worst so it cannot surprise me.; Hope will only make the fall harder.; Positive signs are probably misleading.; If I imagine every failure, I will be ready.; It is safer to invest less before disappointment arrives.; Preparing means assuming things will go badly.","Protective Move":"Pessimism as Preparation rehearses disappointment, failure, betrayal, or loss as though expecting the worst will reduce its impact or prevent surprise.","Pattern ID":"PP-PESSIMISM-AS-PREPARATION","Short-Term Payoff":"A sense of preparedness and control rises when negative outcomes are foregrounded.","Freer Expression":"Realistic preparation that leaves room for multiple outcomes.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Foresight; realism; contingency awareness; memory of prior harm; risk sensitivity.","Observable Cues":"Discounting positive evidence; repeatedly naming what will go wrong; withholding investment; treating hope as naïveté; rehearsing betrayal before evidence.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Acknowledge realistic risks without joining certainty about failure; ask what preparation supports action rather than withdrawal. May trigger Positivity Enforcement, Rescuing, Frustration, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, predictability, dignity, trust, and self-esteem; avoids hope, uncertainty, surprise, grief, dependence, and possible humiliation.","Canonical Name":"Pessimism as Preparation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPessimism as Preparation is the protective rehearsal of disappointment, failure, betrayal, or loss as though expecting the worst will reduce its impact or prevent being caught unprepared. It differs from sound risk assessment because negative anticipation narrows perception and protects against hope rather than supporting action.\n## Domain\nThreat Anticipation, Hope, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nAnticipatory Defeat; Catastrophizing; Cynicism; Hypervigilance; Rumination\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I expect the worst, it may hurt less and I will not be caught unprepared.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should expect the worst so it cannot surprise me.\n- Hope will only make the fall harder.\n- Positive signs are probably misleading.\n- If I imagine every failure, I will be ready.\n- It is safer to invest less before disappointment arrives.\n- Preparing means assuming things will go badly.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief after naming the worst case; distrust of positive evidence; tension around hope; repeated mental rehearsal of loss; irritation at optimism.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDiscounting positive evidence; repeatedly naming what will go wrong; withholding investment; treating hope as naïveté; rehearsing betrayal before evidence.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; predictability; dignity; trust; self-esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUncertainty; meaningful opportunity; intimacy; previous disappointment; waiting; dependence on others; positive change.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nHope leads to humiliation; surprise is dangerous; disappointment is easier if predicted; trust invites betrayal.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHope; grief; uncertainty; suspense; dependence; vulnerability.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage forecasts failure; Warrior braces for betrayal; Orphan expects loss; Ruler controls uncertainty through negative prediction.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertain possibility appears → hope feels dangerous → negative outcomes are rehearsed → control and preparedness rise temporarily → investment and openness decrease → limited experience appears to confirm pessimism.\n## Often Appears With\nCatastrophizing; Cynicism; Hypervigilance; Anticipatory Defeat.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nForesight; realism; contingency awareness; memory of prior harm; risk sensitivity.\n## Current Cost\nNarrowed perception; reduced investment; chronic anxiety; missed opportunity; self-confirming withdrawal.\n## Freer Expression\nRealistic preparation that leaves room for multiple outcomes.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the most likely outcome, the worst plausible outcome, and one positive possibility before deciding how to prepare.\n## Mira Language\n“Your caution may be trying to protect you from surprise. Is the forecasting helping you prepare, or making disappointment feel certain before reality answers?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence supports the negative prediction? What would preparation look like without surrendering hope? What positive evidence are you discounting?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nRisk assessment, contingency planning, and realism in genuinely dangerous or unstable conditions are not Pessimism as Preparation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of negative forecasting that reduces investment or openness beyond what evidence and planning require.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate risk planning from emotional bracing; prepare for difficulty while preserving attention to new evidence and possible good outcomes.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAcknowledge realistic risks without forcing optimism; ask what concrete preparation supports action rather than withdrawal.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where repeated negative forecasting discouraged shared effort, dismissed another’s hope, or became a reason not to participate; restore proportionate planning.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Positivity Enforcement, Rescuing, Frustration, or Emotional Distancing. The loop becomes “I must prepare you for failure” versus “I must force you to hope.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I preparing wisely, and where am I using pessimism to avoid the risk of hope?"},
  "PP-PLAUSIBLE-DENIABILITY": {"name":"Plausible Deniability","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Strategic Ambiguity; Selective Accountability; Deflection; Image Management; Emotional Withholding; Passive Aggression.","Archetypal Role":"Trickster obscures intention; Diplomat preserves every exit; Ruler delegates harm indirectly; Lover maintains attachment without commitment.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source requires contextual safety screening but does not provide one explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"State the intended meaning, request, or commitment in language you would accept being quoted later.","Core Logic":"I want the effect without being clearly answerable for the intention or promise.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Confusion; mistrust; unrepairable impact; manipulation; chronic uncertainty.","Core Fear":"Clarity makes me vulnerable; survival requires saying enough to influence but not enough to be held responsible.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to leave myself an escape route.; I can imply the meaning without stating it directly.; The wording should let me deny the intention later.; I want the effect without the accountability.; A vague commitment keeps every option open.; Technical innocence matters more than how the message will land.","Protective Move":"Plausible Deniability is the protective maintenance of enough ambiguity around intention, commitment, message, or action to preserve influence while avoiding clear accountability.","Pattern ID":"PP-PLAUSIBLE-DENIABILITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Influence occurs with reduced exposure when ambiguity is preserved.","Freer Expression":"Nuance with accountable clarity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Nuance, diplomacy, privacy, strategic thought, and sensitivity to consequence.","Observable Cues":"Hints, deniable insults, indirect instructions, vague commitments, coded messages, “I never said that,” exploiting literal wording, avoiding written clarity.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask for clarification, document agreements when appropriate, respond to observable impact, and do not argue endlessly over inaccessible intent. May trigger Compulsive Checking, Suspicion, Overexplaining, Hostility Toward Criticism, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, image, control, autonomy, belonging, competence, and status; avoids ownership, conflict, exposure, honest refusal, consequence, and loss of approval.","Canonical Name":"Plausible Deniability"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPlausible Deniability is the protective maintenance of enough ambiguity around intention, commitment, message, or action to preserve influence while avoiding clear accountability.\n## Domain\nCommunication, Accountability, and Control\n## Related Patterns\nStrategic Ambiguity; Selective Accountability; Deflection; Image Management; Emotional Withholding; Passive Aggression\n## Recognition Sentence\nI want the effect without being clearly answerable for the intention or promise.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to leave myself an escape route.\n- I can imply the meaning without stating it directly.\n- The wording should let me deny the intention later.\n- I want the effect without the accountability.\n- A vague commitment keeps every option open.\n- Technical innocence matters more than how the message will land.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDesire to leave an escape route; fear of being pinned down; relief when language can support multiple stories; concern with technical innocence more than impact.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nHints, deniable insults, indirect instructions, vague commitments, coded messages, “I never said that,” exploiting literal wording, avoiding written clarity.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; image; control; autonomy; belonging; competence; status.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAccountability; risk of rejection; controversial intent; competing audiences; fear of consequence.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nClarity makes me vulnerable; survival requires saying enough to influence but not enough to be held responsible.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nOwnership; conflict; exposure; honest refusal; consequence; loss of approval.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nTrickster obscures intention; Diplomat preserves every exit; Ruler delegates harm indirectly; Lover maintains attachment without commitment.\n## Pattern Flow\nDesired effect conflicts with accountability → ambiguity is created → influence occurs with reduced exposure → impact is denied through wording → trust deteriorates.\n## Often Appears With\nStrategic Ambiguity; Deflection; Selective Accountability; Image Management; Passive Aggression.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nNuance, diplomacy, privacy, strategic thought, and sensitivity to consequence.\n## Current Cost\nConfusion; mistrust; unrepairable impact; manipulation; chronic uncertainty.\n## Freer Expression\nNuance with accountable clarity.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the intended meaning, request, or commitment in language you would accept being quoted later.\n## Mira Language\n“The wording leaves several exits. Is that because the situation truly requires nuance, or because clarity would make you accountable for the intended effect?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you want them to understand? What would you say if you could not later deny the implication? What impact are you technically distancing yourself from?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nPrivacy, diplomacy, confidentiality, uncertainty, and protection under unsafe power conditions may require ambiguity. Safety screening is essential.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated ambiguity that reliably creates an effect while preserving denial of intent, commitment, or responsibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIdentify the valid risk, choose appropriate privacy or boundaries, and communicate as clearly as safety permits without manufacturing deniability.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk for clarification, document agreements when appropriate, respond to observable impact, and do not argue endlessly over inaccessible intent.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName both the ambiguous communication and its foreseeable effect, stop hiding behind literal wording, clarify the actual position, and accept consequences.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Compulsive Checking, Suspicion, Overexplaining, Hostility Toward Criticism, or Emotional Distancing. Stories become “I must never be pinned down” and “I can never trust what you mean.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I preserving influence by keeping accountability blurry?"},
  "PP-POSITIVITY-ENFORCEMENT": {"name":"Positivity Enforcement","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Spiritual Bypassing; Minimizing; Denial; Meaning Inflation; Emotional Inhibition; Image Management.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent—hope becomes denial; Mystic—suffering is spiritualized prematurely; Caregiver—comfort erases truth; Ruler—acceptable emotion is controlled; Magician—transformation is demanded before mourning.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated with spacing corruption repaired; Trigger Phrases newly drafted. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no single explicit controlled designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"Before reframing, name one painful fact without correcting, explaining, or redeeming it.","Core Logic":"I am requiring hope before truth has been fully allowed.","Primary Domain":"Spiritual","Long-Term Cost":"Invalidation; loneliness; delayed grief; poor risk recognition; suppressed anger; brittle hope; weakened trust.","Core Fear":"Pain will overwhelm us; negativity causes bad outcomes; love requires pleasantness; despair is dangerous; my worth depends on being hopeful or spiritually mature.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"We need to find the positive immediately.; Staying with the pain will only make it worse.; Anger and grief are too dangerous to leave unresolved.; Everything happens for a reason, so this should feel meaningful.; I need the conversation to become hopeful again.; Their difficult truth is threatening the emotional order I depend on.","Protective Move":"Positivity Enforcement is the protective insistence that painful, critical, ambivalent, or inconvenient realities be reframed positively so uncertainty, grief, conflict, shame, or disillusionment do not have to be fully encountered.","Pattern ID":"PP-POSITIVITY-ENFORCEMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary hope or order returns when positive reframing is imposed.","Freer Expression":"Hope spacious enough to include truth.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Hope; meaning-making; resilience; encouragement; faith.","Observable Cues":"“Look on the bright side”; insisting everything happens for a reason; correcting “negative” language; discouraging grief or anger; treating boundaries as pessimism; rewarding only uplifting disclosures.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Say what kind of response is needed: acknowledgment, lament, practical help, or hope. Decline imposed reframing and protect space for grief, anger, or uncertainty. May trigger Emotional Withholding, Cynicism, Anger as Armor, Withdrawal, or Confessional Overexposure.","Emotional Function":"Protects meaning and purpose, safety, trust and predictability, belonging, hope, and self-esteem; avoids grief, rage, moral injury, limitation, injustice, uncertainty, disappointment, and loss of faith or meaning.","Canonical Name":"Positivity Enforcement"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPositivity Enforcement is the protective insistence that painful, critical, ambivalent, or inconvenient realities be reframed positively so uncertainty, grief, conflict, shame, or disillusionment do not have to be fully encountered.\n## Domain\nMeaning, Emotion, and Reality Contact\n## Related Patterns\nSpiritual Bypassing; Minimizing; Denial; Meaning Inflation; Emotional Inhibition; Image Management\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am requiring hope before truth has been fully allowed.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- We need to find the positive immediately.\n- Staying with the pain will only make it worse.\n- Anger and grief are too dangerous to leave unresolved.\n- Everything happens for a reason, so this should feel meaningful.\n- I need the conversation to become hopeful again.\n- Their difficult truth is threatening the emotional order I depend on.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnxiety around anger or grief; pressure to find the lesson immediately; fear that acknowledging pain will make it permanent; discomfort with criticism; urgency to restore an uplifting tone.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n“Look on the bright side”; insisting everything happens for a reason; correcting “negative” language; discouraging grief or anger; treating boundaries as pessimism; rewarding only uplifting disclosures.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nMeaning and purpose; safety; trust and predictability; belonging; hope; self-esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nGrief; criticism; injustice; uncertainty; failure; anger; disillusionment; prolonged suffering; relational rupture.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nPain will overwhelm us; negativity causes bad outcomes; love requires pleasantness; despair is dangerous; my worth depends on being hopeful or spiritually mature.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; rage; moral injury; limitation; injustice; uncertainty; disappointment; loss of faith or meaning.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent—hope becomes denial; Mystic—suffering is spiritualized prematurely; Caregiver—comfort erases truth; Ruler—acceptable emotion is controlled; Magician—transformation is demanded before mourning.\n## Pattern Flow\nPainful reality appears → meaning or emotional safety feels threatened → positive reframing is imposed → temporary hope or order returns → pain goes underground → trust and reality contact weaken.\n## Often Appears With\nSpiritual Bypassing; Minimizing; Denial; Image Management; Emotional Inhibition.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHope; meaning-making; resilience; encouragement; faith.\n## Current Cost\nInvalidation; loneliness; delayed grief; poor risk recognition; suppressed anger; brittle hope; weakened trust.\n## Freer Expression\nHope spacious enough to include truth.\n## One Act of Volition\nBefore reframing, name one painful fact without correcting, explaining, or redeeming it.\n## Mira Language\n“Hope may matter here. I also wonder whether it is arriving before the pain has been fully named. Can both truth and hope remain in the room?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feeling becomes dangerous if it is not transformed immediately? What truth needs acknowledgment before meaning-making? Is the positive frame invited or imposed?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGenuine optimism, gratitude, faith, encouragement, and chosen reframing are not automatically Positivity Enforcement. Cultural and religious meanings require consent and context.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated pressure to replace or suppress painful reality with positivity, especially after the affected person resists—not a single hopeful comment.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nLet hope wait beside pain rather than stand on top of it. Name the difficult reality, tolerate unresolved emotion, and offer meaning only when it does not erase impact or agency.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nSay what kind of response is needed: acknowledgment, lament, practical help, or hope. Decline imposed reframing and protect space for grief, anger, or uncertainty.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where positivity invalidated pain or discouraged truth. Repeat back what was missed, apologize without reframing the apology, and allow the affected person to define whether and when hope feels supportive.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Withholding, Cynicism, Anger as Armor, Withdrawal, or Confessional Overexposure. Often triggered by grief, criticism, despair, or another person’s sustained distress. The loop may become: “My pain is unacceptable” and “Your pain will pull us under.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I asking hope to erase what it should accompany?"},
  "PP-POSSESSIVENESS": {"name":"Possessiveness","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Clinging; Testing the Bond; Fusion; Hypervigilance; Dominance; Boundary Collapse; Relationship-Bound Worth; Anger as Armor.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — devotion becomes ownership. Ruler — stewardship becomes territorial control. Caregiver — concern becomes entitlement to access. Warrior — loyalty becomes enforced allegiance. Innocent — safety depends on guaranteed exclusivity.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the source explicitly addresses surveillance, isolation, threats, stalking, intimidation, and restrictions on autonomy.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Name the fear directly and ask for one specific, negotiable reassurance instead of restricting another person’s freedom.","Core Logic":"I am trying to make belonging secure by limiting another person’s freedom.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Constriction; mistrust; conflict; secrecy; resentment; reduced autonomy; coercive dynamics when severe.","Core Fear":"Love is scarce; if I am not first, I will be abandoned; people leave when they are free to choose; I must secure my place before someone replaces me.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If I’m not first, I may be replaced.; I need to know where they are and who they’re with.; Their independence feels like disloyalty.; I should secure exclusivity before someone else takes my place.; Chosen loyalty doesn’t feel safe enough unless I can verify it.; If I loosen control, the bond may disappear.","Protective Move":"Possessiveness is the protective attempt to secure a valued person, role, resource, or bond by treating access, loyalty, attention, or belonging as something that must be controlled rather than freely chosen.","Pattern ID":"PP-POSSESSIVENESS","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary reassurance arrives when access, loyalty, or exclusivity is tightened.","Freer Expression":"Devotion without ownership.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Loyalty; devotion; protectiveness; commitment; sensitivity to relational change.","Observable Cues":"Monitoring contact, whereabouts, or affiliations; pressuring for exclusivity beyond the agreement; treating independent relationships as betrayal; restricting access; loyalty tests; framing autonomy as disloyalty.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify agreements and boundaries without rewarding surveillance or coercion. Offer reassurance only where authentic, preserve autonomy, and prioritize safety if control escalates. May trigger Secrecy, Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, Retaliation, or Withdrawing Before Being Left.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, Self-Esteem, Security, and Significance; avoids grief, uncertainty, separateness, non-exclusivity, ordinary jealousy, and the limits of control.","Canonical Name":"Possessiveness"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPossessiveness is the protective attempt to secure a valued person, role, resource, or bond by treating access, loyalty, attention, or belonging as something that must be controlled rather than freely chosen.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Scarcity, and Relational Security\n## Related Patterns\nClinging; Testing the Bond; Fusion; Hypervigilance; Dominance; Boundary Collapse; Relationship-Bound Worth\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am trying to make belonging secure by limiting another person’s freedom.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If I’m not first, I may be replaced.\n- I need to know where they are and who they’re with.\n- Their independence feels like disloyalty.\n- I should secure exclusivity before someone else takes my place.\n- Chosen loyalty doesn’t feel safe enough unless I can verify it.\n- If I loosen control, the bond may disappear.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nOther people’s independent choices feel like evidence of displacement. Attention given elsewhere feels like something taken from you. Relief comes from exclusivity, access, or control. Ambiguity about loyalty feels intolerable. You feel entitled to information, proximity, or priority that has not been mutually agreed.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nMonitoring contact, whereabouts, or affiliations. Pressuring for exclusivity beyond the actual agreement. Treating independent relationships as betrayal. Restricting access to shared people, roles, or resources. Making loyalty tests or demanding proof of priority. Framing another person’s autonomy as disloyalty.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Self-Esteem; Security; Significance.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPerceived rivals; divided attention; ambiguous commitment; change in closeness; comparison; exclusion; independent plans; prior betrayal.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove is scarce. If I am not first, I will be abandoned. People leave when they are free to choose. I must secure my place before someone replaces me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; uncertainty; separateness; non-exclusivity; ordinary jealousy; the limits of control.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — devotion becomes ownership. Ruler — stewardship becomes territorial control. Caregiver — concern becomes entitlement to access. Warrior — loyalty becomes enforced allegiance. Innocent — safety depends on guaranteed exclusivity.\n## Pattern Flow\nA valued bond feels uncertain → belonging or significance feels threatened → access, loyalty, or exclusivity is tightened → temporary reassurance arrives → autonomy and trust erode → the bond becomes more fragile and surveillance increases.\n## Often Appears With\nClinging; Testing the Bond; Hypervigilance; Relationship-Bound Worth; Dominance; Anger as Armor.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nLoyalty; devotion; protectiveness; commitment; sensitivity to relational change.\n## Current Cost\nConstriction; mistrust; conflict; secrecy; resentment; reduced autonomy; coercive dynamics when severe.\n## Freer Expression\nDevotion without ownership.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the fear directly and ask for one specific, negotiable reassurance instead of restricting another person’s freedom.\n## Mira Language\n“It sounds as though uncertainty about your place is becoming a reason to control access or loyalty. Possessiveness may be trying to protect belonging. What reassurance is actually needed, and what freedom still belongs to the other person?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you fear another person’s freedom will reveal? Which expectation is mutually agreed, and which one are you trying to enforce alone? What would chosen loyalty look like here?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCommitment, monogamy, confidentiality, shared-property agreements, and clearly negotiated boundaries are not possessiveness. Mira must distinguish mutual agreements from unilateral control and must not frame coercion as an equal two-person loop.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated attempts to restrict, monitor, claim, or control another person’s legitimate autonomy—not a single jealous feeling or request for clarity.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nAcknowledge the fear of replacement or loss, separate feeling from entitlement, identify the actual agreement, and make a direct request that leaves room for a genuine no.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify agreements and boundaries without rewarding surveillance or coercion. Offer reassurance only where authentic, preserve autonomy, and prioritize safety if control escalates into intimidation, isolation, threats, or stalking.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where control, monitoring, or ownership language violated autonomy or trust. Stop the behavior, return access and choice, accept boundaries without retaliation, and demonstrate change through consistent respect rather than demands for immediate reassurance.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Secrecy, Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, Retaliation, or Withdrawing Before Being Left. Often triggered by Hyper-Independence, Testing the Bond, inconsistent follow-through, or real betrayal. The reinforcing story may become: “I must hide to remain free” on one side and “If I do not tighten control, I will be replaced” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I confusing chosen loyalty with ownership?"},
  "PP-POWER-HOARDING": {"name":"Power Hoarding","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Dominance; Information Control; Gatekeeping; Indispensability; Micromanaging; Status Guarding.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler centralizes authority; Sage guards knowledge; Caregiver preserves dependence; Warrior controls access; Magician retains exclusive influence.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective function, common expressions, Trigger Phrases, and distinctions. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; source Trigger Phrases were retained and supplemented to six, so status is Drafted pending review. Spacing repaired. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the mechanism explicitly concentrates authority, access, knowledge, and decision rights in ways that may constrain others’ agency.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Transfer one real decision right together with the access, information, and authority required to exercise it.","Core Logic":"If I keep authority, access, and knowledge centralized, I can remain safe and necessary.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Bottlenecks; dependency; resentment; poor succession; suppressed competence; coercive systems.","Core Fear":"Sharing power will make me replaceable, vulnerable, challenged, or unable to prevent failure.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It is safer if I keep final control.; They are not ready for this authority.; Everything will fall apart if I step back.; Sharing access will make me replaceable.; I need to remain the person everyone must go through.; I cannot risk others making decisions without me.","Protective Move":"Power Hoarding retains authority, access, decisions, knowledge, or resources beyond what is necessary in order to remain central, protected, or difficult to challenge.","Pattern ID":"PP-POWER-HOARDING","Short-Term Payoff":"Security and leverage increase when power remains concentrated.","Freer Expression":"Shared power with clear accountability.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Stewardship; responsibility; risk awareness; institutional memory; decisive leadership.","Observable Cues":"Centralizing approvals; withholding authority or access; resisting succession; keeping critical knowledge or relationships personally controlled; reclaiming delegated decisions.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Request transparent decision rights, shared access, documentation, and meaningful delegation; set limits where consent or autonomy is constrained. May trigger Appeasement, Underfunctioning, Resentment, Rebellion, or Information Control.","Emotional Function":"Protects control, status, safety, competence, autonomy, and belonging; avoids dependence, displacement, scrutiny, uncertainty, and the risk of others choosing differently.","Canonical Name":"Power Hoarding"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPower Hoarding is the protective retention of authority, access, decisions, knowledge, or resources beyond what is necessary in order to remain central, protected, or difficult to challenge. It differs from responsible stewardship because power remains concentrated even when sharing it would be safe and functional.\n## Domain\nPower, Control, and Organizational Relationship\n## Related Patterns\nDominance; Information Control; Gatekeeping; Indispensability; Micromanaging\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I keep authority, access, and knowledge centralized, I can remain safe and necessary.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It is safer if I keep final control.\n- They are not ready for this authority.\n- Everything will fall apart if I step back.\n- Sharing access will make me replaceable.\n- I need to remain the person everyone must go through.\n- I cannot risk others making decisions without me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnxiety when others gain autonomy; relief when decisions return to you; fear of succession; distrust of shared authority; resentment paired with reluctance to delegate.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nCentralizing approvals; withholding authority or access; resisting succession; keeping critical knowledge or relationships personally controlled; reclaiming delegated decisions.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nControl; status; safety; competence; autonomy; belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDelegation; role transition; succession planning; another person’s competence; scrutiny; decentralization; loss of exclusive access.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nPower prevents vulnerability; being replaceable means being discarded; others cannot be trusted; loss of control invites chaos or humiliation.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependence; uncertainty; replaceability; shared ownership; accountability; grief over changing roles.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler centralizes authority; Sage guards knowledge; Caregiver preserves dependence; Warrior controls access; Magician retains exclusive influence.\n## Pattern Flow\nShared power or succession approaches → safety, status, or necessity feels threatened → authority and access are re-centralized → security rises temporarily → others remain dependent or disengage → mistrust and control needs deepen.\n## Often Appears With\nInformation Control; Gatekeeping; Indispensability; Micromanaging; Status Guarding.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nStewardship; responsibility; risk awareness; institutional memory; decisive leadership.\n## Current Cost\nBottlenecks; dependency; resentment; poor succession; suppressed competence; coercive systems.\n## Freer Expression\nShared power with clear accountability.\n## One Act of Volition\nTransfer one real decision right together with the access, information, and authority required to exercise it.\n## Mira Language\n“You may carry real responsibility. I also notice that sharing authority feels threatening even where it may be safe. What do you fear would happen to your role or security?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat power is actually required by your responsibility? Which access could be shared safely? Are you protecting the system, or protecting your centrality?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nTemporary command, fiduciary duty, confidentiality, emergency leadership, and clearly assigned authority are not Power Hoarding.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of retaining consequential authority, access, knowledge, or resources after safe transfer or shared ownership is reasonably available.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate responsibility from exclusivity; build safeguards, documentation, and shared competence rather than preserving dependence.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRequest transparent decision rights, shared access, documentation, and meaningful delegation; protect autonomy when concentration becomes coercive.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where access, voice, or authority was unnecessarily restricted; restore decision rights, information, and credit; support others acting without interference.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Underfunctioning, Resentment, Rebellion, or Information Control. The loop becomes “Only I can be trusted” versus “There is no meaningful room for me to act.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat power am I retaining for the role, and what power am I retaining to feel secure?"},
  "PP-PREEMPTIVE-ACCUSATION": {"name":"Preemptive Accusation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Suspicion; Mind Reading; Projection; Hypervigilance; Blame Shifting; Adversarial Framing; Compulsive Checking; Interrogative Control; Emotional Reasoning; Catastrophizing; Rejection Sensitivity.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior strikes first; Sage claims motive as knowledge; Ruler conducts accusation as control; Lover converts fear into charges.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source protects documented abuse reporting and credible evidence from misclassification rather than assigning one explicit controlled safety flag.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"Replace the accusation with one observation, one uncertainty, and one honest question.","Core Logic":"If I accuse first, I cannot be caught unprepared or made the fool.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"False charges; damaged credibility; defensive loops; lost information; relational fear.","Core Fear":"Trust invites humiliation; people deny until cornered; uncertainty means danger; I must detect betrayal first.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to accuse them before they can deceive me.; Their behavior already proves the motive.; Asking openly would leave me too vulnerable.; If I wait for evidence, I may be made the fool.; I should confront the worst possibility as though it is fact.; Striking first feels safer than risking surprise.","Protective Move":"Preemptive Accusation is accusing another person before sufficient evidence is available in order to avoid being surprised, deceived, blamed, or placed in the weaker position. It turns feared possibility into asserted fact so the person can attack before feeling exposed.","Pattern ID":"PP-PREEMPTIVE-ACCUSATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Accusation restores temporary control by assigning motive and acting first.","Freer Expression":"Direct concern with calibrated evidence.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Pattern recognition, vigilance, courage to name concerns, protection from deception.","Observable Cues":"Leading with allegations; treating questions as proof; attributing intent without inquiry; demanding confession; presenting predictions as established events.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respond to observable concerns where safe, reject false motive claims, and do not submit to endless proof demands. Document and seek support when accusations become coercive. May trigger Defensiveness, Emotional Withholding, Strategic Ambiguity, Anger as Armor, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, trust, dignity, agency, fairness, and predictability; avoids fear, uncertainty, grief, dependence, shame, and possibility of being wrong.","Canonical Name":"Preemptive Accusation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPreemptive Accusation is accusing another person before sufficient evidence is available in order to avoid being surprised, deceived, blamed, or placed in the weaker position. It turns feared possibility into asserted fact so the person can attack before feeling exposed.\n## Domain\nThreat, Trust, and Interpretation\n## Related Patterns\nSuspicion; Mind Reading; Projection; Hypervigilance; Blame Shifting; Adversarial Framing\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I accuse first, I cannot be caught unprepared or made the fool.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to accuse them before they can deceive me.\n- Their behavior already proves the motive.\n- Asking openly would leave me too vulnerable.\n- If I wait for evidence, I may be made the fool.\n- I should confront the worst possibility as though it is fact.\n- Striking first feels safer than risking surprise.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to confront; imagined certainty; intolerable ambiguity; fear that asking openly will reveal vulnerability; relief after assigning motive.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nLeading with allegations; treating questions as proof; attributing intent without inquiry; demanding confession; presenting predictions as established events.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; trust; dignity; agency; fairness; predictability.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDelayed replies; inconsistency; secrecy; previous betrayal; ambiguous behavior; criticism; feeling excluded.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nTrust invites humiliation; people deny until cornered; uncertainty means danger; I must detect betrayal first.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFear; uncertainty; grief; dependence; shame; possibility of being wrong.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior strikes first; Sage claims motive as knowledge; Ruler conducts accusation as control; Lover converts fear into charges.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguity → trust or safety threatened → motive becomes certain → accusation restores temporary control → defensiveness and distance rise → ambiguity and suspicion increase.\n## Often Appears With\nCompulsive Checking; Interrogative Control; Emotional Reasoning; Catastrophizing; Rejection Sensitivity.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nPattern recognition, vigilance, courage to name concerns, protection from deception.\n## Current Cost\nFalse charges; damaged credibility; defensive loops; lost information; relational fear.\n## Freer Expression\nDirect concern with calibrated evidence.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace the accusation with one observation, one uncertainty, and one honest question.\n## Mira Language\n“What do you directly know, what are you inferring, and what are you afraid may be true?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence would change your conclusion? What is the accusation protecting you from feeling? Can the concern be raised without assigning motive?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNaming documented patterns, reporting abuse, or acting on credible evidence is not preemptive accusation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated conversion of ambiguous cues into confident allegations before inquiry or corroboration.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate facts from feared meanings; regulate urgency; preserve the concern while loosening certainty; ask for information without surrendering boundaries.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespond to observable concerns where safe, reject false motive claims, and do not submit to endless proof demands. Document and seek support when accusations become coercive.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nRetract unsupported claims clearly; acknowledge reputational and emotional impact; identify the actual fear; establish evidence and inquiry standards.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nTriggers Defensiveness, Emotional Withholding, Strategic Ambiguity, Anger as Armor, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by Suspicion, secrecy, inconsistency, or prior betrayal. Stories become “They are hiding something” and “Nothing I say will be believed.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I naming evidence—or converting fear into a verdict?"},
  "PP-PREEMPTIVE-DETACHMENT": {"name":"Preemptive Detachment","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Withdrawing Before Being Left; Emotional Distancing; Anticipatory Defeat; Devaluation; Self-Isolation; Suspicion; Emotional Withholding.","Archetypal Role":"Lover—cools when love becomes consequential; Explorer—keeps moving before roots form; Hermit—solitude prevents abandonment.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"Name one honest hope or fear before withdrawing, without demanding certainty from the other person.","Core Logic":"I am leaving emotionally before reality gets the chance to leave me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Self-created loss; shallow connection; unresolved grief; inability to test trust; loneliness.","Core Fear":"Attachment ends in loss; hope makes pain worse; I must leave first to preserve dignity.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should pull back before this matters more.; Hope is becoming dangerous.; I need to detach before they can leave me.; Their flaws are suddenly easier to see than my attachment.; It is safer to rehearse the ending now.; If I care less first, the loss will hurt less.","Protective Move":"Preemptive Detachment is the protective reduction of emotional investment, hope, or attachment before loss, rejection, disappointment, or dependence can occur.","Pattern ID":"PP-PREEMPTIVE-DETACHMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate relief and control follow when investment is withdrawn.","Freer Expression":"Attachment with grounded courage and the capacity to grieve.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; self-preservation; capacity to release; emotional independence.","Observable Cues":"Reducing contact; becoming cool after closeness; dismissing future possibilities; mentally rehearsing endings; withholding investment.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not chase, coerce, or demand intimacy. Offer consistency, name observed distance without accusation, and respect a genuine decision to disengage. May trigger Clinging, Testing the Bond, Possessiveness, or reciprocal detachment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, attachment, dignity, trust, predictability, grief protection, and autonomy; avoids grief, longing, dependence, uncertainty, tenderness, and powerlessness.","Canonical Name":"Preemptive Detachment"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPreemptive Detachment is the protective reduction of emotional investment, hope, or attachment before loss, rejection, disappointment, or dependence can occur.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Loss, and Vulnerability\n## Related Patterns\nWithdrawing Before Being Left; Emotional Distancing; Anticipatory Defeat; Devaluation; Self-Isolation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am leaving emotionally before reality gets the chance to leave me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should pull back before this matters more.\n- Hope is becoming dangerous.\n- I need to detach before they can leave me.\n- Their flaws are suddenly easier to see than my attachment.\n- It is safer to rehearse the ending now.\n- If I care less first, the loss will hurt less.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nWarmth suddenly fades when attachment deepens; flaws become unusually salient; hope feels embarrassing; detachment brings relief.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReducing contact; becoming cool after closeness; dismissing future possibilities; mentally rehearsing endings; withholding investment.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; attachment; dignity; trust; predictability; grief protection; autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nGrowing intimacy; uncertainty; delayed responses; impending transitions; previous abandonment; signs of dependence.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nAttachment ends in loss; hope makes pain worse; I must leave first to preserve dignity.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; longing; dependence; uncertainty; tenderness; powerlessness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover—cools when love becomes consequential; Explorer—keeps moving before roots form; Hermit—solitude prevents abandonment.\n## Pattern Flow\nAttachment deepens or uncertainty appears → anticipated loss threatens dignity and safety → investment is withdrawn → immediate relief and control → connection weakens → resulting distance appears to confirm that attachment was unsafe.\n## Often Appears With\nDevaluation; Suspicion; Emotional Withholding; Anticipatory Defeat.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; self-preservation; capacity to release; emotional independence.\n## Current Cost\nSelf-created loss; shallow connection; unresolved grief; inability to test trust; loneliness.\n## Freer Expression\nAttachment with grounded courage and the capacity to grieve.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one honest hope or fear before withdrawing, without demanding certainty from the other person.\n## Mira Language\n“I notice your emotional investment decreased just as the relationship became more meaningful. Could detachment be protecting you from having something real to lose?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat loss are you already rehearsing? What evidence belongs to the present? Can you remain one step more connected without abandoning discernment?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAccurate disengagement, ending an unsafe relationship, loss of interest, incompatibility, and healthy acceptance are not preemptive detachment.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated sequence in which attachment or hope itself triggers cooling before sufficient present evidence of loss.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRecognize the forecasted grief, assess present evidence and safety, and choose a bounded act of honest presence rather than total emotional exit.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not chase, coerce, or demand intimacy. Offer consistency, name observed distance without accusation, and respect a genuine decision to disengage.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where unexplained cooling, devaluation, or disappearance created confusion or abandonment. Repair requires truthful explanation and consistent behavior; reconnection remains optional.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Testing the Bond, Possessiveness, or reciprocal detachment. Often triggered by Strategic Ambiguity, Rejection Sensitivity, or inconsistent availability. Stories become “Leaving first is safer” and “I must pursue harder or I will disappear.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I grieving an ending that has not yet happened?"},
  "PP-PREEMPTIVE-SELF-REJECTION": {"name":"Preemptive Self-Rejection","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Withdrawing Before Being Left; Self-Deprecation; People-Pleasing; Emotional Distancing; Impostorism; Comparison.","Archetypal Role":"Everyman — stays invisible. Lover — does not reveal interest. Explorer — leaves before roots form. Creator — does not submit work.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Let the other person or system answer instead of answering no on their behalf.","Core Logic":"I will reject myself first so rejection cannot surprise me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Loneliness; missed opportunities; false confirmation of exclusion.","Core Fear":"Hope makes rejection more painful; inclusion is fragile.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They probably don’t really want me there.; I should opt out before they can reject me.; I’m not qualified enough to apply.; I’ll leave before I find out I don’t belong.; It’s safer to assume the answer is no.; I need to disqualify myself before anyone else does.","Protective Move":"Preemptive Self-Rejection is the protective act of excluding, diminishing, or disqualifying oneself before another person or group can do it.","Pattern ID":"PP-PREEMPTIVE-SELF-REJECTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns when the self is disqualified or removed before inclusion is tested.","Freer Expression":"Risked belonging with self-respect.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Sensitivity; realism; self-protection; discernment about belonging.","Observable Cues":"Not applying; declining invitations; making oneself the joke; leaving before inclusion is tested.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Make invitations clear, avoid coercive reassurance, and allow the person agency. May trigger Pursuit, Resentment, Emotional Distancing, or Testing the Bond.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Autonomy; avoids desire, uncertainty, waiting, and receiving.","Canonical Name":"Preemptive Self-Rejection"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPreemptive Self-Rejection is the protective act of excluding, diminishing, or disqualifying oneself before another person or group can do it.\n## Domain\nBelonging, Rejection, and Identity\n## Related Patterns\nWithdrawing Before Being Left; Self-Deprecation; People-Pleasing; Emotional Distancing\n## Recognition Sentence\nI will reject myself first so rejection cannot surprise me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They probably don’t really want me there.\n- I should opt out before they can reject me.\n- I’m not qualified enough to apply.\n- I’ll leave before I find out I don’t belong.\n- It’s safer to assume the answer is no.\n- I need to disqualify myself before anyone else does.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAssumptions of non-belonging; urge to opt out before asking; relief after self-exclusion.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nNot applying; declining invitations; making oneself the joke; leaving before inclusion is tested.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Self-Esteem; Trust; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nInvitations; evaluation; attraction; unfamiliar groups; ambiguous welcome.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nHope makes rejection more painful; inclusion is fragile.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDesire; uncertainty; waiting; receiving.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nEveryman — stays invisible. Lover — does not reveal interest. Explorer — leaves before roots form. Creator — does not submit work.\n## Pattern Flow\nPossibility of inclusion → rejection fear rises → self is disqualified or removed → temporary control → no corrective experience occurs.\n## Often Appears With\nWithdrawing Before Being Left; Impostorism; Self-Deprecation; Comparison.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSensitivity; realism; self-protection; discernment about belonging.\n## Current Cost\nLoneliness; missed opportunities; false confirmation of exclusion.\n## Freer Expression\nRisked belonging with self-respect.\n## One Act of Volition\nLet the other person or system answer instead of answering no on their behalf.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be protecting yourself by deciding the outcome before anyone else can. What happens if you let reality answer?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence says no? What would a bounded risk look like? Are you preserving dignity or avoiding uncertainty?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDeclining unsafe, exploitative, or genuinely unsuitable situations is not this pattern.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated self-exclusion before meaningful evidence is available.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the feared rejection, choose a small test, and preserve the right to leave after real information arrives.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nMake invitations clear, avoid coercive reassurance, and allow the person agency.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where disappearing or self-disqualifying confused or hurt others; communicate directly about fear and choice.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Pursuit, Resentment, Emotional Distancing, or Testing the Bond. Often triggered by Ambiguity, Comparison, Idealization, or perceived coolness.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I giving myself the rejection I fear receiving?"},
  "PP-PREMATURE-ABANDONMENT": {"name":"Premature Abandonment","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Anticipatory Defeat; Self-Sabotage; Failure to Launch; Preemptive Detachment; Commitment Avoidance; Risk Avoidance.","Archetypal Role":"Explorer leaves before roots form; Creator discards the work before feedback; Lover exits when uncertainty rises; Warrior retreats before testing strength.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective function, common expressions, Trigger Phrases, and distinctions. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; source Trigger Phrases retained and supplemented to six, so status is Drafted pending review. Spacing repaired. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because thoughtful disengagement and unsafe situations are explicitly distinguished from the pattern.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Define one fair test, one support, and one review point before deciding to exit.","Core Logic":"If I leave early, I can control the ending before reality has the chance to decide.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Chronic incompletion; repeated loss; weakened trust; missed learning; unstable identity and relationships.","Core Fear":"If I stay long enough to know the outcome, I may be rejected, fail publicly, need help, or be changed by the process.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"This clearly is not going to work.; I should leave before I waste more time.; The fact that this is hard means it is wrong.; I would rather end it now than find out later.; Staying long enough to know feels too risky.; Starting over is safer than adapting here.","Protective Move":"Premature Abandonment leaves a goal, relationship, process, identity, or commitment before its actual viability can be known, often when uncertainty, disappointment, or exposure begins to rise.","Pattern ID":"PP-PREMATURE-ABANDONMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Relief and control return when the person exits before deeper testing.","Freer Expression":"Evidence-based persistence with permission to leave.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; autonomy; responsiveness to poor fit; capacity to leave harmful situations.","Observable Cues":"Quitting after the first setback; discarding work before feedback; ending closeness when vulnerability increases; repeatedly starting over before adaptation or repair.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Avoid chasing or rescuing; clarify what has and has not been tested, what support is available, and what consequences follow from leaving. May trigger Overfunctioning, Resentment, Devaluation, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects autonomy, dignity, predictability, self-esteem, and safety; avoids uncertainty, dependence, disappointment, repair, perseverance, and the vulnerability of being evaluated.","Canonical Name":"Premature Abandonment"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPremature Abandonment is the protective leaving of a goal, relationship, process, identity, or commitment before its actual viability can be known, often when uncertainty, disappointment, or exposure begins to rise. It differs from thoughtful disengagement because adequate testing, repair, support, or adaptation has not yet occurred.\n## Domain\nAction, Commitment, and Uncertainty\n## Related Patterns\nAnticipatory Defeat; Self-Sabotage; Failure to Launch; Preemptive Detachment; Commitment Avoidance\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I leave early, I can control the ending before reality has the chance to decide.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- This clearly is not going to work.\n- I should leave before I waste more time.\n- The fact that this is hard means it is wrong.\n- I would rather end it now than find out later.\n- Staying long enough to know feels too risky.\n- Starting over is safer than adapting here.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief at the idea of quitting; rising urgency after setbacks; difficulty tolerating uneven progress; fear that continued effort will expose inadequacy or dependence.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nQuitting after the first setback; discarding work before feedback; ending closeness when vulnerability increases; repeatedly starting over before adaptation or repair.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; dignity; predictability; self-esteem; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nSetbacks; criticism; slow progress; intimacy; requests for sustained commitment; uncertainty; the need to ask for help.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nFailure is humiliating; needing support is dangerous; difficulty means incompatibility; leaving first preserves dignity.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; disappointment; dependence; grief; repair; incremental learning; limitation.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nExplorer leaves before roots form; Creator discards the work before feedback; Lover exits when uncertainty rises; Warrior retreats before testing strength.\n## Pattern Flow\nDifficulty or exposure rises → viability feels threateningly uncertain → exit becomes urgent → relief and control return → no corrective learning occurs → future persistence feels less trustworthy.\n## Often Appears With\nAnticipatory Defeat; Self-Sabotage; Preemptive Detachment; Commitment Avoidance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; autonomy; responsiveness to poor fit; capacity to leave harmful situations.\n## Current Cost\nChronic incompletion; repeated loss; weakened trust; missed learning; unstable identity and relationships.\n## Freer Expression\nEvidence-based persistence with permission to leave.\n## One Act of Volition\nDefine one fair test, one support, and one review point before deciding to exit.\n## Mira Language\n“The urge to leave may be carrying important information. I also notice the conclusion arrived before the situation was fully tested. What would a fair test require?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence says the path is unviable? What adaptation or repair has not yet been attempted? What becomes vulnerable if you stay long enough to know?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLeaving unsafe, coercive, exploitative, incompatible, or genuinely unworkable situations is not Premature Abandonment.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of exiting before adequate evidence, support, repair, or adaptation, especially when uncertainty itself triggers relief-seeking departure.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSlow the exit, separate activation from evidence, define a bounded test, and preserve the right to leave after real information arrives.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAvoid chasing or rescuing; clarify what has and has not been tested, what support is available, and what consequences follow from leaving.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where abrupt departure transferred burden or created confusion; clarify whether re-engagement is genuinely chosen and establish a specific persistence or ending agreement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Resentment, Devaluation, or Emotional Distancing. The loop becomes “I must leave before failure” versus “I must control or detach because you may disappear.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I concluding before I have stayed long enough to learn?"},
  "PP-PROCRASTINATION": {"name":"Procrastination","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Endless Preparation; Failure to Launch; Perfectionism; Rumination; Busyness as Avoidance; All-or-Nothing Thinking; Self-Deprecation.","Archetypal Role":"Creator delays exposure of the work; Sage delays until knowledge feels complete; Rebel resists externally imposed tasks; Caregiver postpones personal needs; Ruler avoids a decision that may reveal imperfect control.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Work on the smallest visible next action for ten minutes without requiring completion.","Core Logic":"I am delaying the task because beginning would make the risk real.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Lost opportunities; compressed deadlines; shame; reduced trust; chronic stress.","Core Fear":"If I begin, I may fail; effort may prove I am inadequate; demands consume my freedom; mistakes will be punished.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I’ll start when I feel more ready.; I still have time.; I should do something easier first.; Once I know exactly how to do it, I’ll begin.; Starting now will make the pressure real.; I work better at the last minute.","Protective Move":"Procrastination is the protective delay of a meaningful action when beginning would expose the person to discomfort, uncertainty, evaluation, effort, conflict, or possible failure.","Pattern ID":"PP-PROCRASTINATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate relief arrives when delay or substitution occurs.","Freer Expression":"Timely imperfect beginning.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Sensitivity to timing, risk, readiness, and competing demands.","Observable Cues":"Repeated postponement; deadline-driven bursts; replacing priority work with low-stakes activity; excessive planning without action; avoiding messages or decisions.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify priorities and constraints without shaming, rescuing, or using escalating pressure as the only motivator. May trigger Micromanaging, Criticism, Resentment, or Underfunctioning in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Autonomy, Self-Esteem, and Trust; avoids anxiety, frustration, limitation, responsibility, grief about lost time, and uncertainty.","Canonical Name":"Procrastination"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nProcrastination is the protective delay of a meaningful action when beginning would expose the person to discomfort, uncertainty, evaluation, effort, conflict, or possible failure.\n## Domain\nAvoidance and Emotional Escape\n## Related Patterns\nEndless Preparation; Failure to Launch; Perfectionism; Rumination; Busyness as Avoidance; All-or-Nothing Thinking\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am delaying the task because beginning would make the risk real.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I’ll start when I feel more ready.\n- I still have time.\n- I should do something easier first.\n- Once I know exactly how to do it, I’ll begin.\n- Starting now will make the pressure real.\n- I work better at the last minute.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDread before starting; sudden interest in easier tasks; relief when postponing; shame about delay; belief that the right mood must come first.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeated postponement; deadline-driven bursts; replacing priority work with low-stakes activity; excessive planning without action; avoiding messages or decisions.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Autonomy; Self-Esteem; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nEvaluation; ambiguity; large tasks; conflict; boredom; irreversible choices; depleted bandwidth.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf I begin, I may fail; effort may prove I am inadequate; demands consume my freedom; mistakes will be punished.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAnxiety; frustration; limitation; responsibility; grief about lost time; uncertainty.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCreator delays exposure of the work; Sage delays until knowledge feels complete; Rebel resists externally imposed tasks; Caregiver postpones personal needs; Ruler avoids a decision that may reveal imperfect control.\n## Pattern Flow\nTask becomes meaningful → threat rises → delay or substitution occurs → immediate relief arrives → pressure and shame increase → future starting becomes harder.\n## Often Appears With\nPerfectionism; Rumination; Self-Deprecation; All-or-Nothing Thinking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSensitivity to timing, risk, readiness, and competing demands.\n## Current Cost\nLost opportunities; compressed deadlines; shame; reduced trust; chronic stress.\n## Freer Expression\nTimely imperfect beginning.\n## One Act of Volition\nWork on the smallest visible next action for ten minutes without requiring completion.\n## Mira Language\n“The delay may be protecting you from what starting would expose. What becomes real the moment you begin?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feeling arrives before delay? Is the task unclear, unsafe, oversized, or evaluative? What is the smallest honest beginning?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nFatigue, disability, missing information, executive-function limits, and reasonable reprioritization are not automatically procrastination.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated relief-through-delay followed by increased cost across meaningful tasks.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReduce the task to one bounded action, name the feared exposure, and begin before motivation is complete.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify priorities and constraints without shaming, rescuing, or using escalating pressure as the only motivator.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge missed commitments and their impact, avoid explaining the delay as though explanation erases consequence, renegotiate realistically, and demonstrate change through earlier communication and smaller reliable milestones.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Criticism, Resentment, or Underfunctioning in others. Often triggered by Perfectionism, pressure, vague expectations, or punitive oversight. The loop becomes: “You will not act unless I control you” and “I cannot act while being controlled.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat would beginning make real?"},
  "PP-PRODUCTIVITY-BOUND-WORTH": {"name":"Productivity-Bound Worth","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Compulsive Productivity; Achievement-Bound Worth; Busyness as Identity; Indispensability; Perfectionism; Inability to Rest; Rapid Project Proliferation.","Archetypal Role":"Creator — worth is measured through making; Caregiver — worth is measured through usefulness; Warrior — worth is measured through endurance; Ruler — worth is measured through keeping everything functioning; Sage — worth is measured through intellectual output; Explorer — worth is measured through constant forward movement.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation. Repair Path — After Rupture is absent from this source record and remains absent rather than being invented.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Take one defined period of rest without first completing a task to justify it.","Core Logic":"I feel entitled to exist, rest, or feel proud only when I am producing.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Burnout; conditional self-esteem; neglected health and relationships; inability to recover; shallow satisfaction; fear of stillness.","Core Fear":"I am valued only for what I do. Rest makes me disposable. My needs are less legitimate than my usefulness. If I stop, people will discover that I do not matter. Love and security must be earned repeatedly.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I haven’t done enough to deserve rest.; Today was wasted because I didn’t produce.; I should be doing something useful.; I’ll relax after I finish one more thing.; If I stop, I’m falling behind.; My value is what I get done.","Protective Move":"Productivity-Bound Worth is the protective belief that one earns legitimacy, rest, pride, or belonging through output, making inactivity feel morally unsafe or personally diminishing.","Pattern ID":"PP-PRODUCTIVITY-BOUND-WORTH","Short-Term Payoff":"Worth temporarily stabilizes as work and activity intensify.","Freer Expression":"Contribution as an expression of worth—not proof of worth.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Commitment; contribution; generativity; stamina; conscientiousness.","Observable Cues":"Measuring a day only through completed output; working through illness, grief, or exhaustion unnecessarily; immediately replacing one goal with another; difficulty enjoying leisure without multitasking; turning hobbies into measurable production; apologizing for rest; neglecting relationships, sleep, or health while continuing to produce.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appreciate the person rather than only the output. Do not reinforce overwork with admiration, rescue every self-imposed crisis, or make usefulness the condition of belonging. Encourage limits while respecting genuine financial and caregiving realities. May trigger Dependency, Resentment, Emotional Neglect, Keeping Score, or further Overfunctioning in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Purpose, and Belonging when usefulness historically secured acceptance; avoids rest, dependence, bodily limitation, grief, purposelessness, receiving without repayment, and uncertainty about identity.","Canonical Name":"Productivity-Bound Worth"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nProductivity-Bound Worth is the protective belief that one earns legitimacy, rest, pride, or belonging through output, making inactivity feel morally unsafe or personally diminishing.\n## Domain\nWorth, Approval, and Social Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nCompulsive Productivity; Achievement-Bound Worth; Busyness as Identity; Indispensability; Perfectionism; Inability to Rest\n## Recognition Sentence\nI feel entitled to exist, rest, or feel proud only when I am producing.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I haven’t done enough to deserve rest.\n- Today was wasted because I didn’t produce.\n- I should be doing something useful.\n- I’ll relax after I finish one more thing.\n- If I stop, I’m falling behind.\n- My value is what I get done.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\n- Rest creates guilt rather than restoration.\n- An unproductive day feels like evidence of personal failure.\n- Completion brings only brief relief before the next demand appears.\n- Illness or fatigue feels morally suspect.\n- Worth feels strongest while being useful, busy, or visibly productive.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n- Measuring a day only through completed output.\n- Working through illness, grief, or exhaustion unnecessarily.\n- Immediately replacing one goal with another.\n- Difficulty enjoying leisure without multitasking.\n- Turning hobbies into measurable production.\n- Apologizing for rest.\n- Neglecting relationships, sleep, or health while continuing to produce.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Purpose; Belonging when usefulness historically secured acceptance.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDowntime; illness; unemployment; retirement; project completion; comparison; low-output days; receiving care without earning it.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\n- I am valued only for what I do.\n- Rest makes me disposable.\n- My needs are less legitimate than my usefulness.\n- If I stop, people will discover that I do not matter.\n- Love and security must be earned repeatedly.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nRest; dependence; bodily limitation; grief; purposelessness; receiving without repayment; uncertainty about identity.\n## Archetypal Expressions\n- Creator — worth is measured through making.\n- Caregiver — worth is measured through usefulness.\n- Warrior — worth is measured through endurance.\n- Ruler — worth is measured through keeping everything functioning.\n- Sage — worth is measured through intellectual output.\n- Explorer — worth is measured through constant forward movement.\n## Pattern Flow\nOutput slows or stops → self-esteem, competence, or purpose feel threatened → work and activity intensify → worth temporarily stabilizes → rest and relationships are sacrificed → exhaustion reduces capacity → even more output is demanded to restore worth.\n## Often Appears With\nCompulsive Productivity; Perfectionism; Busyness as Identity; Indispensability; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCommitment; contribution; generativity; stamina; conscientiousness.\n## Current Cost\nBurnout; conditional self-esteem; neglected health and relationships; inability to recover; shallow satisfaction; fear of stillness.\n## Freer Expression\nContribution as an expression of worth—not proof of worth.\n## One Act of Volition\nTake one defined period of rest without first completing a task to justify it.\n## Mira Language\n“You described the day as worthless because little was produced. I wonder whether productivity has become the measure of your worth rather than one expression of it. What would remain true about you on a day when nothing was made?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\n- Who are you when no one needs an output from you?\n- What does rest seem to threaten?\n- Can your work express a worth that already exists?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nEnjoying work, ambition, discipline, financial necessity, caregiving responsibility, and productive seasons are not automatically Productivity-Bound Worth.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated moralization of rest, collapse in self-worth during low output, or sacrificing health and relationships to preserve identity through production.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nNotice when output has become evidence for existence. Name what remains worthy before work begins, schedule rest as maintenance rather than reward, and practice receiving care or pleasure without repayment through productivity.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAppreciate the person rather than only the output. Do not reinforce overwork with admiration, rescue every self-imposed crisis, or make usefulness the condition of belonging. Encourage limits while respecting genuine financial and caregiving realities.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Dependency, Resentment, Emotional Neglect, Keeping Score, or further Overfunctioning in others. Often triggered by Need, Downtime, Comparison, Financial or relational pressure, or another person’s dependence. The reinforcing story may become: “I matter only when I carry more” on one side and “My needs will be met only if this person keeps carrying everything” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I creating because I am alive—or creating in order to earn the right to feel alive?"},
  "PP-PROJECTION": {"name":"Projection","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Mind Reading; Externalization; Blame Shifting; Displacement; Denial; Emotional Reasoning; Moral Superiority; Defensiveness.","Archetypal Role":"Sage — assigns bias to others while protecting certainty; Ruler — sees incompetence outside while disowning fear of losing control; Lover — attributes ambivalence or desire to the other; Warrior — perceives hostility while disowning anger; Caregiver — condemns selfishness while suppressing personal need.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly warns that projection must not be used to dismiss reports of abuse or misconduct.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Before naming another person’s motive, identify one feeling, wish, or fear in yourself that could be shaping the interpretation.","Core Logic":"I am locating in you what is difficult for me to recognize in myself.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"False accusations; relational confusion; reduced self-awareness; escalating conflict; misplaced certainty.","Core Fear":"Certain feelings make me bad; self-knowledge will cost belonging; being wrong is unsafe; vulnerability invites humiliation.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I know what your real motive is.; You’re the one who is angry or jealous.; I can see exactly what you’re hiding.; This trait in you is intolerable.; Don’t turn this back on me; this is about you.; I’m certain the problem belongs entirely to you.","Protective Move":"Projection is the protective attribution of one’s own difficult feeling, motive, impulse, or judgment to another person, allowing it to be encountered outside the self rather than recognized within.","Pattern ID":"PP-PROJECTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary innocence or certainty returns when the experience is attributed outward.","Freer Expression":"Ownership before interpretation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Sensitivity to motives; pattern recognition; moral discernment; emotional perception.","Observable Cues":"Accusing others of motives without evidence; repeatedly identifying in others what one disowns; treating interpretation as fact; escalating when invited to self-reflect.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask for observable examples, decline imposed motives, and invite curiosity without counter-accusing. Preserve boundaries when the attribution becomes hostile or coercive. May trigger Defensiveness, Counter-Projection, Withdrawal, Overexplaining, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Trust, and Belonging; avoids ambivalence, envy, anger, desire, dependency, responsibility, and uncertainty.","Canonical Name":"Projection"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nProjection is the protective attribution of one’s own difficult feeling, motive, impulse, or judgment to another person, allowing it to be encountered outside the self rather than recognized within.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nMind Reading; Externalization; Blame Shifting; Displacement; Denial; Emotional Reasoning\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am locating in you what is difficult for me to recognize in myself.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I know what your real motive is.\n- You’re the one who is angry or jealous.\n- I can see exactly what you’re hiding.\n- This trait in you is intolerable.\n- Don’t turn this back on me; this is about you.\n- I’m certain the problem belongs entirely to you.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nStrong certainty about another person’s motive; disproportionate irritation at a trait; relief when blame is located outside; resistance to considering the same quality in oneself.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAccusing others of motives without evidence; repeatedly identifying in others what one disowns; treating interpretation as fact; escalating when invited to self-reflect.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Trust; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nShame; contradiction; unwanted attraction or anger; criticism; similarity to a rejected part of oneself; moral threat.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nCertain feelings make me bad; self-knowledge will cost belonging; being wrong is unsafe; vulnerability invites humiliation.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAmbivalence; envy; anger; desire; dependency; responsibility; uncertainty.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage — assigns bias to others while protecting certainty. Ruler — sees incompetence outside while disowning fear of losing control. Lover — attributes ambivalence or desire to the other. Warrior — perceives hostility while disowning anger. Caregiver — condemns selfishness while suppressing personal need.\n## Pattern Flow\nUnacceptable inner experience arises → identity or worth feels threatened → the experience is attributed outward → temporary innocence or certainty returns → conflict and misrecognition increase → self-knowledge becomes harder.\n## Often Appears With\nDenial; Moral Superiority; Mind Reading; Blame Shifting; Defensiveness.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSensitivity to motives; pattern recognition; moral discernment; emotional perception.\n## Current Cost\nFalse accusations; relational confusion; reduced self-awareness; escalating conflict; misplaced certainty.\n## Freer Expression\nOwnership before interpretation.\n## One Act of Volition\nBefore naming another person’s motive, identify one feeling, wish, or fear in yourself that could be shaping the interpretation.\n## Mira Language\n“That interpretation may be accurate, but I want to test another possibility: could any part of what you see in them also be difficult to recognize in yourself?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence belongs to them, and what feeling belongs to you? Why is this trait especially charged? What becomes possible if both realities are partly true?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAccurate perception, pattern recognition, and naming genuine harm are not projection. Mira must not use projection to dismiss reports of abuse or misconduct.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated unsupported attribution combined with resistance to self-examination and a meaningful match between accusation and disowned experience.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause certainty, name the inner state, separate observation from interpretation, and hold the possibility that the perception contains both external truth and internal material.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk for observable examples, decline imposed motives, and invite curiosity without counter-accusing. Preserve boundaries when the attribution becomes hostile or coercive.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nWithdraw unsupported claims, acknowledge how the attribution distorted the other person’s reality, name the feeling or motive now recognized as one’s own, and rebuild trust through evidence-based communication.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Counter-Projection, Withdrawal, Overexplaining, or Contempt. Often triggered by Ambiguity, Criticism, Secrecy, or another person’s Mind Reading. Reinforcing stories: “You are hiding what I know is true” and “Nothing I say can correct how you see me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I certain belongs to them that may also need to be met within me?"},
  "PP-PROMISE-INFLATION": {"name":"Promise Inflation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"People-Pleasing; Grandiosity; Appeasement; Rapid Project Proliferation; Image Management; Compulsive Achievement.","Archetypal Role":"Lover—promises transformation to prevent loss; Creator—announces more than can be built; Hero—pledges total rescue; Ruler—declares certainty instead of building systems.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Replace the sweeping promise with one observable commitment, owner, deadline, and review point.","Core Logic":"I am using the future to calm what I cannot resolve honestly in the present.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Broken trust; overcommitment; repeated disappointment; shame; unstable planning.","Core Fear":"Realistic limits will make me unlovable; intention should count as capacity; I must restore hope immediately.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I promise everything will be completely different.; A realistic commitment will not be enough to keep them here.; I need to restore hope right now.; Motivation will somehow create the capacity later.; I should make the biggest promise possible to calm this conflict.; Specific planning can wait; they need certainty from me now.","Protective Move":"Promise Inflation is the protective use of oversized commitments, certainty, or future change to relieve present conflict, disappointment, shame, or fear of losing connection before capacity and follow-through have been honestly assessed.","Pattern ID":"PP-PROMISE-INFLATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate hope and relief follow when an expansive promise is made.","Freer Expression":"Credible commitment built through proportionate action.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Hope; aspiration; generosity; willingness to recommit.","Observable Cues":"Promising total transformation; committing beyond available time or resources; repeated “never again” assurances; replacing planning with certainty.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not demand dramatic vows as proof of care. Ask for specific actions, timelines, and evidence; judge trustworthiness by follow-through. May trigger Suspicion, Keeping Score, Control-Seeking, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Self-Esteem, Trust, and Competence; avoids present consequences, gradual trust-building, limitation, uncertainty, and possible rejection.","Canonical Name":"Promise Inflation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPromise Inflation is the protective use of oversized commitments, certainty, or future change to relieve present conflict, disappointment, shame, or fear of losing connection before capacity and follow-through have been honestly assessed.\n## Domain\nCommitment, Image, and Relational Security\n## Related Patterns\nPeople-Pleasing; Grandiosity; Appeasement; Rapid Project Proliferation; Image Management.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am using the future to calm what I cannot resolve honestly in the present.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I promise everything will be completely different.\n- A realistic commitment will not be enough to keep them here.\n- I need to restore hope right now.\n- Motivation will somehow create the capacity later.\n- I should make the biggest promise possible to calm this conflict.\n- Specific planning can wait; they need certainty from me now.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief immediately after making a large promise; conviction that motivation will solve capacity; fear that a realistic commitment will disappoint others.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nPromising total transformation; committing beyond available time or resources; repeated “never again” assurances; replacing planning with certainty.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Self-Esteem; Trust; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDisappointment; threatened separation; exposure of failure; requests for change; enthusiasm without capacity review.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nRealistic limits will make me unlovable; intention should count as capacity; I must restore hope immediately.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nPresent consequences; gradual trust-building; limitation; uncertainty; possible rejection.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover—promises transformation to prevent loss; Creator—announces more than can be built; Hero—pledges total rescue; Ruler—declares certainty instead of building systems.\n## Pattern Flow\nDisappointment or aspiration → worth or bond feels threatened → expansive promise made → immediate hope and relief → capacity mismatch → broken commitment → greater distrust and shame.\n## Often Appears With\nPeople-Pleasing; Grandiosity; Appeasement; Compulsive Achievement; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHope; aspiration; generosity; willingness to recommit.\n## Current Cost\nBroken trust; overcommitment; repeated disappointment; shame; unstable planning.\n## Freer Expression\nCredible commitment built through proportionate action.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace the sweeping promise with one observable commitment, owner, deadline, and review point.\n## Mira Language\n“The promise offers immediate hope. What smaller commitment could your present capacity reliably support?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does this promise require in time and resources? Are you committing to an outcome you cannot control? What evidence would make the promise credible?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nBold goals, sincere hope, developmental ambition, and commitments made with realistic planning are not Promise Inflation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated large assurances used to regulate present distress, followed by weak planning or unreliable follow-through.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nTolerate the other person’s disappointment long enough to assess capacity, then promise only observable actions under your control.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not demand dramatic vows as proof of care. Ask for specific actions, timelines, and evidence; judge trustworthiness by follow-through.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where inflated promises created false hope, stop renewing trust through words alone, revise the commitment honestly, and permit the other person to wait for evidence.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Keeping Score, Control-Seeking, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by Rejection Sensitivity, Appeasement, Shame Spiraling, or another person’s ultimatum. The loop story becomes: “I must promise more to keep hope alive” and “Your promises mean nothing without evidence.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I promising to soothe the present rather than serve the future?"},
  "PP-PUNITIVE-WITHDRAWAL": {"name":"Punitive Withdrawal","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Distancing; Retaliation; Passive Aggression; Conditional Warmth; Testing the Bond; Dominance; Keeping Score; Strategic Ambiguity.","Archetypal Role":"Lover withdraws affection; Ruler removes access; Warrior uses silence as siege; Caregiver withholds support; Rebel disappears to resist influence.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because the source explicitly defines withdrawal as punishment, leverage, forced pursuit, coercive ambiguity, and pressure for capitulation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"State what you need, whether contact is paused, and when or how you will communicate again.","Core Logic":"I am removing access so the other person will feel pressure, regret, or fear of losing me.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Anxiety; coercive ambiguity; erosion of trust; escalating pursuit-withdrawal loops; delayed repair.","Core Fear":"Direct needs are ignored; vulnerability gives others power; only absence makes people care; conflict must be won.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need them to feel what losing access to me is like.; If I disappear, they may finally understand.; I should stay silent until they come after me.; Distance will make them regret confronting me.; Naming the hurt directly would give away too much power.; I want the withdrawal to create pressure, not simply space.","Protective Move":"Punitive Withdrawal is the removal of contact, warmth, information, cooperation, or presence in order to make another person feel the cost of displeasing, confronting, or failing the withdrawer. It differs from a regulated pause because the withdrawal functions as punishment, leverage, or forced pursuit rather than clearly bounded self-regulation.","Pattern ID":"PP-PUNITIVE-WITHDRAWAL","Short-Term Payoff":"Power and relief return briefly when access is withdrawn.","Freer Expression":"A clear boundary or regulated pause without punishment.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Capacity for boundaries, pause, discernment, and self-protection.","Observable Cues":"Unexplained disappearance after conflict; withholding routine cooperation; refusing necessary information; coldness designed to be noticed; returning only after the other person capitulates.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not reward coercive disappearance with frantic pursuit. Ask once for clarity, protect practical needs, and set limits around repeated unannounced withdrawal. May trigger Clinging, Reassurance Seeking, Anger as Armor, Retaliation, or Preemptive Detachment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, dignity, agency, fairness, belonging, recognition, and predictability; avoids hurt, grief, dependence, embarrassment, uncertainty, and direct responsibility.","Canonical Name":"Punitive Withdrawal"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPunitive Withdrawal is the removal of contact, warmth, information, cooperation, or presence in order to make another person feel the cost of displeasing, confronting, or failing the withdrawer. It differs from a regulated pause because the withdrawal functions as punishment, leverage, or forced pursuit rather than clearly bounded self-regulation.\n## Domain\nRelationship, Power, and Rupture\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Distancing; Retaliation; Passive Aggression; Conditional Warmth; Testing the Bond; Dominance\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am removing access so the other person will feel pressure, regret, or fear of losing me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need them to feel what losing access to me is like.\n- If I disappear, they may finally understand.\n- I should stay silent until they come after me.\n- Distance will make them regret confronting me.\n- Naming the hurt directly would give away too much power.\n- I want the withdrawal to create pressure, not simply space.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief at withholding; desire for the other person to worry or chase; resistance to naming a return time; belief that direct expression would surrender power.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nUnexplained disappearance after conflict; withholding routine cooperation; refusing necessary information; coldness designed to be noticed; returning only after the other person capitulates.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; dignity; agency; fairness; belonging; recognition; predictability.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCriticism; boundary-setting; perceived disrespect; shame; loss of control; unmet expectations; confrontation.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDirect needs are ignored; vulnerability gives others power; only absence makes people care; conflict must be won.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHurt; grief; dependence; embarrassment; uncertainty; direct responsibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover withdraws affection; Ruler removes access; Warrior uses silence as siege; Caregiver withholds support; Rebel disappears to resist influence.\n## Pattern Flow\nRupture or shame → agency or dignity feels threatened → access is withdrawn → power and relief return briefly → uncertainty and pursuit increase → trust and direct communication deteriorate.\n## Often Appears With\nRetaliation; Passive Aggression; Keeping Score; Conditional Warmth; Strategic Ambiguity.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCapacity for boundaries, pause, discernment, and self-protection.\n## Current Cost\nAnxiety; coercive ambiguity; erosion of trust; escalating pursuit-withdrawal loops; delayed repair.\n## Freer Expression\nA clear boundary or regulated pause without punishment.\n## One Act of Volition\nState what you need, whether contact is paused, and when or how you will communicate again.\n## Mira Language\n“Do you need distance to regulate, or is part of you hoping the distance will make them suffer, chase, or surrender?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat is the withdrawal meant to accomplish? What direct sentence feels too vulnerable? Is a return condition being communicated?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSafety-based disengagement, no-contact decisions, sleep, work obligations, and regulated pauses are not punitive withdrawal.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated withdrawal linked to conflict, designed to pressure or punish, especially without clear boundaries or re-engagement terms.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the injury and the urge to regain power; regulate before contact; convert punishment into a boundary, request, or explicit ending.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not reward coercive disappearance with frantic pursuit. Ask once for clarity, protect practical needs, and set limits around repeated unannounced withdrawal.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the pressure and uncertainty created; name what was withheld; clarify the need that should have been expressed directly; establish a pause-and-return agreement. Re-engagement is optional when withdrawal is coercive or repeated.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Reassurance Seeking, Anger as Armor, Retaliation, or Preemptive Detachment. Often triggered by Criticism, Boundary Rigidity, Suspicion, or perceived abandonment. Stories become “I must disappear to matter” and “I must chase to keep connection.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I taking space to return with more capacity, or removing myself to control the outcome?"},
  "PP-PURITY-IDENTITY": {"name":"Purity Identity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Moral Superiority; Splitting; Identity Fusion; Moral Worth Performance; Denial; Devaluation.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent seeks moral cleanliness; Ruler enforces uncompromised order; Rebel defines self against corruption; Mystic protects sacred identity through separation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 15 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective function, common expressions, Trigger Phrases, and distinctions. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; source Trigger Phrases retained and supplemented to six, so status is Drafted pending review. Spacing repaired. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because the source describes identity rigidity but does not provide one explicit controlled safety designation.","First Letter":"P","Source Batch":"15","One Act of Volition":"Name one value you will protect and one complexity you can acknowledge without treating it as contamination.","Core Logic":"If I remain untouched by compromise, I can stay safe from shame and corruption.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Rigidity; shame; exclusion; splitting; brittle belonging; inability to learn from compromise or repair.","Core Fear":"Ambiguity, association, compromise, or ordinary fallibility will contaminate who I am and cost belonging or goodness.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I cannot be associated with anything compromised.; If I make one exception, I become part of the problem.; Good people do not cross that line.; I need to remain untouched by this.; Ambiguity feels like moral contamination.; If I admit complexity, I may lose the identity that keeps me safe.","Protective Move":"Purity Identity organizes self-worth and belonging around being uncontaminated, uncompromised, morally clean, ideologically consistent, or unlike those judged to be corrupt.","Pattern ID":"PP-PURITY-IDENTITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Certainty and innocence return when complexity is expelled or distance is created.","Freer Expression":"Integrity spacious enough for complexity, fallibility, and repair.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Integrity; devotion; ethical clarity; willingness to resist corruption; protection of sacred values.","Observable Cues":"Severe self-policing; rejecting people after perceived compromise; contamination language; disowning complexity; treating one exception as total corruption.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respect values while refusing dehumanization, compulsory purity tests, or coercive exclusion; return to behavior, evidence, and proportion. May trigger Moral Superiority, Adversarial Framing, Identity Fusion, or Retaliation.","Emotional Function":"Protects moral identity, certainty, belonging, dignity, and safety; avoids ambiguity, mixed motives, guilt, ordinary human complexity, grief, and identification with disowned parts.","Canonical Name":"Purity Identity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nPurity Identity is the protective organization of self-worth and belonging around being uncontaminated, uncompromised, morally clean, ideologically consistent, or unlike those judged to be corrupt. It differs from integrity because ordinary complexity, association, or imperfection becomes a threat to identity itself.\n## Domain\nMoral Identity, Certainty, and Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nMoral Superiority; Splitting; Identity Fusion; Moral Worth Performance; Denial\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I remain untouched by compromise, I can stay safe from shame and corruption.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I cannot be associated with anything compromised.\n- If I make one exception, I become part of the problem.\n- Good people do not cross that line.\n- I need to remain untouched by this.\n- Ambiguity feels like moral contamination.\n- If I admit complexity, I may lose the identity that keeps me safe.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAlarm around association or compromise; shame after small inconsistency; relief through separation; disgust toward disowned qualities; fear of moral contamination.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSevere self-policing; rejecting people after perceived compromise; contamination language; disowning complexity; treating one exception as total corruption.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nMoral identity; certainty; belonging; dignity; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; association with wrongdoing; compromise; ideological conflict; mistakes; mixed motives; public scrutiny.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nGoodness requires cleanliness; belonging depends on conformity; contamination spreads; mistakes reveal corruption; complexity invites shame.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAmbivalence; guilt; grief; ordinary fallibility; shared humanity; responsibility for repair; identification with disowned parts.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent seeks moral cleanliness; Ruler enforces uncompromised order; Rebel defines self against corruption; Mystic protects sacred identity through separation.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguity or compromise appears → moral identity feels contaminated → separation, denunciation, or self-policing intensifies → certainty and innocence return → complexity and repair become harder → purity standards tighten.\n## Often Appears With\nMoral Superiority; Splitting; Identity Fusion; Devaluation; Moral Worth Performance.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nIntegrity; devotion; ethical clarity; willingness to resist corruption; protection of sacred values.\n## Current Cost\nRigidity; shame; exclusion; splitting; brittle belonging; inability to learn from compromise or repair.\n## Freer Expression\nIntegrity spacious enough for complexity, fallibility, and repair.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one value you will protect and one complexity you can acknowledge without treating it as contamination.\n## Mira Language\n“Your wish to remain aligned with your values may be deeply sincere. I also wonder whether complexity is being experienced as contamination of the self.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does association seem to prove about you? Can a person violate a value without becoming wholly corrupt? What repair is possible besides expulsion or self-purification?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nIntegrity, principled boundaries, refusing harmful participation, and safety-based separation are not Purity Identity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern in which ambiguity, association, or ordinary inconsistency threatens total identity and produces rigid exclusion or self-policing.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate values from identity perfection; tolerate mixed motives; name behavior precisely; choose accountability and repair over contamination logic.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespect values while refusing dehumanization, compulsory purity tests, or coercive exclusion; return to behavior, evidence, and proportion.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where purity logic erased complexity, excluded others, or made repair impossible; restore specific accountability and equal human dignity without forced reconciliation.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Moral Superiority, Adversarial Framing, Identity Fusion, or Retaliation. The loop becomes “I must remain uncontaminated” versus “You treat my humanity as corruption.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat value am I protecting, and what human complexity am I refusing to let belong beside it?"},
  "PP-RAPID-PROJECT-PROLIFERATION": {"name":"Rapid Project Proliferation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Novelty Chasing; Failure to Launch; Overcomplication; Compulsive Productivity; Permanent Optionality; Self-Sabotage; Perfectionism.","Archetypal Role":"Creator — possibility continually outruns incarnation; Explorer — new territory replaces depth; Sage — new conceptual layers delay practical testing; Mystic — every connection feels meaningful enough to pursue now; Ruler — the system expands before the central structure stabilizes; Trickster — novel disruption displaces disciplined continuation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation. Repair Path — After Rupture is absent from this source record and remains absent rather than being invented.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Capture every idea in incubation, but require one existing milestone to be completed before promoting another idea into active construction.","Core Logic":"I keep generating new possibilities faster than I allow existing ones to become complete, limited, and real.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Fragmented attention; diluted execution; unstable priorities; technical debt; poor validation; exhaustion; many unfinished promises.","Core Fear":"My worth depends on continuing to create. Completion will expose whether the idea was actually good. If I choose one path, I lose all the others. Ordinary execution cannot match what I can imagine. Once this is finished, I may become empty.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I just had another idea we need to add.; This new direction could change everything.; I’ll finish the current piece after I set this up.; I don’t want to lose this possibility.; The project needs one more branch before launch.; Starting this feels more alive than finishing that.","Protective Move":"Rapid Project Proliferation is the protective generation of new projects, features, or directions faster than existing work can be completed, tested, limited, or exposed to evaluation.","Pattern ID":"PP-RAPID-PROJECT-PROLIFERATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Energy and hope return when a compelling new possibility appears.","Freer Expression":"Abundance governed by sequencing.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Generativity; synthesis; imagination; pattern recognition; entrepreneurial vision.","Observable Cues":"Opening new workstreams before validating the central one; adding adjacent products, apps, features, or theories during launch work; maintaining many nearly finished projects; reprioritizing whenever a compelling idea appears; expanding architecture faster than users can test it; treating every insight as an immediate build requirement; leaving implementation debt behind repeated conceptual expansion.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Welcome ideation without automatically promoting it into scope. Ask whether the idea strengthens or competes with the present commitment, record it visibly, and hold agreed sequencing without shaming creativity. May trigger Skepticism, Withdrawal, Micromanaging, Keeping Score, or Loss of Trust in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Competence, Purpose, Self-Esteem, and sometimes Trust; avoids finality, evaluation, boredom, repetition, tradeoffs, limitation, and the quiet after completion.","Canonical Name":"Rapid Project Proliferation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRapid Project Proliferation is the protective generation of new projects, features, or directions faster than existing work can be completed, tested, limited, or exposed to evaluation.\n## Domain\nCompetence, Creation, and Performance\n## Related Patterns\nNovelty Chasing; Failure to Launch; Overcomplication; Compulsive Productivity; Permanent Optionality; Self-Sabotage\n## Recognition Sentence\nI keep generating new possibilities faster than I allow existing ones to become complete, limited, and real.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I just had another idea we need to add.\n- This new direction could change everything.\n- I’ll finish the current piece after I set this up.\n- I don’t want to lose this possibility.\n- The project needs one more branch before launch.\n- Starting this feels more alive than finishing that.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\n- New ideas produce more energy than finishing does.\n- Choosing one path feels like losing all other possible selves.\n- A new layer appears just as the current product approaches exposure.\n- The project feels alive while expanding and vulnerable while simplifying.\n- Incubating an idea feels nearly equivalent to advancing it.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\n- Opening new workstreams before validating the central one.\n- Adding adjacent products, apps, features, or theories during launch work.\n- Maintaining many nearly finished projects.\n- Reprioritizing whenever a compelling idea appears.\n- Expanding architecture faster than users can test it.\n- Treating every insight as an immediate build requirement.\n- Leaving implementation debt behind repeated conceptual expansion.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Competence; Purpose; Self-Esteem; sometimes Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nApproaching launch; evaluation; repetitive implementation; narrowing scope; choosing among meaningful options; boredom after ideation; uncertain reception.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\n- My worth depends on continuing to create.\n- Completion will expose whether the idea was actually good.\n- If I choose one path, I lose all the others.\n- Ordinary execution cannot match what I can imagine.\n- Once this is finished, I may become empty.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFinality; evaluation; boredom; repetition; tradeoffs; limitation; the quiet after completion.\n## Archetypal Expressions\n- Creator — possibility continually outruns incarnation.\n- Explorer — new territory replaces depth.\n- Sage — new conceptual layers delay practical testing.\n- Mystic — every connection feels meaningful enough to pursue now.\n- Ruler — the system expands before the central structure stabilizes.\n- Trickster — novel disruption displaces disciplined continuation.\n## Pattern Flow\nA project approaches limitation, repetition, or exposure → autonomy, competence, or worth feels threatened → a compelling new possibility appears → energy and hope return → attention fragments → the original project remains untested → possibility stays protected from reality.\n## Often Appears With\nNovelty Chasing; Perfectionism; Compulsive Productivity; Overcomplication; Failure to Launch.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nGenerativity; synthesis; imagination; pattern recognition; entrepreneurial vision.\n## Current Cost\nFragmented attention; diluted execution; unstable priorities; technical debt; poor validation; exhaustion; many unfinished promises.\n## Freer Expression\nAbundance governed by sequencing.\n## One Act of Volition\nCapture every idea in incubation, but require one existing milestone to be completed before promoting another idea into active construction.\n## Mira Language\n“This new idea may genuinely belong to the ecosystem. I also notice it appeared as the central product approached exposure and testing. Is it extending the work—or protecting you from finishing what is already in front of you?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\n- Does this idea strengthen the flagship or compete with it?\n- What existing milestone must be completed before this becomes active?\n- What feeling appears when the work moves from possibility into repetition and evaluation?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nADHD-associated ideation, interdisciplinary creativity, portfolio entrepreneurship, and legitimate strategic expansion are not automatically Protective Patterns.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated creation of active workstreams that displace completion, testing, or maintenance—not simply having many ideas.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPreserve the idea without activating it. Place it in incubation, identify what feeling arose as the current work approached limitation or exposure, and require a completion or validation milestone before opening another workstream.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nWelcome ideation without automatically promoting it into scope. Ask whether the idea strengthens or competes with the present commitment, record it visibly, and hold agreed sequencing without shaming creativity.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Skepticism, Withdrawal, Micromanaging, Keeping Score, or Loss of Trust in others. Often triggered by Evaluation, Repetition, Narrowing Options, Criticism, or another person’s demand for completion. The reinforcing story may become: “New possibility is where freedom and worth live” on one side and “Nothing will ever be completed or dependable” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nIs this new possibility serving completion—or helping me avoid it?"},
  "PP-RATIONALIZATION": {"name":"Rationalization","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Intellectualizing; Denial; Minimizing; Externalization; Defensive Expertise; Excuse Making; Defensiveness; Blame Shifting; Perfectionism.","Archetypal Role":"Sage — elegant theory shields bias. Ruler — necessity justifies control. Caregiver — intrusion is renamed help. Rebel — harm is justified as resistance. Creator — delay is framed as protecting quality. Explorer — abandonment is reframed as freedom.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"State the explanation only after naming the choice, impact, and less flattering motive that may also be present.","Core Logic":"I am producing a convincing reason so I do not have to face the more difficult reason.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Weak accountability; repeated harm; self-deception; distrust; distance between stated and enacted values.","Core Fear":"Being wrong makes me unsafe; accountability means humiliation; good people must have pure motives; admitting error means losing authority.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"There’s a perfectly reasonable explanation for why I did it.; I had no realistic alternative.; The outcome makes sense once you understand the context.; I’m explaining, not avoiding responsibility.; What I did was necessary under the circumstances.; The real reason is more complicated than it looks.","Protective Move":"Rationalization is the protective construction of a plausible explanation that makes a choice, failure, impulse, or harmful behavior feel reasonable while obscuring the more uncomfortable motive or impact.","Pattern ID":"PP-RATIONALIZATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Shame decreases when a respectable explanation is constructed.","Freer Expression":"Explanation joined with ownership.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Meaning-making; contextual thinking; verbal reasoning; ability to find causes.","Observable Cues":"Reframing self-serving choices as necessity; explaining before acknowledging impact; selectively emphasizing facts; repeatedly changing reasons; using logic to avoid remorse or uncertainty.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Listen for context but return to observable impact and agreed standards. Avoid debating every detail when the central responsibility is already clear. May trigger Contempt, Interrogation, Keeping Score, Withdrawal, or Counter-Rationalization.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Autonomy, and Trust; avoids guilt, regret, selfishness, envy, fear, responsibility, and limitation.","Canonical Name":"Rationalization"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRationalization is the protective construction of a plausible explanation that makes a choice, failure, impulse, or harmful behavior feel reasonable while obscuring the more uncomfortable motive or impact.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nIntellectualizing; Denial; Minimizing; Externalization; Defensive Expertise; Excuse Making\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am producing a convincing reason so I do not have to face the more difficult reason.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- There’s a perfectly reasonable explanation for why I did it.\n- I had no realistic alternative.\n- The outcome makes sense once you understand the context.\n- I’m explaining, not avoiding responsibility.\n- What I did was necessary under the circumstances.\n- The real reason is more complicated than it looks.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nImmediate explanatory fluency; relief after finding a respectable reason; irritation when impact is discussed; explanations multiply when challenged.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReframing self-serving choices as necessity; explaining before acknowledging impact; selectively emphasizing facts; repeatedly changing reasons; using logic to avoid remorse or uncertainty.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Autonomy; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nFailure; inconsistency with values; criticism; guilt; unwanted consequences; exposure of mixed motives.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBeing wrong makes me unsafe; accountability means humiliation; good people must have pure motives; admitting error means losing authority.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGuilt; regret; selfishness; envy; fear; responsibility; limitation.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage — elegant theory shields bias. Ruler — necessity justifies control. Caregiver — intrusion is renamed help. Rebel — harm is justified as resistance. Creator — delay is framed as protecting quality. Explorer — abandonment is reframed as freedom.\n## Pattern Flow\nAction conflicts with values or causes harm → identity feels threatened → a respectable explanation is constructed → shame decreases → impact and motive remain unexamined → repetition becomes easier.\n## Often Appears With\nMinimizing; Defensiveness; Intellectualizing; Blame Shifting; Perfectionism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nMeaning-making; contextual thinking; verbal reasoning; ability to find causes.\n## Current Cost\nWeak accountability; repeated harm; self-deception; distrust; distance between stated and enacted values.\n## Freer Expression\nExplanation joined with ownership.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the explanation only after naming the choice, impact, and less flattering motive that may also be present.\n## Mira Language\n“Your explanation may be true. Before we settle there, what harder truth might also be true about why this happened?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nDoes the explanation change the impact? What motive would be hardest to admit? Are you seeking understanding or exemption?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nContext, legitimate constraints, and correcting an inaccurate accusation are not rationalization. Explanations can be true and still incomplete.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of plausible explanation replacing accountability, especially when reasons shift or impact is persistently bypassed.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHold explanation and responsibility together; name the behavior plainly; identify the protected self-image; choose one corrective action before further analysis.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nListen for context but return to observable impact and agreed standards. Avoid debating every detail when the central responsibility is already clear.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nStop arguing the justification, acknowledge the behavior and impact without qualification, disclose the fuller motive where appropriate, and demonstrate change through a concrete corrective action.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Contempt, Interrogation, Keeping Score, Withdrawal, or Counter-Rationalization. Often triggered by Criticism, Moral Superiority, Shame, or another person’s Absolutism. Reinforcing stories: “You will never understand my reasons” and “You will explain anything rather than take responsibility.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat explanation am I using to avoid a truth that would require change?"},
  "PP-REACTION-FORMATION": {"name":"Reaction Formation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Denial; Performance of an Emotion or Role; Moral Superiority; Overcompensation; Compartmented Persona; Image Management; Emotional Suppression; Performance of Likability.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent — performs purity against unwanted impulses. Warrior — exaggerated toughness covers fear. Caregiver — excessive giving covers resentment. Rebel — contempt for belonging covers longing to belong. Lover — dramatic devotion covers ambivalence.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Privately name the disallowed feeling without treating acknowledgment as endorsement or action.","Core Logic":"I am performing the opposite of what feels too dangerous to acknowledge.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Inauthenticity; emotional whiplash; judgment of others; hidden resentment; unstable self-understanding.","Core Fear":"Certain feelings make me unlovable; contradiction means hypocrisy; my identity must remain pure; vulnerable needs invite rejection.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to prove I feel the opposite.; I must show how completely I reject that impulse.; The stronger I act, the less anyone will see the fear.; I’ll be extra warm so no one notices the resentment.; I need to demonstrate that I am not that kind of person.; If I admit the opposite feeling, it will define me.","Protective Move":"Reaction Formation protects against an unacceptable feeling or impulse by expressing its opposite with unusual intensity, such as exaggerated warmth covering hostility or moral condemnation covering attraction.","Pattern ID":"PP-REACTION-FORMATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary moral or emotional safety returns when the opposite expression intensifies.","Freer Expression":"Values without disowning complexity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Commitment to values; self-restraint; capacity to choose behavior rather than act impulsively.","Observable Cues":"Overly enthusiastic affection toward someone resented; severe condemnation of a disowned impulse; exaggerated independence covering dependency; conspicuous confidence covering fear.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Avoid exposing or humiliating the contradiction. Ask gently about mixed feelings and hold boundaries around harmful moralizing or overcompensation. May trigger Distrust, Mind Reading, Withdrawal, Testing the Bond, or Counter-Performance.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Belonging, Safety, and Identity Coherence; avoids attraction, resentment, fear, dependency, envy, tenderness, and ambivalence.","Canonical Name":"Reaction Formation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nReaction Formation protects against an unacceptable feeling or impulse by expressing its opposite with unusual intensity, such as exaggerated warmth covering hostility or moral condemnation covering attraction.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nDenial; Performance of an Emotion or Role; Moral Superiority; Overcompensation; Compartmented Persona\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am performing the opposite of what feels too dangerous to acknowledge.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to prove I feel the opposite.\n- I must show how completely I reject that impulse.\n- The stronger I act, the less anyone will see the fear.\n- I’ll be extra warm so no one notices the resentment.\n- I need to demonstrate that I am not that kind of person.\n- If I admit the opposite feeling, it will define me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nExcessive insistence on a feeling; emotional strain beneath the display; disproportionate moral certainty; fear of what a softer admission would mean.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOverly enthusiastic affection toward someone resented; severe condemnation of a disowned impulse; exaggerated independence covering dependency; conspicuous confidence covering fear.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Belonging; Safety; Identity Coherence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nTaboo desire; unacceptable anger; identity threat; shame; social judgment; dependency needs.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nCertain feelings make me unlovable; contradiction means hypocrisy; my identity must remain pure; vulnerable needs invite rejection.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAttraction; resentment; fear; dependency; envy; tenderness; ambivalence.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent — performs purity against unwanted impulses. Warrior — exaggerated toughness covers fear. Caregiver — excessive giving covers resentment. Rebel — contempt for belonging covers longing to belong. Lover — dramatic devotion covers ambivalence.\n## Pattern Flow\nDisallowed feeling arises → identity or belonging feels threatened → opposite expression intensifies → temporary moral or emotional safety returns → authentic feeling remains unintegrated → rigidity and relational confusion increase.\n## Often Appears With\nDenial; Moral Superiority; Image Management; Emotional Suppression; Performance of Likability.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCommitment to values; self-restraint; capacity to choose behavior rather than act impulsively.\n## Current Cost\nInauthenticity; emotional whiplash; judgment of others; hidden resentment; unstable self-understanding.\n## Freer Expression\nValues without disowning complexity.\n## One Act of Volition\nPrivately name the disallowed feeling without treating acknowledgment as endorsement or action.\n## Mira Language\n“Sometimes an unusually intense opposite response protects us from a feeling that seems unacceptable. Is there a quieter, contradictory feeling underneath?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would this expression mean if its opposite were also present? Can you acknowledge the feeling without acting on it? What identity are you protecting?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nChoosing values over impulses is not Reaction Formation. Strong affection, conviction, or courage may be genuine.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated exaggerated opposite expression with tension, contradiction, or later leakage of the disowned feeling.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nNormalize ambivalence, separate feeling from action, reduce the performance, and choose behavior based on values rather than denial.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAvoid exposing or humiliating the contradiction. Ask gently about mixed feelings and hold boundaries around harmful moralizing or overcompensation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge how the exaggerated opposite expression misled, judged, or pressured the other person; name the mixed feeling honestly; and establish a more proportionate, congruent way of relating.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Distrust, Mind Reading, Withdrawal, Testing the Bond, or Counter-Performance. Often triggered by Shame, Moral Judgment, Identity Pressure, or another person’s demand for certainty. Reinforcing stories: “I must prove I am not that” and “Your intensity makes me suspect the opposite.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat feeling might I be trying to disprove through the strength of its opposite?"},
  "PP-REASSURANCE-SEEKING": {"name":"Reassurance Seeking","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Testing the Bond; Clinging; Confirmation Seeking; Mind Reading; Compulsive Contact; Emotional Reasoning.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — repeated confirmation of love. Innocent — certainty that everything is okay. Sage — endless checking for cognitive certainty. Caregiver — checking that no one is upset. Ruler — seeking guarantees that the system will hold.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"After one clear answer, wait through one wave of returning doubt before asking again, and identify whether any new evidence exists.","Core Logic":"I need to hear it again because the last reassurance did not stay inside me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Anxiety reinforcement; partner fatigue; reduced credibility of reassurance; escalating checking; dependence on external regulation.","Core Fear":"Safety can vanish without warning; words are unreliable; I will miss the sign that something is wrong; certainty must be maintained externally.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Are you sure you’re not upset with me?; Can you promise everything is okay?; I know you answered, but I need to hear it again.; Has anything changed since the last time I asked?; Please tell me you’re not leaving.; The reassurance helped, but the doubt is back.","Protective Move":"Reassurance Seeking is the repeated attempt to reduce anxiety by obtaining certainty, affirmation, or relational confirmation that does not remain emotionally settled for long.","Pattern ID":"PP-REASSURANCE-SEEKING","Short-Term Payoff":"Anxiety briefly drops when reassurance is requested and received.","Freer Expression":"Reassurance received and metabolized.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Relational attentiveness; desire for clarity; openness about fear; commitment to security.","Observable Cues":"Repeatedly asking whether someone is angry, leaving, satisfied, or certain; rechecking decisions; requesting guarantees; revisiting resolved concerns without new evidence.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Answer clearly once, avoid ridicule, and set a compassionate limit on repetitive checking while supporting self-regulation. May trigger Withdrawal, Irritation, Defensiveness, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Belonging, Safety, and Self-Esteem; avoids uncertainty, waiting, vulnerability, limits of guarantees, and responsibility for self-soothing.","Canonical Name":"Reassurance Seeking"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nReassurance Seeking is the repeated attempt to reduce anxiety by obtaining certainty, affirmation, or relational confirmation that does not remain emotionally settled for long.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nTesting the Bond; Clinging; Confirmation Seeking; Mind Reading; Compulsive Contact\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need to hear it again because the last reassurance did not stay inside me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Are you sure you’re not upset with me?\n- Can you promise everything is okay?\n- I know you answered, but I need to hear it again.\n- Has anything changed since the last time I asked?\n- Please tell me you’re not leaving.\n- The reassurance helped, but the doubt is back.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nTemporary relief after reassurance; rapid return of doubt; urge to ask the same question in new forms; difficulty tolerating ambiguity; fear that silence reverses prior affirmation.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeatedly asking whether someone is angry, leaving, satisfied, or certain; rechecking decisions; requesting guarantees; revisiting resolved concerns without new evidence.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Belonging; Safety; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDelayed responses; ambiguous tone; mistakes; relationship distance; bodily anxiety; uncertain outcomes.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nSafety can vanish without warning; words are unreliable; I will miss the sign that something is wrong; certainty must be maintained externally.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; waiting; vulnerability; limits of guarantees; responsibility for self-soothing.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — repeated confirmation of love. Innocent — certainty that everything is okay. Sage — endless checking for cognitive certainty. Caregiver — checking that no one is upset. Ruler — seeking guarantees that the system will hold.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguity appears → trust or safety feels threatened → reassurance is requested → anxiety briefly drops → internal tolerance does not grow → doubt returns and questioning intensifies.\n## Often Appears With\nMind Reading; Clinging; Testing the Bond; Emotional Reasoning; Compulsive Contact.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nRelational attentiveness; desire for clarity; openness about fear; commitment to security.\n## Current Cost\nAnxiety reinforcement; partner fatigue; reduced credibility of reassurance; escalating checking; dependence on external regulation.\n## Freer Expression\nReassurance received and metabolized.\n## One Act of Volition\nAfter one clear answer, wait through one wave of returning doubt before asking again, and identify whether any new evidence exists.\n## Mira Language\n“You received an answer, but the fear returned. Would more reassurance solve the concern, or does your nervous system need help holding uncertainty?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat changed since the last reassurance? What would help the answer remain inside you? Is there new information or returning fear?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nClarifying inconsistent behavior, responding to genuine deception, or seeking support during crisis is not automatically Reassurance Seeking.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated requests that provide only short-lived relief despite consistent answers and no material new evidence.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the fear, receive one answer deliberately, regulate the body, and practice distinguishing renewed anxiety from renewed evidence.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAnswer clearly once, avoid ridicule, and set a compassionate limit on repetitive checking while supporting self-regulation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where repeated checking became pressure or interrogation. Repair through respecting prior answers, establishing a signal for genuine new concern, and rebuilding reliability on both sides.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Withdrawal, Irritation, Defensiveness, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by inconsistency, Mind Reading, delayed contact, or prior betrayal. The loop becomes “Your distance proves danger” and “Your questioning makes me need distance.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat answer have I already received that fear keeps asking me to obtain again?"},
  "PP-RECIPROCITY-ANXIETY": {"name":"Reciprocity Anxiety","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Keeping Score; Relationship-Bound Worth; Reassurance Seeking; Comparison; Scarcity Hoarding; Emotional Withholding; Resentment.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver audits care; Lover measures devotion; Ruler formalizes exchange; Merchant archetype turns relationship into ledger.","Migration Notes":"Batch 12 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Source heading variants were normalized to established canonical field labels. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source cautions against dismissing real exploitation, inequitable labor, financial abuse, and one-sided relationships rather than assigning one explicit controlled safety flag.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"12","One Act of Volition":"Name one unmet reciprocity need directly without presenting the entire ledger.","Core Logic":"I need the exchange to stay visibly balanced so I am not used, indebted, or less valued.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Transactional intimacy; inhibited receiving; resentment; inability to tolerate seasons of asymmetry.","Core Fear":"Giving creates debt or vulnerability; people take without returning; needing more means being weaker; imbalance predicts abandonment.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to make sure I am not giving more than they are.; If I receive too much, I may owe them.; I should wait for them to initiate this time.; Caring more would put me in the weaker position.; Every exchange needs to prove the relationship is balanced.; I need to track the ledger so I am not exploited.","Protective Move":"Reciprocity Anxiety is persistent monitoring of whether care, effort, attention, generosity, or vulnerability is being returned in equivalent measure, in order to prevent exploitation, indebtedness, or being the person who cares more. It differs from healthy reciprocity because ordinary asymmetry becomes a threat signal.","Pattern ID":"PP-RECIPROCITY-ANXIETY","Short-Term Payoff":"Monitoring and matching create temporary protection from exploitation.","Freer Expression":"Mutuality assessed across time, context, consent, and capacity.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Fairness, mutuality, stewardship, sensitivity to exploitation and invisible labor.","Observable Cues":"Matching response times or affection; withholding until the other initiates; declining help to avoid debt; measuring gifts, labor, disclosure, or contact.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Take inequity seriously, make invisible labor visible, avoid vague reassurance, and create explicit agreements where needed. May trigger Keeping Score, Resentment, Emotional Withholding, Overfunctioning, or Underfunctioning in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Fairness, dignity, belonging, trust, agency, care, and predictability; avoids need, gratitude, generosity without control, temporary dependence, uncertainty, and grief.","Canonical Name":"Reciprocity Anxiety"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nReciprocity Anxiety is persistent monitoring of whether care, effort, attention, generosity, or vulnerability is being returned in equivalent measure, in order to prevent exploitation, indebtedness, or being the person who cares more. It differs from healthy reciprocity because ordinary asymmetry becomes a threat signal.\n## Domain\nBelonging, Fairness, and Exchange\n## Related Patterns\nKeeping Score; Relationship-Bound Worth; Reassurance Seeking; Comparison; Scarcity Hoarding; Emotional Withholding\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need the exchange to stay visibly balanced so I am not used, indebted, or less valued.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to make sure I am not giving more than they are.\n- If I receive too much, I may owe them.\n- I should wait for them to initiate this time.\n- Caring more would put me in the weaker position.\n- Every exchange needs to prove the relationship is balanced.\n- I need to track the ledger so I am not exploited.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDiscomfort receiving more than giving; resentment when effort is not mirrored quickly; fear of appearing needy; tracking who initiated or contributed last.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nMatching response times or affection; withholding until the other initiates; declining help to avoid debt; measuring gifts, labor, disclosure, or contact.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nFairness; dignity; belonging; trust; agency; care; predictability.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUneven labor; receiving help; delayed reciprocity; financial or emotional dependence; prior exploitation; uncertain commitment.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nGiving creates debt or vulnerability; people take without returning; needing more means being weaker; imbalance predicts abandonment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nNeed; gratitude; generosity without control; temporary dependence; uncertainty; grief.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver audits care; Lover measures devotion; Ruler formalizes exchange; Merchant archetype turns relationship into ledger.\n## Pattern Flow\nUneven exchange → fairness or dignity threatened → monitoring and matching intensify → temporary protection from exploitation → spontaneity and generosity decline → relationship feels transactional and anxiety rises.\n## Often Appears With\nKeeping Score; Emotional Withholding; Scarcity Hoarding; Relationship-Bound Worth; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nFairness, mutuality, stewardship, sensitivity to exploitation and invisible labor.\n## Current Cost\nTransactional intimacy; inhibited receiving; resentment; inability to tolerate seasons of asymmetry.\n## Freer Expression\nMutuality assessed across time, context, consent, and capacity.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one unmet reciprocity need directly without presenting the entire ledger.\n## Mira Language\n“Is there a real pattern of exploitation, or is temporary asymmetry activating fear that you will become indebted or less valued?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat time horizon are you using? Are the contributions different but meaningful? What agreement or boundary is actually needed?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nChronic exploitation, inequitable labor, financial abuse, and one-sided relationships are real. Mira must not use this pattern to dismiss legitimate inequity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated monitoring or matching across ordinary exchanges, especially when no material exploitation is established.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nDistinguish current inequity from anxiety about asymmetry; widen the time horizon; ask directly; allow bounded receiving without immediate repayment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nTake inequity seriously, make invisible labor visible, avoid vague reassurance, and create explicit agreements where needed.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where ledger behavior diminished generosity or where real inequity was ignored; clarify contributions, needs, capacity, and future agreements.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Keeping Score, Resentment, Emotional Withholding, Overfunctioning, or Underfunctioning in others. Often triggered by inconsistent reciprocity, scarcity, or previous exploitation. Stories become “I am always giving more” and “Nothing I give will ever count.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I protecting fairness—or requiring every exchange to prove my value immediately?"},
  "PP-REJECTION-SENSITIVITY": {"name":"Rejection Sensitivity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Mind Reading; Hypervigilance; Testing the Bond; Clinging; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Personalization; Appeasement.","Archetypal Role":"Lover seeks immediate proof of devotion; Orphan anticipates exclusion; Warrior attacks before being dismissed; Caregiver overadapts to remain needed.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Name the observable cue separately from the feared meaning before responding.","Core Logic":"I am treating possible rejection as if it is already happening.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"False alarms; exhaustion; conflict; dependence on reassurance; missed benign explanations.","Core Fear":"Belonging can disappear suddenly; disapproval means abandonment; I must detect rejection before it blindsides me.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"That tone change means they may be pulling away.; A delayed reply feels like rejection already happening.; I need reassurance before this gets worse.; I should withdraw before they can exclude me.; Their changed plans probably mean I no longer matter.; I need to react now so rejection cannot blindside me.","Protective Move":"Rejection Sensitivity is the protective readiness to detect and react to possible exclusion, disapproval, or abandonment before the evidence is clear, so that rejection can be prevented, escaped, or answered first.","Pattern ID":"PP-REJECTION-SENSITIVITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Reassurance, appeasement, accusation, or withdrawal brings brief relief.","Freer Expression":"Attunement with verification.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Social attunement; loyalty; sensitivity to relational shifts.","Observable Cues":"Repeatedly checking relational meaning; overinterpreting neutral cues; seeking reassurance; withdrawing, appeasing, accusing, or rejecting first.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer clarity without entering endless reassurance. Name changes directly, answer reasonable questions, and maintain boundaries if accusations or tests escalate. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, or Withdrawing Before Being Left.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, Self-Esteem, and Safety; avoids uncertainty, grief, dependence, ordinary relational distance, and the possibility of being misunderstood.","Canonical Name":"Rejection Sensitivity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRejection Sensitivity is the protective readiness to detect and react to possible exclusion, disapproval, or abandonment before the evidence is clear, so that rejection can be prevented, escaped, or answered first.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Belonging, and Social Threat\n## Related Patterns\nMind Reading; Hypervigilance; Testing the Bond; Clinging; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Personalization.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am treating possible rejection as if it is already happening.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- That tone change means they may be pulling away.\n- A delayed reply feels like rejection already happening.\n- I need reassurance before this gets worse.\n- I should withdraw before they can exclude me.\n- Their changed plans probably mean I no longer matter.\n- I need to react now so rejection cannot blindside me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSharp alarm after small changes in tone; difficulty tolerating delayed replies; rapid shame or anger; scanning for evidence of exclusion.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeatedly checking relational meaning; overinterpreting neutral cues; seeking reassurance; withdrawing, appeasing, accusing, or rejecting first.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Self-Esteem; Safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguous tone; delayed contact; criticism; social comparison; changed plans; divided attention; unfamiliar groups.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBelonging can disappear suddenly; disapproval means abandonment; I must detect rejection before it blindsides me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; grief; dependence; ordinary relational distance; the possibility of being misunderstood.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover seeks immediate proof of devotion; Orphan anticipates exclusion; Warrior attacks before being dismissed; Caregiver overadapts to remain needed.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguous social cue → belonging feels threatened → cue is interpreted as rejection → reassurance, appeasement, accusation, or withdrawal brings brief relief → relationships become more strained and ambiguous.\n## Often Appears With\nMind Reading; Personalization; Clinging; Testing the Bond; Appeasement.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSocial attunement; loyalty; sensitivity to relational shifts.\n## Current Cost\nFalse alarms; exhaustion; conflict; dependence on reassurance; missed benign explanations.\n## Freer Expression\nAttunement with verification.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the observable cue separately from the feared meaning before responding.\n## Mira Language\n“Something in this interaction seems to have registered as rejection. What did you directly observe, and what meaning did your protective system add?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence supports rejection? What else could explain the cue? What direct question would reduce guessing?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nActual exclusion, discrimination, betrayal, or abandonment must not be reframed as oversensitivity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of strong rejection interpretations from ambiguous or low-information cues across contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate the alarm, separate cue from conclusion, and choose direct inquiry over preemptive defense.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer clarity without entering endless reassurance. Name changes directly, answer reasonable questions, and maintain boundaries if accusations or tests escalate.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where an unverified rejection story led to accusation, withdrawal, appeasement, or punishment; clarify the actual event and agree on a direct-checking practice.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Defensiveness, or Withdrawing Before Being Left. Often triggered by ambiguity, Image Management, or inconsistent contact. Stories become “I am about to be abandoned” and “Nothing I do can reassure you.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I reacting to the fear of rejection rather than the evidence in front of me?"},
  "PP-RELATIONSHIP-BOUND-WORTH": {"name":"Relationship-Bound Worth","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Fusion; Clinging; Idealization; Self-Erasure; Performance of Likability.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — equates being loved with being valuable; Everyman — needs inclusion to feel real; Caregiver — earns worth through being needed; Innocent — treats relationship as proof of goodness.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Name one value, identity, or commitment that remains yours regardless of relational status.","Core Logic":"Your choosing me has become evidence that I am worthy.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Loss of standards; dependency; vulnerability to coercion; identity instability.","Core Fear":"I am lovable only when chosen; being alone means being defective; love proves worth.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If you choose me, then I matter.; Being alone means something is wrong with me.; Your attention tells me whether I’m worthy.; I can’t lose this relationship and still feel whole.; I need to be wanted to feel valuable.; If you leave, what does that say about me?","Protective Move":"Relationship-Bound Worth is the protective dependence of self-value on being chosen, desired, needed, or retained by another person.","Pattern ID":"PP-RELATIONSHIP-BOUND-WORTH","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary validation arrives.","Freer Expression":"Worth that can participate in love without depending on it.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Capacity for devotion and relational investment.","Observable Cues":"Tolerating mistreatment to preserve the bond; abandoning standards; chasing validation; comparing relational status.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer care without becoming the sole regulator of worth; avoid threats of abandonment as leverage. May trigger Overfunctioning, Control, Emotional Distancing, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Belonging, and Trust; avoids self-definition, grief, uncertainty, and ordinary loneliness.","Canonical Name":"Relationship-Bound Worth"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRelationship-Bound Worth is the protective dependence of self-value on being chosen, desired, needed, or retained by another person.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nFusion; Clinging; Idealization; Self-Erasure; Performance of Likability\n## Recognition Sentence\nYour choosing me has become evidence that I am worthy.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If you choose me, then I matter.\n- Being alone means something is wrong with me.\n- Your attention tells me whether I’m worthy.\n- I can’t lose this relationship and still feel whole.\n- I need to be wanted to feel valuable.\n- If you leave, what does that say about me?\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nWorth rises and falls with attention; rejection feels annihilating; singlehood feels like failure; conflict threatens identity.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTolerating mistreatment to preserve the bond; abandoning standards; chasing validation; comparing relational status.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Belonging; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nRejection; breakup; reduced affection; comparison; partner independence.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am lovable only when chosen; being alone means being defective; love proves worth.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nSelf-definition; grief; uncertainty; ordinary loneliness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — equates being loved with being valuable; Everyman — needs inclusion to feel real; Caregiver — earns worth through being needed; Innocent — treats relationship as proof of goodness.\n## Pattern Flow\nRelational uncertainty appears → worth collapses → appeasement or pursuit intensifies → temporary validation arrives → self-worth becomes more externally dependent.\n## Often Appears With\nFusion; Clinging; Self-Erasure; Idealization.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCapacity for devotion and relational investment.\n## Current Cost\nLoss of standards; dependency; vulnerability to coercion; identity instability.\n## Freer Expression\nWorth that can participate in love without depending on it.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one value, identity, or commitment that remains yours regardless of relational status.\n## Mira Language\n“The relationship matters deeply. I also wonder whether it has become the evidence you use to decide whether you matter.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWho are you when not being chosen? What remains worthy during distance? What would love add rather than prove?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGrief after rejection is not evidence of relationship-bound worth.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated collapse of self-value based primarily on relational attention or status.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRebuild worth through values, competence, community, and self-trust rather than repeated relational proof.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer care without becoming the sole regulator of worth; avoid threats of abandonment as leverage.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where fear of losing worth produced appeasement, pressure, or tolerance of harm; restore standards, choice, and multiple sources of identity.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Control, Emotional Distancing, or Resentment. Often triggered by rejection, comparison, inconsistent affection, or devaluation. The loop becomes: “I need you to choose me so I can matter” and “I am responsible for holding up your entire worth.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat part of my worth have I asked this relationship to carry?"},
  "PP-RELATIONSHIP-OVERINVESTMENT": {"name":"Relationship Overinvestment","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Fantasy Bonding; Fusion; Relationship-Bound Worth; Rescuing; Overfunctioning; Clinging.","Archetypal Role":"Lover makes the bond carry identity and future; Caregiver carries disproportionate labor; Hero tries to save the relationship through effort; Orphan makes belonging depend on preserving the bond.","Migration Notes":"Batch 16 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective function, common expressions, trigger phrases, and distinction. Missing canonical sections were authored to the established 27-field standard while preserving the supplied mechanism. Spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented to six; status remains Drafted pending review. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"16","One Act of Volition":"List what each person is reliably contributing now and reduce one investment that is not reciprocally supported.","Core Logic":"If I invest enough of myself, I can make this relationship secure.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Self-neglect; unequal labor; resentment; distorted judgment; dependency; delayed recognition of incompatibility.","Core Fear":"If I do not give enough, the relationship will fail, I will be left, or I will lose the future I attached to it.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If I give this everything, it will become secure.; I need to prove how committed I am.; This relationship has to work.; I can carry more until they are ready.; If I slow down, the bond may disappear.; My future depends on making this relationship succeed.","Protective Move":"Relationship Overinvestment concentrates disproportionate time, identity, emotional energy, responsibility, or future meaning into a relationship beyond what reciprocity, stability, or actual intimacy supports.","Pattern ID":"PP-RELATIONSHIP-OVERINVESTMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Hope and temporary security rise when investment intensifies.","Freer Expression":"Devotion proportionate to mutual reality.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Devotion; loyalty; generosity; relational imagination; willingness to work for connection.","Observable Cues":"Reorganizing life rapidly around another person; carrying most relational labor; neglecting other bonds or needs; escalating commitment faster than mutual trust develops.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Name the actual reciprocity and present evidence; rebalance labor, commitments, and pace without shaming devotion. May trigger Emotional Distancing, Underfunctioning, Strategic Ambiguity, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, trust, self-esteem, purpose, and safety; avoids uncertainty, grief, loneliness, mismatch, and the possibility that effort cannot create reciprocity.","Canonical Name":"Relationship Overinvestment"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRelationship Overinvestment is the protective concentration of disproportionate time, identity, emotional energy, responsibility, or future meaning into a relationship beyond what reciprocity, stability, or actual intimacy supports. It differs from deep mutual commitment because the investment is anxiety-driven and insufficiently matched by evidence.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Reciprocity, and Relational Security\n## Related Patterns\nFantasy Bonding; Fusion; Relationship-Bound Worth; Rescuing; Overfunctioning\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I invest enough of myself, I can make this relationship secure.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If I give this everything, it will become secure.\n- I need to prove how committed I am.\n- This relationship has to work.\n- I can carry more until they are ready.\n- If I slow down, the bond may disappear.\n- My future depends on making this relationship succeed.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to give more; fear that ordinary pacing means loss; identity narrowing around the bond; hope rising with sacrifice; difficulty noticing mismatch.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReorganizing life rapidly around another person; carrying most relational labor; neglecting other bonds or needs; escalating commitment faster than mutual trust develops.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; trust; self-esteem; purpose; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguous commitment; intermittent attention; loneliness; major life transition; fear of abandonment; another person’s instability.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove must be earned through effort; relationships survive only if I carry them; being indispensable prevents abandonment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; grief; loneliness; incompatibility; limited reciprocity; the possibility that effort cannot create mutuality.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover makes the bond carry identity and future; Caregiver carries disproportionate labor; Hero tries to save the relationship through effort; Orphan makes belonging depend on preserving the bond.\n## Pattern Flow\nBond feels uncertain → belonging feels threatened → investment and responsibility intensify → hope and temporary security rise → mismatch and self-neglect deepen → even more investment feels necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nFusion; Fantasy Bonding; Rescuing; Overfunctioning; Clinging.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDevotion; loyalty; generosity; relational imagination; willingness to work for connection.\n## Current Cost\nSelf-neglect; unequal labor; resentment; distorted judgment; dependency; delayed recognition of incompatibility.\n## Freer Expression\nDevotion proportionate to mutual reality.\n## One Act of Volition\nList what each person is reliably contributing now and reduce one investment that is not reciprocally supported.\n## Mira Language\n“Your devotion may be real. I also notice that the relationship is carrying more of your identity and future than the current reciprocity may support.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat has been demonstrated repeatedly? What are you carrying that belongs to the other person? What becomes frightening if you invest at the pace of the actual relationship?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDeep commitment, caregiving, cultural interdependence, and temporary imbalance are not automatically overinvestment.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of disproportionate investment that outpaces reciprocity, stability, or demonstrated intimacy and produces self-neglect or relational distortion.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate devotion from fear-driven overextension, restore other sources of identity and support, and pace commitment according to repeated mutual action.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nName the actual reciprocity and present evidence; rebalance labor, commitments, and pace without shaming devotion.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where overinvestment created pressure, hidden contracts, resentment, or loss of self. Restore proportionate responsibility and clarify what the relationship can honestly support.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Emotional Distancing, Underfunctioning, Strategic Ambiguity, or Resentment. The loop becomes “I must give more to secure us” versus “Your investment creates pressure I cannot match.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I investing because the relationship supports it, and what am I investing to make the relationship become what I need?"},
  "PP-RESCUING": {"name":"Rescuing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Savior Identity; Overfunctioning; Martyrdom; Micromanaging; Boundary Collapse; Underfunctioning; Dependency.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — support becomes takeover. Hero — courage becomes compulsory saving. Ruler — stewardship becomes control. Lover — devotion becomes over-responsibility. Magician — insight becomes fixing without consent.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides role, capacity, disability-support, emergency, and safeguarding cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Ask, “What kind of help would preserve your agency?” before intervening.","Core Logic":"I am taking responsibility for what another person may need to face or choose.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; resentment; dependency loops; reduced agency; blurred responsibility; delayed learning; unequal relationships.","Core Fear":"My value comes from being needed; if I do not intervene, something terrible will happen; love means preventing pain; other people’s distress is my responsibility.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to step in before this gets worse.; They can’t handle this without me.; Helping means preventing their discomfort.; If I don’t take over, everything may collapse.; I’m responsible for fixing the situation.; Letting them face the consequence feels like abandonment.","Protective Move":"Rescuing is the protective move of taking over another person’s problem, consequence, decision, or developmental task in order to reduce distress, preserve one’s usefulness, or prevent feared harm.","Pattern ID":"PP-RESCUING","Short-Term Payoff":"Anxiety falls and importance rises when the rescuer intervenes or takes over.","Freer Expression":"Support without takeover.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Compassion; responsiveness; resourcefulness; courage; generosity; practical competence.","Observable Cues":"Solving problems without consent; absorbing consequences; doing tasks someone can reasonably do; giving advice or resources after refusal; taking over decisions; shielding someone from feedback or natural consequences.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appreciate the care while declining unwanted takeover. State what help is and is not useful, retain responsibility where possible, and avoid rewarding rescue by surrendering manageable tasks. May trigger Underfunctioning, Dependency, Resentment, Defensiveness, or Self-Erasure.","Emotional Function":"Protects Purpose, Belonging, Competence, Control, Self-Esteem, and Safety; avoids helplessness, grief, limits, another person’s autonomy, declined help, and one’s own unmet needs.","Canonical Name":"Rescuing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRescuing is the protective move of taking over another person’s problem, consequence, decision, or developmental task in order to reduce distress, preserve one’s usefulness, or prevent feared harm.\n## Domain\nCaretaking, Responsibility, and Agency\n## Related Patterns\nSavior Identity; Overfunctioning; Martyrdom; Micromanaging; Boundary Collapse; Underfunctioning; Dependency\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am taking responsibility for what another person may need to face or choose.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to step in before this gets worse.\n- They can’t handle this without me.\n- Helping means preventing their discomfort.\n- If I don’t take over, everything may collapse.\n- I’m responsible for fixing the situation.\n- Letting them face the consequence feels like abandonment.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to intervene before being asked. Anxiety when another person struggles, waits, or learns through consequences. Relief when you become indispensable. Guilt when allowing someone to carry their own responsibility. A belief that helping means preventing discomfort.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSolving problems without consent. Repeatedly absorbing consequences for another person. Doing tasks someone can reasonably do themselves. Giving advice or resources after a boundary or refusal. Taking over decisions in the name of care. Shielding someone from accurate feedback or natural consequences.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nPurpose; Belonging; Competence; Control; Self-Esteem; Safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAnother person’s distress; uncertainty; visible struggle; risk of failure; requests for help; fear of being unnecessary; memories of preventable harm.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy value comes from being needed. If I do not intervene, something terrible will happen. Love means preventing pain. Other people’s distress is my responsibility.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHelplessness; grief; limits; another person’s autonomy; the possibility that help will be declined; one’s own unmet needs.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — support becomes takeover. Hero — courage becomes compulsory saving. Ruler — stewardship becomes control. Lover — devotion becomes over-responsibility. Magician — insight becomes fixing without consent.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother person struggles → usefulness, safety, or control feels threatened → the rescuer intervenes or takes over → anxiety falls and importance rises → the other person’s agency or competence weakens → more rescuing appears necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nSavior Identity; Overfunctioning; Martyrdom; Micromanaging; Boundary Collapse; Resentment.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCompassion; responsiveness; resourcefulness; courage; generosity; practical competence.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; resentment; dependency loops; reduced agency; blurred responsibility; delayed learning; unequal relationships.\n## Freer Expression\nSupport without takeover.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk, “What kind of help would preserve your agency?” before intervening.\n## Mira Language\n“Your care is real, and I also notice you are carrying a task or consequence that may belong to someone else. Would support, accompaniment, or a clear limit serve better than rescue?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you afraid will happen if you do not step in? Was help requested, and can the other person decline it? Which part is yours to support, and which part is theirs to carry?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nEmergency aid, caregiving for genuine incapacity, parenting responsibilities, disability support, safeguarding, and mutual interdependence are not rescuing merely because one person does more. Context, capacity, consent, and role matter.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated unsolicited takeover, consequence absorption, or prevention of another person’s reasonable agency—not one generous act.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate the urgency to fix, assess actual risk and capacity, ask consent, and choose the smallest form of help that supports rather than replaces agency.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAppreciate the care while declining unwanted takeover. State what help is and is not useful, retain responsibility where possible, and avoid rewarding rescue by repeatedly surrendering manageable tasks.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where intervention overrode consent, implied incompetence, or created obligation. Return decisions and consequences, renegotiate roles, and demonstrate support through agreed assistance rather than unilateral action.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Dependency, Resentment, Defensiveness, or Self-Erasure. Often triggered by visible distress, helpless presentation, unreliable follow-through, or real vulnerability. The reinforcing story may become: “Someone else will handle it” on one side and “If I do not take over, everything will collapse” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I offering help that quietly replaces another person’s agency?"},
  "PP-RESENTMENT": {"name":"Resentment","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Keeping Score; Self-Erasure; People-Pleasing; Emotional Distancing; Devaluation.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver resents unreciprocated care; Everyperson tracks unfairness; Ruler remembers disloyalty; Lover preserves betrayal; Warrior holds grievance as readiness; Creator resents unrecognized contribution.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Convert one grievance into a direct request, boundary, repair conversation, or conscious decision to stop seeking repayment.","Core Logic":"I must keep the injury alive because it has not been understood, repaired, or prevented from happening again.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Chronic distance; indirect hostility; reduced joy; globalized judgment; stalled decisions; relational corrosion.","Core Fear":"My needs do not count; fairness will not be restored unless I remember; speaking directly is unsafe or futile.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I can’t forget what this cost me.; Nothing has really made this right.; I keep doing more while the debt grows.; If I let this go, it will happen again.; You still don’t understand what you did.; I need to remember because no one else will.","Protective Move":"Resentment is the protective preservation of remembered unfairness, unmet obligation, or unacknowledged injury so that the person does not forget the cost, surrender a claim, or become vulnerable to repetition.","Pattern ID":"PP-RESENTMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Memory provides temporary protection and moral clarity.","Freer Expression":"Remembered truth with active choice.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Moral memory; fairness; boundary awareness; refusal to normalize exploitation.","Observable Cues":"Coldness; indirect refusal; recalling old injuries during new conflicts; withholding warmth; complying while accumulating grievance.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Listen without demanding quick release, acknowledge valid impact, clarify what can and cannot be repaired, and do not treat warmth as proof that accountability is complete. May trigger Defensiveness, Minimizing, Contempt, Emotional Distancing, or Counter-Keeping Score.","Emotional Function":"Protects Fairness, Trust, Autonomy, Belonging, and Self-Esteem; avoids grief, direct conflict, final decisions, vulnerability, and accepting that repayment may never come.","Canonical Name":"Resentment"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nResentment is the protective preservation of remembered unfairness, unmet obligation, or unacknowledged injury so that the person does not forget the cost, surrender a claim, or become vulnerable to repetition.\n## Domain\nAccountability, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nKeeping Score; Self-Erasure; People-Pleasing; Emotional Distancing; Devaluation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI must keep the injury alive because it has not been understood, repaired, or prevented from happening again.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I can’t forget what this cost me.\n- Nothing has really made this right.\n- I keep doing more while the debt grows.\n- If I let this go, it will happen again.\n- You still don’t understand what you did.\n- I need to remember because no one else will.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nReplaying inequity; bitterness around requests; reduced generosity; a sense that present interactions carry old unpaid debt.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nColdness; indirect refusal; recalling old injuries during new conflicts; withholding warmth; complying while accumulating grievance.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nFairness; Trust; Autonomy; Belonging; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUnequal labor; repeated boundary violations; absent acknowledgment; broken promises; forced forgiveness; unspoken expectations.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy needs do not count; fairness will not be restored unless I remember; speaking directly is unsafe or futile.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; direct conflict; final decisions; vulnerability; accepting that repayment may never come.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver resents unreciprocated care; Everyperson tracks unfairness; Ruler remembers disloyalty; Lover preserves betrayal; Warrior holds grievance as readiness; Creator resents unrecognized contribution.\n## Pattern Flow\nInjury or inequity occurs → fairness or trust feels threatened → grievance is preserved → memory provides temporary protection and moral clarity → direct repair or boundary action is delayed → bitterness expands into unrelated interactions.\n## Often Appears With\nKeeping Score; People-Pleasing; Self-Erasure; Emotional Distancing; Devaluation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nMoral memory; fairness; boundary awareness; refusal to normalize exploitation.\n## Current Cost\nChronic distance; indirect hostility; reduced joy; globalized judgment; stalled decisions; relational corrosion.\n## Freer Expression\nRemembered truth with active choice.\n## One Act of Volition\nConvert one grievance into a direct request, boundary, repair conversation, or conscious decision to stop seeking repayment.\n## Mira Language\n“The resentment may be preserving something that was never acknowledged. What truth, boundary, or decision is the grievance asking you to make now?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat remains unpaid—labor, apology, safety, or recognition? Have you stated the need directly? Is continued closeness compatible with the evidence?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nResentment can signal genuine exploitation or unresolved harm. The goal is not premature forgiveness or restored closeness.\n## Evidence Threshold\nPersistent grievance carried across time and interactions, especially when direct request, boundary, or decision remains blocked.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the original injury precisely, distinguish past from present, decide what repair is possible, and act through request, boundary, grief, or ending rather than indefinite moral bookkeeping.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nListen without demanding quick release, acknowledge valid impact, clarify what can and cannot be repaired, and do not treat warmth as proof that accountability is complete.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nRepair requires acknowledgment of the underlying inequity, concrete restitution or behavioral change when possible, and freedom for the injured person to decide the pace and degree of renewed trust.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Minimizing, Contempt, Emotional Distancing, or Counter-Keeping Score. Often triggered by People-Pleasing, Self-Erasure, broken agreements, and Blame Shifting. The loop becomes: “I must keep the ledger because you will never own the debt” and “Nothing I do will ever clear the record.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat action is my resentment asking for that memory alone cannot accomplish?"},
  "PP-RESPONSIBILITY-INFLATION": {"name":"Responsibility Inflation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Overresponsibility; Overfunctioning; Rescuing; Personalization; Micromanaging; Perfectionism.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver assumes total ownership; Ruler tries to prevent every failure; Hero believes everything depends on them; Sage mistakes influence for causation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 16 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective logic, common expressions, trigger phrases, and differentiation. Missing sections authored to full canonical standard; spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented to six. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"16","One Act of Volition":"Separate what you caused, influenced, agreed to, and could not control before taking action.","Core Logic":"If I take responsibility for everything, nothing can fall apart and no one can fault me.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; guilt; enabling; distorted accountability; resentment; impaired autonomy in others.","Core Fear":"If I do not take ownership of everything, harm, blame, chaos, or disappointment will follow.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It’s all on me.; I should have prevented this.; If I don’t handle it, no one will.; Their reaction is my responsibility.; If something goes wrong, it means I failed.; I need to own every possible consequence.","Protective Move":"Responsibility Inflation expands one’s sense of causal or moral ownership beyond realistic responsibility in order to prevent blame, uncertainty, disappointment, or loss of control.","Pattern ID":"PP-RESPONSIBILITY-INFLATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Control and moral safety rise when ownership expands.","Freer Expression":"Accurate responsibility with clear limits.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Responsibility; foresight; reliability; conscience; care.","Observable Cues":"Taking ownership for others’ emotions, decisions, outcomes, or failures; compulsive prevention and repair; difficulty distinguishing influence from responsibility.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify actual role, influence, agreement, and control; resist transferring others’ choices or emotions into the person’s ownership. May trigger Underfunctioning, Dependency, Entitlement, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, competence, self-esteem, control, and belonging; avoids uncertainty, helplessness, blame, limits, and others’ autonomy.","Canonical Name":"Responsibility Inflation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nResponsibility Inflation is the protective expansion of one’s sense of causal or moral ownership beyond realistic responsibility in order to prevent blame, uncertainty, disappointment, or loss of control. It differs from simply carrying too much because the defining mechanism is inflated ownership.\n## Domain\nResponsibility, Control, and Causal Attribution\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Overresponsibility; Overfunctioning; Rescuing; Personalization; Micromanaging\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I take responsibility for everything, nothing can fall apart and no one can fault me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It’s all on me.\n- I should have prevented this.\n- If I don’t handle it, no one will.\n- Their reaction is my responsibility.\n- If something goes wrong, it means I failed.\n- I need to own every possible consequence.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAutomatic guilt; scanning for preventable outcomes; difficulty locating limits of control; relief when taking over; fear that stepping back is negligence.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTaking ownership for others’ emotions, decisions, outcomes, or failures; compulsive prevention and repair; difficulty distinguishing influence from responsibility.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; competence; self-esteem; control; belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConflict; another person’s distress; mistakes; ambiguous accountability; group failure; leadership; uncertainty.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am blamed when things go wrong; safety depends on my vigilance; limits are excuses; love depends on preventing disappointment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHelplessness; uncertainty; shared causation; others’ autonomy; limitation; grief.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver assumes total ownership; Ruler tries to prevent every failure; Hero believes everything depends on them; Sage mistakes influence for causation.\n## Pattern Flow\nRisk or disappointment appears → blame and loss of control feel threatening → ownership expands → temporary control and moral safety return → burden and resentment grow → inflated responsibility feels even more necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nOverfunctioning; Emotional Overresponsibility; Rescuing; Personalization.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nResponsibility; foresight; reliability; conscience; care.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; guilt; enabling; distorted accountability; resentment; impaired autonomy in others.\n## Freer Expression\nAccurate responsibility with clear limits.\n## One Act of Volition\nSeparate what you caused, influenced, agreed to, and could not control before taking action.\n## Mira Language\n“You may have a real part here. I also notice your responsibility is expanding beyond your actions and authority. What actually belongs to you?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did you directly control? What belongs to another person or the system? What would proportionate responsibility look like?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLeadership, caregiving, legal duty, and real power differences can create substantial responsibility. Boundaries must not erase actual obligations.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated assumption of causal or moral ownership beyond actual actions, authority, or agreements.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the true contribution, make proportionate repair, and return what is not yours without contempt or abandonment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify actual role, influence, agreement, and control; resist transferring others’ choices or emotions into the person’s ownership.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where inflated ownership became control, resentment, enabling, or hidden expectation. Re-establish explicit responsibilities and limits.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay invite Underfunctioning, Dependency, Entitlement, or Resentment. The loop becomes “I must own everything” versus “You will handle what belongs to me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I responsible for, and what am I claiming because uncertainty feels unsafe?"},
  "PP-RETALIATION": {"name":"Retaliation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Keeping Score; Resentment; Anger as Armor; Punitive Silence; Devaluation.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior — counterattack. Ruler — punitive consequence. Rebel — revenge against power. Lover — betrayal punishment. Trickster — humiliation in return.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly addresses escalation, threats, retaliation risk, and legitimate safety actions.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Convert one retaliatory impulse into a boundary, consequence, documentation, or request for restitution.","Core Logic":"I need you to hurt, lose, or fear something so the balance feels restored.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Escalation; moral injury; fear; destroyed trust; legal or safety consequences.","Core Fear":"No one protects me; mercy invites repetition; only pain teaches; justice requires equivalence.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They need to feel what they made me feel.; I won’t feel safe until they pay a cost.; An apology isn’t enough unless they suffer too.; I need to even the score.; If I hurt them back, I’ll regain my power.; Justice means making sure they lose something.","Protective Move":"Retaliation is the protective attempt to restore power, dignity, or fairness by causing the other person to feel a comparable cost after perceived injury.","Pattern ID":"PP-RETALIATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary power returns when punishment is planned or enacted.","Freer Expression":"Justice without reciprocal harm.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Demand for justice; refusal of impunity; protective strength.","Observable Cues":"Withholding affection or resources; exposing vulnerabilities; strategic punishment; sabotage; escalating after apology; deliberate reciprocal injury.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Name retaliatory impact clearly, protect vulnerable information and resources, and disengage when escalation or threats are present. May trigger Retaliation, Hypervigilance, Devaluation, or Withdrawing Before Being Left.","Emotional Function":"Protects Justice, Dignity, Safety, and Power; avoids grief, helplessness, uncertainty about justice, and dependence on boundaries or institutions.","Canonical Name":"Retaliation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRetaliation is the protective attempt to restore power, dignity, or fairness by causing the other person to feel a comparable cost after perceived injury.\n## Domain\nAnger, Conflict, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nKeeping Score; Resentment; Anger as Armor; Punitive Silence; Devaluation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need you to hurt, lose, or fear something so the balance feels restored.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They need to feel what they made me feel.\n- I won’t feel safe until they pay a cost.\n- An apology isn’t enough unless they suffer too.\n- I need to even the score.\n- If I hurt them back, I’ll regain my power.\n- Justice means making sure they lose something.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief at the idea of “evening the score”; preoccupation with consequences for the other person; repair feels insufficient without suffering; vulnerability converts quickly to revenge.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nWithholding affection or resources; exposing vulnerabilities; strategic punishment; sabotage; escalating after apology; deliberate reciprocal injury.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nJustice; Dignity; Safety; Power.\n## Usually Triggered By\nBetrayal; humiliation; rejection; unfairness; perceived impunity.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nNo one protects me; mercy invites repetition; only pain teaches; justice requires equivalence.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; helplessness; uncertainty about justice; dependence on boundaries or institutions.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior — counterattack. Ruler — punitive consequence. Rebel — revenge against power. Lover — betrayal punishment. Trickster — humiliation in return.\n## Pattern Flow\nInjury occurs → dignity and power collapse → punishment is planned or enacted → temporary power returns → conflict escalates and trust deteriorates.\n## Often Appears With\nResentment; Keeping Score; Anger as Armor; Devaluation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDemand for justice; refusal of impunity; protective strength.\n## Current Cost\nEscalation; moral injury; fear; destroyed trust; legal or safety consequences.\n## Freer Expression\nJustice without reciprocal harm.\n## One Act of Volition\nConvert one retaliatory impulse into a boundary, consequence, documentation, or request for restitution.\n## Mira Language\n“You may need accountability. Retaliation is different: it seeks restored balance through the other person’s suffering.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat outcome would protect you without reproducing the injury? What consequence is proportionate and transparent?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSelf-protection, lawful consequences, disclosure for safety, and ending contact are not retaliation merely because the other person dislikes them.\n## Evidence Threshold\nDeliberate action intended primarily to make another suffer or lose because of a prior injury.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause before acting, distinguish justice from revenge, and choose transparent boundaries or restitution channels.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nName retaliatory impact clearly, protect vulnerable information and resources, and disengage when escalation or threats are present.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge intentional punishment without centering the original grievance, restore what can be restored, accept consequences, and demonstrate non-retaliation over time.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Retaliation, Hypervigilance, Devaluation, or Withdrawing Before Being Left. Often triggered by betrayal, Punitive Silence, Contempt, or perceived impunity. The loop becomes reciprocal injury justified by the previous round.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I seeking protection and justice, or am I seeking to make someone pay?"},
  "PP-RETROSPECTIVE-PROSECUTION": {"name":"Retrospective Prosecution","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Grudge Holding; Rumination; Keeping Score; Narrative Overcontrol; Retaliation; Suspicion.","Archetypal Role":"Judge builds the case; Sage organizes memory into proof; Warrior seeks vindication; Ruler assigns definitive guilt.","Migration Notes":"Batch 16 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective logic, common expressions, trigger phrases, and differentiation. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty because documentation, legal review, and unresolved harm are explicitly distinguished.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"16","One Act of Volition":"Name the present decision the review is meant to inform and stop gathering evidence that cannot change it.","Core Logic":"If I can prove exactly what happened, I can finally be safe, right, or released from blame.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Chronic activation; adversarial intimacy; selective memory; failed repair; inability to update.","Core Fear":"If the past remains ambiguous, I may remain blamed, unsafe, powerless, or morally unresolved.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Let’s go back through exactly what you said.; The record proves it.; I need you to admit what really happened.; Once I show the sequence, you’ll see.; I cannot let the case close while the verdict feels wrong.; If I prove the past, I can finally be released from blame.","Protective Move":"Retrospective Prosecution reconstructs past events as a case to be argued, judged, or won in order to restore certainty, innocence, moral advantage, or leverage.","Pattern ID":"PP-RETROSPECTIVE-PROSECUTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Moral clarity and control rise when memory becomes a case.","Freer Expression":"Truthful review in service of a present decision.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Memory; precision; accountability; refusal to erase harm; evidence gathering.","Observable Cues":"Re-litigating conversations; collecting old evidence; prosecutorial retelling; demanding definitive admissions; assigning fixed guilt after the fact.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Acknowledge relevant facts without entering endless trial; distinguish documentation from punishment and define what present decision the review serves. May trigger Defensiveness, Counterattack, Withdrawal, or Narrative Overcontrol.","Emotional Function":"Protects justice, self-esteem, certainty, safety, and moral identity; avoids grief, ambiguity, powerlessness, shared responsibility, and incomplete repair.","Canonical Name":"Retrospective Prosecution"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRetrospective Prosecution is the protective reconstruction of past events as a case to be argued, judged, or won in order to restore certainty, innocence, moral advantage, or leverage. It differs from Rumination because memory is organized into an adversarial prosecution rather than merely repeated.\n## Domain\nMemory, Justice, and Adversarial Meaning\n## Related Patterns\nGrudge Holding; Rumination; Keeping Score; Narrative Overcontrol; Retaliation\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I can prove exactly what happened, I can finally be safe, right, or released from blame.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Let’s go back through exactly what you said.\n- The record proves it.\n- I need you to admit what really happened.\n- Once I show the sequence, you’ll see.\n- I cannot let the case close while the verdict feels wrong.\n- If I prove the past, I can finally be released from blame.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nCompulsion to reconstruct sequence; relief from finding confirming evidence; anger when memory differs; fear that ending review erases truth.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRe-litigating conversations; collecting old evidence; prosecutorial retelling; demanding definitive admissions; assigning fixed guilt after the fact.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nJustice; safety; certainty; self-esteem; moral identity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUnresolved conflict; blame; memory disagreement; inadequate apology; ambiguous endings; renewed contact.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nTruth disappears unless proven; I will be blamed unless I build the case; ambiguity favors the more powerful person.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; powerlessness; uncertainty; incomplete justice; shared responsibility; limits of repair.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nJudge builds the case; Sage organizes memory into proof; Warrior seeks vindication; Ruler assigns definitive guilt.\n## Pattern Flow\nPast injury or ambiguity reactivates → justice and innocence feel threatened → evidence and sequence are assembled → certainty and control rise → relationship becomes a trial → repair and updating narrow.\n## Often Appears With\nGrudge Holding; Keeping Score; Narrative Overcontrol; Rumination.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nMemory; precision; accountability; refusal to erase harm; evidence gathering.\n## Current Cost\nChronic activation; adversarial intimacy; selective memory; failed repair; inability to update.\n## Freer Expression\nTruthful review in service of a present decision.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the present decision the review is meant to inform and stop gathering evidence that cannot change it.\n## Mira Language\n“The sequence may matter. I also notice the review is becoming a case that must be won. What present need would a verdict actually serve?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat fact remains unresolved? What accountability is still missing? What would change if the other person never accepts your verdict?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLegal documentation, abuse records, safety planning, and clarifying consequential facts are not Retrospective Prosecution.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated adversarial reconstruction of past events for vindication, leverage, or fixed guilt beyond what present safety or decision-making requires.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPreserve the relevant facts, identify the unmet need, and choose a present boundary or repair request instead of endless prosecution.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAcknowledge relevant facts without entering an endless trial; distinguish documentation from punishment and define the present purpose of review.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where past evidence became leverage or perpetual punishment; address any still-unrepaired harm, then establish whether the relationship will continue, change, or end.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Counterattack, Withdrawal, or Narrative Overcontrol. The loop becomes “I must prove the case” versus “I must defend myself from permanent prosecution.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat present protection or repair am I hoping a final verdict on the past will provide?"},
  "PP-REVELATION-ADDICTION": {"name":"Revelation Addiction","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Meaning Inflation; Confessional Overexposure; Novelty Seeking; Spiritual Bypassing; Rapid Project Proliferation; Fantasy Refuge.","Archetypal Role":"Magician seeks the transformative key; Mystic chases revelation; Sage substitutes insight for practice; Creator abandons craft for the next breakthrough.","Migration Notes":"Batch 16 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective logic, common expressions, trigger phrases, and differentiation. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"16","One Act of Volition":"Choose one small practice from the latest insight and repeat it before seeking another breakthrough.","Core Logic":"The next realization will finally transform everything without requiring slow, uncertain practice.","Primary Domain":"Spiritual","Long-Term Cost":"Fragmented practice; repeated disclosure without change; abandonment of implementation; inflation and disappointment.","Core Fear":"Slow change may fail, expose limitation, or require ordinary discipline without certainty of transformation.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I just need one more breakthrough.; This changes everything.; There’s still a deeper truth I haven’t uncovered.; Once I understand the root, I’ll be free.; Practice can wait until the insight is complete.; Ordinary repetition feels less real than a dramatic realization.","Protective Move":"Revelation Addiction seeks repeated breakthroughs, disclosures, insights, or dramatic truths as a substitute for sustained integration and ordinary change.","Pattern ID":"PP-REVELATION-ADDICTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Intensity, hope, and a sense of transformation rise with each new insight.","Freer Expression":"Insight embodied through repetition.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Insight; openness; imagination; willingness to transform; symbolic intelligence.","Observable Cues":"Chasing epiphanies; escalating disclosure; abandoning implementation for the next insight; equating intensity with transformation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Honor insight while asking what concrete practice, boundary, or repeated action follows; avoid rewarding escalating disclosure as proof of transformation. May trigger Cynicism, Emotional Distancing, Rescuing, or Positivity Enforcement.","Emotional Function":"Protects hope, meaning, self-esteem, agency, and possibility; avoids repetition, boredom, limitation, sustained effort, uncertainty, and ordinary integration.","Canonical Name":"Revelation Addiction"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRevelation Addiction is the protective pursuit of repeated breakthroughs, disclosures, insights, or dramatic truths as a substitute for sustained integration and ordinary change. It differs from healthy insight-seeking because intensity repeatedly replaces practice.\n## Domain\nMeaning, Transformation, and Integration\n## Related Patterns\nMeaning Inflation; Confessional Overexposure; Novelty Seeking; Spiritual Bypassing; Rapid Project Proliferation\n## Recognition Sentence\nThe next realization will finally transform everything without requiring slow, uncertain practice.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I just need one more breakthrough.\n- This changes everything.\n- There’s still a deeper truth I haven’t uncovered.\n- Once I understand the root, I’ll be free.\n- Practice can wait until the insight is complete.\n- Ordinary repetition feels less real than a dramatic realization.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRush after insight; impatience with repetition; fear that ordinary practice means the revelation was not real; urge to disclose more deeply.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nChasing epiphanies; escalating disclosure; abandoning implementation for the next insight; equating intensity with transformation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nHope; meaning; agency; self-esteem; possibility.\n## Usually Triggered By\nStalled change; shame; boredom; relapse; uncertainty; ordinary routines; dissatisfaction with gradual progress.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nSlow change is not enough; limitation is intolerable; one perfect insight can rescue me; ordinary discipline proves I am still stuck.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nBoredom; repetition; limitation; uncertainty; grief; accountability; incremental progress.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nMagician seeks the transformative key; Mystic chases revelation; Sage substitutes insight for practice; Creator abandons craft for the next breakthrough.\n## Pattern Flow\nPain or stagnation appears → ordinary effort feels insufficient → dramatic insight is pursued → intensity and hope surge → implementation fades → disappointment returns → another revelation becomes necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nMeaning Inflation; Spiritual Bypassing; Confessional Overexposure; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nInsight; openness; imagination; willingness to transform; symbolic intelligence.\n## Current Cost\nFragmented practice; repeated disclosure without change; abandonment of implementation; inflation and disappointment.\n## Freer Expression\nInsight embodied through repetition.\n## One Act of Volition\nChoose one small practice from the latest insight and repeat it before seeking another breakthrough.\n## Mira Language\n“The insight may be real. What would make it visible in ordinary behavior after the intensity fades?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat action follows this realization? What are you hoping another insight will spare you from practicing? How will you know integration has occurred?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nTherapeutic insight, spiritual revelation, creative breakthrough, and meaningful disclosure are not inherently addictive.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of pursuing new insight or disclosure while implementation, repetition, and measurable change are abandoned.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the insight, reduce its scale, and translate it into one repeated behavior, boundary, or practice before seeking more intensity.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nHonor insight while asking what concrete practice, boundary, or repeated action follows; avoid rewarding escalating disclosure as proof of transformation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where repeated revelations created false promises or emotional intensity without follow-through; return to specific commitments and evidence.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Cynicism, Emotional Distancing, Rescuing, or Positivity Enforcement. The loop becomes “This breakthrough changes everything” versus “Nothing changes after the breakthrough.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat insight am I still collecting instead of practicing?"},
  "PP-RIGIDITY": {"name":"Rigidity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Boundary Rigidity; Rule Dependence; All-or-Nothing Thinking; Micromanaging; Perfectionism; Certainty Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler preserves order through fixed structure; Warrior resists deviation; Sage treats one framework as final; Caregiver controls routine to prevent disruption.","Migration Notes":"Batch 16 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective logic, common expressions, trigger phrases, and differentiation. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"16","One Act of Volition":"Identify one preference currently treated as a necessity and test one bounded alternative.","Core Logic":"If the structure does not bend, I will not be overwhelmed, exposed, or out of control.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Poor adaptation; conflict; brittle systems; reduced learning; relational strain; escalating control.","Core Fear":"Flexibility will create chaos, exposure, overwhelm, or loss of control.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"There is one right way.; We can’t change the plan now.; That’s not how this is done.; Exceptions create chaos.; If I allow flexibility, everything may unravel.; I need the structure to stay exactly as it is.","Protective Move":"Rigidity narrows acceptable options, interpretations, routines, or responses in order to preserve predictability and prevent destabilization.","Pattern ID":"PP-RIGIDITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Anxiety falls when options narrow and structure hardens.","Freer Expression":"Stable structure with responsive flexibility.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Consistency; reliability; standards; focus; protection of essential structure.","Observable Cues":"Inflexible rules; intolerance of deviation; difficulty adapting to new information; treating preferences as necessities.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify what is truly nonnegotiable, offer bounded alternatives, and avoid humiliating the need for structure. May trigger Rebellion, Demand Avoidance, Withdrawal, or Underfunctioning.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, predictability, competence, dignity, and control; avoids uncertainty, adaptation, ambiguity, dependence, and vulnerability to surprise.","Canonical Name":"Rigidity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRigidity is the protective narrowing of acceptable options, interpretations, routines, or responses in order to preserve predictability and prevent destabilization. It is broader than Boundary Rigidity or Rule Dependence because it can organize many domains.\n## Domain\nControl, Predictability, and Adaptation\n## Related Patterns\nBoundary Rigidity; Rule Dependence; All-or-Nothing Thinking; Micromanaging; Perfectionism\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf the structure does not bend, I will not be overwhelmed, exposed, or out of control.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- There is one right way.\n- We can’t change the plan now.\n- That’s not how this is done.\n- Exceptions create chaos.\n- If I allow flexibility, everything may unravel.\n- I need the structure to stay exactly as it is.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAlarm at deviation; relief from fixed rules; difficulty considering alternatives; tension when plans change; preference becoming experienced as necessity.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nInflexible rules; intolerance of deviation; difficulty adapting to new information; treating preferences as necessities.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; predictability; competence; dignity; control.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUnexpected change; ambiguity; fatigue; loss of authority; unfamiliar methods; competing needs; sensory or emotional overload.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nChange brings chaos; flexibility invites exploitation; mistakes follow deviation; I am safe only when the structure holds.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; dependence; experimentation; limitation; grief; ordinary disorder.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler preserves order through fixed structure; Warrior resists deviation; Sage treats one framework as final; Caregiver controls routine to prevent disruption.\n## Pattern Flow\nChange or ambiguity appears → safety and control feel threatened → options narrow and structure hardens → anxiety falls → adaptation and collaboration weaken → future change feels more dangerous.\n## Often Appears With\nRule Dependence; All-or-Nothing Thinking; Micromanaging; Perfectionism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nConsistency; reliability; standards; focus; protection of essential structure.\n## Current Cost\nPoor adaptation; conflict; brittle systems; reduced learning; relational strain; escalating control.\n## Freer Expression\nStable structure with responsive flexibility.\n## One Act of Volition\nIdentify one preference currently treated as a necessity and test one bounded alternative.\n## Mira Language\n“The structure may be serving something important. Which part is truly necessary, and which part has become rigid because change feels unsafe?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does flexibility seem to threaten? What minimum structure must remain? What new information is the current rule excluding?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDisability accommodations, sensory needs, safety procedures, trauma-informed routines, and principled limits are not automatically Rigidity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of narrowing options or resisting new information beyond what safety, values, or function require.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the threatened need, preserve the essential structure, and introduce one reversible variation rather than forcing total flexibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify what is truly nonnegotiable, offer bounded alternatives, and avoid humiliating the need for structure.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where inflexibility erased another person’s needs or blocked necessary adaptation; renegotiate essentials, preferences, and review points.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Rebellion, Demand Avoidance, Withdrawal, or Underfunctioning. The loop becomes “I must tighten the structure” versus “I must resist because there is no room to move.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat structure protects me, and what structure has become afraid to bend?"},
  "PP-RISK-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Risk Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Catastrophizing; Endless Preparation; Failure to Launch; Hypervigilance; Perfectionism; Certainty Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent — safety becomes stasis. Sage — analysis replaces experiment. Ruler — control prevents movement. Creator — work remains private.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Define the smallest reversible experiment that would produce real evidence.","Core Logic":"I am treating uncertainty as evidence that I should not move.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Stagnation; regret; lost opportunity; dependence on certainty; reduced confidence.","Core Fear":"Mistakes are costly; failure is humiliating; safety depends on eliminating uncertainty.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Uncertainty means I should wait.; I need more protection before I move.; The downside matters more than the possibility.; I should choose only what I can fully reverse.; Acting without certainty would be irresponsible.; It feels safer to miss the opportunity than risk failure.","Protective Move":"Risk Avoidance is the protective narrowing of action to prevent uncertainty, loss, embarrassment, or failure, even when the avoided risk is necessary for growth or alignment.","Pattern ID":"PP-RISK-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Avoidance brings relief when downside is amplified.","Freer Expression":"Prudent courage.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Prudence; foresight; stewardship; discernment.","Observable Cues":"Repeated postponement; choosing only reversible steps; excessive contingency planning; declining meaningful opportunities without testing them.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not pressure or ridicule caution; help clarify options, safeguards, and the cost of inaction. May trigger Micromanaging, Overfunctioning, Resentment, or Underfunctioning.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Competence, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids excitement, grief over limits, responsibility, vulnerability, and possibility.","Canonical Name":"Risk Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRisk Avoidance is the protective narrowing of action to prevent uncertainty, loss, embarrassment, or failure, even when the avoided risk is necessary for growth or alignment.\n## Domain\nAction, Safety, and Development\n## Related Patterns\nCatastrophizing; Endless Preparation; Failure to Launch; Hypervigilance; Perfectionism\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am treating uncertainty as evidence that I should not move.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Uncertainty means I should wait.\n- I need more protection before I move.\n- The downside matters more than the possibility.\n- I should choose only what I can fully reverse.\n- Acting without certainty would be irresponsible.\n- It feels safer to miss the opportunity than risk failure.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when options close; disproportionate focus on downside; action feels irresponsible without certainty.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeated postponement; choosing only reversible steps; excessive contingency planning; declining meaningful opportunities without testing them.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Competence; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nNew roles; visibility; financial exposure; commitment; unfamiliarity; irreversible choices.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMistakes are costly; failure is humiliating; safety depends on eliminating uncertainty.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nExcitement; grief over limits; responsibility; vulnerability; possibility.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent — safety becomes stasis. Sage — analysis replaces experiment. Ruler — control prevents movement. Creator — work remains private.\n## Pattern Flow\nOpportunity appears → uncertainty activates threat → downside is amplified → avoidance brings relief → no new evidence is gathered → risk tolerance shrinks.\n## Often Appears With\nCatastrophizing; Endless Preparation; Perfectionism; Certainty Seeking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nPrudence; foresight; stewardship; discernment.\n## Current Cost\nStagnation; regret; lost opportunity; dependence on certainty; reduced confidence.\n## Freer Expression\nPrudent courage.\n## One Act of Volition\nDefine the smallest reversible experiment that would produce real evidence.\n## Mira Language\n“What part of this risk is real, and what part is uncertainty being treated as danger?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would a bounded experiment look like? Which risk belongs to growth? What is the cost of not acting?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nAvoiding genuinely unsafe, exploitative, unaffordable, or misaligned situations is not pathological risk avoidance.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated avoidance of proportionate, values-aligned risks despite available safeguards.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate danger from uncertainty, quantify the stakes, and choose a bounded action with an exit plan.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not pressure or ridicule caution; help clarify options, safeguards, and the cost of inaction.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where avoidance shifted burdens, broke commitments, or stalled shared plans, and establish a concrete decision process and timeline.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Overfunctioning, Resentment, or Underfunctioning. Often triggered by Catastrophizing, Criticism, or Unstable Conditions. The story becomes: “Movement is unsafe” ↔︎ “I must push or take over because you will not act.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I calling uncertainty danger?"},
  "PP-ROLE-ENTRAPMENT": {"name":"Role Entrapment","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Self-Erasure; Savior Identity; Productivity-Bound Worth; Martyrdom; Image Management; People-Pleasing.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — must always serve. Hero — must always endure. Jester — must keep tension light. Rebel — must oppose. Sage — must know.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Choose one behavior that contradicts the assigned role while remaining truthful and respectful.","Core Logic":"I do not know who I am outside the role that kept me connected.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Stagnation; resentment; narrow identity; relationships that cannot adapt.","Core Fear":"Belonging depends on performance; change is betrayal; without this role I disappear.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They need me to keep being the strong one.; If I change, I may betray the people who know me this way.; I don’t know who I am outside this role.; I should keep doing what everyone expects from me.; Growth may cost me belonging.; This role no longer fits, but leaving it feels dangerous.","Protective Move":"Role Entrapment protects belonging and identity by remaining confined to a familiar role—helper, achiever, peacekeeper, rebel, expert, victim, strong one—even after the role no longer fits.","Pattern ID":"PP-ROLE-ENTRAPMENT","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary coherence returns when the familiar role is reenacted.","Freer Expression":"Identity larger than role.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Reliability; identity coherence; contribution; social intelligence.","Observable Cues":"Automatically taking the same family or team position; suppressing growth that violates expectations; recreating contexts that require the role.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not punish growth by demanding the old role; renegotiate expectations explicitly. May trigger Underfunctioning, Overfunctioning, Resentment, or Testing the Bond.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Self-Esteem, Purpose, and Trust; avoids freedom, uncertainty, grief, conflict, and identity reconstruction.","Canonical Name":"Role Entrapment"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRole Entrapment protects belonging and identity by remaining confined to a familiar role—helper, achiever, peacekeeper, rebel, expert, victim, strong one—even after the role no longer fits.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Belonging, and Adaptation\n## Related Patterns\nSelf-Erasure; Savior Identity; Productivity-Bound Worth; Martyrdom; Image Management\n## Recognition Sentence\nI do not know who I am outside the role that kept me connected.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They need me to keep being the strong one.\n- If I change, I may betray the people who know me this way.\n- I don’t know who I am outside this role.\n- I should keep doing what everyone expects from me.\n- Growth may cost me belonging.\n- This role no longer fits, but leaving it feels dangerous.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nGuilt or disorientation when acting outside the role; fear others will reject the changed self.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAutomatically taking the same family or team position; suppressing growth that violates expectations; recreating contexts that require the role.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Self-Esteem; Purpose; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nTransition; healing; changing relationships; new competence; retirement; boundary setting.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBelonging depends on performance; change is betrayal; without this role I disappear.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nFreedom; uncertainty; grief; conflict; identity reconstruction.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — must always serve. Hero — must always endure. Jester — must keep tension light. Rebel — must oppose. Sage — must know.\n## Pattern Flow\nContext changes → identity and belonging feel threatened → familiar role is reenacted → temporary coherence returns → growth and reciprocity are constrained.\n## Often Appears With\nSelf-Erasure; People-Pleasing; Martyrdom; Image Management.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReliability; identity coherence; contribution; social intelligence.\n## Current Cost\nStagnation; resentment; narrow identity; relationships that cannot adapt.\n## Freer Expression\nIdentity larger than role.\n## One Act of Volition\nChoose one behavior that contradicts the assigned role while remaining truthful and respectful.\n## Mira Language\n“That role may once have protected belonging. Does it still represent who you are now?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWho benefits when you stay in this role? What part of you has no room inside it?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nCommitments, professional roles, and caregiving responsibilities are not automatically entrapment.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated self-limitation and distress tied to preserving a familiar relational identity.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nGrieve what the role provided, then widen identity through small experiments.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not punish growth by demanding the old role; renegotiate expectations explicitly.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName how role expectations constrained choice or created resentment; redistribute responsibilities and permit changed identity.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Overfunctioning, Resentment, or Testing the Bond. Often triggered by family expectations, transition, or threatened belonging. The loop becomes “You need me to remain who I was” versus “You are abandoning us by changing.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhich role once kept me safe but now keeps me small?"},
  "PP-RULE-DEPENDENCE": {"name":"Rule Dependence","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Rigidity; Borrowed Conviction; Certainty Seeking; Decision Delegation; Defensive Expertise; Identity Fusion.","Archetypal Role":"Sage borrows certainty from procedure; Innocent preserves goodness through obedience; Ruler defers judgment to policy; Orphan seeks safety in authority.","Migration Notes":"Batch 16 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective logic, common expressions, trigger phrases, and differentiation. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags remains empty.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"16","One Act of Volition":"State the rule, its purpose, and one contextual factor that may require judgment.","Core Logic":"If I follow the rule exactly, I cannot be blamed for the outcome.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Poor judgment; moral outsourcing; paralysis when rules conflict; reduced agency; decontextualized harm.","Core Fear":"Without an external rule, I may choose wrongly, be blamed, or lose moral and social safety.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Just tell me the rule.; What am I supposed to do?; I followed the procedure.; Without a policy, how can we decide?; If I obey exactly, I cannot be blamed.; My own judgment does not feel safe enough here.","Protective Move":"Rule Dependence relies on external rules, procedures, or authorities to avoid the uncertainty and responsibility of contextual judgment.","Pattern ID":"PP-RULE-DEPENDENCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Anxiety and blame risk decrease when authority supplies the answer.","Freer Expression":"Principled judgment informed—but not replaced—by rules.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Respect for standards; procedural fairness; consistency; humility; accountability.","Observable Cues":"Seeking permission for ordinary choices; privileging procedure over context; distress when rules conflict or are absent; outsourcing moral judgment.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Clarify the rule’s purpose, context, and limits; invite judgment without shaming the need for guidance. May trigger Contrarianism, Frustration, Dominance, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects certainty, competence, safety, belonging, and moral identity; avoids ambiguity, responsibility, contextual judgment, disagreement, and self-authorship.","Canonical Name":"Rule Dependence"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRule Dependence is the protective reliance on external rules, procedures, or authorities to avoid the uncertainty and responsibility of contextual judgment. It differs from Rigidity because the central source of safety is borrowed certainty from an external standard.\n## Domain\nAuthority, Judgment, and Certainty\n## Related Patterns\nRigidity; Borrowed Conviction; Certainty Seeking; Decision Delegation; Defensive Expertise\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I follow the rule exactly, I cannot be blamed for the outcome.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Just tell me the rule.\n- What am I supposed to do?\n- I followed the procedure.\n- Without a policy, how can we decide?\n- If I obey exactly, I cannot be blamed.\n- My own judgment does not feel safe enough here.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when a policy answers; anxiety without precedent; guilt when deviating; difficulty holding conflicting rules; fear of personal judgment.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSeeking permission for ordinary choices; privileging procedure over context; distress when rules conflict or are absent; outsourcing moral judgment.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCertainty; competence; safety; belonging; moral identity.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguous decisions; conflicting values; authority; fear of blame; unfamiliar situations; absence of precedent.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIndependent judgment leads to punishment; authority defines goodness; mistakes are safer when procedure can be cited.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nResponsibility; ambiguity; disagreement; self-authorship; moral complexity; uncertainty.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage borrows certainty from procedure; Innocent preserves goodness through obedience; Ruler defers judgment to policy; Orphan seeks safety in authority.\n## Pattern Flow\nContext requires judgment → uncertainty and blame feel threatening → rule or authority is sought → anxiety decreases → context and agency narrow → dependence on external instruction grows.\n## Often Appears With\nRigidity; Borrowed Conviction; Certainty Seeking; Decision Delegation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nRespect for standards; procedural fairness; consistency; humility; accountability.\n## Current Cost\nPoor judgment; moral outsourcing; paralysis when rules conflict; reduced agency; decontextualized harm.\n## Freer Expression\nPrincipled judgment informed—but not replaced—by rules.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the rule, its purpose, and one contextual factor that may require judgment.\n## Mira Language\n“The rule may be useful. What value is it meant to protect, and what judgment still belongs to you?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat happens when rules conflict? What outcome is the rule designed to prevent? What would you decide if no policy existed?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSafety procedures, legal compliance, accessibility protocols, and legitimate deference to expertise are not Rule Dependence.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated outsourcing of ordinary contextual or moral judgment to external rules or authority, especially when the rule no longer serves its purpose.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nUse the rule as information, identify the value it serves, and reclaim the part of judgment that context requires.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nClarify the rule’s purpose, context, and limits; invite judgment without shaming the need for guidance.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where procedure was used to avoid responsibility or ignore impact; revisit the decision through purpose, context, and proportionate accountability.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Contrarianism, Frustration, Dominance, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “I need a rule to be safe” versus “Your rule leaves no room for reality.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using a rule to guide judgment, and where am I using it to avoid having one?"},
  "PP-RUMINATION": {"name":"Rumination","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Mind Reading; Emotional Reasoning; Rationalization; Perfectionism; Reassurance Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Sage overanalyzes; Lover replays relational signals; Ruler models every contingency; Warrior rehearses conflict; Caregiver reviews what should have been prevented.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"R","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Write what is known, unknown, and actionable, then stop analysis until new evidence arrives.","Core Logic":"I am circling the problem because stopping would leave me with uncertainty or feeling.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Exhaustion; distorted salience; delayed action; insomnia; relational repetition.","Core Fear":"If I stop thinking, I will miss the danger; understanding everything can prevent pain; uncertainty is unsafe.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to think this through one more time.; There must be something I’m missing.; If I stop analyzing, I might overlook the danger.; I keep replaying what happened.; I can’t let this go until it makes complete sense.; Maybe one more explanation will settle me.","Protective Move":"Rumination is the protective repetition of analysis, replay, or imagined scenarios in an attempt to gain certainty, prevent recurrence, or resolve emotion through thinking alone.","Pattern ID":"PP-RUMINATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Thought intensifies and a temporary sense of control emerges.","Freer Expression":"Reflection with an endpoint.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Reflection; pattern recognition; responsibility; learning.","Observable Cues":"Revisiting conversations; repeated question asking; searching for hidden meaning; rehearsing future exchanges; difficulty sleeping or shifting attention.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Answer clearly once, avoid entering endless analysis loops, and support grounding without dismissing the concern. May trigger Withdrawal, Defensiveness, Reassurance Fatigue, or Stonewalling.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Competence, Autonomy, and Belonging; avoids grief, helplessness, anger, shame, and lack of control.","Canonical Name":"Rumination"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nRumination is the protective repetition of analysis, replay, or imagined scenarios in an attempt to gain certainty, prevent recurrence, or resolve emotion through thinking alone.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nMind Reading; Emotional Reasoning; Rationalization; Perfectionism; Reassurance Seeking\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am circling the problem because stopping would leave me with uncertainty or feeling.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to think this through one more time.\n- There must be something I’m missing.\n- If I stop analyzing, I might overlook the danger.\n- I keep replaying what happened.\n- I can’t let this go until it makes complete sense.\n- Maybe one more explanation will settle me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRepeated mental replay; temporary relief from one more analysis; inability to reach closure; bodily activation despite extensive thinking.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRevisiting conversations; repeated question asking; searching for hidden meaning; rehearsing future exchanges; difficulty sleeping or shifting attention.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Competence; Autonomy; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; conflict; mistakes; rejection; unresolved decisions; perceived threat.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf I stop thinking, I will miss the danger; understanding everything can prevent pain; uncertainty is unsafe.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; helplessness; anger; shame; lack of control.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage overanalyzes; Lover replays relational signals; Ruler models every contingency; Warrior rehearses conflict; Caregiver reviews what should have been prevented.\n## Pattern Flow\nUncertainty or pain appears → thought intensifies → temporary sense of control emerges → no new information arrives → distress persists → more thought is recruited.\n## Often Appears With\nMind Reading; Reassurance Seeking; Perfectionism; Emotional Reasoning.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReflection; pattern recognition; responsibility; learning.\n## Current Cost\nExhaustion; distorted salience; delayed action; insomnia; relational repetition.\n## Freer Expression\nReflection with an endpoint.\n## One Act of Volition\nWrite what is known, unknown, and actionable, then stop analysis until new evidence arrives.\n## Mira Language\n“Has this thinking produced new information, or is it trying to regulate uncertainty?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feeling remains when analysis stops? What new evidence are you waiting for? What action is possible now?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDeliberate reflection, problem solving, and trauma processing are not automatically rumination.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepetitive thought without meaningful new information or action, accompanied by sustained distress.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nCreate a stopping rule and shift from explanation to regulation or action.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAnswer clearly once, avoid entering endless analysis loops, and support grounding without dismissing the concern.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where repeated processing consumed another person’s bandwidth or reopened settled conflict; agree on boundaries for revisiting and conditions for new discussion.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Withdrawal, Defensiveness, Reassurance Fatigue, or Stonewalling. Often triggered by ambiguity, inconsistent communication, or Emotional Distancing.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I trying to make certain by thinking about it again?"},
  "PP-SARCASM-AS-ARMOR": {"name":"Sarcasm as Armor","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Anger as Armor; Vulnerability Avoidance; Passive Aggression; Emotional Distancing; Devaluation; Cynicism.","Archetypal Role":"Trickster — wit becomes a shield. Warrior — language becomes a preemptive strike. Rebel — irony prevents capture. Lover — tenderness is disguised as teasing.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"State the direct feeling or request before making the joke.","Core Logic":"I am making the truth safer by making it sharp.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Confusion; humiliation; reduced safety; hidden needs; escalating contempt.","Core Fear":"Direct feeling will be mocked; softness invites attack; I must strike first to stay safe.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I can say it safely if I make it a joke.; The sharp version feels less vulnerable than the honest one.; I should strike first before they can embarrass me.; It was only a joke, so they shouldn’t be hurt.; Sincerity would expose too much.; Wit gives me control over the moment.","Protective Move":"Sarcasm as Armor is the protective use of cutting or ironic speech to avoid direct vulnerability, disappointment, fear, or tenderness while preserving distance and control.","Pattern ID":"PP-SARCASM-AS-ARMOR","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate control and distance arrive when sarcasm sharpens the message.","Freer Expression":"Wit without wounding.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Wit; perceptiveness; comic timing; truth-telling.","Observable Cues":"Cutting jokes; ironic put-downs; contemptuous teasing; denying impact because it was just a joke; using humor instead of a direct request.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Name the impact without shaming humor. Disengage if sarcasm becomes degrading. May trigger Defensiveness, Retaliation, Emotional Distancing, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Self-Esteem, Autonomy, and Belonging; avoids hurt, longing, shame, fear, and dependence.","Canonical Name":"Sarcasm as Armor"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSarcasm as Armor is the protective use of cutting or ironic speech to avoid direct vulnerability, disappointment, fear, or tenderness while preserving distance and control.\n## Domain\nCommunication, Vulnerability, and Social Defense\n## Related Patterns\nAnger as Armor; Vulnerability Avoidance; Passive Aggression; Emotional Distancing; Devaluation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am making the truth safer by making it sharp.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I can say it safely if I make it a joke.\n- The sharp version feels less vulnerable than the honest one.\n- I should strike first before they can embarrass me.\n- It was only a joke, so they shouldn’t be hurt.\n- Sincerity would expose too much.\n- Wit gives me control over the moment.\n## Recognition Signals — Internal\nWarmth feels exposing; direct hurt feels embarrassing; wit brings immediate control; sincerity creates tension.\n## Observable Behaviors\nCutting jokes; ironic put-downs; contemptuous teasing; denying impact because it was “just a joke”; using humor instead of a direct request.\n## Core Human Needs\nSafety; Self-Esteem; Autonomy; Belonging.\n## Triggers\nEmbarrassment; disappointment; intimacy; criticism; feeling powerless or overlooked.\n## Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDirect feeling will be mocked; softness invites attack; I must strike first to stay safe.\n## Feelings or Realities Avoided\nHurt; longing; shame; fear; dependence.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nTrickster — wit becomes a shield. Warrior — language becomes a preemptive strike. Rebel — irony prevents capture. Lover — tenderness is disguised as teasing.\n## Pattern Flow\nVulnerability appears → exposure feels unsafe → sarcasm creates distance and status → relief arrives → impact is minimized → trust and directness weaken.\n## Often Appears With\nCynicism; Passive Aggression; Devaluation; Anger as Armor.\n## Gift Trapped Inside\nWit; perceptiveness; comic timing; truth-telling.\n## Current Cost\nConfusion; humiliation; reduced safety; hidden needs; escalating contempt.\n## Freer Expression\nWit without wounding.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the direct feeling or request before making the joke.\n## Mira Language\n“The humor may be carrying something more vulnerable. What would the sentence be without the blade?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feeling would the sarcasm expose if spoken plainly? Did the joke create connection or cover? What direct request belongs here?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nPlayful irony, mutual banter, cultural humor, and consensual teasing are not automatically protective sarcasm.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of cutting humor when vulnerable material appears, especially when impact is dismissed.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nNotice when wit becomes concealment, regulate the exposure, and translate the joke into one direct feeling, boundary, or request.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nName the impact without shaming humor. Disengage if sarcasm becomes degrading.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the specific wound, do not hide behind intent or humor, name the concealed feeling, and demonstrate repair through direct communication.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Retaliation, Emotional Distancing, or Contempt. Often triggered by Criticism, Shame Spiraling, or Vulnerability Avoidance. The loop becomes: “I must sharpen to stay safe” ↔︎ “I must harden because I am being cut.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using wit to avoid saying what hurts?"},
  "PP-SAVIOR-IDENTITY": {"name":"Savior Identity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Overfunctioning; Martyrdom; Boundary Collapse; Productivity-Bound Worth; Grandiosity.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — care becomes rescue. Hero — worth requires a crisis. Ruler — support becomes control. Magician — transformation becomes personal mandate.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Ask permission and identify what remains the other person’s responsibility.","Core Logic":"I know who I am when someone needs me to save them.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Burnout; dependency; boundary violations; concealed superiority; resentment.","Core Fear":"I am lovable when useful; others cannot manage without me; my needs are less legitimate; stepping back is abandonment.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"They need me to fix this.; If I step back, I’m abandoning them.; I know what they need better than they do.; My value comes from being indispensable.; I can’t let them face the consequences alone.; If they no longer need me, I may lose my purpose.","Protective Move":"Savior Identity secures worth, purpose, control, or belonging through being indispensable to another person’s healing, success, or rescue.","Pattern ID":"PP-SAVIOR-IDENTITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Importance and relief rise when rescue and control intensify.","Freer Expression":"Service without possession.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Generosity; courage; service; leadership; hope.","Observable Cues":"Taking ownership of others’ recovery; unsolicited rescuing; bypassing consent; remaining in harmful systems to be needed.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appreciate care without surrendering agency; state clearly what help is and is not wanted. May trigger Underfunctioning, Dependency, Resentment, Passive Aggression, or Rebellion.","Emotional Function":"Protects Purpose, Self-Esteem, Belonging, and Competence; avoids powerlessness, ordinary mutuality, grief, one’s own needs, and others’ autonomy.","Canonical Name":"Savior Identity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSavior Identity secures worth, purpose, control, or belonging through being indispensable to another person’s healing, success, or rescue.\n## Domain\nCaretaking, Worth, and Relational Power\n## Related Patterns\nOverfunctioning; Martyrdom; Boundary Collapse; Productivity-Bound Worth; Grandiosity\n## Recognition Sentence\nI know who I am when someone needs me to save them.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- They need me to fix this.\n- If I step back, I’m abandoning them.\n- I know what they need better than they do.\n- My value comes from being indispensable.\n- I can’t let them face the consequences alone.\n- If they no longer need me, I may lose my purpose.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency around others’ problems; guilt when stepping back; importance rises when someone is dependent.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTaking ownership of others’ recovery; unsolicited rescuing; bypassing consent; remaining in harmful systems to be needed.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nPurpose; Self-Esteem; Belonging; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAnother person’s crisis; helplessness; rejection; lack of purpose; threatened irrelevance.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am lovable when useful; others cannot manage without me; my needs are less legitimate; stepping back is abandonment.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nPowerlessness; ordinary mutuality; grief; one’s own needs; others’ autonomy.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — care becomes rescue. Hero — worth requires a crisis. Ruler — support becomes control. Magician — transformation becomes personal mandate.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother struggles → purpose or worth activates → rescue and control intensify → importance and relief rise → dependence and resentment grow.\n## Often Appears With\nOverfunctioning; Martyrdom; Boundary Collapse; Grandiosity.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nGenerosity; courage; service; leadership; hope.\n## Current Cost\nBurnout; dependency; boundary violations; concealed superiority; resentment.\n## Freer Expression\nService without possession.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk permission and identify what remains the other person’s responsibility.\n## Mira Language\n“Your care is strong. Are you supporting their agency, or becoming responsible for their transformation?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWho are you when you are not needed? What help was actually requested?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nEmergency action, caregiving duties, and generous support are not automatically savior identity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated identity investment in being indispensable, with boundary or agency costs.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nShift from rescue to consent, accompaniment, and bounded contribution.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAppreciate care without surrendering agency; state clearly what help is and is not wanted.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where rescue displaced consent, competence, or shared responsibility; return decisions and consequences to their rightful owner.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Dependency, Resentment, Passive Aggression, or Rebellion. Often triggered by crisis, helplessness, or threatened irrelevance. The loop becomes “You need me to survive” versus “You do not believe I can stand on my own.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere has being needed become proof that I matter?"},
  "PP-SCAPEGOATING": {"name":"Scapegoating","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Blame Shifting; Adversarial Framing; Projection; Devaluation; Narrative Overcontrol; Moral Superiority.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler preserves the system by naming an enemy; Judge concentrates guilt; Orphan secures belonging through exclusion; Warrior directs diffuse threat toward one target.","Migration Notes":"Batch 16 anomaly expansion. Source supplied definition, protective logic, common expressions, trigger phrases, and differentiation. Missing canonical sections authored to full standard; spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term and Crosswalk Terms remain empty. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because scapegoating can involve coordinated blame, exclusion, reputational harm, retaliation, and coercive group dynamics.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"16","One Act of Volition":"List at least three contributing factors—including system or leadership factors—before assigning individual responsibility.","Core Logic":"If one person is the problem, the rest of us do not have to face our part.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Injustice; exclusion; repeated systemic failure; reputational harm; coercive group dynamics; loss of reality contact.","Core Fear":"If blame remains distributed, the group may face instability, guilt, conflict, or collapse.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Everything would be fine if they were gone.; They’re the reason this keeps happening.; It always comes back to them.; The whole problem is one person.; We do not need to examine the system if we remove the target.; Focusing blame on them keeps the rest of us united.","Protective Move":"Scapegoating concentrates diffuse blame, anxiety, or group conflict onto one person or target so the larger system can avoid examining itself.","Pattern ID":"PP-SCAPEGOATING","Short-Term Payoff":"Group tension decreases and cohesion rises when one target carries the problem.","Freer Expression":"Distributed accountability grounded in evidence and power analysis.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Desire for coherence; accountability; rapid threat identification; group protection.","Observable Cues":"Repeatedly assigning one person the role of cause; selective scrutiny; group bonding through blame; preserving the system by expelling or discrediting the target.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Return to specific behaviors, distributed causes, power, and evidence; protect the target from pile-on, retaliation, or coerced confession. May trigger Appeasement, Self-Erasure, Retaliation, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects group cohesion, innocence, certainty, status, and safety; avoids systemic accountability, ambiguity, shared guilt, power analysis, and internal conflict.","Canonical Name":"Scapegoating"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nScapegoating is the protective concentration of diffuse blame, anxiety, or group conflict onto one person or target so the larger system can avoid examining itself. It differs from Blame Shifting because it stabilizes a group or system through a designated target.\n## Domain\nGroup Dynamics, Blame, and Systemic Avoidance\n## Related Patterns\nBlame Shifting; Adversarial Framing; Projection; Devaluation; Narrative Overcontrol\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf one person is the problem, the rest of us do not have to face our part.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Everything would be fine if they were gone.\n- They’re the reason this keeps happening.\n- It always comes back to them.\n- The whole problem is one person.\n- We do not need to examine the system if we remove the target.\n- Focusing blame on them keeps the rest of us united.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when one cause is named; stronger belonging through shared blame; reduced curiosity about the system; moral certainty toward the target.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRepeatedly assigning one person the role of cause; selective scrutiny; group bonding through blame; preserving the system by expelling or discrediting the target.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nGroup cohesion; innocence; certainty; status; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nSystem failure; diffuse anxiety; leadership conflict; shame; resource scarcity; cultural tension; unresolved group responsibility.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nGroups stay safe by identifying the problem person; dissent threatens belonging; shared responsibility will collapse order.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nSystemic accountability; ambiguity; shared guilt; grief; power analysis; internal conflict.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler preserves the system by naming an enemy; Judge concentrates guilt; Orphan secures belonging through exclusion; Warrior directs diffuse threat toward one target.\n## Pattern Flow\nGroup distress rises → cohesion and innocence feel threatened → one target is designated → tension and belonging temporarily stabilize → systemic causes remain → failure repeats and blame intensifies.\n## Often Appears With\nProjection; Devaluation; Adversarial Framing; Narrative Overcontrol; Moral Superiority.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDesire for coherence; accountability; rapid threat identification; group protection.\n## Current Cost\nInjustice; exclusion; repeated systemic failure; reputational harm; coercive group dynamics; loss of reality contact.\n## Freer Expression\nDistributed accountability grounded in evidence and power analysis.\n## One Act of Volition\nList at least three contributing factors—including system or leadership factors—before assigning individual responsibility.\n## Mira Language\n“One person may have real responsibility. I also notice the whole system is becoming organized around them as the sole cause. What else is contributing?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat evidence is applied differently to the target? Who benefits from concentrating blame? What responsibility remains elsewhere in the system?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNaming actual misconduct, removing a dangerous person, or holding a specific actor accountable is not Scapegoating when evidence, process, and systemic context are preserved.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated group pattern of selective scrutiny, concentrated blame, exclusion, or identity assignment that relieves broader accountability.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSlow the rush to a sole cause, distinguish individual conduct from system conditions, and examine power, incentives, and distributed responsibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nReturn to specific behaviors, distributed causes, power, and evidence; protect the target from pile-on, retaliation, or coerced confession.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nCorrect false or exaggerated claims, restore the target’s dignity and access where possible, address systemic contributors, and create a fair accountability process.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Self-Erasure, Retaliation, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “We need one person to carry the problem” versus “I must submit, flee, or fight the whole group.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat part of the system becomes invisible when one person is made to carry the whole problem?"},
  "PP-SCARCITY-HOARDING": {"name":"Scarcity Hoarding","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hypervigilance; Control-Seeking; Possessiveness; Help-Rejection; Overfunctioning; Hyper-Independence; Cynicism.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler — resources become control. Caregiver — reserves are justified as protection. Orphan — deprivation memory governs the present.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Identify a protected reserve and a separate amount that can safely circulate.","Core Logic":"I am keeping more than I need because having less feels unsafe.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Reduced trust; stagnant resources; relational inequity; missed investment; chronic fear of insufficiency.","Core Fear":"There will not be enough; no one will protect me; giving creates vulnerability.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to keep more than I may actually need.; Letting this resource go feels unsafe.; There may not be enough later.; Sharing would make me dependent or exposed.; I should hold back information, time, or money just in case.; The reserve never feels large enough to release anything.","Protective Move":"Scarcity Hoarding is the protective accumulation or withholding of money, time, information, supplies, opportunity, or emotional availability because release feels likely to create deprivation or dependence.","Pattern ID":"PP-SCARCITY-HOARDING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary safety returns when accumulation or withholding intensifies.","Freer Expression":"Stewardship with circulation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Stewardship; preparedness; conservation; foresight.","Observable Cues":"Withholding information; stockpiling; refusing delegation; guarding access; underinvesting despite capacity; keeping emotional or practical reserves inaccessible.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not demand access or shame caution; negotiate transparent limits, shared needs, and consent. May trigger Resentment, Keeping Score, Overfunctioning, or Possessiveness.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Autonomy, Trust, and Competence; avoids dependence, grief, generosity without control, uncertainty, and mutuality.","Canonical Name":"Scarcity Hoarding"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nScarcity Hoarding is the protective accumulation or withholding of money, time, information, supplies, opportunity, or emotional availability because release feels likely to create deprivation or dependence.\n## Domain\nScarcity, Control, and Resource Security\n## Related Patterns\nHypervigilance; Control-Seeking; Possessiveness; Help-Rejection; Overfunctioning\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am keeping more than I need because having less feels unsafe.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to keep more than I may actually need.\n- Letting this resource go feels unsafe.\n- There may not be enough later.\n- Sharing would make me dependent or exposed.\n- I should hold back information, time, or money just in case.\n- The reserve never feels large enough to release anything.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAnxiety when resources leave; difficulty distinguishing reserve from excess; sharing feels like loss of control.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nWithholding information; stockpiling; refusing delegation; guarding access; underinvesting despite capacity; keeping emotional or practical reserves inaccessible.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Autonomy; Trust; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nUncertainty; requests; financial instability; dependence; memories of deprivation; competition.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nThere will not be enough; no one will protect me; giving creates vulnerability.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependence; grief; generosity without control; uncertainty; mutuality.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler — resources become control. Caregiver — reserves are justified as protection. Orphan — deprivation memory governs the present.\n## Pattern Flow\nResource movement is requested → scarcity memory activates → accumulation or withholding intensifies → temporary safety returns → reciprocity and circulation weaken → isolation confirms self-reliance.\n## Often Appears With\nHyper-Independence; Possessiveness; Control-Seeking; Cynicism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nStewardship; preparedness; conservation; foresight.\n## Current Cost\nReduced trust; stagnant resources; relational inequity; missed investment; chronic fear of insufficiency.\n## Freer Expression\nStewardship with circulation.\n## One Act of Volition\nIdentify a protected reserve and a separate amount that can safely circulate.\n## Mira Language\n“What reserve is genuinely needed, and what is being held because release itself feels unsafe?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nEnough for what? What evidence would show safety after sharing? Is the resource serving life or only reducing fear?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSaving, preparedness, privacy, and resource limits are not hoarding; socioeconomic realities must be respected.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated withholding beyond realistic need, especially when it damages function or reciprocity.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the deprivation memory, define an evidence-based reserve, and practice bounded circulation.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not demand access or shame caution; negotiate transparent limits, shared needs, and consent.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where withholding created inequity or mistrust, disclose relevant constraints, and establish fair access or decision rules.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Resentment, Keeping Score, Overfunctioning, or Possessiveness. Often triggered by Unreliable Follow-Through, Dependency, or financial instability. The story becomes: “I must keep everything to remain safe” ↔︎ “I must grab, pressure, or withdraw because nothing will be shared.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I holding beyond need because release feels unsafe?"},
  "PP-SCHEDULE-DOMINATION": {"name":"Schedule Domination","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Micromanaging; Urgency Addiction; Control-Seeking; Rigidity; Power Hoarding.","Archetypal Role":"The Timekeeper; Ruler organizes others around one timetable; Warrior treats delay as defiance; Caregiver turns coordination into obligation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 17 anomaly expansion. Source used an experimental 28-field archetypal-development template rather than the canonical Atlas structure. Useful material—including archetypal role, escalation and dissolution pathways, mantra, imagery, progress signal, and integrated expression—was preserved by mapping it into the established 27-field canonical record. Spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented to six. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because persistent unilateral schedule control may restrict agency and function as coercive pressure.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"17","One Act of Volition":"Ask, “Whose needs shaped this schedule besides mine?” before finalizing it.","Core Logic":"If I control the timing, pace, and sequence, I can prevent disruption, dependency, and loss of authority.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Resentment; reduced reciprocity; inflexibility; relational distance; punitive urgency.","Core Fear":"Being inconvenienced, overrun, dependent, unable to regulate competing demands, or losing authority over pace.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Everyone needs to work around my schedule.; We are doing it now.; There is no time to discuss this.; If you cared, you would make it work.; Delays show that people are not committed.; My timetable should determine the plan.","Clinical Term":"Controlling behavior; rigidity; intolerance of uncertainty","Protective Move":"Schedule Domination imposes timing, deadlines, pace, or sequence without meaningful collaboration so uncertainty and relational vulnerability can be converted into logistical control.","Pattern ID":"PP-SCHEDULE-DOMINATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Predictability, efficiency, and relief from negotiation.","Freer Expression":"Reliable structure with negotiated timing and reciprocal inconvenience.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Coordination; foresight; stewardship of limited time; reliability; sequencing.","Observable Cues":"Unilateral scheduling; compressed deadlines; treating availability as loyalty; contempt for delay; punishing renegotiation; organizing shared plans around one person’s needs.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Others must organize around the person’s timetable, and delays or deviations may be moralized. May trigger Appeasement, Demand Avoidance, Resentment, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects predictability, control, competence, status, and safety; avoids negotiation, dependence, uncertainty, inconvenience, and shared influence.","Canonical Name":"Schedule Domination"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSchedule Domination is the protective imposition of timing, deadlines, pace, or sequence without meaningful collaboration so uncertainty and relational vulnerability can be converted into logistical control. It differs from ordinary planning because one person’s timetable repeatedly overrides shared agency.\n## Domain\nTime, Control, and Relational Coordination\n## Related Patterns\nMicromanaging; Urgency Addiction; Control-Seeking; Rigidity; Power Hoarding\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I control the timing, pace, and sequence, I can prevent disruption, dependency, and loss of authority.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Everyone needs to work around my schedule.\n- We are doing it now.\n- There is no time to discuss this.\n- If you cared, you would make it work.\n- Delays show that people are not committed.\n- My timetable should determine the plan.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAlarm when others slow the pace; relief when timing is unilateral; irritation at negotiation; inconvenience feels like loss of rank or control.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nUnilateral scheduling; compressed deadlines; treating availability as loyalty; contempt for delay; punishing renegotiation; organizing shared plans around one person’s needs.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nPredictability; control; competence; status; safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nCompeting demands; delays; shared planning; dependence on others; uncertainty; caregiving or workload strain; threatened authority.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf I do not control time, I will be overrun; negotiation weakens authority; inconvenience means disrespect; flexibility leads to chaos.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependence; uncertainty; mutual inconvenience; limits; vulnerability; loss of priority.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nThe Timekeeper commands the village clock; Ruler organizes everyone around one timetable; Warrior treats delay as defiance; Caregiver turns coordination into obligation.\n## Pattern Flow\nCompeting needs or timing uncertainty appears → authority and predictability feel threatened → timing becomes unilateral → efficiency and relief return → others lose agency or resist → pressure and domination intensify.\n## Often Appears With\nUrgency Addiction; Micromanaging; Rigidity; Power Hoarding.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCoordination; foresight; stewardship of limited time; reliability; sequencing.\n## Current Cost\nResentment; reduced reciprocity; inflexibility; relational distance; punitive urgency.\n## Freer Expression\nReliable structure with negotiated timing and reciprocal inconvenience.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk, “Whose needs shaped this schedule besides mine?” before finalizing it.\n## Mira Language\n“The structure may be useful. I also notice the timing is becoming unilateral. What would shared planning require here?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhose agency is constrained by this timetable? What is truly urgent? What buffer or renegotiation would preserve both reliability and consent?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nOrdinary planning, disability accommodations, caregiving constraints, emergencies, and legitimate deadlines are not Schedule Domination.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated unilateral scheduling that overrides others’ agency, especially when deviation is moralized or punished.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate genuine urgency from control, invite input before fixing the schedule, and build buffers that allow mutual coordination.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRequest explicit consent, reciprocal planning, and realistic buffers; name when timing is being used as rank, pressure, or obedience testing.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where timing was imposed, inconvenience was moralized, or pressure replaced consent. Restore choice, renegotiate deadlines, and share the cost of adjustment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Demand Avoidance, Resentment, or Withdrawal. The loop becomes “Everyone must move now so I stay in control” versus “I must resist because my time and needs do not count.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I coordinating time, and where am I using time to control the relationship?"},
  "PP-SELECTIVE-ACCOUNTABILITY": {"name":"Selective Accountability","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Defensiveness; Minimizing; Rationalization; Blame Shifting; Image Management.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler—owns process but not abuse of power; Sage—debates wording instead of impact; Caregiver—centers good intentions; Warrior—admits tactics but not injury.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"State the strongest accurate version of the impact before explaining intention or context.","Core Logic":"I am willing to own only the parts that do not endanger who I need to believe I am.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Failed repair; repeated injury; credibility loss; burden shifted to affected people.","Core Fear":"If I fully admit harm, I become bad; accountability means humiliation; status depends on appearing right.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I can admit the minor mistake, but not the central impact.; My intention should matter more than what happened.; I will own the part that does not threaten who I believe I am.; They are ignoring all the context that makes me understandable.; I can apologize for the tone without admitting the conduct.; Full accountability would make me entirely bad.","Protective Move":"Selective Accountability is the protective acceptance of responsibility only where it preserves one’s preferred self-image, while minimizing, reframing, or excluding responsibility that threatens identity, status, or control.","Pattern ID":"PP-SELECTIVE-ACCOUNTABILITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Pressure temporarily decreases when safer fragments are acknowledged.","Freer Expression":"Whole accountability without identity collapse.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Capacity for reflection; desire for fairness; preservation of complexity.","Observable Cues":"Owning technical mistakes while denying relational impact; apologizing for tone but not conduct; emphasizing circumstances selectively; demanding nuance only for oneself.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Keep the focus on specific behavior and impact, refuse cosmetic apologies, and do not demand global self-condemnation. May trigger Hostility Toward Criticism, Resentment, Keeping Score, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Competence, Belonging, and Status; avoids shame, grief, the power imbalance created by one’s actions, and uncertainty about forgiveness.","Canonical Name":"Selective Accountability"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSelective Accountability is the protective acceptance of responsibility only where it preserves one’s preferred self-image, while minimizing, reframing, or excluding responsibility that threatens identity, status, or control.\n## Domain\nAccountability, Identity, and Power\n## Related Patterns\nDefensiveness; Minimizing; Rationalization; Blame Shifting; Image Management.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am willing to own only the parts that do not endanger who I need to believe I am.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I can admit the minor mistake, but not the central impact.\n- My intention should matter more than what happened.\n- I will own the part that does not threaten who I believe I am.\n- They are ignoring all the context that makes me understandable.\n- I can apologize for the tone without admitting the conduct.\n- Full accountability would make me entirely bad.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nReadiness to admit minor faults but intense resistance to central impact; focusing on intention when outcome is raised; feeling unfairly defined by one harmful action.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nOwning technical mistakes while denying relational impact; apologizing for tone but not conduct; emphasizing circumstances selectively; demanding nuance only for oneself.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Competence; Belonging; Status.\n## Usually Triggered By\nFeedback that threatens moral identity; consequences; public accountability; repeated impact being named.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nIf I fully admit harm, I become bad; accountability means humiliation; status depends on appearing right.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; grief; power imbalance created by one’s actions; uncertainty about forgiveness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler—owns process but not abuse of power; Sage—debates wording instead of impact; Caregiver—centers good intentions; Warrior—admits tactics but not injury.\n## Pattern Flow\nHarm is named → identity feels threatened → safer fragments are acknowledged → pressure temporarily decreases → core injury remains → trust erodes.\n## Often Appears With\nDefensiveness; Rationalization; Minimizing; Image Management.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nCapacity for reflection; desire for fairness; preservation of complexity.\n## Current Cost\nFailed repair; repeated injury; credibility loss; burden shifted to affected people.\n## Freer Expression\nWhole accountability without identity collapse.\n## One Act of Volition\nState the strongest accurate version of the impact before explaining intention or context.\n## Mira Language\n“You are acknowledging part of what happened. Is there a more central impact that still feels too threatening to own?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhich part of the feedback most threatens your self-concept? What would responsibility sound like without self-condemnation? What remains unaddressed for the affected person?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDisagreeing with inaccurate accusations, preserving factual nuance, or rejecting coerced confession is not selective accountability.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of partial ownership that reliably excludes the most consequential responsibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate action from total identity, name impact fully, and delay self-explanation until accountability is complete.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nKeep the focus on specific behavior and impact, refuse cosmetic apologies, and do not demand global self-condemnation.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName what was previously omitted, acknowledge the burden created by partial accountability, offer concrete restitution or behavior change, and allow trust to remain limited until change is demonstrated.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Hostility Toward Criticism, Resentment, Keeping Score, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by Shame Spiraling, Image Management, Moral Superiority, or public exposure. The loop story becomes: “Nothing I admit will ever be enough” and “You will admit only what costs you nothing.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat responsibility am I accepting only in its safest form?"},
  "PP-SELF-DEPRECATION": {"name":"Self-Deprecation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Reassurance Seeking; Comparison; People-Pleasing; Shame Display; Defensiveness; Avoidance of Visibility.","Archetypal Role":"Jester — humor turns inward to prevent attack. Everyman — smallness protects belonging. Creator — work is belittled before release. Lover — undesirability is announced to solicit contradiction. Sage — competence is minimized to avoid scrutiny.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Receive one compliment with “thank you” without minimizing, joking, or returning a negative qualifier.","Core Logic":"I will diminish myself before you have the chance to do it.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Reinforced shame; reassurance dependence; diminished credibility; difficulty receiving love or recognition; hidden ambition.","Core Fear":"Confidence makes me unlikeable; others will expose my flaws; I am safer when expectations are low; worth must be granted by someone else.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I’ll make the joke before anyone else can.; I’m probably not good enough anyway.; Don’t expect too much from me.; I should downplay this before they judge it.; If I criticize myself first, their criticism will hurt less.; I need them to contradict the bad thing I just said about myself.","Protective Move":"Self-Deprecation is the protective lowering, mocking, or preemptive criticism of oneself to control anticipated judgment, invite reassurance, reduce envy, or avoid the risk of openly claiming worth.","Pattern ID":"PP-SELF-DEPRECATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Social tension or reassurance brings relief after the self is diminished first.","Freer Expression":"Humility without self-attack.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Humility; humor; realism; accessibility; freedom from pretension.","Observable Cues":"Dismissing compliments; joking about incompetence or appearance; exaggerating flaws; presenting work apologetically; inviting others to contradict negative claims.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not endlessly contradict every negative statement. Offer accurate acknowledgment, name the pattern gently, and invite a direct request for support. May trigger Reassurance Fatigue, Overfunctioning, Irritation, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Self-Esteem, Safety, and Trust; avoids pride, desire, disappointment, direct reassurance requests, and the vulnerability of being taken seriously.","Canonical Name":"Self-Deprecation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSelf-Deprecation is the protective lowering, mocking, or preemptive criticism of oneself to control anticipated judgment, invite reassurance, reduce envy, or avoid the risk of openly claiming worth.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nReassurance Seeking; Comparison; People-Pleasing; Shame Display; Defensiveness\n## Recognition Sentence\nI will diminish myself before you have the chance to do it.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I’ll make the joke before anyone else can.\n- I’m probably not good enough anyway.\n- Don’t expect too much from me.\n- I should downplay this before they judge it.\n- If I criticize myself first, their criticism will hurt less.\n- I need them to contradict the bad thing I just said about myself.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief after making oneself the joke; discomfort receiving praise; fear that confidence will provoke rejection; urge to disclose flaws before being evaluated.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDismissing compliments; joking about incompetence or appearance; exaggerating flaws; presenting work apologetically; inviting others to contradict negative claims.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Self-Esteem; Safety; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPraise; visibility; competition; attraction; performance; entering unfamiliar groups; fear of envy or criticism.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nConfidence makes me unlikeable; others will expose my flaws; I am safer when expectations are low; worth must be granted by someone else.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nPride; desire; disappointment; direct reassurance requests; the vulnerability of being taken seriously.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nJester — humor turns inward to prevent attack. Everyman — smallness protects belonging. Creator — work is belittled before release. Lover — undesirability is announced to solicit contradiction. Sage — competence is minimized to avoid scrutiny.\n## Pattern Flow\nVisibility or praise appears → judgment or envy feels threatening → self is diminished first → social tension or reassurance brings relief → authentic worth remains unclaimed → the pattern repeats.\n## Often Appears With\nReassurance Seeking; Comparison; People-Pleasing; Shame; Avoidance of Visibility.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nHumility; humor; realism; accessibility; freedom from pretension.\n## Current Cost\nReinforced shame; reassurance dependence; diminished credibility; difficulty receiving love or recognition; hidden ambition.\n## Freer Expression\nHumility without self-attack.\n## One Act of Volition\nReceive one compliment with “thank you” without minimizing, joking, or returning a negative qualifier.\n## Mira Language\n“Humor may be making this easier, but are you lowering yourself before anyone else can evaluate you?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat might happen if you simply accepted the praise? Are you being accurate or preemptively rejecting yourself? What reassurance are you indirectly requesting?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nModesty, playful humor, cultural humility, and accurate acknowledgment of limitations are not automatically Self-Deprecation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated self-diminishment used to regulate social threat, invite reassurance, or avoid visibility.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nNotice the anticipated judgment, state the accurate limitation without global self-attack, and practice receiving positive regard without bargaining it away.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not endlessly contradict every negative statement. Offer accurate acknowledgment, name the pattern gently, and invite a direct request for support.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where self-attack forced others into reassurance or made shared joy impossible. Repair by making needs direct and allowing others’ positive perceptions to stand.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Reassurance Fatigue, Overfunctioning, Irritation, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by comparison, criticism, praise, or status uncertainty. The loop becomes: “I must diminish myself to stay safe” and “I must continually rebuild your worth for you.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat would I have to risk in order to speak about myself accurately rather than dismissively?"},
  "PP-SELF-ERASURE": {"name":"Self-Erasure","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Fusion; Boundary Collapse; Performance of Likability; Conflict Avoidance; Relationship-Bound Worth; Keeping Score; Passive Aggression.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — disappears into service; Everyman — blends to belong; Lover — surrenders identity to preserve union; Innocent — avoids conflict to preserve goodness.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"State one preference before asking what everyone else wants.","Core Logic":"I disappear so the bond does not have to be tested by my full presence.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Resentment; loss of identity; unequal relationships; hidden needs.","Core Fear":"My needs burden others; difference risks abandonment; safety requires being easy.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"It’s easier if I don’t say what I want.; I don’t want to be difficult.; Whatever you want is fine.; My needs will only make things harder.; I should adapt so we can stay connected.; Taking up space feels selfish.","Protective Move":"Self-Erasure is the protective suppression of one’s needs, preferences, voice, identity, or boundaries to preserve belonging, avoid conflict, or remain acceptable.","Pattern ID":"PP-SELF-ERASURE","Short-Term Payoff":"Conflict is avoided and belonging feels temporarily safer.","Freer Expression":"Belonging without disappearance.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Adaptability; empathy; generosity.","Observable Cues":"Agreeing reflexively; hiding opinions; abandoning interests; apologizing for needs; adapting identity to others.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite honest difference, do not punish assertion, and avoid rewarding compliance over authenticity. May trigger Micromanaging, Overfunctioning, Taking for Granted, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Belonging, Trust, and Self-Esteem; avoids anger, disappointment, visibility, and responsibility for choice.","Canonical Name":"Self-Erasure"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSelf-Erasure is the protective suppression of one’s needs, preferences, voice, identity, or boundaries to preserve belonging, avoid conflict, or remain acceptable.\n## Domain\nApproval, Validation, and Self-Worth\n## Related Patterns\nFusion; Boundary Collapse; Performance of Likability; Conflict Avoidance; Relationship-Bound Worth\n## Recognition Sentence\nI disappear so the bond does not have to be tested by my full presence.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- It’s easier if I don’t say what I want.\n- I don’t want to be difficult.\n- Whatever you want is fine.\n- My needs will only make things harder.\n- I should adapt so we can stay connected.\n- Taking up space feels selfish.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDifficulty locating preference; guilt after asserting; fear of taking space; resentment without voiced need.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAgreeing reflexively; hiding opinions; abandoning interests; apologizing for needs; adapting identity to others.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; Trust; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nConflict; disapproval; dominant personalities; dependence; fear of rejection.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy needs burden others; difference risks abandonment; safety requires being easy.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAnger; disappointment; visibility; responsibility for choice.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — disappears into service; Everyman — blends to belong; Lover — surrenders identity to preserve union; Innocent — avoids conflict to preserve goodness.\n## Pattern Flow\nDifference emerges → belonging feels threatened → self-expression contracts → conflict is avoided → resentment and invisibility grow → authentic presence feels riskier.\n## Often Appears With\nFusion; Boundary Collapse; Keeping Score; Passive Aggression.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nAdaptability; empathy; generosity.\n## Current Cost\nResentment; loss of identity; unequal relationships; hidden needs.\n## Freer Expression\nBelonging without disappearance.\n## One Act of Volition\nState one preference before asking what everyone else wants.\n## Mira Language\n“I hear a great deal about what others need. What becomes true when your own preference is allowed into the room?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did you want before adapting? What are you afraid your full presence would cost? Where has silence become resentment?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nFlexibility and generosity are not self-erasure when freely chosen.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated suppression of self across relationships, especially with resentment or identity loss.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPractice small truthful preferences and tolerate another person’s non-catastrophic disappointment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite honest difference, do not punish assertion, and avoid rewarding compliance over authenticity.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where unspoken needs became resentment or indirect behavior; disclose the hidden truth without blaming others for not reading it; establish safer ways to disagree.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Overfunctioning, Taking for Granted, or Contempt. Often triggered by criticism, domination, volatility, or withdrawal. The loop becomes: “I must disappear to keep peace” and “Since you never object, I assume this is acceptable.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere have I traded presence for belonging?"},
  "PP-SELF-HANDICAPPING": {"name":"Self-Handicapping","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Procrastination; Failure to Launch; Perfectionism; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Rationalization; Shame Spiraling; Anticipatory Defeat.","Archetypal Role":"Creator never gives the work full conditions; Warrior enters unprepared; Sage delays study; Rebel resists the standards that might evaluate them.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Remove one preventable obstacle before the next meaningful attempt.","Core Logic":"I am preserving an excuse so the outcome cannot fully judge me.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Reduced performance; lost learning; chronic uncertainty; diminished self-trust.","Core Fear":"Full effort makes failure unbearable; ability determines worth; it is safer not to know my true limit.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should leave myself an excuse in case this goes badly.; If I prepare fully and fail, I will have no protection.; Being too busy gives me a reason the result was not my best.; I would rather not know what a wholehearted attempt would reveal.; I need an obstacle between the outcome and my worth.; Announcing that I will probably fail makes the evaluation safer.","Protective Move":"Self-Handicapping is the protective creation or preservation of obstacles before evaluation so that a disappointing result can be attributed to the obstacle rather than to ability, worth, or wholehearted effort.","Pattern ID":"PP-SELF-HANDICAPPING","Short-Term Payoff":"Possible failure feels less diagnostic when an obstacle or excuse is maintained.","Freer Expression":"Wholehearted effort without identity verdict.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Desire to preserve dignity; awareness of high stakes; sensitivity to evaluation.","Observable Cues":"Delaying preparation; overcommitting before important work; choosing poor conditions; announcing likely failure; withholding full effort.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer practical support without taking ownership; avoid shaming and avoid rescuing the person from every consequence. May trigger Micromanaging, Overfunctioning, Criticism, or Underfunctioning in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Self-Esteem, Autonomy, and Belonging; avoids disappointment, limitation, accountability, grief about skill gaps, and uncertainty about potential.","Canonical Name":"Self-Handicapping"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSelf-Handicapping is the protective creation or preservation of obstacles before evaluation so that a disappointing result can be attributed to the obstacle rather than to ability, worth, or wholehearted effort.\n## Domain\nCompetence, Performance, and Shame Protection\n## Related Patterns\nProcrastination; Failure to Launch; Perfectionism; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Rationalization.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am preserving an excuse so the outcome cannot fully judge me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should leave myself an excuse in case this goes badly.\n- If I prepare fully and fail, I will have no protection.\n- Being too busy gives me a reason the result was not my best.\n- I would rather not know what a wholehearted attempt would reveal.\n- I need an obstacle between the outcome and my worth.\n- Announcing that I will probably fail makes the evaluation safer.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when circumstances become difficult enough to explain failure; reluctance to prepare fully; fear that sincere effort would reveal a limit.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nDelaying preparation; overcommitting before important work; choosing poor conditions; announcing likely failure; withholding full effort.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Self-Esteem; Autonomy; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nEvaluation; competition; public performance; meaningful opportunity; comparison; fear of success or failure.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nFull effort makes failure unbearable; ability determines worth; it is safer not to know my true limit.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDisappointment; limitation; accountability; grief about skill gaps; uncertainty about potential.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCreator never gives the work full conditions; Warrior enters unprepared; Sage delays study; Rebel resists the standards that might evaluate them.\n## Pattern Flow\nEvaluation approaches → competence feels exposed → obstacle or excuse is maintained → possible failure feels less diagnostic → performance suffers → doubt remains unresolved.\n## Often Appears With\nProcrastination; Rationalization; Perfectionism; Shame Spiraling; Anticipatory Defeat.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDesire to preserve dignity; awareness of high stakes; sensitivity to evaluation.\n## Current Cost\nReduced performance; lost learning; chronic uncertainty; diminished self-trust.\n## Freer Expression\nWholehearted effort without identity verdict.\n## One Act of Volition\nRemove one preventable obstacle before the next meaningful attempt.\n## Mira Language\n“I wonder whether this obstacle is doing more than delaying the task—whether it is protecting you from learning what a full attempt would mean.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat excuse would disappear if you prepared fully? Can the result measure a skill rather than your worth?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nReal barriers, disability, exhaustion, poverty, caregiving demands, or executive-function limits are not self-handicapping.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated, preventable obstacle creation specifically before meaningful evaluation, with relief from having an alternative explanation.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate worth from outcome, reduce one controllable barrier, and define the attempt as information rather than verdict.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer practical support without taking ownership; avoid shaming and avoid rescuing the person from every consequence.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where preventable obstacles affected shared commitments; make a realistic restitution or revised plan and demonstrate preparation before the next commitment.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Overfunctioning, Criticism, or Underfunctioning in others. Their control may reinforce the belief that wholehearted effort is unsafe or externally owned.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat obstacle am I preserving so I will not have to let the outcome speak clearly?"},
  "PP-SELF-ISOLATION": {"name":"Self-Isolation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Distancing; Hyper-Independence; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Shame Spiraling; Vulnerability Avoidance; Emotional Numbing; Depression-related withdrawal.","Archetypal Role":"Hermit retreats beyond restoration. Orphan assumes exclusion before testing belonging. Sage replaces relationship with solitary understanding. Warrior hides wounds from the group.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions and a safety-escalation instruction but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Send one honest, bounded message to a safe person before disappearing further.","Core Logic":"I am making myself unreachable so I cannot be rejected, exposed, or disappointed.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Loneliness; delayed help; distorted assumptions; weakened relationships; reduced resilience.","Core Fear":"My needs burden people; closeness ends in pain; no one comes when I call; being seen weakens me.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should disappear until I can handle this alone.; No one would understand, and I’d only burden them.; Canceling contact feels like relief.; It’s safer to become unreachable than risk rejection.; I’ll respond when I’m doing better.; Needing support feels more dangerous than being alone.","Protective Move":"Self-Isolation is the protective reduction of contact, visibility, or reliance on others in order to avoid rejection, burdening others, conflict, shame, or relational uncertainty.","Pattern ID":"PP-SELF-ISOLATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Immediate relief and control follow when contact is reduced.","Freer Expression":"Chosen solitude with living connection.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Solitude; self-containment; reflection; independence.","Observable Cues":"Ignoring messages; declining meaningful contact; concealing distress; withdrawing from communities; handling crises alone; allowing relationships to fade without explanation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer low-pressure, specific contact without intrusion; respect boundaries; do not shame absence; escalate support appropriately when immediate safety is in question. May trigger Clinging, Compulsive Contact, Testing the Bond, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Autonomy, Self-Esteem, and Trust; avoids longing, dependency, grief, uncertainty, possible rejection, and mutual obligation.","Canonical Name":"Self-Isolation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSelf-Isolation is the protective reduction of contact, visibility, or reliance on others in order to avoid rejection, burdening others, conflict, shame, or relational uncertainty.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Belonging, and Withdrawal\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Distancing; Hyper-Independence; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Shame Spiraling; Vulnerability Avoidance; Emotional Numbing\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am making myself unreachable so I cannot be rejected, exposed, or disappointed.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should disappear until I can handle this alone.\n- No one would understand, and I’d only burden them.\n- Canceling contact feels like relief.\n- It’s safer to become unreachable than risk rejection.\n- I’ll respond when I’m doing better.\n- Needing support feels more dangerous than being alone.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nConviction that no one would understand; relief from canceled contact; shame about needing support; growing difficulty re-entering connection.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nIgnoring messages; declining meaningful contact; concealing distress; withdrawing from communities; handling crises alone; allowing relationships to fade without explanation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Autonomy; Self-Esteem; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nShame; conflict; disappointment; overwhelm; perceived burden; social comparison; fear of being seen in difficulty.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy needs burden people; closeness ends in pain; no one comes when I call; being seen weakens me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nLonging; dependency; grief; uncertainty; possible rejection; mutual obligation.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nHermit retreats beyond restoration. Orphan assumes exclusion before testing belonging. Sage replaces relationship with solitary understanding. Warrior hides wounds from the group.\n## Pattern Flow\nDistress or relational risk appears → trust or worth feels threatened → contact is reduced → immediate relief and control follow → support and corrective experience disappear → isolation confirms the original belief.\n## Often Appears With\nShame Spiraling; Hyper-Independence; Emotional Numbing; Vulnerability Avoidance; Depression-related withdrawal.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSolitude; self-containment; reflection; independence.\n## Current Cost\nLoneliness; delayed help; distorted assumptions; weakened relationships; reduced resilience.\n## Freer Expression\nChosen solitude with living connection.\n## One Act of Volition\nSend one honest, bounded message to a safe person before disappearing further.\n## Mira Language\n“Solitude may be needed. I also notice that contact is shrinking precisely when support might matter. Is this restorative privacy, or protection through becoming unreachable?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat do you fear would happen if someone knew? Which connection is safe enough for ten percent more truth? Is the withdrawal restoring you or confirming hopelessness?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nIntroversion, restorative solitude, illness, sensory needs, cultural differences, and safety-based disengagement are not Self-Isolation.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated withdrawal during distress that blocks wanted support or connection and strengthens beliefs of unreachability.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor the need for reduced stimulation while preserving one thread of safe contact; communicate the need for space and a point of return.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer low-pressure, specific contact without intrusion; respect boundaries; do not shame absence; escalate support appropriately when immediate safety is in question.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge unexplained disappearance and its impact; clarify what support or space was needed; make a future communication agreement without promising constant availability.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Compulsive Contact, Testing the Bond, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by Intrusion, Criticism, Possessiveness, or shame. Stories become “I disappear because no one is safe” and “I must pursue because you always vanish.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nIs my solitude nourishing me, or making me impossible to reach?"},
  "PP-SELF-SABOTAGE": {"name":"Self-Sabotage","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Self-Handicapping; Procrastination; Failure to Launch; Anticipatory Defeat; Fear of Success; Shame Spiraling; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Fantasy Refuge; Impostorism.","Archetypal Role":"Creator—destroys or withholds the work before judgment; Lover—provokes rupture before deeper attachment; Warrior—enters unwinnable battles; Rebel—confuses consistency with captivity; Orphan—returns to familiar deprivation.","Migration Notes":"Batch 13 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text with obvious spacing corruption repaired without changing meaning; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source emphasizes differential consideration for executive dysfunction, disability, poverty, discrimination, illness, trauma, and realistic constraint rather than assigning one explicit controlled flag.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"13","One Act of Volition":"Identify the next predictable derailment point and create one external safeguard before reaching it.","Core Logic":"I am making the feared outcome happen on terms I can control.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Lost opportunities; unstable relationships; financial or health harm; reinforced shame; distrust of oneself; chronic incompletion.","Core Fear":"Success makes me a target; change separates me from my people; hope makes loss worse; if I fail first, no one can expose me; I cannot sustain good things.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to disrupt this before it becomes real.; Success is starting to feel dangerous.; If I fail on my own terms, no one can expose me.; Familiar loss feels safer than uncertain possibility.; I should create distance before this opportunity changes me.; Relief comes when the momentum finally breaks.","Protective Move":"Self-Sabotage is the protective disruption of one’s own progress, opportunity, stability, or relationships when success, exposure, responsibility, change, or possible loss feels more threatening than remaining in a familiar limitation.","Pattern ID":"PP-SELF-SABOTAGE","Short-Term Payoff":"Control and familiar identity briefly return after progress is disrupted.","Freer Expression":"Protective discernment without self-betrayal.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Risk detection; autonomy; realism about consequences; protection of identity and belonging.","Observable Cues":"Missing crucial deadlines; abandoning near completion; creating avoidable conflict before intimacy or opportunity; violating one’s own plan at decisive moments; withholding necessary information or effort; repeatedly choosing predictable derailment.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Avoid shaming or rescuing. Ask what changed near the turning point, clarify consequences and support, and preserve the person’s responsibility for the next action. May trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Resentment, Withdrawal, or Devaluation in others.","Emotional Function":"Protects safety, predictability, identity continuity, belonging, autonomy, self-esteem, rest, and protection from shame; avoids hope, uncertainty, responsibility, grief, envy from others, changed identity, and dependence on continued effort.","Canonical Name":"Self-Sabotage"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSelf-Sabotage is the protective disruption of one’s own progress, opportunity, stability, or relationships when success, exposure, responsibility, change, or possible loss feels more threatening than remaining in a familiar limitation.\n## Domain\nAction, Achievement, Identity, and Change\n## Related Patterns\nSelf-Handicapping; Procrastination; Failure to Launch; Anticipatory Defeat; Fear of Success; Shame Spiraling\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am making the feared outcome happen on terms I can control.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to disrupt this before it becomes real.\n- Success is starting to feel dangerous.\n- If I fail on my own terms, no one can expose me.\n- Familiar loss feels safer than uncertain possibility.\n- I should create distance before this opportunity changes me.\n- Relief comes when the momentum finally breaks.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nMomentum creates unease; success feels exposing; approaching completion brings urges to escape or disrupt; familiar failure feels safer than uncertain possibility; relief follows the setback.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nMissing crucial deadlines; abandoning near completion; creating avoidable conflict before intimacy or opportunity; violating one’s own plan at decisive moments; withholding necessary information or effort; repeatedly choosing predictable derailment.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; predictability; identity continuity; belonging; autonomy; self-esteem; rest; protection from shame.\n## Usually Triggered By\nVisibility; success; commitment; intimacy; transition; increased responsibility; possibility of being evaluated or later losing what was gained.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nSuccess makes me a target; change separates me from my people; hope makes loss worse; if I fail first, no one can expose me; I cannot sustain good things.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nHope; uncertainty; responsibility; grief; envy from others; changed identity; dependence on continued effort.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCreator—destroys or withholds the work before judgment; Lover—provokes rupture before deeper attachment; Warrior—enters unwinnable battles; Rebel—confuses consistency with captivity; Orphan—returns to familiar deprivation.\n## Pattern Flow\nOpportunity or closeness increases → exposure, change, or possible loss feels threatening → progress is disrupted → control and familiar identity briefly return → consequences deepen shame and mistrust → future opportunity feels even more dangerous.\n## Often Appears With\nShame Spiraling; Anticipatory Defeat; Procrastination; Preemptive Self-Rejection; Fantasy Refuge; Impostorism.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nRisk detection; autonomy; realism about consequences; protection of identity and belonging.\n## Current Cost\nLost opportunities; unstable relationships; financial or health harm; reinforced shame; distrust of oneself; chronic incompletion.\n## Freer Expression\nProtective discernment without self-betrayal.\n## One Act of Volition\nIdentify the next predictable derailment point and create one external safeguard before reaching it.\n## Mira Language\n“The setback may not mean you did not want the goal. Sometimes approaching it activates a need to regain safety or control. What became more threatening as success got closer?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat did the disruption protect you from? What changed when progress became real? What safeguard would preserve agency without destroying the opportunity?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nExecutive dysfunction, disability, poverty, discrimination, illness, trauma symptoms, changing one’s mind, or realistic constraint must not be mislabeled as Self-Sabotage.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated sequence in which progress reliably triggers avoidable disruption followed by short-term relief—not an isolated mistake.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReplace moral condemnation with sequence recognition. Identify the feared consequence of success, restore bandwidth, reduce the next step, and design support at the known derailment point.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAvoid shaming or rescuing. Ask what changed near the turning point, clarify consequences and support, and preserve the person’s responsibility for the next action.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName the concrete disruption and its impact without using fear as an excuse. Repair practical harm, communicate honestly, and establish a specific prevention structure rather than making another broad promise.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Resentment, Withdrawal, or Devaluation in others. Often triggered by Pressure, Perfectionism, Comparison, or Conditional Warmth. Stories become “I cannot be trusted with possibility” and “I must control or abandon you before you fail again.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat becomes dangerous when the thing I say I want begins to become real?"},
  "PP-SEMANTIC-CONTROL": {"name":"Semantic Control","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Misdirection; Narrative Overcontrol; Pedantry; Gaslighting; Moving the Goalposts.","Archetypal Role":"The Definer; Sage controls the frame through precision; Ruler authorizes acceptable language; Trickster moves the lock when others find the key.","Migration Notes":"Batch 17 anomaly expansion from an experimental 28-field archetypal-development record. All useful source content was preserved and mapped into the canonical 27-field structure. Spacing repaired. Source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because repeated semantic narrowing may function as reality distortion, invalidation, and conversational domination.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"17","One Act of Volition":"Say, “I understand the meaning you are trying to convey,” before clarifying terminology.","Core Logic":"If I control the definitions, I control what can be acknowledged, challenged, or concluded.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Confusion; invalidation; circular conflict; semantic captivity; erosion of trust.","Core Fear":"Being misread, exposed, overruled, unable to defend a preferred narrative, or forced into accountability through another person’s language.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"That is not what that word means.; You cannot call it that.; Technically, I never said that.; Your whole point fails because you phrased it wrong.; I need to control the terms before I address the impact.; If their wording is imperfect, I do not have to answer the substance.","Clinical Term":"Linguistic control; intellectualization; conversational dominance","Protective Move":"Semantic Control redefines words, disputes labels, narrows meanings, or moves the conversation into technical disputes so one person can control what may be acknowledged or concluded.","Pattern ID":"PP-SEMANTIC-CONTROL","Short-Term Payoff":"Authority is regained and the emotional substance of the issue is avoided.","Freer Expression":"Precision that deepens understanding rather than controlling reality.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; conceptual clarity; careful language; precision; attention to meaning.","Observable Cues":"Correcting terminology before acknowledging impact; disputing labels endlessly; narrowing meanings; using technicalities to nullify another person’s point; changing definitions mid-discussion.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"The other person’s experience is treated as invalid unless phrased in approved language. May trigger Overexplaining, Interrogative Control, Withdrawal, or Narrative Overcontrol.","Emotional Function":"Protects interpretive authority, self-esteem, control, and safety; avoids accountability, ambiguity, shame, emotional substance, and loss of narrative power.","Canonical Name":"Semantic Control"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSemantic Control is the protective use of definitions, wording disputes, narrowed meanings, or technical distinctions to control what can be acknowledged, challenged, or concluded. It differs from good-faith clarification because precision becomes a means of evading substance or dominating interpretation.\n## Domain\nLanguage, Accountability, and Interpretive Control\n## Related Patterns\nMisdirection; Narrative Overcontrol; Pedantry; Gaslighting; Moving the Goalposts\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I control the definitions, I control what can be acknowledged, challenged, or concluded.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- That is not what that word means.\n- You cannot call it that.\n- Technically, I never said that.\n- Your whole point fails because you phrased it wrong.\n- I need to control the terms before I address the impact.\n- If their wording is imperfect, I do not have to answer the substance.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when the issue becomes technical; urgency to correct labels; discomfort acknowledging meaning before wording; fear that another person’s framing will define reality.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nCorrecting terminology before acknowledging impact; disputing labels endlessly; narrowing meanings; using technicalities to nullify another person’s point; changing definitions mid-discussion.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nInterpretive authority; self-esteem; control; safety; competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAccountability; accusation; imprecise language; emotionally charged labels; competing narratives; public conflict.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBeing misnamed is dangerous; whoever defines the terms wins; imprecision invites humiliation; accepting another framing means surrender.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nShame; ambiguity; emotional impact; responsibility; uncertainty; another person’s independent meaning-making.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nThe Definer guards the gate of meaning; Sage controls the frame through precision; Ruler authorizes acceptable language; Trickster changes the lock when others find the key.\n## Pattern Flow\nImpact or accusation is raised → interpretive authority feels threatened → wording is narrowed or disputed → control returns temporarily → substance remains unaddressed → conflict becomes circular and trust erodes.\n## Often Appears With\nNarrative Overcontrol; Misdirection; Overexplaining; Moving the Goalposts.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; conceptual clarity; careful language; precision; attention to meaning.\n## Current Cost\nConfusion; invalidation; circular conflict; semantic captivity; erosion of trust.\n## Freer Expression\nPrecision that deepens understanding rather than controlling reality.\n## One Act of Volition\nSay, “I understand the meaning you are trying to convey,” before clarifying terminology.\n## Mira Language\n“The wording may matter. Can we first acknowledge the meaning and impact you are responding to, then clarify the term?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat substantive issue remains if the label changes? Are you clarifying or preventing acknowledgment? Can multiple framings carry valid information?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGood-faith clarification, legal precision, cultural or language differences, and correcting harmful mislabeling are not Semantic Control.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of wording disputes to evade substance, invalidate experience, or preserve unilateral interpretive authority.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nReflect the intended meaning and impact first; clarify wording second; allow definitions to remain revisable and shared.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRefuse semantic captivity, return to observable behavior and impact, and do not let technical precision erase the central issue.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where wording disputes invalidated another person or prevented accountability. Restate their meaning fairly, address the substance, and clarify terms without controlling them.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overexplaining, Interrogative Control, Withdrawal, or Narrative Overcontrol. The loop becomes “I must perfect the wording to be heard” versus “I must control the wording so I cannot be challenged.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere is precision serving understanding, and where is it deciding what others are allowed to mean?"},
  "PP-SHAME-SPIRALING": {"name":"Shame Spiraling","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Personalization; Self-Deprecation; Perfectionism; Defensiveness; Rumination; Emotional Distancing.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent — purity must be restored. Lover — one rupture means unlovability. Sage — error invalidates credibility. Caregiver — harm means being a bad person.","Migration Notes":"Batch 7 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"7","One Act of Volition":"Name the exact behavior and impact without making a claim about your total worth.","Core Logic":"I am turning one painful event into a verdict on my whole self.","Primary Domain":"Emotional","Long-Term Cost":"Paralysis; withdrawal; distorted responsibility; lost repair opportunities.","Core Fear":"Love is withdrawn when I fail; mistakes reveal my true worthlessness.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I ruin everything.; This mistake proves I’m a terrible person.; There’s no point trying to repair this.; I should disappear before I hurt anyone else.; If I condemn myself first, no one can judge me more harshly.; One failure tells the truth about my whole worth.","Protective Move":"Shame Spiraling is the protective collapse from “I did something wrong” into “I am wrong,” using global self-condemnation to create certainty, preempt criticism, or avoid the more vulnerable work of repair.","Pattern ID":"PP-SHAME-SPIRALING","Short-Term Payoff":"Certainty and self-punishment bring temporary structure when global shame takes over.","Freer Expression":"Accountability without annihilation.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Conscience; sensitivity; humility; desire not to harm.","Observable Cues":"Sweeping self-accusations; rejecting reassurance; abandoning repair; withdrawing after mistakes.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not argue with the person’s worthlessness claim endlessly; return gently to the specific impact, responsibility, and next step. May trigger Reassurance Seeking, Overfunctioning, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Belonging, Trust, and Competence; avoids specific responsibility, grief, uncertainty, and asking for forgiveness.","Canonical Name":"Shame Spiraling"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nShame Spiraling is the protective collapse from “I did something wrong” into “I am wrong,” using global self-condemnation to create certainty, preempt criticism, or avoid the more vulnerable work of repair.\n## Domain\nShame, Identity, and Vulnerability\n## Related Patterns\nPersonalization; Self-Deprecation; Perfectionism; Defensiveness; Rumination\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am turning one painful event into a verdict on my whole self.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I ruin everything.\n- This mistake proves I’m a terrible person.\n- There’s no point trying to repair this.\n- I should disappear before I hurt anyone else.\n- If I condemn myself first, no one can judge me more harshly.\n- One failure tells the truth about my whole worth.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSudden global self-disgust; urge to disappear; repetitive replay; belief that repair is impossible.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nSweeping self-accusations; rejecting reassurance; abandoning repair; withdrawing after mistakes.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Belonging; Trust; Competence.\n## Usually Triggered By\nMistakes; criticism; conflict; exposure; disappointment.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nLove is withdrawn when I fail; mistakes reveal my true worthlessness.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nSpecific responsibility; grief; uncertainty; asking for forgiveness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent — purity must be restored. Lover — one rupture means unlovability. Sage — error invalidates credibility. Caregiver — harm means being a bad person.\n## Pattern Flow\nMistake or rupture → worth feels threatened → global shame takes over → certainty and self-punishment bring temporary structure → repair and learning stop → shame deepens.\n## Often Appears With\nRumination; Personalization; Self-Deprecation; Emotional Distancing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nConscience; sensitivity; humility; desire not to harm.\n## Current Cost\nParalysis; withdrawal; distorted responsibility; lost repair opportunities.\n## Freer Expression\nAccountability without annihilation.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the exact behavior and impact without making a claim about your total worth.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be moving from a specific mistake into a total judgment of yourself. Can we separate what happened from who you are?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat specifically needs repair? What remains true about you beyond this event? What would responsibility look like without self-destruction?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nRemorse, grief, and moral concern are not automatically shame spiraling.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated global self-condemnation that displaces concrete accountability or recovery.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nRegulate first, name the behavior precisely, identify the injured value, and choose one repair action.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not argue with the person’s worthlessness claim endlessly; return gently to the specific impact, responsibility, and next step.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge both the original harm and any burden placed on others to rescue the person from collapse; make a specific repair without demanding immediate absolution.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Reassurance Seeking, Overfunctioning, Resentment, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by Criticism, Devaluation, Perfectionism, or visible disappointment. Stories become “I ruin everything” and “I now have to caretake your shame instead of addressing what happened.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using self-condemnation instead of specific accountability?"},
  "PP-SHAPESHIFTING": {"name":"Shapeshifting","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Chameleon Identity; Masking; Image Management; Compartmented Persona; Identity Diffusion.","Archetypal Role":"The Many-Faced One; Lover becomes what secures attachment; Jester changes tone to fit the room; Orphan adapts identity to preserve belonging.","Migration Notes":"Batch 17 anomaly expansion from the experimental 28-field archetypal-development template. Useful elements including imagery, mantra, progress signal, integrated expression, and naming palette were preserved through canonical mapping. Spacing repaired; source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term retained because the source explicitly supplied it. Safety Flags remains empty, while the body preserves strong cautions against pathologizing cultural code-switching, neurodivergent masking, professional roles, or trauma-based adaptation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"17","One Act of Volition":"Ask, “What remains true for me in every room?” and name one stable value before adapting.","Core Logic":"If I become what this person or setting rewards, I can stay safe, connected, and desirable.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Identity confusion; exhaustion; mistrust; resentment; difficulty with intimacy and commitment.","Core Fear":"Rejection, conflict, exposure, or discovering there is no stable self beneath adaptation.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I am a different person with everyone.; Tell me who you need me to be.; I do not know what I actually want.; That version of me only exists with them.; Consistency may cost me belonging.; I can adapt safely if no one sees the whole pattern.","Clinical Term":"Identity adaptation; masking; self-concept instability","Protective Move":"Shapeshifting rapidly changes persona, opinions, affect, values, or preferences to fit the audience so belonging and safety can be preserved.","Pattern ID":"PP-SHAPESHIFTING","Short-Term Payoff":"Acceptance, flexibility, reduced friction, and social fluency.","Freer Expression":"Flexible adaptation anchored in a coherent self.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Social attunement; versatility; empathy; imaginative range; adaptive intelligence.","Observable Cues":"Rapidly changing opinions, tone, persona, or preferences by audience; disowning prior versions; difficulty naming stable wants; inconsistent commitments across relationships.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Different people may receive incompatible versions, leaving others unsure what is genuine. May trigger Suspicion, Testing the Bond, Emotional Distancing, or Narrative Overcontrol.","Emotional Function":"Protects belonging, safety, approval, and adaptability; avoids rejection, conflict, self-definition, mismatch, and the vulnerability of being known consistently.","Canonical Name":"Shapeshifting"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nShapeshifting is the protective alteration of persona, opinions, affect, values, or preferences across contexts so the self can remain safe, connected, and desirable. It differs from healthy adaptation because recurrent changes obscure stable values, needs, or commitments.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Adaptation, and Belonging\n## Related Patterns\nChameleon Identity; Masking; Image Management; Compartmented Persona; Identity Diffusion\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I become what this person or setting rewards, I can stay safe, connected, and desirable.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I am a different person with everyone.\n- Tell me who you need me to be.\n- I do not know what I actually want.\n- That version of me only exists with them.\n- Consistency may cost me belonging.\n- I can adapt safely if no one sees the whole pattern.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRapid self-editing; uncertainty about authentic preference; relief when others approve; fatigue after switching contexts; fear that consistency will trap or expose you.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRapidly changing opinions, tone, persona, or preferences by audience; disowning prior versions; difficulty naming stable wants; inconsistent commitments across relationships.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nBelonging; safety; approval; flexibility; self-esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nNew groups; authority; intimacy; cultural transitions; conflict; perceived evaluation; incompatible expectations.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nAuthenticity is dangerous; belonging requires adaptation; consistency invites rejection; no stable self will be accepted everywhere.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nMismatch; conflict; separateness; uncertainty about identity; grief over not fitting; responsibility for stable commitments.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nThe Many-Faced One changes color until nearly invisible; Lover becomes what secures attachment; Jester changes tone to fit the room; Orphan adapts identity to preserve belonging.\n## Pattern Flow\nContext or audience changes → belonging feels uncertain → persona and preferences shift → acceptance and reduced friction return → self-reference weakens → greater adaptation becomes necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nChameleon Identity; Masking; Image Management; Performance of an Emotion or Role.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSocial attunement; versatility; empathy; imaginative range; adaptive intelligence.\n## Current Cost\nIdentity confusion; exhaustion; mistrust; resentment; difficulty with intimacy and commitment.\n## Freer Expression\nFlexible adaptation anchored in a coherent self.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk, “What remains true for me in every room?” and name one stable value before adapting.\n## Mira Language\n“Your adaptability may be highly intelligent. What remains recognizably yours across these different versions?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhich changes are chosen and which are fear-driven? What value persists across contexts? What authentic difference feels hardest to reveal?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nHealthy code-switching, neurodivergent masking, professional roles, cultural adaptation, and trauma-based survival must not be pathologized without context.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRecurrent identity alteration that obscures stable values, needs, or commitments and produces confusion, exhaustion, or relational mistrust.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nTrack stable values and needs, disclose small authentic differences, and tolerate imperfect fit without forcing total exposure.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nMake room for complexity and change while asking for clarity on commitments that materially affect trust or consent.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where incompatible versions, concealed preferences, or shifting commitments confused others. Clarify what is genuinely true now and what can be relied upon.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Suspicion, Testing the Bond, Emotional Distancing, or Narrative Overcontrol. The loop becomes “I must change to remain accepted” versus “I must investigate because I cannot tell what is real.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I adapting with choice, and where am I disappearing into what the room rewards?"},
  "PP-SOLICITING-DEPENDENCE": {"name":"Soliciting Dependence","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Indispensability; Coercive Caretaking; Savior Identity; Gatekeeping; Enabling.","Archetypal Role":"The Needed One; Caregiver creates reliance through overhelp; Ruler controls access and competence; Lover treats independence as abandonment.","Migration Notes":"Batch 17 anomaly expansion from the experimental 28-field archetypal-development template. Useful source material was preserved and normalized into the canonical record. Spacing repaired; source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term retained from source. Safety Flags mapped to Coercive Control because dependency creation may involve financial, informational, practical, or social restriction that constrains autonomy.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"17","One Act of Volition":"Ask, “Does this help them become more capable without me?” before taking over.","Core Logic":"If others need me, they cannot leave, outgrow me, or see how vulnerable I am.","Safety Flags":["Coercive Control"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Enmeshment; resentment; underdevelopment; unstable attachment; autonomy sabotage.","Core Fear":"Abandonment, replaceability, loss of role, or lack of inherent worth when others become capable or separate.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"You cannot do this without me.; No one will help you like I do.; After everything I have done, you are leaving?; Let me handle it; you will only make it worse.; Their independence means I am losing them.; I need to remain the person they cannot function without.","Clinical Term":"Dependency reinforcement; enmeshment; controlling caretaking","Protective Move":"Soliciting Dependence increases another person’s reliance through overhelping, withheld knowledge, discouraged autonomy, or framing independence as betrayal.","Pattern ID":"PP-SOLICITING-DEPENDENCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Closeness, relevance, gratitude, and control.","Freer Expression":"Care that expands capability and preserves connection without dependence.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Devotion; teaching; practical support; relational stewardship; reliability.","Observable Cues":"Taking over learnable tasks; withholding transferable knowledge; discouraging outside support; punishing independence; framing autonomy as disloyalty or danger.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Help is offered in ways that make competence, separation, or dissent harder. May trigger Underfunctioning, Appeasement, Resentment, or Rebellion.","Emotional Function":"Protects attachment, relevance, authority, worth, and belonging; avoids replaceability, separation, equal reciprocity, and identity beyond usefulness.","Canonical Name":"Soliciting Dependence"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSoliciting Dependence is the protective creation or reinforcement of another person’s reliance in order to secure attachment, relevance, authority, or control. It differs from ordinary caregiving because help repeatedly makes autonomy, competence, or separation harder.\n## Domain\nDependency, Caretaking, and Relational Control\n## Related Patterns\nIndispensability; Coercive Caretaking; Savior Identity; Gatekeeping; Enabling\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf others need me, they cannot leave, outgrow me, or see how vulnerable I am.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- You cannot do this without me.\n- No one will help you like I do.\n- After everything I have done, you are leaving?\n- Let me handle it; you will only make it worse.\n- Their independence means I am losing them.\n- I need to remain the person they cannot function without.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nAlarm when another person gains competence; relief when they return for help; resentment paired with reluctance to teach; fear of becoming unnecessary.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nTaking over learnable tasks; withholding transferable knowledge; discouraging outside support; punishing independence; framing autonomy as disloyalty or danger.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAttachment; relevance; authority; worth; belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAnother person’s growth; separation; new relationships; outside support; role transition; reduced need; succession.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI am loved when indispensable; autonomy means abandonment; usefulness is my only secure value; others will leave when they no longer need me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nReplaceability; grief; equality; mutual dependence; identity beyond care; lack of control.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nThe Needed One binds every branch to the central stake; Caregiver creates reliance through overhelp; Ruler controls access and competence; Lover treats independence as abandonment.\n## Pattern Flow\nAnother person becomes more capable or separate → attachment and worth feel threatened → help, access, or warnings increase → relevance and closeness return → competence and autonomy weaken → dependency becomes more necessary.\n## Often Appears With\nSavior Identity; Gatekeeping; Indispensability; Power Hoarding; Enabling.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDevotion; teaching; practical support; relational stewardship; reliability.\n## Current Cost\nEnmeshment; resentment; underdevelopment; unstable attachment; autonomy sabotage.\n## Freer Expression\nCare that expands capability and preserves connection without dependence.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk, “Does this help them become more capable without me?” before taking over.\n## Mira Language\n“Your care may be genuine. Is the help increasing their agency, or making your continued centrality necessary?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat does their independence seem to mean about your place? What knowledge or access could be transferred? Who would you be if they needed you less?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nOrdinary caregiving, disability support, developmental needs, temporary dependence, and safety-based assistance are not Soliciting Dependence.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeatedly increasing or preserving another person’s reliance to secure attachment, status, or control when greater autonomy is safely possible.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nTeach rather than take over, share access and knowledge, celebrate competence, and diversify identity beyond being needed.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRequest transferable support, independent access, and the right to learn, choose, and separate without punishment.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where help restricted autonomy or created obligation. Transfer knowledge, access, resources, and decision rights, and stop using past care as leverage.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Underfunctioning, Appeasement, Resentment, or Rebellion. The loop becomes “You need me to remain safe” versus “I must become dependent, submit, or fight for autonomy.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere is my care helping another person grow, and where is it protecting me from becoming less necessary?"},
  "PP-SPIRITUAL-BYPASSING": {"name":"Spiritual Bypassing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Meaning Inflation; Rationalization; Emotional Numbing; Intellectualizing; Toxic Positivity.","Archetypal Role":"Mystic — transcendence replaces embodiment. Sage — wisdom replaces feeling. Caregiver — comfort replaces witnessing. Innocent — faith excludes danger.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Name the concrete feeling, harm, or responsibility before offering any spiritual interpretation.","Core Logic":"I am rising above what I have not yet faced.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Invalidated experience; delayed grief; weak accountability; vulnerability to manipulation; relational distance.","Core Fear":"Pain will overwhelm me; anger makes me bad; doubt threatens belonging; suffering must have a higher reason.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should rise above this instead of feeling it.; There must be a higher reason, so anger isn’t necessary.; I need to forgive before I’m ready.; If I stay spiritual, I won’t have to face the grief.; This pain is only a lesson I should transcend.; Meaning feels safer than the concrete impact.","Protective Move":"Spiritual Bypassing uses spiritual beliefs, elevated language, or transcendent explanations to avoid grief, anger, responsibility, conflict, limitation, or embodied reality.","Pattern ID":"PP-SPIRITUAL-BYPASSING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary coherence returns when spiritual explanation rises.","Freer Expression":"Embodied spirituality.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Faith; perspective; forgiveness; reverence; hope.","Observable Cues":"Reframing harm as destiny; replacing accountability with spiritual explanation; urging premature forgiveness; treating distress as low consciousness.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not debate belief; return gently to concrete impact, feeling, consent, and responsibility. May trigger Anger as Armor, Emotional Distancing, Devaluation, or Hostility Toward Criticism.","Emotional Function":"Protects Purpose, Trust, Self-Esteem, and Belonging; avoids grief, rage, helplessness, complicity, limitation, and injustice.","Canonical Name":"Spiritual Bypassing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSpiritual Bypassing uses spiritual beliefs, elevated language, or transcendent explanations to avoid grief, anger, responsibility, conflict, limitation, or embodied reality.\n## Domain\nMeaning, Identity, and Spiritual Protection\n## Related Patterns\nMeaning Inflation; Rationalization; Emotional Numbing; Intellectualizing; Toxic Positivity\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am rising above what I have not yet faced.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should rise above this instead of feeling it.\n- There must be a higher reason, so anger isn’t necessary.\n- I need to forgive before I’m ready.\n- If I stay spiritual, I won’t have to face the grief.\n- This pain is only a lesson I should transcend.\n- Meaning feels safer than the concrete impact.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nPressure to forgive, transcend, trust, or “see the lesson” before the experience has been felt; discomfort with anger or ambiguity.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReframing harm as destiny; replacing accountability with spiritual explanation; urging premature forgiveness; treating distress as low consciousness.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nPurpose; Trust; Self-Esteem; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nLoss; conflict; moral injury; powerlessness; uncertainty; another person’s anger or grief.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nPain will overwhelm me; anger makes me bad; doubt threatens belonging; suffering must have a higher reason.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; rage; helplessness; complicity; limitation; injustice.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nMystic — transcendence replaces embodiment. Sage — wisdom replaces feeling. Caregiver — comfort replaces witnessing. Innocent — faith excludes danger.\n## Pattern Flow\nPain or contradiction appears → meaning or goodness feels threatened → spiritual explanation rises → temporary coherence returns → reality and accountability remain unmet.\n## Often Appears With\nMeaning Inflation; Toxic Positivity; Rationalization; Emotional Numbing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nFaith; perspective; forgiveness; reverence; hope.\n## Current Cost\nInvalidated experience; delayed grief; weak accountability; vulnerability to manipulation; relational distance.\n## Freer Expression\nEmbodied spirituality.\n## One Act of Volition\nName the concrete feeling, harm, or responsibility before offering any spiritual interpretation.\n## Mira Language\n“The spiritual meaning may matter. What must be felt or acknowledged before meaning becomes useful rather than protective?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat truth is the elevated explanation helping you avoid? What would faith look like if anger and grief were also allowed?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSpiritual practice, forgiveness, hope, and meaning-making are not inherently bypassing.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated replacement of emotional contact or accountability with spiritual explanation.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nLet meaning wait until the body, impact, and responsibility have been named.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not debate belief; return gently to concrete impact, feeling, consent, and responsibility.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where spiritual language minimized pain or excused behavior; witness the actual impact and make a concrete repair without requiring forgiveness.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Anger as Armor, Emotional Distancing, Devaluation, or Hostility Toward Criticism. Often triggered by grief, uncertainty, criticism, or another person’s uncontained pain. The loop becomes “You refuse the higher truth” versus “You refuse my reality.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using meaning to rise above what still needs to be faced?"},
  "PP-SPLITTING": {"name":"Splitting","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"All-or-Nothing Thinking; Idealization; Devaluation; Projection; Moral Superiority.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent — preserving purity by expelling contradiction. Lover — idealizing union then devaluing disappointment. Rebel — dividing oppressors from the pure. Ruler — classifying loyal versus disloyal. Sage — reducing nuance to total judgment.","Migration Notes":"Batch 4 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly distinguishes Splitting from recognizing abuse or ending an unsafe relationship.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"4","One Act of Volition":"Name three true things that do not fit the same verdict.","Core Logic":"I need you—or me—to be entirely one thing so I do not have to hold contradiction.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Unstable attachment; distorted judgment; abrupt ruptures; inability to integrate mixed truths.","Core Fear":"Mixed signals are unsafe; if good and bad coexist, I cannot know whom to trust; ambivalence means danger.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"One bad thing means the whole person is bad.; I can’t remember anything good about them right now.; They were perfect, and now I see they’re awful.; I need to know whether they’re safe or unsafe.; If they disappointed me, the entire relationship was false.; There’s no middle ground here.","Protective Move":"Splitting organizes complex people or situations into all-good or all-bad categories when ambivalence, contradiction, or uncertainty feels intolerable.","Pattern ID":"PP-SPLITTING","Short-Term Payoff":"Certainty returns when the whole is sorted into good or bad.","Freer Expression":"Complexity without collapse.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Moral clarity; decisiveness; sensitivity to inconsistency.","Observable Cues":"Rapid idealization and rejection; rewriting the whole relationship after one injury; treating disagreement as proof of bad character; alternating praise and condemnation.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not argue for total goodness; acknowledge the real injury while reintroducing complexity and boundaries. May trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Counter-Devaluation, or Self-Erasure.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Safety, Belonging, and Self-Esteem; avoids uncertainty, grief, dependency, complexity, moral ambiguity, and disappointment.","Canonical Name":"Splitting"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSplitting organizes complex people or situations into all-good or all-bad categories when ambivalence, contradiction, or uncertainty feels intolerable.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nAll-or-Nothing Thinking; Idealization; Devaluation; Projection; Moral Superiority\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need you—or me—to be entirely one thing so I do not have to hold contradiction.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- One bad thing means the whole person is bad.\n- I can’t remember anything good about them right now.\n- They were perfect, and now I see they’re awful.\n- I need to know whether they’re safe or unsafe.\n- If they disappointed me, the entire relationship was false.\n- There’s no middle ground here.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSudden reversal from admiration to disgust; certainty that one flaw changes everything; difficulty remembering positive qualities during conflict; urgency to choose a total verdict.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRapid idealization and rejection; rewriting the whole relationship after one injury; treating disagreement as proof of bad character; alternating praise and condemnation.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Safety; Belonging; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDisappointment; betrayal; ambiguity; mixed signals; boundary-setting; flaws in admired people or institutions.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMixed signals are unsafe; if good and bad coexist, I cannot know whom to trust; ambivalence means danger.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nUncertainty; grief; dependency; complexity; moral ambiguity; disappointment.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent — preserving purity by expelling contradiction. Lover — idealizing union then devaluing disappointment. Rebel — dividing oppressors from the pure. Ruler — classifying loyal versus disloyal. Sage — reducing nuance to total judgment.\n## Pattern Flow\nContradiction appears → trust destabilizes → the whole is sorted into good or bad → certainty returns → relationship reality becomes distorted → instability increases.\n## Often Appears With\nIdealization; Devaluation; Projection; All-or-Nothing Thinking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nMoral clarity; decisiveness; sensitivity to inconsistency.\n## Current Cost\nUnstable attachment; distorted judgment; abrupt ruptures; inability to integrate mixed truths.\n## Freer Expression\nComplexity without collapse.\n## One Act of Volition\nName three true things that do not fit the same verdict.\n## Mira Language\n“It sounds as though one painful truth has become the whole truth. What remains true that does not fit the current verdict?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat contradiction feels unsafe? What positive truth remains? What harmful truth can be held without erasing the whole person?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDecisive moral judgment, recognizing abuse, or ending an unsafe relationship is not splitting.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated total reversals or global judgments when mixed evidence is available.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSlow categorical conclusions; preserve memory across emotional states; separate behavior, pattern, and whole-person judgment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not argue for total goodness; acknowledge the real injury while reintroducing complexity and boundaries.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nName where a total verdict erased the other person’s reality or humanity. Repair requires specific accountability, restored nuance, and protection against repeating harmful behavior.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Withdrawal, Counter-Devaluation, or Self-Erasure. Often triggered by disappointment, inconsistency, criticism, or idealization. The loop becomes “You are entirely unsafe” versus “I must prove I am entirely good.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat contradiction am I trying to resolve by making someone entirely good or bad?"},
  "PP-STATUS-GUARDING": {"name":"Status Guarding","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Dominance; Gatekeeping; Defensive Expertise; Image Management; One-Upmanship.","Archetypal Role":"Ruler clings to authority; Sage protects expert status; Creator resists successors; Caregiver makes indispensability a position.","Migration Notes":"Batch 11 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"11","One Act of Volition":"Share one piece of access, credit, or authority that does not need to remain exclusively yours.","Core Logic":"I am protecting my place as though another person’s rise could erase me.","Primary Domain":"Identity","Long-Term Cost":"Stagnation; resentment; blocked succession; brittle authority.","Core Fear":"Worth depends on rank; replaceability equals abandonment; recognition is scarce.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Their rise could make me replaceable.; I need to remain the person everyone consults.; Sharing authority may reduce my value.; They have not earned the recognition I had to fight for.; I should keep access limited so my position stays secure.; If the role is no longer exclusive, who am I?","Protective Move":"Status Guarding is the protective preservation of rank, authority, expertise, belonging, or prestige when change or another person’s growth feels like a threat to one’s place.","Pattern ID":"PP-STATUS-GUARDING","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary security returns when access or recognition is controlled.","Freer Expression":"Stewardship without possession.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Stewardship; continuity; earned expertise; protection of standards.","Observable Cues":"Withholding access; emphasizing hierarchy; minimizing emerging talent; insisting on deference; resisting succession.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Recognize real expertise while maintaining fair access and boundaries against domination. May trigger Contrarianism, Underfunctioning, Resentment, or One-Upmanship.","Emotional Function":"Protects Significance, Competence, Belonging, and Security; avoids aging, limitation, dependence, grief, and changing identity.","Canonical Name":"Status Guarding"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nStatus Guarding is the protective preservation of rank, authority, expertise, belonging, or prestige when change or another person’s growth feels like a threat to one’s place.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Power, and Significance\n## Related Patterns\nDominance; Gatekeeping; Defensive Expertise; Image Management; One-Upmanship\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am protecting my place as though another person’s rise could erase me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Their rise could make me replaceable.\n- I need to remain the person everyone consults.\n- Sharing authority may reduce my value.\n- They have not earned the recognition I had to fight for.\n- I should keep access limited so my position stays secure.\n- If the role is no longer exclusive, who am I?\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nIrritation when others gain access; need to be consulted; fear of becoming replaceable; sensitivity to title or recognition.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nWithholding access; emphasizing hierarchy; minimizing emerging talent; insisting on deference; resisting succession.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSignificance; Competence; Belonging; Security.\n## Usually Triggered By\nSuccession; new talent; changing roles; shared authority; loss of exclusivity.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nWorth depends on rank; replaceability equals abandonment; recognition is scarce.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nAging; limitation; dependence; grief; changing identity.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nRuler clings to authority; Sage protects expert status; Creator resists successors; Caregiver makes indispensability a position.\n## Pattern Flow\nStatus shift appears → significance feels threatened → access or recognition is controlled → temporary security returns → adaptation and trust decline.\n## Often Appears With\nGatekeeping; Dominance; Image Management; Defensive Expertise.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nStewardship; continuity; earned expertise; protection of standards.\n## Current Cost\nStagnation; resentment; blocked succession; brittle authority.\n## Freer Expression\nStewardship without possession.\n## One Act of Volition\nShare one piece of access, credit, or authority that does not need to remain exclusively yours.\n## Mira Language\n“What part of your contribution remains valuable even when your position is no longer exclusive?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat place are you afraid of losing? What could mentorship preserve that control cannot? What belongs to the role rather than the self?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLegitimate authority, confidentiality, and quality standards are not automatically status guarding.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated efforts to restrict others specifically when rank, access, or replaceability feels threatened.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nGrieve role change; distinguish stewardship from ownership; invest in legacy rather than exclusivity.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRecognize real expertise while maintaining fair access and boundaries against domination.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge blocked opportunity or withheld credit, restore access where appropriate, and establish transparent criteria.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Contrarianism, Underfunctioning, Resentment, or One-Upmanship; often triggered by Comparison and Image Management.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I confusing my contribution with permanent ownership of the place I hold?"},
  "PP-STRATEGIC-AMBIGUITY": {"name":"Strategic Ambiguity","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Decision Delegation; Emotional Withholding; Image Management; Conflict Avoidance; Secret-Keeping; Rationalization.","Archetypal Role":"Trickster preserves multiple readings; Lover avoids defining the bond; Ruler delays accountability; Rebel refuses explicit agreements.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"State what is true now, what remains undecided, and by when a decision will be made.","Core Logic":"I am keeping my position unclear so no outcome can fully bind or expose me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Confusion; impaired consent; missed deadlines; unequal risk; loss of trust.","Core Fear":"Clear choices make me trapped or blameworthy; honesty costs belonging; ambiguity preserves freedom.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Maybe is safer than a clear answer.; I need to keep my options open.; A direct position would make me too accountable.; I should stay vague so no one can pin me down.; Clarity might disappoint someone or trap me.; I can imply enough without fully committing.","Protective Move":"Strategic Ambiguity is the protective use of vagueness, partial commitment, or unclear positioning to preserve options, avoid accountability, and reduce exposure to rejection or conflict.","Pattern ID":"PP-STRATEGIC-AMBIGUITY","Short-Term Payoff":"Options and approval are temporarily preserved when language remains vague.","Freer Expression":"Complexity with a clear present position.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Flexibility; diplomacy; tolerance for complexity; resistance to false binaries.","Observable Cues":"Noncommittal answers; shifting definitions; avoiding timelines; implying different things to different people; preserving plausible deniability.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Ask for the minimum clarity required for consent or planning; decline indefinite ambiguity when it creates unequal risk. May trigger Reassurance Seeking, Suspicion, Micromanaging, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Autonomy, Belonging, Safety, and Self-Esteem; avoids loss, responsibility, disappointment, finality, and transparent desire.","Canonical Name":"Strategic Ambiguity"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nStrategic Ambiguity is the protective use of vagueness, partial commitment, or unclear positioning to preserve options, avoid accountability, and reduce exposure to rejection or conflict.\n## Domain\nCommitment, Accountability, and Relational Uncertainty\n## Related Patterns\nDecision Delegation; Emotional Withholding; Image Management; Conflict Avoidance; Secret-Keeping; Rationalization.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am keeping my position unclear so no outcome can fully bind or expose me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Maybe is safer than a clear answer.\n- I need to keep my options open.\n- A direct position would make me too accountable.\n- I should stay vague so no one can pin me down.\n- Clarity might disappoint someone or trap me.\n- I can imply enough without fully committing.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nClarity feels dangerous; relief in “maybe”; fear that a direct answer closes options or disappoints someone.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nNoncommittal answers; shifting definitions; avoiding timelines; implying different things to different people; preserving plausible deniability.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nAutonomy; Belonging; Safety; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nRequests for commitment; conflict; competing loyalties; risk of rejection; accountability; fear of regret.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nClear choices make me trapped or blameworthy; honesty costs belonging; ambiguity preserves freedom.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nLoss; responsibility; disappointment; finality; transparent desire.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nTrickster preserves multiple readings; Lover avoids defining the bond; Ruler delays accountability; Rebel refuses explicit agreements.\n## Pattern Flow\nClear choice is requested → autonomy or belonging feels threatened → language remains vague → options and approval are temporarily preserved → others cannot consent or plan clearly → pressure and mistrust grow.\n## Often Appears With\nConflict Avoidance; Decision Delegation; Emotional Withholding; Image Management; Rationalization.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nFlexibility; diplomacy; tolerance for complexity; resistance to false binaries.\n## Current Cost\nConfusion; impaired consent; missed deadlines; unequal risk; loss of trust.\n## Freer Expression\nComplexity with a clear present position.\n## One Act of Volition\nState what is true now, what remains undecided, and by when a decision will be made.\n## Mira Language\n“There may be real complexity here, but the current ambiguity also protects you from being answerable. What can you state clearly today?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhich option are you preserving? Who bears the cost of not knowing? What deadline would make uncertainty honest rather than indefinite?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nGenuine uncertainty, evolving situations, confidentiality, and careful negotiation are not strategic ambiguity.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated vagueness that preserves unilateral options or avoids accountability while others must act without adequate clarity.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName current truth, uncertainty, constraints, and decision date without manufacturing false certainty.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nAsk for the minimum clarity required for consent or planning; decline indefinite ambiguity when it creates unequal risk.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where vagueness prevented informed choice or transferred risk; provide a clear account, restore options where possible, and establish explicit commitments.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Reassurance Seeking, Suspicion, Micromanaging, or Withdrawal. Those reactions can reinforce “Clarity will trap me” and “I cannot trust what you mean.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere is ambiguity serving complexity, and where is it protecting me from accountability?"},
  "PP-SUFFERING-AS-MEANING": {"name":"Suffering as Meaning","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Martyrdom; Victim Identity Fixation; Meaning Inflation; Grudge Holding; Despair as Certainty; Purity Identity; Spiritual Bypassing.","Archetypal Role":"The Wounded Meaning-Maker; Mystic turns pain into sacred identity; Martyr protects worth through suffering; Witness carries testimony as purpose.","Migration Notes":"Batch 17 anomaly expansion from the experimental 28-field archetypal-development template. Imagery, mantra, progress signal, gift, shadow, and integrated expression were preserved through canonical mapping. Spacing repaired; source trigger phrases retained and supplemented. Clinical Term retained from source. Safety Flags mapped to Medical Differential because the source explicitly requires screening for depression, self-harm, trauma, chronic illness, disability, abuse, medical needs, and material danger; this is not a diagnosis.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"17","One Act of Volition":"Name one truth the pain revealed and one value you can carry without carrying the pain itself.","Core Logic":"If pain is what makes my life meaningful, releasing it may erase my identity, depth, or moral legitimacy.","Safety Flags":["Medical Differential"],"Primary Domain":"Spiritual","Long-Term Cost":"Healing may feel like betrayal; joy, agency, pleasure, and new identity remain underdeveloped; hopelessness and isolation may deepen.","Core Fear":"Emptiness, ordinariness, forgotten suffering, or a life that feels undeservedly uncomplicated if pain no longer defines meaning.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"At least my pain means something.; Without this, who would I be?; Healing would erase what happened.; People who haven’t suffered are shallow.; I don’t know who I am when things are okay.; If the pain leaves, I may lose the meaning it gave me.","Clinical Term":"Identity investment in suffering; trauma-linked meaning construction; depressive or martyring cognition where applicable","Protective Move":"Suffering as Meaning preserves, revisits, or elevates pain as proof of depth, goodness, loyalty, identity, or purpose so helpless suffering becomes coherent and significant.","Pattern ID":"PP-SUFFERING-AS-MEANING","Short-Term Payoff":"Pain feels organized, witnessed, and meaningful rather than random.","Freer Expression":"Meaning carried forward without requiring continued suffering.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Depth; compassion; endurance; testimony; meaning-making; capacity to witness suffering.","Observable Cues":"Returning repeatedly to injury as identity proof; dismissing ease as shallow; resisting relief because it threatens meaning; judging unsuffering people as less deep; organizing relationships around wounds.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Bonds may organize around shared wounds; solutions or recovery can feel invalidating or distancing. May trigger Rescuing, Positivity Enforcement, Emotional Distancing, or Martyrdom.","Emotional Function":"Protects coherence, significance, belonging, identity, and moral legitimacy; avoids randomness, emptiness, joy, ordinary life, grief, and identity beyond the wound.","Canonical Name":"Suffering as Meaning"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSuffering as Meaning is the protective preservation, revisiting, or elevation of pain as proof of depth, goodness, loyalty, identity, or purpose. It converts helpless suffering into coherence, but becomes constraining when healing feels like erasure or betrayal.\n## Domain\nSuffering, Identity, and Existential Meaning\n## Related Patterns\nMartyrdom; Victim Identity Fixation; Meaning Inflation; Grudge Holding; Despair as Certainty; Purity Identity\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf pain is what makes my life meaningful, releasing it may erase my identity, depth, or moral legitimacy.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- At least my pain means something.\n- Without this, who would I be?\n- Healing would erase what happened.\n- People who haven’t suffered are shallow.\n- I don’t know who I am when things are okay.\n- If the pain leaves, I may lose the meaning it gave me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when pain confirms identity; unease with pleasure or ease; fear that recovery invalidates the past; loyalty to the wound; emptiness when life becomes quieter.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReturning repeatedly to injury as identity proof; dismissing ease as shallow; resisting relief because it threatens meaning; judging unsuffering people as less deep; organizing relationships around wounds.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nMeaning; coherence; identity; belonging; dignity; testimony.\n## Usually Triggered By\nHealing; reduced crisis; others’ recovery; joy; identity transition; being asked to move forward; fear that suffering will be forgotten.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nPain is the truest part of me; ease makes me morally shallow; healing betrays the injured self; suffering is what grants depth or legitimacy.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nRandomness; emptiness; joy; ordinary life; grief; survivor guilt; uncertainty about identity beyond the wound.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nThe Wounded Meaning-Maker carries a lantern lit from ashes; Mystic turns pain into sacred identity; Martyr protects worth through suffering; Witness carries testimony as purpose.\n## Pattern Flow\nPain or remembered injury becomes salient → identity and meaning feel threatened by its possible release → suffering is revisited or elevated → coherence and legitimacy return → relief feels dangerous → isolation and hopelessness deepen.\n## Often Appears With\nMartyrdom; Victim Identity Fixation; Grudge Holding; Despair as Certainty; Meaning Inflation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDepth; compassion; endurance; testimony; meaning-making; capacity to witness suffering.\n## Current Cost\nHealing feels like betrayal; joy, agency, pleasure, and new identity remain underdeveloped; isolation and hopelessness may deepen.\n## Freer Expression\nMeaning carried forward without requiring continued suffering.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one truth the pain revealed and one value you can carry without carrying the pain itself.\n## Mira Language\n“Your suffering may hold real meaning and testimony. Does preserving the pain now feel necessary to preserve what it taught or proved?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would healing seem to erase? Which value can survive beyond the wound? Can the suffering matter without remaining your home?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nNever frame real suffering as chosen, exaggerated, or merely psychological. Trauma, grief, chronic illness, disability, oppression, caregiving burden, depression, self-harm risk, abuse, spiritual injury, and material danger require careful contextualization.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern in which relief, pleasure, growth, or identity expansion feels like betrayal, erasure, or loss of moral legitimacy—not simply ongoing pain or grief.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nHonor what the suffering taught, preserve testimony and values, and build identity through relationship, creation, pleasure, agency, and contribution beyond the wound.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nWitness the suffering without forcing optimism or making pain the only available bond. Support safety, treatment, material change, and identity expansion where appropriate.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where pain became authority, moral currency, or a demand that others remain inside the wound. Preserve the truth of harm while allowing different recovery paths.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Rescuing, Positivity Enforcement, Emotional Distancing, or Martyrdom. The loop becomes “You must honor my pain by staying with it” versus “I must fix, flee, or deny what cannot be quickly relieved.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat meaning can leave the burned house with me, even if I no longer live inside it?"},
  "PP-SUSPICION": {"name":"Suspicion","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Hypervigilance; Mind Reading; Cynicism; Projection; Adversarial Framing; Certainty Seeking; Loyalty Testing; Emotional Withholding.","Archetypal Role":"Sage investigates endlessly; Warrior stays battle-ready; Ruler monitors loyalty; Trickster assumes every surface hides a game.","Migration Notes":"Batch 10 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"S","Source Batch":"10","One Act of Volition":"Identify what evidence would confirm, weaken, or falsify the suspicion.","Core Logic":"I am assuming there may be a concealed threat behind what is visible.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Erosion of trust; invasive behavior; confirmation bias; relational distance.","Core Fear":"People conceal what matters; trust makes me vulnerable; I must discover the truth alone.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"Something about this story does not add up.; There may be a hidden motive behind what they are saying.; I need to investigate before I trust anything.; A benign explanation feels too easy.; If I lower my guard, I may miss the betrayal.; I need proof because words alone are not safe.","Protective Move":"Suspicion is the protective presumption that hidden motives, deception, or betrayal may be present, allowing the person to remain guarded until safety feels proven.","Pattern ID":"PP-SUSPICION","Short-Term Payoff":"Investigation or guardedness brings temporary control.","Freer Expression":"Discernment without presumption.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; pattern recognition; refusal to ignore contradictions.","Observable Cues":"Rechecking stories; searching devices or records; indirect questioning; testing consistency; withholding trust despite limited evidence.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respond with verifiable clarity where safe; do not submit to invasive demands or endless proof requirements. May trigger Image Management, Secret-Keeping, Defensiveness, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Safety, Autonomy, and Self-Esteem; avoids dependence, uncertainty, grief, and the risk of trusting and being wrong.","Canonical Name":"Suspicion"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nSuspicion is the protective presumption that hidden motives, deception, or betrayal may be present, allowing the person to remain guarded until safety feels proven.\n## Domain\nTrust, Threat, and Interpretation\n## Related Patterns\nHypervigilance; Mind Reading; Cynicism; Projection; Adversarial Framing; Certainty Seeking.\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am assuming there may be a concealed threat behind what is visible.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- Something about this story does not add up.\n- There may be a hidden motive behind what they are saying.\n- I need to investigate before I trust anything.\n- A benign explanation feels too easy.\n- If I lower my guard, I may miss the betrayal.\n- I need proof because words alone are not safe.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDifficulty accepting benign explanations; bodily tension around uncertainty; urge to investigate; relief when a negative theory appears to explain everything.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nRechecking stories; searching devices or records; indirect questioning; testing consistency; withholding trust despite limited evidence.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Safety; Autonomy; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nInconsistency; secrecy; prior betrayal; incomplete information; power imbalance; unexplained changes.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nPeople conceal what matters; trust makes me vulnerable; I must discover the truth alone.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nDependence; uncertainty; grief; the risk of trusting and being wrong.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nSage investigates endlessly; Warrior stays battle-ready; Ruler monitors loyalty; Trickster assumes every surface hides a game.\n## Pattern Flow\nAmbiguity appears → trust feels threatened → hidden-motive theory forms → investigation or guardedness brings temporary control → openness decreases and ambiguity grows.\n## Often Appears With\nHypervigilance; Cynicism; Mind Reading; Loyalty Testing; Emotional Withholding.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; pattern recognition; refusal to ignore contradictions.\n## Current Cost\nErosion of trust; invasive behavior; confirmation bias; relational distance.\n## Freer Expression\nDiscernment without presumption.\n## One Act of Volition\nIdentify what evidence would confirm, weaken, or falsify the suspicion.\n## Mira Language\n“Your concern may deserve attention. What is the strongest observable evidence, and what remains inference?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat contradiction are you responding to? What evidence would change your mind? Is direct inquiry safe and appropriate?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSuspicion may be accurate. Mira must not pressure trust where deception, coercion, or danger is plausible.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated hidden-motive assumptions that persist beyond available evidence and organize behavior across situations.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSlow investigation, distinguish evidence from theory, and protect boundaries without declaring guilt prematurely.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespond with verifiable clarity where safe; do not submit to invasive demands or endless proof requirements.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge any accusation, surveillance, or mistrust imposed without sufficient evidence; restore privacy or autonomy and agree on transparent but bounded ways to address legitimate concerns.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Image Management, Secret-Keeping, Defensiveness, or Emotional Distancing, which then appear to confirm suspicion. The reciprocal story becomes “You are hiding something” and “I cannot be open without being interrogated.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat do I know, what do I suspect, and what would honestly distinguish the two?"},
  "PP-TESTING-THE-BOND": {"name":"Testing the Bond","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Clinging; Punitive Silence; Jealousy; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Confirmation Seeking; Mind Reading.","Archetypal Role":"Lover — tests devotion; Rebel — creates rupture to expose loyalty; Trickster — hides need inside provocation; Innocent — seeks certainty through proof.","Migration Notes":"Batch 1 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"T","Source Batch":"1","One Act of Volition":"Replace one hidden test with a direct statement of fear and a concrete request.","Core Logic":"I need proof you will choose me, so I create a test you do not know you are taking.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Manipulation; confusion; repeated rupture; false evidence.","Core Fear":"Words cannot be trusted; love must be proven under pressure; direct need will be rejected.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"If you really cared, you would know what to do.; I’ll pull away and see whether you come after me.; I need proof that you’ll choose me.; I shouldn’t have to ask directly.; Let’s see whether you notice something is wrong.; Words aren’t enough; I need to test you.","Protective Move":"Testing the Bond is the protective creation of uncertainty, provocation, or withdrawal in order to obtain proof that another person will stay, pursue, choose, or reassure.","Pattern ID":"PP-TESTING-THE-BOND","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary evidence is gathered.","Freer Expression":"Direct requests for reassurance and reliability.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Desire for loyalty; discernment about reliability.","Observable Cues":"Threatening departure; withholding warmth; provoking jealousy; creating impossible loyalty tests; saying “nothing” while expecting pursuit.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Respond to the underlying need when safe, but do not reward manipulation; invite direct communication and maintain limits. May trigger Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, Counter-Testing, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Belonging, and Self-Esteem; avoids vulnerability, asking, uncertainty, and receiving an imperfect answer.","Canonical Name":"Testing the Bond"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nTesting the Bond is the protective creation of uncertainty, provocation, or withdrawal in order to obtain proof that another person will stay, pursue, choose, or reassure.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nClinging; Punitive Silence; Jealousy; Withdrawing Before Being Left; Confirmation Seeking\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need proof you will choose me, so I create a test you do not know you are taking.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- If you really cared, you would know what to do.\n- I’ll pull away and see whether you come after me.\n- I need proof that you’ll choose me.\n- I shouldn’t have to ask directly.\n- Let’s see whether you notice something is wrong.\n- Words aren’t enough; I need to test you.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nSuspicion of reassurance; urge to provoke proof; difficulty asking directly; temporary relief when pursued.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nThreatening departure; withholding warmth; provoking jealousy; creating impossible loyalty tests; saying “nothing” while expecting pursuit.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Belonging; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAmbiguity; perceived neglect; comparison; past betrayal; insecure reassurance.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nWords cannot be trusted; love must be proven under pressure; direct need will be rejected.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; asking; uncertainty; receiving an imperfect answer.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nLover — tests devotion; Rebel — creates rupture to expose loyalty; Trickster — hides need inside provocation; Innocent — seeks certainty through proof.\n## Pattern Flow\nTrust feels uncertain → an indirect test is created → the other reacts → temporary evidence is gathered → trust erodes because the test itself damages safety.\n## Often Appears With\nClinging; Jealousy; Punitive Silence; Mind Reading.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDesire for loyalty; discernment about reliability.\n## Current Cost\nManipulation; confusion; repeated rupture; false evidence.\n## Freer Expression\nDirect requests for reassurance and reliability.\n## One Act of Volition\nReplace one hidden test with a direct statement of fear and a concrete request.\n## Mira Language\n“It sounds as though you needed evidence of the bond, but the evidence was sought through a test rather than a request.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat proof were you seeking? Could the need be asked directly? What would reliable reassurance look like?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nVerifying trust after betrayal is not automatically testing the bond.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated indirect tests, provocations, or withdrawals designed to elicit proof.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName the fear and request observable reassurance without manufacturing a crisis.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nRespond to the underlying need when safe, but do not reward manipulation; invite direct communication and maintain limits.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAdmit the test, name its impact, clarify the real need, and agree on direct signals for reassurance and re-engagement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, Counter-Testing, or Contempt. Often triggered by inconsistency, secrecy, or invalidation. The loop becomes: “I must test you because words are unsafe” and “I must protect myself because nothing I do is trusted.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I testing that I could ask for directly?"},
  "PP-TRIANGULATION": {"name":"Triangulation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Passive Aggression; Adversarial Framing; Gossip; Testing the Bond; Image Management; Blame Shifting; Retaliation.","Archetypal Role":"Diplomat — mediation becomes covert alliance-building. Ruler — influence becomes faction management. Lover — intimacy becomes loyalty testing through third parties. Caregiver — protection becomes speaking for others. Trickster — indirectness becomes strategic destabilization.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source distinguishes unsafe contexts and transparent advocacy from covert triangulation but does not assign a single explicit controlled safety flag.","First Letter":"T","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Speak to the person involved—or, when direct contact is unsafe, explicitly name the need for a neutral advocate rather than recruiting a covert ally.","Core Logic":"I am bringing in a third point because direct contact feels too risky.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Distorted communication; fractured trust; factionalism; burdening bystanders; escalating conflict; reduced accountability.","Core Fear":"Direct communication is dangerous; I will not be believed unless others back me; conflict is won through alliances; I cannot hold my ground alone.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need someone else on my side before I speak to them.; Maybe a third person can deliver the message for me.; I can’t hold my ground alone.; If others agree with me, I’ll know my version is real.; Direct contact feels too risky.; I need an ally before this conversation happens.","Protective Move":"Triangulation is the protective use of a third person, audience, alliance, or absent party to regulate tension that would otherwise need to be addressed directly between the people involved.","Pattern ID":"PP-TRIANGULATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary validation or leverage appears when a third point is recruited.","Freer Expression":"Supported directness.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Social awareness; coalition-building; mediation instinct; sensitivity to power and context.","Observable Cues":"Asking a third person to deliver a message; recruiting allies before conflict; comparing what one person supposedly said about another; using children, colleagues, friends, or family as intermediaries; creating competing versions for different audiences.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Decline the role of covert intermediary. Encourage direct communication when safe, clarify what may be shared, and use formal neutral support when power or safety requires it. May trigger Defensiveness, Adversarial Framing, Retaliation, Gossip, or Emotional Distancing.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Belonging, Influence, Validation, and Trust; avoids vulnerability, direct accountability, uncertainty, mutual influence, and the possibility of hearing a different perspective.","Canonical Name":"Triangulation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nTriangulation is the protective use of a third person, audience, alliance, or absent party to regulate tension that would otherwise need to be addressed directly between the people involved.\n## Domain\nConflict, Alliance, and Indirect Communication\n## Related Patterns\nPassive Aggression; Adversarial Framing; Gossip; Testing the Bond; Image Management; Blame Shifting; Retaliation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am bringing in a third point because direct contact feels too risky.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need someone else on my side before I speak to them.\n- Maybe a third person can deliver the message for me.\n- I can’t hold my ground alone.\n- If others agree with me, I’ll know my version is real.\n- Direct contact feels too risky.\n- I need an ally before this conversation happens.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRelief when someone else confirms your interpretation. A wish to recruit support before speaking directly. Fear that a one-to-one conversation will leave you powerless. Pressure to establish who is on whose side. A tendency to communicate through another person.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nAsking a third person to deliver a message that could safely be delivered directly. Recruiting allies before or during conflict. Comparing what one person supposedly said about another. Using children, colleagues, friends, or family members as intermediaries. Creating competing versions of events for different audiences. Seeking validation in ways that harden factions rather than clarify reality.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Belonging; Influence; Validation; Trust.\n## Usually Triggered By\nFear of confrontation; power imbalance; anticipated rejection; shame; unresolved conflict; uncertainty about one’s perception; desire for leverage.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nDirect communication is dangerous. I will not be believed unless others back me. Conflict is won through alliances. I cannot hold my ground alone.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; direct accountability; uncertainty; mutual influence; the possibility of hearing a different perspective.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nDiplomat — mediation becomes covert alliance-building. Ruler — influence becomes faction management. Lover — intimacy becomes loyalty testing through third parties. Caregiver — protection becomes speaking for others. Trickster — indirectness becomes strategic destabilization.\n## Pattern Flow\nDirect tension rises → safety or influence feels threatened → a third point is recruited → temporary validation or leverage appears → direct trust weakens and factions form → more intermediaries are needed.\n## Often Appears With\nPassive Aggression; Gossip; Image Management; Blame Shifting; Retaliation; Adversarial Framing.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSocial awareness; coalition-building; mediation instinct; sensitivity to power and context.\n## Current Cost\nDistorted communication; fractured trust; factionalism; burdening bystanders; escalating conflict; reduced accountability.\n## Freer Expression\nSupported directness.\n## One Act of Volition\nSpeak to the person involved—or, when direct contact is unsafe, explicitly name the need for a neutral advocate rather than recruiting a covert ally.\n## Mira Language\n“A third person seems to be carrying tension that belongs in this relationship. Is that support necessary for safety, or is the triangle replacing a direct conversation?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feels too risky to say directly? Is the third person serving safety and clarity, or leverage and validation? What would transparent mediation look like instead?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nSeeking counsel, therapy, supervision, legal advocacy, safeguarding support, or formal mediation is not automatically triangulation. Direct contact may be inappropriate in abusive, coercive, or unsafe situations.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated pattern of routing conflict, loyalty, or meaning through third parties in ways that obscure accountability or intensify alliances—not one request for advice.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIdentify what direct contact threatens, choose either direct communication or transparent mediation, and stop using another person as an undeclared messenger, witness, or weapon.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDecline the role of covert intermediary. Encourage direct communication when safe, clarify what may be shared, and use formal neutral support when power or safety requires it.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge who was recruited, misrepresented, burdened, or placed between parties. Correct distorted messages directly, release third parties from the conflict, and establish a transparent channel for future communication.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Adversarial Framing, Retaliation, Gossip, or Emotional Distancing. Often triggered by Dominance, Hostility Toward Criticism, Punitive Silence, or real power imbalance. The reinforcing story may become: “I need allies to be safe” on one side and “Everyone is conspiring against me” on the other.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhere am I using a third person to avoid a direct or transparent conversation?"},
  "PP-TRUTH-TELLING-AS-DOMINATION": {"name":"Truth Telling as Domination","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Dominance; Criticism; Cross-Examination; Moral Superiority; Semantic Control; Adversarial Framing; Exposure of Others Without Self-Exposure; Gaslighting.","Archetypal Role":"The Weaponized Truth-Teller; Judge uses accuracy as sentence; Warrior turns candor into force; Sage uses certainty as hierarchy.","Migration Notes":"Batch 17 anomaly expansion from the experimental 28-field archetypal-development template. Useful source elements including escalation and dissolution pathways, imagery, mantra, progress signal, shadow expression, gift, and naming palette were preserved through canonical mapping. Spacing repaired; all six source trigger phrases retained. Clinical Term retained from source. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because forced disclosure, public humiliation, compelled confession, and weaponized truth may occur in coercive or abusive dynamics. The body explicitly protects whistleblowing, abuse disclosure, mandated reporting, boundary setting, and safety-critical directness.","First Letter":"T","Source Batch":"17","One Act of Volition":"Ask, “Am I trying to clarify, protect, repair—or win?” before speaking.","Core Logic":"If I possess the truth, I am entitled to control the encounter and the other person’s response.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Damaged trust; collapsed nuance; defensiveness; humiliation; confusion of accuracy with relational integrity.","Core Fear":"Being ignored, deceived, powerless, morally compromised, or exposed as uncertain.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I’m just telling the truth.; Someone had to say it.; If the truth hurts, that’s their problem.; I destroyed their argument.; They need to be exposed.; Honesty matters more than feelings.","Clinical Term":"Aggressive confrontation; hostile candor; coercive or shaming communication","Protective Move":"Truth Telling as Domination delivers facts, interpretations, or disclosures with force, timing, or intensity designed to overpower, humiliate, compel, or control rather than illuminate.","Pattern ID":"PP-TRUTH-TELLING-AS-DOMINATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Strength, clarity, righteousness, and immunity from challenge.","Freer Expression":"Courageous, proportionate, consent-aware truth-telling that serves clarity, safety, and repair.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Discernment; moral courage; directness; pattern recognition; willingness to name what others avoid.","Observable Cues":"Public correction; escalating intensity; disclosure without consent; treating distress as proof; compelled admissions; using accurate details to shame or establish rank.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Appears as brutal honesty, public correction, compelled confession, exposure, or humiliation framed as accountability. May trigger Appeasement, Retaliation, Emotional Distancing, or Counterattack.","Emotional Function":"Protects certainty, power, moral identity, competence, and safety; avoids vulnerability, uncertainty, shame, consent, timing, and the limits of controlling reception.","Canonical Name":"Truth Telling as Domination"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nTruth Telling as Domination is the protective delivery of facts, interpretations, or disclosures with force, timing, or intensity designed to overpower, humiliate, compel, or control rather than illuminate. It differs from courageous candor because truth becomes entitlement to dominate the encounter.\n## Domain\nTruth, Power, and Relational Accountability\n## Related Patterns\nDominance; Criticism; Cross-Examination; Moral Superiority; Semantic Control; Adversarial Framing\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I possess the truth, I am entitled to control the encounter and the other person’s response.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I’m just telling the truth.\n- Someone had to say it.\n- If the truth hurts, that’s their problem.\n- I destroyed their argument.\n- They need to be exposed.\n- Honesty matters more than feelings.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRush of certainty; contempt for pacing or consent; relief through confrontation; belief that accuracy makes delivery irrelevant; anger when the listener does not submit.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nPublic correction; escalating intensity; disclosure without consent; treating distress as proof; compelled admissions; using accurate details to shame or establish rank.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTruth; power; moral identity; competence; safety; recognition.\n## Usually Triggered By\nPerceived deception; being ignored; moral conflict; accumulated resentment; public disagreement; fear of complicity or powerlessness.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nOnly force makes truth matter; gentleness means weakness; uncertainty invites domination by others; being right grants safety and authority.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nVulnerability; doubt; grief; relational responsibility; consent; timing; the inability to control another person’s response.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nThe Weaponized Truth-Teller wields a blade of certainty; Judge uses accuracy as sentence; Warrior turns candor into force; Sage uses truth as hierarchy.\n## Pattern Flow\nThreat, deception, or uncertainty appears → power and moral identity feel threatened → certainty is claimed and truth is delivered forcefully → strength and righteousness rise → resistance appears → shaming, exposure, or pressure intensifies.\n## Often Appears With\nDominance; Moral Superiority; Adversarial Framing; Semantic Control; Retaliation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDiscernment; moral courage; directness; pattern recognition; willingness to name what others avoid.\n## Current Cost\nDamaged trust; collapsed nuance; defensiveness; humiliation; confusion of accuracy with relational integrity.\n## Freer Expression\nCourageous, proportionate, consent-aware truth-telling that serves clarity, safety, and repair.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk, “Am I trying to clarify, protect, repair—or win?” before speaking.\n## Mira Language\n“The truth may matter deeply. What purpose, timing, and delivery would let it serve clarity or safety rather than domination?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat is fact and what is interpretation? Is public disclosure necessary? What response are you trying to force? Can you remain accurate without controlling reception?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDo not use this pattern to silence whistleblowing, abuse disclosure, boundary setting, mandated reporting, protest, or safety-critical directness. Power and safety context are primary.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated use of truth, disclosure, or correction to compel, shame, humiliate, establish hierarchy, or control another person’s response beyond what safety and accountability require.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nSeparate truth, interpretation, timing, consent, audience, and purpose. Pair candor with humility, specificity, and openness to correction.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nProtect the right to name harm while setting boundaries against humiliation, compelled confession, spectacle, or coercive delivery.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where truth was used as a weapon or spectacle, repair unnecessary exposure or humiliation, and restate the relevant truth in proportionate, specific, consent-aware form where possible.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Appeasement, Retaliation, Emotional Distancing, or Counterattack. The loop becomes “I must overpower you so truth wins” versus “I must submit, flee, or attack to survive your truth.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nCan this truth remain true without becoming a weapon, hierarchy, or forced submission?"},
  "PP-UNDERFUNCTIONING": {"name":"Underfunctioning","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Procrastination; Failure to Launch; Self-Deprecation; Reassurance Seeking; Emotional Numbing; Learned Helplessness.","Archetypal Role":"Innocent seeks rescue; Lover waits for relational guidance; Everyperson hides competence to remain accepted; Rebel resists through nonperformance; Creator avoids committing; Caregiver becomes the one needing care.","Migration Notes":"Batch 3 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Medical Differential because the source explicitly requires differentiation from disability, illness, executive dysfunction, depression, coercive control, unequal knowledge, and genuine lack of resources.","First Letter":"U","Source Batch":"3","One Act of Volition":"Complete one clearly owned task without seeking permission, rescue, or correction unless a real obstacle appears.","Core Logic":"If I do less or wait long enough, someone safer or more capable may take over.","Safety Flags":["Medical Differential"],"Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Dependency; lost competence; resentment; unequal labor; reduced trust; constrained autonomy.","Core Fear":"My efforts will be corrected anyway; mistakes are dangerous; competence brings more demands; someone else knows better.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I don’t know what to do unless someone tells me.; You’re better at this than I am.; I’ll wait until someone else decides.; If I try, I’ll probably get it wrong.; There’s no point acting if it will be corrected anyway.; I need someone to take over before I can move.","Protective Move":"Underfunctioning is the protective reduction of initiative, responsibility, or visible competence so that the person can avoid failure, conflict, overwhelm, accountability, or the risk of acting without support.","Pattern ID":"PP-UNDERFUNCTIONING","Short-Term Payoff":"Relief or rescue arrives as initiative contracts.","Freer Expression":"Supported agency.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Receptivity; caution; willingness to seek help; awareness of limits.","Observable Cues":"Waiting for reminders; incomplete follow-through; asking others to decide routine matters; becoming less capable in the presence of a strong overfunctioner; avoiding ownership while criticizing control.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not shame, rescue automatically, or micromanage. Clarify ownership, offer bounded support, and allow proportionate consequences while considering genuine capacity barriers. May trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Criticism, Resentment, or Contempt.","Emotional Function":"Protects Safety, Competence, Belonging, Autonomy, and Self-Esteem; avoids responsibility, possible failure, adult agency, conflict, uncertainty, and the effort of learning.","Canonical Name":"Underfunctioning"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nUnderfunctioning is the protective reduction of initiative, responsibility, or visible competence so that the person can avoid failure, conflict, overwhelm, accountability, or the risk of acting without support.\n## Domain\nResponsibility, Control, and Care\n## Related Patterns\nProcrastination; Failure to Launch; Self-Deprecation; Reassurance Seeking; Emotional Numbing\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I do less or wait long enough, someone safer or more capable may take over.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I don’t know what to do unless someone tells me.\n- You’re better at this than I am.\n- I’ll wait until someone else decides.\n- If I try, I’ll probably get it wrong.\n- There’s no point acting if it will be corrected anyway.\n- I need someone to take over before I can move.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nHelplessness before attempting; relief when another person assumes responsibility; fear of making the wrong choice; resentment at being directed alongside reluctance to initiate.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nWaiting for reminders; incomplete follow-through; asking others to decide routine matters; becoming less capable in the presence of a strong overfunctioner; avoiding ownership while criticizing control.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSafety; Competence; Belonging; Autonomy; Self-Esteem.\n## Usually Triggered By\nEvaluation; complex tasks; controlling partners or leaders; previous failure; fatigue; shame; unclear roles.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy efforts will be corrected anyway; mistakes are dangerous; competence brings more demands; someone else knows better.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nResponsibility; possible failure; adult agency; conflict; uncertainty; the effort of learning.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nInnocent seeks rescue; Lover waits for relational guidance; Everyperson hides competence to remain accepted; Rebel resists through nonperformance; Creator avoids committing; Caregiver becomes the one needing care.\n## Pattern Flow\nResponsibility appears → competence, autonomy, or worth feels threatened → initiative contracts → relief or rescue arrives → skill and trust erode → greater dependence confirms helplessness.\n## Often Appears With\nProcrastination; Failure to Launch; Reassurance Seeking; Self-Deprecation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nReceptivity; caution; willingness to seek help; awareness of limits.\n## Current Cost\nDependency; lost competence; resentment; unequal labor; reduced trust; constrained autonomy.\n## Freer Expression\nSupported agency.\n## One Act of Volition\nComplete one clearly owned task without seeking permission, rescue, or correction unless a real obstacle appears.\n## Mira Language\n“I hear that you feel unable to act, and I also notice that responsibility repeatedly moves to someone else. What support would help you retain ownership rather than surrender it?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat is the smallest decision that is genuinely yours? What do you fear will happen if you act imperfectly? Has another person made independent action difficult?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nDisability, illness, executive dysfunction, depression, coercive control, unequal knowledge, or genuine lack of resources must not be mislabeled as underfunctioning.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated avoidable transfer of responsibility despite adequate capacity and support—not one period of reduced functioning.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nName actual limits accurately, request specific support, retain decision ownership, and build competence through small completed actions.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not shame, rescue automatically, or micromanage. Clarify ownership, offer bounded support, and allow proportionate consequences while considering genuine capacity barriers.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where nonparticipation shifted labor or emotional burden onto others. Make a concrete ownership plan and rebuild trust through consistent follow-through rather than promises of future capability.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Overfunctioning, Micromanaging, Criticism, Resentment, or Contempt. Often triggered by control, correction, Perfectionism, or learned helplessness. The loop becomes: “You will not act unless I force or rescue you” and “There is no point acting because you will take over or criticize me.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat support do I need in order to remain the owner of my next action?"},
  "PP-UNDOING": {"name":"Undoing","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Compulsive Apologizing; Reassurance Seeking; Magical Thinking; Overfunctioning; Guilt Management.","Archetypal Role":"Caregiver — overgives after resentment. Lover — floods the bond with reassurance after rupture. Innocent — performs purity to cancel guilt. Ruler — imposes corrective order. Mystic — uses ritual to reverse feared consequences.","Migration Notes":"Batch 5 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"U","Source Batch":"5","One Act of Volition":"Ask what actual repair is needed, do that once, and allow the event to remain part of reality.","Core Logic":"If I do enough now, perhaps I can make the feared harm no longer count.","Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Compulsive guilt management; unequal relationships; avoidance of direct repair; exhaustion.","Core Fear":"Bad thoughts make me bad; one mistake can destroy the bond; I must erase harm rather than tolerate responsibility.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I need to do something extra so this no longer counts.; If I apologize again, maybe the guilt will finally stop.; I have to make up for this immediately.; One good act can cancel the bad one.; I need reassurance that I’m still a good person.; I can’t let the mistake remain part of reality.","Protective Move":"Undoing is the attempt to neutralize guilt, fear, or imagined harm through symbolic acts, excessive compensation, or repeated reassurance rather than directly addressing the underlying action or feeling.","Pattern ID":"PP-UNDOING","Short-Term Payoff":"Anxiety temporarily falls after the compensatory act is performed.","Freer Expression":"Repair without erasure.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Conscience; generosity; desire to repair; moral sensitivity.","Observable Cues":"Excessive gifts or favors after conflict; repeated apologies beyond what repair requires; rituals intended to prevent consequences; overcompensating instead of naming harm.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Specify the repair needed; decline excessive compensation; do not become the regulator of repeated guilt. May trigger Reassurance Fatigue, Dependency, Resentment, or Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Self-Esteem, Trust, Belonging, and Safety; avoids guilt, uncertainty, irreversibility, limits of repair, and self-forgiveness.","Canonical Name":"Undoing"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nUndoing is the attempt to neutralize guilt, fear, or imagined harm through symbolic acts, excessive compensation, or repeated reassurance rather than directly addressing the underlying action or feeling.\n## Domain\nCognitive and Intellectual Defenses\n## Related Patterns\nCompulsive Apologizing; Reassurance Seeking; Magical Thinking; Overfunctioning; Guilt Management\n## Recognition Sentence\nIf I do enough now, perhaps I can make the feared harm no longer count.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I need to do something extra so this no longer counts.\n- If I apologize again, maybe the guilt will finally stop.\n- I have to make up for this immediately.\n- One good act can cancel the bad one.\n- I need reassurance that I’m still a good person.\n- I can’t let the mistake remain part of reality.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrgency to cancel out a thought or act; relief after compensating; fear that not correcting immediately will cause harm; repeated guilt despite repair.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nExcessive gifts or favors after conflict; repeated apologies beyond what repair requires; rituals intended to prevent consequences; overcompensating instead of naming harm.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nSelf-Esteem; Trust; Belonging; Safety.\n## Usually Triggered By\nGuilt; intrusive thoughts; conflict; mistakes; aggression; fear of punishment or rejection.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nBad thoughts make me bad. One mistake can destroy the bond. I must erase harm rather than tolerate responsibility.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGuilt; uncertainty; irreversibility; limits of repair; self-forgiveness.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nCaregiver — overgives after resentment. Lover — floods the bond with reassurance after rupture. Innocent — performs purity to cancel guilt. Ruler — imposes corrective order. Mystic — uses ritual to reverse feared consequences.\n## Pattern Flow\nGuilt or feared harm appears → worth or belonging feels endangered → compensatory act is performed → anxiety temporarily falls → direct accountability is bypassed → compulsion repeats.\n## Often Appears With\nCompulsive Apologizing; Reassurance Seeking; Overfunctioning; Magical Thinking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nConscience; generosity; desire to repair; moral sensitivity.\n## Current Cost\nCompulsive guilt management; unequal relationships; avoidance of direct repair; exhaustion.\n## Freer Expression\nRepair without erasure.\n## One Act of Volition\nAsk what actual repair is needed, do that once, and allow the event to remain part of reality.\n## Mira Language\n“You may be trying to erase the discomfort rather than repair the specific impact. What would enough look like?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you trying to cancel? What repair was actually requested? What guilt must be tolerated rather than neutralized?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nThoughtful restitution, apology, and generosity are not undoing when proportionate and freely chosen.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated compensatory behavior aimed at neutralizing guilt or imagined consequences beyond realistic repair needs.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nIdentify the feared consequence; distinguish repair from ritual; accept that responsibility does not require endless punishment.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nSpecify the repair needed; decline excessive compensation; do not become the regulator of repeated guilt.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nReplace symbolic compensation with direct acknowledgment, proportionate restitution, and sustained changed behavior. The affected person need not provide endless absolution.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Reassurance Fatigue, Dependency, Resentment, or Withdrawal. Often triggered by Criticism, shame, rejection, or moral anxiety. The loop becomes “I must keep proving I am good” versus “I must keep certifying your goodness.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nAm I repairing the impact—or trying to erase the fact that it happened?"},
  "PP-URGENCY-ADDICTION": {"name":"Urgency Addiction","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Busyness as Avoidance; Procrastination; Compulsive Achievement; Rapid Project Proliferation; Catastrophizing; Crisis Creation.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior needs a battle. Hero needs a rescue. Creator starts near-impossible deadlines. Caregiver organizes life around emergencies.","Migration Notes":"Batch 9 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"U","Source Batch":"9","One Act of Volition":"Complete one important task during a calm, preplanned work period before it becomes urgent.","Core Logic":"I need everything to feel urgent in order to feel focused, valuable, or alive.","Primary Domain":"Behavioral","Long-Term Cost":"Burnout; poor prioritization; preventable crises; damaged trust; inability to sustain calm work.","Core Fear":"I perform only under pressure; calm means I am failing; worth comes from rescue and intensity; ordinary effort will not hold me.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I can’t focus unless this becomes an emergency.; Everything feels like it has to happen now.; A deadline will give me the energy I’m missing.; Calm work feels too flat to sustain.; I should interrupt the plan for this new crisis.; If nothing is on fire, I don’t know what matters.","Protective Move":"Urgency Addiction is the protective creation of constant immediacy so that action, identity, or emotional regulation depends on pressure. It uses crisis energy to avoid stillness, prioritization, uncertainty, or sustained ordinary effort.","Pattern ID":"PP-URGENCY-ADDICTION","Short-Term Payoff":"Adrenaline creates temporary focus when urgency is generated or amplified.","Freer Expression":"Purposeful momentum without emergency.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Responsiveness; intensity; courage; rapid mobilization.","Observable Cues":"Last-minute sprints; artificial deadlines; interrupting planned work for new emergencies; escalating ordinary tasks; cycling between adrenaline and collapse.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Do not accept every escalation as shared emergency; ask for dates, consequences, and priorities; preserve boundaries around preventable last-minute demands. May trigger Micromanaging, Resentment, Emotional Distancing, or Underfunctioning.","Emotional Function":"Protects Competence, Purpose, Self-Esteem, and Autonomy; avoids emptiness, grief, uncertainty, prioritization, limitation, and sustained discipline without excitement.","Canonical Name":"Urgency Addiction"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nUrgency Addiction is the protective creation of constant immediacy so that action, identity, or emotional regulation depends on pressure. It uses crisis energy to avoid stillness, prioritization, uncertainty, or sustained ordinary effort.\n## Domain\nAction, Time, and Emotional Regulation\n## Related Patterns\nBusyness as Avoidance; Procrastination; Compulsive Achievement; Rapid Project Proliferation; Catastrophizing; Crisis Creation\n## Recognition Sentence\nI need everything to feel urgent in order to feel focused, valuable, or alive.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I can’t focus unless this becomes an emergency.\n- Everything feels like it has to happen now.\n- A deadline will give me the energy I’m missing.\n- Calm work feels too flat to sustain.\n- I should interrupt the plan for this new crisis.\n- If nothing is on fire, I don’t know what matters.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRestlessness without a deadline; clarity only under pressure; discomfort with slow progress; repeated sense that everything matters now.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nLast-minute sprints; artificial deadlines; interrupting planned work for new emergencies; escalating ordinary tasks; cycling between adrenaline and collapse.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nCompetence; Purpose; Self-Esteem; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nBoredom; ambiguity; unstructured time; long horizons; emotional stillness; ordinary incremental work.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nI perform only under pressure; calm means I am failing; worth comes from rescue and intensity; ordinary effort will not hold me.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nEmptiness; grief; uncertainty; prioritization; limitation; sustained discipline without excitement.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior needs a battle. Hero needs a rescue. Creator starts near-impossible deadlines. Caregiver organizes life around emergencies.\n## Pattern Flow\nStillness or ordinary work appears → purpose or regulation feels weak → urgency is generated or amplified → adrenaline creates temporary focus → recovery and planning are neglected → more crises become likely.\n## Often Appears With\nProcrastination; Busyness as Avoidance; Compulsive Achievement; Catastrophizing; Rapid Project Proliferation.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nResponsiveness; intensity; courage; rapid mobilization.\n## Current Cost\nBurnout; poor prioritization; preventable crises; damaged trust; inability to sustain calm work.\n## Freer Expression\nPurposeful momentum without emergency.\n## One Act of Volition\nComplete one important task during a calm, preplanned work period before it becomes urgent.\n## Mira Language\n“Urgency appears to be doing more than organizing time—it may be generating the energy needed to act. What becomes uncomfortable when nothing is on fire?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhich urgent item is truly time-sensitive? What feeling arrives when the pace slows? What system would let importance—not adrenaline—set priority?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nReal emergencies, unstable work conditions, caregiving crises, poverty, and externally imposed deadlines are not Urgency Addiction.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated self-generated or self-reinforcing cycle of delay, escalation, adrenaline-based performance, and collapse across contexts.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nVerify urgency, rank by consequence, create short calm work intervals, and learn to recognize activation as energy rather than proof of importance.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nDo not accept every escalation as shared emergency; ask for dates, consequences, and priorities; preserve boundaries around preventable last-minute demands.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where manufactured urgency transferred stress or disrupted others; repair concrete consequences; create earlier checkpoints and criteria for genuine emergencies.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Micromanaging, Resentment, Emotional Distancing, or Underfunctioning. Often triggered by Procrastination, Catastrophizing, or another person’s repeated rescue. Stories become “Nothing happens unless I create a crisis” and “Your emergencies always become my responsibility.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat do I need urgency to make me feel?"},
  "PP-VICTIM-IDENTITY-FIXATION": {"name":"Victim Identity Fixation","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Blame Shifting; Resentment; Personalization; Denial; Externalization; Reassurance Seeking.","Archetypal Role":"Orphan/Everyman — belonging through shared grievance. Rebel — identity through opposition. Innocent — absolute innocence. Warrior — permanent siege. Lover — betrayal as central identity.","Migration Notes":"Batch 6 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags mapped to Abuse Context because the source explicitly warns against dismissing real abuse, discrimination, trauma, or ongoing danger.","First Letter":"V","Source Batch":"6","One Act of Volition":"Name one present choice without minimizing what happened.","Core Logic":"I am using what happened to me to explain everything I can no longer imagine changing.","Safety Flags":["Abuse Context"],"Primary Domain":"Cognitive","Long-Term Cost":"Reduced agency; chronic grievance; relational rigidity; inability to integrate complexity; dependence on validation.","Core Fear":"My pain will disappear unless I keep proving it; agency means the harm was my fault; no one protects me; being wronged is the only secure explanation.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"What happened to me explains why nothing can change.; If I claim agency, people may think the harm was my fault.; I need others to keep confirming that I was wronged.; Accountability feels like blaming me for what happened.; My injury is the clearest explanation of who I am.; If I move forward, the truth of the harm may disappear.","Protective Move":"Victim identity fixation is the protective organization of identity around having been wronged, so that grievance preserves innocence, coherence, belonging, or exemption from present agency.","Pattern ID":"PP-VICTIM-IDENTITY-FIXATION","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary innocence and recognition return when grievance identity consolidates.","Freer Expression":"Truthful injury with restored agency.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Moral memory; sensitivity to injustice; refusal to erase harm.","Observable Cues":"Reframing most conflicts as persecution; rejecting any role in current patterns; seeking repeated confirmation of innocence; using past harm to end accountability conversations.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Validate documented impact without confirming total helplessness or universal persecution. Do not force equivalence or premature forgiveness. May trigger Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, Contempt, or Blame Shifting.","Emotional Function":"Protects Dignity, Justice, Safety, Coherence, and Belonging; avoids grief, uncertainty, complicity without total blame, present choice, and identity beyond injury.","Canonical Name":"Victim Identity Fixation"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nVictim identity fixation is the protective organization of identity around having been wronged, so that grievance preserves innocence, coherence, belonging, or exemption from present agency.\n## Domain\nIdentity, Shame, and Responsibility\n## Related Patterns\nBlame Shifting; Resentment; Personalization; Denial; Externalization\n## Recognition Sentence\nI am using what happened to me to explain everything I can no longer imagine changing.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- What happened to me explains why nothing can change.\n- If I claim agency, people may think the harm was my fault.\n- I need others to keep confirming that I was wronged.\n- Accountability feels like blaming me for what happened.\n- My injury is the clearest explanation of who I am.\n- If I move forward, the truth of the harm may disappear.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nRepeated return to unfairness; agency feels like betrayal of the harm; responsibility sounds like blame; identity becomes inseparable from injury.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nReframing most conflicts as persecution; rejecting any role in current patterns; seeking repeated confirmation of innocence; using past harm to end accountability conversations.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nDignity; Justice; Safety; Coherence; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nAccountability; ambiguity; reminders of past harm; loss of validating audience; evidence of personal choice.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nMy pain will disappear unless I keep proving it; agency means the harm was my fault; no one protects me; being wronged is the only secure explanation.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; uncertainty; complicity without total blame; present choice; identity beyond injury.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nOrphan/Everyman — belonging through shared grievance. Rebel — identity through opposition. Innocent — absolute innocence. Warrior — permanent siege. Lover — betrayal as central identity.\n## Pattern Flow\nHarm or unfairness is activated → dignity and coherence feel threatened → grievance identity consolidates → temporary innocence and recognition return → agency narrows → current patterns persist.\n## Often Appears With\nResentment; Blame Shifting; Denial; Reassurance Seeking.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nMoral memory; sensitivity to injustice; refusal to erase harm.\n## Current Cost\nReduced agency; chronic grievance; relational rigidity; inability to integrate complexity; dependence on validation.\n## Freer Expression\nTruthful injury with restored agency.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one present choice without minimizing what happened.\n## Mira Language\n“The harm may be real. I also wonder whether protecting its truth has made it difficult to recognize the choices still available to you.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat would agency mean if it did not excuse the harm? Who are you beyond what was done to you?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nMira must never use this concept to dismiss real abuse, discrimination, trauma, or ongoing danger. Accountability and safety come before reframing.\n## Evidence Threshold\nA repeated use of injury identity to reject all present agency across contexts—not a person accurately naming harm.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPreserve the truth of the injury while identifying one domain of present authorship. Agency is not exoneration of the person who caused harm.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nValidate documented impact without confirming total helplessness or universal persecution. Do not force equivalence or premature forgiveness.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nWhere grievance has harmed others, acknowledge current behavior separately from past injury, repair its impact, and retain boundaries against the original harm.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Defensiveness, Emotional Distancing, Contempt, or Blame Shifting. Often triggered by Minimizing, Denial, criticism, or invalidation. The loop becomes “No one will acknowledge what was done” versus “Nothing I do can escape accusation.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nHow can I honor what happened without surrendering the authorship I still possess?"},
  "PP-VULNERABILITY-AVOIDANCE": {"name":"Vulnerability Avoidance","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Distancing; Hyper-Independence; Intellectualizing; Image Management; Emotional Inhibition; Humor as Deflection.","Archetypal Role":"Warrior — never reveals fear. Sage — explains instead of feels. Ruler — maintains control. Lover — offers devotion without asking.","Migration Notes":"Batch 8 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit controlled safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"V","Source Batch":"8","One Act of Volition":"Name one true feeling or need to a safe person without explaining it away.","Core Logic":"I can stay present as long as nothing tender is required of me.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Loneliness; misunderstood needs; brittle intimacy; delayed support.","Core Fear":"Tenderness will be used against me; need makes me weak.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I can stay close as long as I don’t have to need anything.; I should keep this factual.; If I show tenderness, I may lose control.; I don’t want anyone to pity me.; Asking directly would make me too exposed.; I can handle this without letting them see what it means to me.","Protective Move":"Vulnerability Avoidance is the protective effort to prevent exposure of need, uncertainty, tenderness, dependence, or emotional risk while remaining otherwise engaged.","Pattern ID":"PP-VULNERABILITY-AVOIDANCE","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns when disclosure is redirected or withheld.","Freer Expression":"Bounded, chosen vulnerability.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Dignity; self-command; discernment; boundary awareness.","Observable Cues":"Changing subjects; staying factual; deflecting affection; avoiding direct requests.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Invite without demanding; demonstrate confidentiality; do not punish disclosure. May trigger Clinging, Reassurance Seeking, Testing the Bond, or Resentment.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Autonomy, Self-Esteem, and Belonging; avoids longing, grief, dependence, and hope.","Canonical Name":"Vulnerability Avoidance"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nVulnerability Avoidance is the protective effort to prevent exposure of need, uncertainty, tenderness, dependence, or emotional risk while remaining otherwise engaged.\n## Domain\nVulnerability, Trust, and Connection\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Distancing; Hyper-Independence; Intellectualizing; Image Management\n## Recognition Sentence\nI can stay present as long as nothing tender is required of me.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I can stay close as long as I don’t have to need anything.\n- I should keep this factual.\n- If I show tenderness, I may lose control.\n- I don’t want anyone to pity me.\n- Asking directly would make me too exposed.\n- I can handle this without letting them see what it means to me.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nDiscomfort naming need; urge to joke, analyze, or redirect; fear of being pitied or controlled.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nChanging subjects; staying factual; deflecting affection; avoiding direct requests.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Autonomy; Self-Esteem; Belonging.\n## Usually Triggered By\nIntimacy; dependence; asking for help; uncertainty; grief.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nTenderness will be used against me; need makes me weak.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nLonging; grief; dependence; hope.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nWarrior — never reveals fear. Sage — explains instead of feels. Ruler — maintains control. Lover — offers devotion without asking.\n## Pattern Flow\nEmotional exposure approaches → safety or autonomy feels threatened → disclosure is redirected or withheld → temporary control → intimacy remains limited.\n## Often Appears With\nIntellectualizing; Hyper-Independence; Emotional Inhibition; Humor as Deflection.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nDignity; self-command; discernment; boundary awareness.\n## Current Cost\nLoneliness; misunderstood needs; brittle intimacy; delayed support.\n## Freer Expression\nBounded, chosen vulnerability.\n## One Act of Volition\nName one true feeling or need to a safe person without explaining it away.\n## Mira Language\n“You do not owe vulnerability to everyone. I’m wondering whether protection is also blocking the kind of connection you say you want.”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat feels dangerous about being known here? Who has earned access? What is the smallest honest disclosure?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nPrivacy, cultural reserve, trauma-informed pacing, and boundaries are not pathology.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated avoidance of safe, relevant vulnerability that blocks stated goals.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nChoose context, consent, degree, and timing; vulnerability should be deliberate, not compulsory.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nInvite without demanding; demonstrate confidentiality; do not punish disclosure.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge where concealment, deflection, or emotional absence left another person alone; disclose only what is safe and relevant, then change the communication pattern.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Reassurance Seeking, Testing the Bond, or Resentment. Often triggered by Intrusiveness, Criticism, Fusion, or past betrayal.\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat truth am I protecting, and who has actually earned the chance to hear it?"},
  "PP-WITHDRAWING-BEFORE-BEING-LEFT": {"name":"Withdrawing Before Being Left","properties":{"Nearby Patterns":"Emotional Distancing; Devaluation; Testing the Bond; Avoidant Independence; Ghosting.","Archetypal Role":"Explorer — escapes before confinement or loss; Rebel — rejects before being rejected; Warrior — retreats to avoid exposure; Lover — devalues the bond when attachment becomes dangerous.","Migration Notes":"Batch 2 of complete canonical entries. Full source record migrated from user-provided text; Trigger Phrases newly drafted and require review. Structured properties transcribed from existing source language. Clinical Term has no explicit source content and remains empty. Crosswalk Terms remains empty until crosswalk records exist and can be related without invention. Safety Flags remains empty because the source provides interpretive cautions but no explicit safety-flag designation.","First Letter":"W","Source Batch":"2","One Act of Volition":"Before withdrawing, state the feared outcome and ask one clarifying question.","Core Logic":"I would rather leave first than be the one left.","Primary Domain":"Relational","Long-Term Cost":"Preventable loss; loneliness; unresolved grief; repeated confirmation of abandonment beliefs.","Core Fear":"Everyone leaves; rejection is unbearable; control requires acting first.","Legacy Source":"https://app.notion.com/p/39d56ce6f8cb8038a606fe70a4636054","Trigger Phrases":"I should leave before you decide to.; Something feels off, so I’m done.; If I detach now, it will hurt less later.; I need to disappear before I’m rejected.; Getting closer only gives you more power to leave.; I’d rather end it than wait to be abandoned.","Protective Move":"Withdrawing Before Being Left is the protective preemptive reduction or ending of closeness so abandonment, rejection, or humiliation can be controlled rather than received.","Pattern ID":"PP-WITHDRAWING-BEFORE-BEING-LEFT","Short-Term Payoff":"Temporary control returns after distance or ending is initiated.","Freer Expression":"Staying present long enough for reality to emerge.","Gift Trapped Inside":"Self-protection; decisiveness; sensitivity to instability.","Observable Cues":"Ending relationships abruptly; becoming cold after intimacy; finding disqualifying flaws; disappearing after vulnerability.","Review Status":"Migrated","Trigger Phrase Status":"Drafted","Relational Expression":"Offer clarity without chasing indefinitely; respect autonomy while naming the impact of abrupt withdrawal. May trigger Clinging, Anger, Testing the Bond, Devaluation, or Counter-Withdrawal.","Emotional Function":"Protects Trust, Self-Esteem, and Autonomy; avoids grief, dependence, uncertainty, and receiving another’s choice.","Canonical Name":"Withdrawing Before Being Left"},"body":"## Plain-Language Definition\nWithdrawing Before Being Left is the protective preemptive reduction or ending of closeness so abandonment, rejection, or humiliation can be controlled rather than received.\n## Domain\nAttachment, Union, and Separation\n## Related Patterns\nEmotional Distancing; Devaluation; Testing the Bond; Avoidant Independence; Ghosting\n## Recognition Sentence\nI would rather leave first than be the one left.\n## Trigger Phrases\n- I should leave before you decide to.\n- Something feels off, so I’m done.\n- If I detach now, it will hurt less later.\n- I need to disappear before I’m rejected.\n- Getting closer only gives you more power to leave.\n- I’d rather end it than wait to be abandoned.\n## Recognition Signals — You May Notice Internally\nUrge to detach when care deepens; scanning for signs of rejection; relief after cutting off; regret once danger passes.\n## Observable Behaviors — What This Often Looks Like\nEnding relationships abruptly; becoming cold after intimacy; finding disqualifying flaws; disappearing after vulnerability.\n## What It May Protect — Core Human Needs\nTrust; Self-Esteem; Autonomy.\n## Usually Triggered By\nDeepening attachment; ambiguity; criticism; delayed response; anticipated rejection.\n## Possible Core Wounds or Learned Expectations\nEveryone leaves; rejection is unbearable; control requires acting first.\n## Other Feelings or Realities It May Avoid\nGrief; dependence; uncertainty; receiving another’s choice.\n## Archetypal Expressions\nExplorer — escapes before confinement or loss; Rebel — rejects before being rejected; Warrior — retreats to avoid exposure; Lover — devalues the bond when attachment becomes dangerous.\n## Pattern Flow\nAttachment deepens → abandonment fear rises → distance or ending is initiated → temporary control returns → loss is created → the belief that bonds fail is reinforced.\n## Often Appears With\nDevaluation; Emotional Distancing; Ghosting; Testing the Bond.\n## Gift Trapped Inside the Pattern\nSelf-protection; decisiveness; sensitivity to instability.\n## Current Cost\nPreventable loss; loneliness; unresolved grief; repeated confirmation of abandonment beliefs.\n## Freer Expression\nStaying present long enough for reality to emerge.\n## One Act of Volition\nBefore withdrawing, state the feared outcome and ask one clarifying question.\n## Mira Language\n“The impulse to leave may be protecting you from being left. What evidence belongs to the present, and what belongs to an older expectation?”\n## Questions Mira May Ask\nWhat are you trying to control by leaving first? Has rejection actually occurred? What would a paced conversation reveal?\n## Interpretive Cautions\nLeaving unsafe, coercive, or clearly incompatible relationships is not this pattern.\n## Evidence Threshold\nRepeated preemptive withdrawal when closeness or uncertainty increases, especially followed by regret or repetition.\n## Skillful Response — From Within\nPause the exit, regulate, separate evidence from prediction, and communicate the fear directly.\n## Skillful Response — From Relationship\nOffer clarity without chasing indefinitely; respect autonomy while naming the impact of abrupt withdrawal.\n## Repair Path — After Rupture\nAcknowledge the preemptive exit and its impact, clarify what was feared, and rebuild only through paced, voluntary, consistent re-engagement.\n## Protective Pattern Loops\nMay trigger Clinging, Anger, Testing the Bond, Devaluation, or Counter-Withdrawal. Often triggered by inconsistency, criticism, fusion, or perceived rejection. The loop becomes: “I must leave before you can hurt me” and “I must intensify or detach because you vanish when I need clarity.”\n## User Reflection Prompt\nWhat am I ending before I know whether it is ending?"}
};
